<HEADLINE>
NOW RICE IS COOKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Ask Glen Rice, and he'll tell you directly: He
wasn't missing for the last few weeks, just underused.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's breakout, 21-point effort Sunday lifted the Lakers to
their Game 4 victory at Portland. And although he had averaged just
12.9 points in the postseason, Rice assured that he's still capable
of a surge like that any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, I was already in gear. Anytime you go out there and
you get anywhere from five to eight shots, it's kind of hard to do
the things that you want to do,'' he said Monday. ``But they got me
a little more involved, and I've always said all along that once
I'm involved and moving around a lot more, it's going to help the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to start the third quarter, when coach Phil
Jackson designed a play for Rice to come off two screens a strength
of his game, but not a staple of the Lakers offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thought that came to my mind was, `All right, now I
can do what I do best.' And when I'm able to do that, I'm much,
much better for the team,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly found a rhythm, scoring 12 points in a pivotal
10-minute stretch of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always make a conscious effort to try and get Glen the ball
if he's hot,'' Jackson said. But consistently designing plays for
Rice ``would mean calling sets or calling plays, and we're not
about that as a team. We do it occasionally on timeouts or after
halftimes. Then once Glen got going he was fine. We didn't even
have to go back to specific sets. But it was something that got him
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, Rice hadn't hit the 20-point plateau since an
April 14 regular-season game against Sacramento. Averaging 12.9
points in the playoffs wasn't a comfortable feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always get down a little bit when you can't go out there
and do the things you know you're capable of doing,'' he said. ``It
makes it much easier when we are winning. ... I realize the games
are long, the series is not over, we got a lot more playoff games,
just realize I gotta be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates have been supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been real tough for him,'' Robert Horry said. ``He goes
from a guy who's a go-to guy to a third option on a team. It kind
of plays mind tricks on you. But Glen's a competitor, he just stays
in there and he goes for what he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspended animation: An NBA suspension meant Brian Shaw had to
watch Sunday's game from his Portland hotel room, and he said it
wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like when you have a kid and they're out playing Pop
Warner football, and they get hit real hard by a big lineman,'' he
said. ``I was kind of flinching at different times when things
weren't going good, and I was jumping up and cheering like I was in
the stands when we got on a good run.''
</P>
<P>
   And when in the closing minutes, he saw his teammates take turns
wearing his No. 20 jersey in tribute?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was touched. It made me feel special,'' he said. ``It made
me feel that my presence was with them, and it was a great feeling.
It got me pumped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Rookie Devean George (sprained left ankle) will be
re-evaluated today but is considered doubtful for tonight's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
