<SLUG> BC-FBN-BONSIGNORE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNER'S DEATH IS DIFFICULT TO ACCEPT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There is a photo hanging on the wall in my
mother's home in Ventura. In it she is standing next to Eric
Turner, who looks proud and strong and distinguished as he drapes
an arm around my mom's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The inscription, written by Turner, reads: ``Mom, thank you for
everything. Love, Eric Turner.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought about that photo when I got word that Turner, the
former UCLA and Oakland Raiders safety, died Sunday of
complications from abdominal cancer at the age of 31.
</P>
<P>
   Eric always considered my mother Sylvia his second mom. She
worked in the Guidance Counselor's Office at Ventura High when he
was a student there from 1984-86, and they formed a special bond
that strengthened over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Eric may never have known, but his friends in Ventura looked at
him likewise. He was, in essence, Ventura's son, our hero and star.
His success was our success, something to be shared and enjoyed
together.
</P>
<P>
   So when he rose from little Ventura to stardom at UCLA, a little
bit of us rose with him. When he moved on to the Cleveland Browns
as the second overall pick in the 1991 NFL draft, was selected to
the Pro Bowl in 1994 then signed with the Oakland Raiders in 1997
as a free agent, part of us was there, too.
</P>
<P>
   What's so wonderful is that Eric never minded the company. He
appreciated the fortunate position he was in and the unique chance
he had to let all his friends share some of the glory.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 31, an age when most people are just finding themselves,
Eric is gone, and a little bit of us is, too.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't fair, but death never is. It hovers over us, reminding
us again and again that it can quickly snatch away the young and
the old alike. We see it every day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no way to prepare for the times when death
brushes against us in such a personal, powerful way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Eric closed himself off to his friends the last
few months, denying to the very end the seriousness of his
condition. Maybe he wanted to spare us the agony he was going
through, or shield us from the pain of seeing this indestructible
force succumbing to such an unforgiving illness.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been Eric's wish that we remember him as the
6-foot-1-inch, 215-pound package of power, speed and athletic
ability he was. The guy who roamed football fields searching out
running backs and wide receivers to destroy.
</P>
<P>
   And so we will.
</P>
<P>
   Eric's nickname is E-Rock, and as any ballcarrier who had the
misfortune of getting hit by him knows, it was an appropriate name.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember watching Eric, who was a few years younger than
me, play at Ventura High and worry that he might hurt opposing
players. That's how big and fast he was, and how hard he hit.
</P>
<P>
   As physical and intimidating as he was one the field, Eric was a
gentleman off it. I personally appreciate how he looked upon my
mom, surprising her with phone calls and flowers and inviting her
to come see him play when his teams were in town.
</P>
<P>
   He'll never know how wonderful he made her feel when she'd get a
card from him thanking her for always believing in him over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   I will remember how he trusted my father and considered him an
influence. When Eric was struggling with his decision on where to
go to college in 1986, he invited my dad to dinner one night so
they could talk about it. My dad, who died a few years later and
never saw Eric play in the NFL, would brag that he was the reason
Eric went to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   I'll also recall those recent afternoons during the offseason
when I'd see Eric at the gym in Ventura, lifting weights and
playing basketball with the fellas. We'd talk about how his year
went and what lied ahead, the moves his teams were making and the
great football stars he played with and against.
</P>
<P>
   He never minded. But he was always just as interested in what
was happening in our lives and jobs, inquiring about our families
and mutual friends.
</P>
<P>
   That's Eric.
</P>
<P>
   I'll remember how close he was to his mother and stepfather,
Joan and Mark Bailey, and to his older brother, Art Malone Jr., and
younger brother, Derrick.
</P>
<P>
   Art, a terrific athlete who played football at the University of
Washington, was Eric's best friend. I can't even imagine how
difficult the past few months have been on Art and the rest of
Eric's family.
</P>
<P>
   I will remember how devoted Eric was to his 8-year-old son Eric
Jr., attending every youth game he played in around town the last
few years. Eric returned to the West Coast to play for the Raiders
when he was a free agent just so he could be closer to his boy.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Jr., of course, deserves better than this.
</P>
<P>
   We all do.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to put this in perspective, why such a horrible
fate was inflicted on such a young, healthy, giving person. To even
try makes it all the more unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we focus on what Eric stood for and follow the example
he set. The kindness and generosity, the two scholarships he
endowed at Ventura High, the work he did with the Make-a-Wish
Foundation and the Fellowship of Christian Athletes.
</P>
<P>
   This is what we will remember about Eric Turner, who was taken
from us far too soon, leaving behind memories that will never fade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
