<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9334 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-PACERS-KNICKS-HNS     05-30 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-KNICKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a joke going around the Big Apple that if the
Knicks lose a few more players to injury, they're a lock to win the
NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   The more adversity they face, the better the Knicks seem to
play. And things could scarcely have been worse for the Knicks
entering Game 4 of the Eastern Conference finals against the
Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing was again out with a sore foot. Marcus Camby was
hobbled with a gimpy knee. Then it was discovered that Latrell
Sprewell had a broken bone in his left foot, just the latest in a
string of cosmic jokes being played on the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out the joke was on the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we should say the choke was on the Pacers after the
Knicks walked off the floor Monday with a stunning 91-89 victory
Sunday before 19,763 true believers at Madison Square Garden, a win
that evened the best-of-seven series 2-2 entering Wednesday's game
at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake, true believers are the only ones who would
have bothered showing up considering the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers obviously didn't believe the Knicks had a chance,
because they didn't bother to show up. Until it was too late, that
is.
</P>
<P>
   While Ewing missed his second straight game with acute
tendinitis in his right foot, Sprewell _ true to his word _ played,
as did Camby.
</P>
<P>
   For Sprewell, it was a performance that even his harshest
critics will have to admit was gutsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to try and suck it up and give us what I could,''
said Sprewell, who wound up scoring 12 points in 44 minutes despite
the broken bone. ``I feel like I can't explode the way I normally
like to. I didn't feel comfortable out there.''
</P>
<P>
   One player who looked supremely comfortable was Larry Johnson,
who carpet-bombed the Pacers with a game-high 25 points. Johnson
hit 10 of 16 shots, including all five of his 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I was so open for those 3-pointers,'' said
Johnson, who added seven rebounds and four assists. ``I need a
little time to get that thing off, and if somebody's there, it's
going to bother my shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's most crucial 3-pointer came with 6:24 remaining in the
game, right after Reggie Miller hit a 3 to cut the Knicks' lead to
one point. But after Kurt Thomas missed a layup, Camby grabbed the
loose ball and hit Johnson for another 3-pointer _ one that not
only bumped the Knicks' lead back up to 80-76 but seemed to deflate
the Pacers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was probably the biggest basket of the game,''
said Miller, who finished with a team-high 24 points. ``He hit some
big shots tonight to really carry that team, especially with Allan
(Houston) and Latrell struggling a little bit. He was their go-to
guy, and he hit some big shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had fought our way back into the ballgame, cutting it (the
Knicks' lead) to one (point), and the momentum was kind of changing
a little bit. If he had missed that shot, it probably comes off
long and we get a fast break. But, as you know, he knocked it
down.''
</P>
<P>
   He knocked a lot of them down, as did the rest of the Knicks,
who wound up shooting just a tick under 50 percent for the game
(35-of-71), and over 71 percent on their 3-point attempts
(10-of-14). Houston scored 17 points, Charlie Ward had 16 points
and seven assists, and Thomas came off the bench to throw in 16
points for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers were manhandled in the first half, falling behind by
14 points at the end of the first period and by 17 at halftime. And
while Indiana made a run in the second half, the Knicks had a
counterpunch for every late jab the Pacers threw at them late in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play defense in the first quarter,'' said Indiana
coach Larry Bird, obviously frustrated by his team's performance.
``They were hitting shots and just ripping us apart. In the second
half we decided to defend, but we forgot to rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Pacers were able to rally, scoring seven straight
points in a span of 1:06 to pull to within 90-87 with 6.4 seconds
left. But the Pacers' next mistake was their last _ and most
costly.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Best had just hit a jumper that the referees mistakenly
counted as a 3-pointer even though his foot was clearly on the
line, pulling the Pacers to within three points. The Knicks
inbounded the ball to Sprewell, who was fouled with 4.1 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell missed his first foul shot, giving the Pacers a glimmer
of hope. But as he drew the ball up for the second shot, Jalen
Rose, anticipating a miss and hoping for the rebound, leaped into
the lane to block Sprewell out. Sure enough, the ball skipped off
the rim and Indiana's Dale Davis ripped down the rebound and
signaled for a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   But the referees whistled Rose for an obvious lane violation,
giving Sprewell yet another shot, which he made, giving the Knicks
a four-point cushion and putting the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
