<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND ALLIES WARN PERU ABOUT ELECTION RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and its allies issued stern
warnings to Peru on Monday, saying that the re-election of
President Alberto K. Fujimori without opposition risked serious
harm to Peru's standing in the international community.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
prepared for consultations with their counterparts in Europe and
the Americas, U.S. officials called the handling of the election
undemocratic and its result illegitimate. The election was
boycotted by the opposition and was carried out despite objections
from the Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official called the handling of the voting
``a serious threat to the inter-American system and its commitment
to democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, the official said that ``no president
emerging from such a flawed process can claim legitimacy'' and that
``we do not see the election as being valid.'' But later, the
official said in an interview that the comments were intended as
``guidance'' rather than as a formal statement of U.S. policy. The
official spoke on condition of not being identified. Richard
Boucher, the department's top spokesman, was traveling with
Albright to a meeting in Europe and could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton said he regretted Peru's insistence on not
delaying the election and added that ``we are consulting with our
partners in the hemisphere and the international community to
determine appropriate next steps.''
</P>
<P>
   The first opportunity for consultations comes in Portugal, where
European leaders are meeting this week. Clinton is leading the U.S.
delegation before going on to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   European nations joined in the criticism on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the foreign ministry spokeswoman, Anne Gazeau-Secret,
said that ``conditions under which the balloting was held were not
satisfactory.'' In Spain, Foreign Minister Josep Pique said there
had been ``no guarantees of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of American States is to meet in Canada on
Wednesday to hear a report from election observers, who backed out
after Fujimori's government refused to delay the election.
</P>
<P>
   The election, which brought him his third term, was criticized
for numerous irregularities including state support for his
campaign and questions about the computerized system for counting
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said on Monday that the date of the election could not
be legally changed, and defended it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a result of an election which is just, fair,
transparent,'' he said on the CNN program ``Worldview.'' ``And
unfortunately we couldn't have these international observers as we
wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Peru's foreign minister would attend the meeting of
American states in Canada to defend the election process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
