<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9337 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-30 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPEN CAN'T CONVINCE CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A small-time player in the basketball shoe
business hooked up with the third pick in the 1984 NBA draft and
everybody snickered, the way everybody did recently when Angelina
Jolie and Billy Bob Thornton got hitched.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's laughing now, of course, about the union of Nike and
Michael Jordan. Consummated in the Oregon burgh of Beaverton in
1984, it would go on to become the model of all marriages between
an athlete and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, Jordan became one of the most recognizable
athletes on the planet even before he established himself as one of
the all-time best and Nike's swoosh was branded into the sports
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was so big on Madison Avenue, it was really onerous for
anybody else affiliated with the Chicago Bulls to reap much
recognition beyond Madison Street, where the Bulls' home arena
stands.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Scottie Pippen, who ripened into a superstar while
everybody was riveted on Jordan. He developed into one of the
game's most dogged defenders and became a chameleon on offense,
adapting his skills to give the Bulls whatever look they needed to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's highest scoring average in his 11 years with the Bulls
was 22.0 points in 1993-94, the year Jordan ditched basketball for
baseball. His collaboration with Jordan resulted in six NBA
championship rings but there never seemed any question in the
public's eye whose legacy the Bulls' dynasty secured:
</P>
<P>
   It was Michael Jordan's production, everybody else was just
props.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen yearned to direct his own perfect ending, longed to step
out from Jordan's enormous shadow. After a trying season in
Houston, providence delivered Pippen to Portland. (Providence
appeared to have a keen eye for irony, sending Pippen to a region
that has Jordan's, uh, footprints all over it.)
</P>
<P>
   But Rasheed Wallace was there and Damon Stoudamire and Brian
Grant and Arvydas Sabonis. It was a supporting cast in search of a
star, and Pippen perfectly fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The pity is that Pippen's world validation tour had to stop in
L.A. on its way to the NBA Finals. Because the ongoing Western
Conference finals between the Trail Blazers and the Lakers feature
more than one ex-Bull with assumptions to grind.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers last summer brought in an entire coaching staff that
was highly motivated to prove the triangle offense could shine
without Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pippen, coach Phil Jackson has six NBA rings and an ego
healthy enough to try to defy the notion that he owes all of his
success to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Tex Winter, the architect of the triangle offense and
Jackson's longtime assistant in Chicago, whose rightful place in
the basketball Hall of Fame has been denied him because it's so
hard for some people to see where Jordan's influence on the
triangle ended and Winter's began.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to dust for fingerprints to find evidence of
Jackson's and Winter's impact on this year's Lakers, who are 77-19
(10-4 in the postseason). The proof is in Shaquille O'Neal's pretty
passes and shuddering shot-blocking.
</P>
<P>
   It's in Kobe Bryant's reeled-in offense and relentless defense.
It's in the team's spacing on the floor, its serenity in the final
minutes of close games and its solidarity (witness O'Neal and Derek
Fisher donning Brian Shaw jerseys toward the end of Sunday's game,
which the Laker reserve sat out because of a league-imposed
suspension).
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has taken a parental interest in seeing O'Neal and
Bryant grow up, and with his prodding they have matured faster than
even Jackson could have foreseen.
</P>
<P>
   They've carried the Lakers to within one victory of a berth in
the NBA Finals by sinking last-second shots, staging second-half
revivals and making their teammates around them better.
</P>
<P>
   Their success reflects well on Jackson. His contribution to the
Bulls' dynasty will be upgraded, in retrospect.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers' failings against the Lakers, meantime, aren't
likely to change the opinions of those who've wondered all along
whether Pippen possesses the leadership qualities to will a team to
wins as Jordan did.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers have a slew of weapons, but they find
themselves down for the count _ a loss tonight and the Lakers win
by TKO _ because they've had no answer for the Lakers' one-two
punch of O'Neal and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, the Trail Blazers were able to counter-attack nicely,
with Wallace collecting 29 points and Pippen contributing 11
rebounds, three assists and 21 points in a 106-77 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3, Pippen had 12 points, nine rebounds and six assists
but Wallace and Sabonis contributed just two points apiece in the
fourth quarter, and the Trail Blazers lost by two points.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace collected 34 points and 13 rebounds in Game 4, but
Pippen, perhaps exhausted from trying to guard every Laker at once,
petered out at the end of the Trail Blazers' 103-91 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen missed all three shots he tried over the final 12 minutes
and appeared to spend what little energy he had left jawing at
Jackson on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, his breath would have been better spent rallying his
troops.
</P>
<P>
   We're not saying Pippen isn't a great player. We're not
questioning his competitiveness. We're simply wondering whether
this series isn't confirming what some people suspected all along:
that Pippen makes a better consort than captain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
