<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS NOT READY TO GIVE UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They're circling the wagons, talking brave and
preparing for a long series.
</P>
<P>
   They're also getting testy, crying about the officials and
blowing off the media.
</P>
<P>
   When you're down three games to one like the Trail Blazers,
there is no single approach. There might be no life preserver,
either, but that doesn't mean you don't look for one.
</P>
<P>
   What the Blazers and everyone else can agree upon is, if they
lose tonight's Game 5 of the Western Conference finals to the
Lakers, that's a wrap.
</P>
<P>
   If few right-thinking people can imagine Portland defeating the
Lakers three consecutive times, the Blazers are still claiming all
things are possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of people, the way we've played, who
feel that we can still do it,'' Blazers guard Steve Smith said. ``I
don't think it's been a lopsided series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's 3-1, but look at each game. We've pretty much
dominated the first half, and they've played well the second half.
But we dominated Game 2, so people know we're capable of beating
them. I don't think it's `shock the world.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get this one, we go back to Portland. I don't feel we'll
lose three games in a row in Portland. So we're thinking we can
make it back here.''
</P>
<P>
   They have, of course, lost two consecutive at home to the
Lakers, which left them with their precarious hold to their season.
</P>
<P>
   But they take hope in knowing they defeated the Lakers at
Staples Center during the regular season and blew them out 106-77
here in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news for us is, we're not in uncharted territory for
ourselves,'' Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``We've been here in
tough times during the year and come up with big wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the focus from our standpoint is, we have to be more
aggressive. We have to take the ball to them and see if we can get
the referees to call any fouls on Shaq (O'Neal). There were three
times in (Sunday's) game where they don't call any fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, he's not Wilt Chamberlain yet. You can foul him out of
a game between now and when he retires.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy also complained O'Neal was frequently guilty of hanging
around the paint defensively, but officials failed to call illegal
defense.
</P>
<P>
   At least Smith and Dunleavy were talking. After the Blazers flew
Monday morning from Portland, they bussed directly to Staples for
an afternoon media session and workout.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace, who played all 48 minutes on a sprained ankle
Sunday, refused to talk to the media. Scottie Pippen, the man
Lakers coach Phil Jackson put the onus on for the Blazers' series
hopes, spoke but briefly before walking off miffed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was frustrated by Portland's situation, Pippen
said: ``Me? Nah, I'm fine. Trust me, I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the Blazers started each game so well in Portland,
only to fizzle, he said: ``I don't know. You watch the game a lot
more than I do, so I'm going to let you answer that. That's it. I'm
done for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, everyone had their head up. The Blazers all know it's
getting late in the game for any magical answers. Dunleavy said he
didn't expect to come up with any special strategy now.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers are just counting on sneaking one away tonight, and
then figuring anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll have an attitude of desperation in a positive
way,'' forward Brian Grant said. ``This is it. Let's give
everything we've got, or go home. I think we'll come out ready to
play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
