r a BC-OLD-TEACHER-LADN     05-30 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-TEACHER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER'S SEEN IT ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eleanor Bralver is Sylmar High School's hedge
against sexually transmitted diseases, gang violence and teen
pregnancy. The ninth-grade health teacher is a focus of school
spirit, leading the ``Spartan Spellout'' at football games.
</P>
<P>
   And when her union needs her support, Bralver can be found
downtown, chanting and marching shoulder to shoulder with her
United Teachers Los Angeles comrades.
</P>
<P>
   There might be only one thing Bralver isn't gung-ho about:
</P>
<P>
   Retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly the nation's oldest working teacher, the 86-year-old
Bralver plans to work until she's 90.
</P>
<P>
   One recent Thursday morning, she was working just as she has
since 1967 at Sylmar, northwest of downtown Los Angeles, teaching
her young charges about avoiding the primary pitfalls of their
young lives.
</P>
<P>
   There's sex and its consequences, such as AIDS and other
sexually transmitted diseases. There's drugs. There's gangs.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a 4-foot-11-inch grandmother standing in front of
them, wearing a blue denim vest and pants and wire-rimmed glasses,
telling them she knows the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not ready to have sex yet,'' she told her class.
``There are too many risks.''
</P>
<P>
   And in case they're not worried about acquiring a fatal illness,
she's supplied them with a handout one of perhaps 1,000 she gives
out for the year on what the schedule of the average teen mother is
like, colicky baby and all.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the attendant risks of childbirth. Hammering
home one example after another, Bralver explains dozens of possible
birth defects, risk factors for those defects and the pain of
giving birth.
</P>
<P>
   To drive the point home, a bulletin board has tabloid newspaper
clippings, one in Spanish about a ``monster baby'' next to a large,
grotesque photograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had probably more energy than most of the people on
campus,'' said Principal Linda Calvo. ``She's genuinely interested
and concerned about students, and she genuinely loves teaching. I
think she derives her energy and her focus from that. It's her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also a popular figure at football games, where she leads
the fans in the ``S-P-A-R-T-A-N-S'' cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as she walks up to the podium'' in her white slacks
and blue Spartans sweat shirt, Calvo explains, ``the fans start to
cheer.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bralver was a grade-school student in the 1920s, students
still dipped their pens in inkwells and the principal marked the
end of periods by ringing a hand-bell.
</P>
<P>
   When she began teaching physical education in 1935, in the
middle of the Great Depression, ``kids were much more respectful of
teachers,'' Bralver said. ``The kids dressed decently and you
didn't find gum on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bralver got married, raised two sons and 22 years later
time-warped into the modern era of education.
</P>
<P>
   The behavior was lacking, but the teacher adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a tough teacher with love,'' she said. ``I
will not talk when they are talking.''
</P>
<P>
   When students misbehave or show a lack of respect, however,
``they will get their comeuppance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a fun teacher and she encourages us to learn,'' said
sophomore Sulma Sandoval, 16. ``She's pretty old but she's
interesting she laughs and makes jokes about things.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things Bralver prizes most about her decades of
experience is her look into what makes teens tick.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Simon and Schuster published her book, ``Teenagers
Inside Out,'' a collection of her students' papers that gave
insight into the values and opinions of youth, she said. ``You have
to love what you do,'' Bralver said earnestly. ``With me, it's a
passion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9343 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-HNS &LR;      05-30 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal seemed almost to have grown bored
with toying with supposed rival Portland. The Los Angeles center
was looking for other challenges, something to excite him as this
series had in its season-long buildup.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the anticipation that led to the Western Conference
finals meeting of the Lakers and Trail Blazers, only one team has
shown any real growth since last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers did surprise the Lakers with a 29-point win in
Los Angeles. But the Lakers' weekend sweep in Portland turned that
bad night into a fluke, an aberration of a trick defense and the
Lakers' temporary inability to exploit it.
</P>
<P>
   Since that night eight days ago, the Blazers have looked every
bit as fragile as they were last spring, when the Spurs used a
miracle trey to send them reeling toward another two-game Rose
Garden collapse in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, O'Neal decided, now needed to test themselves
against something greater, something tougher than the Trail Blazers
and their still-delicate psyches. So he called out natural science.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hot,'' O'Neal said, dismissing the Blazers' fast
starts and looking elsewhere for a rival. ``Nothing stays hot
forever. Look out there at the sun. Nothing stays hot forever. It's
not hot today.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, the universe's first rapping, dunking and now even
free-throw-shooting eclipse in size-22 high-tops, decided the
Lakers had evolved beyond the reach of the Blazers and their
arrested development.
</P>
<P>
   This day, the NBA knew, could eventually come. The Lakers, it
seems, have grown up.
</P>
<P>
   Harper
</P>
<P>
   ``We have matured some, I think,'' said Ron Harper, a veteran of
14 NBA seasons and three titles with the Bulls. ``We came in at
halftime, and I felt guys were very calm and confident. So I
believe we came a ways. We were very calm in the fourth quarter. We
feel good. We still have some things we can do. But we know what we
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Lakers were also swept out of the playoffs by
the Spurs. Like the Blazers then and now, when tough times hit,
they crumbled. The confidence they put on display proved a false
bravado, too brittle to withstand a worthy competitor.
</P>
<P>
   They still have not been tested by actually falling behind in a
series, but the Lakers have struggled at times. They lost three
games in the first two series, clinching both with home routs.
Against Portland, they faced double-digit first-half deficits in
perhaps the most hostile and ear-splitting of road venues.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike past seasons, they never cracked, seeming to almost
relish a chance to exercise their new poise and composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Lakers _ from last year or two or three years ago _
they might have panicked,'' Lakers veteran center John Salley said.
``This team now, no.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking their impressive, series-changing win in Game 3 on
Friday, the Lakers seemed primed for one of their familiar,
immature letdowns. Under similar circumstances in the series
against the Suns, they barely showed up at the arena, and then it
seemed only to trade tales of the previous evening's revelry.
Lakers coach Phil Jackson lamented before that game, ``We're just
not a mature team.'' The Lakers were routed.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, with the home-court advantage already reclaimed, they
took the Blazers' best shot, calmly got back up and rolled to a
decisive win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it builds character,'' Lakers guard Kobe Bryant said.
``It builds toughness and togetherness. We hung in there together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like playoff basketball at its finest. There was a lot
of trash-talking going on. It was physical _ guys throwing balls at
one another, throwing elbows at one another. That's fine. That
forces us to step up as basketball players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' weekend in Portland might have shown the maturation
many have predicted and perhaps even feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're growing stronger game to game,'' Bryant said. ``Every
tough game, every adverse situation we put ourselves in makes us
stronger. I'm learning how to play every game I'm in. This is the
deepest in the playoffs I've ever been. This is new territory for
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about challenges in this game. If this game did not
present any kind of a challenge, I would not play it. It makes it
more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence is not a sudden discovery for the Lakers. But it
seems more genuine now and far less fleeting under pressure. These
might only be steps in that direction. But they have been
unflappable under the pressure of the road and the Blazers' fast
starts, executing their game plan coolly and making the decisive
plays down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in that situation before,'' O'Neal said. ``A couple
times, we went to a couple arenas, we messed around, and teams were
up by 14. We had to say, `All right, let's go.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to beat us. Everybody's always pumped up to
play us. They always play their `A' game. No team has beat us. We
always beat ourselves. No team has dominated us. They might hit a
couple 3s or might get a couple calls or score off turnovers. No
team has beat us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though they (the Blazers) beat us by 29, they didn't beat
us. We beat ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a collapse seems impossible now. And as troublesome as that
development has been for the Trail Blazers, it could be as
distressing for the rest of the league. If the Lakers will not beat
themselves, there might not be anyone left who can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we found our rhythm,'' Bryant said. ``And once we're
able to figure out a team, and where their heart is, we feel like
we can take it right from them.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
