<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HN     05-30 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A cloud of predictability hovered above the Astros' 8-7
loss to the Colorado Rockies on Monday, and there was no silver
lining in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Octavio Dotel was on the mound, which almost certainly meant the
bullpen would play a key role in the outcome. Considering the
unreliability of the Astros' bullpen this season, that in itself
was somewhat predictable.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros blew a two-run lead over the final two innings to
lose for the 14th time in 16 one-run games. They have lost 10 of
their last 14 games and 12 of their last 15 on the road, including
the past seven in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Want more predictability? The Astros have an all-time record of
9-25 in Denver, where they seem to find a way to lose more times
than not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been difficult here,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the keys to winning at Coors Field is to keep putting
runs on the scoreboard, which the Astros were unable to do. Each
team scored four runs through the first three innings, but while
the Rockies kept scoring, the Astros' offense hibernated. The
Astros scored just one more run after leading 6-4 through four
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of zeros on the board late in the game, and they
kept putting up numbers,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies' bullpen had something to do with the Astros' sudden
run stoppage. After Rockies starter Pedro Astacio left the game
with two out in the sixth, the Astros managed just three hits and
struck out six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't walk guys, and they made good pitches,'' Astros
first baseman Jeff Bagwell said of the Rockies' relievers. ``They
came right at us.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the Astros' bullpen, which allowed three runs
on five hits over the final 2 innings. The decisive blow was Todd
Helton's eighth-inning solo homer off Jose Cabrera. It was the
second homer of the game for Helton, who is hitting .417 with 17
homers and 49 RBIs this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's amazing,'' Bagwell said of his Rockies counterpart.
``He's been doing it all year. He's been the best first baseman in
the game this year. It's tough to defend those balls that go over
the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker wasn't pleased with the way his pitchers approached
Helton, particularly considering Larry Walker is on the disabled
list, and Helton's lineup protection consisted of Darren Bragg and
Jeffrey Hammonds, who have a cumulative batting average of .280,
compared to Walker's .347.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was a weakness in Helton's game, Dierker said:
``He's not very fast. You can walk him. You're better off to walk
him. There's no one behind him. The whole idea was not to throw him
any strikes. We threw it right down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel's season has consisted of one no-decision after another,
and that trend is likely to continue until he doesn't run his pitch
counts so high so soon.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel needed 111 pitches to get through 5 innings, and he has
pitched more than six innings just once in his 10 starts. Monday
was his sixth no-decision of the season and his fourth in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is when he pitches,'' Dierker said. ``He
runs high pitch counts, and it's tough because you have to use up
the bullpen every time he pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the option of facing the Astros at home or on the road,
it's safe to assume Astacio wouldn't pick Coors Field. After
allowing seven runs in 5 innings Monday, Astacio has an 11.81 ERA
against the Astros at Coors.
</P>
<P>
   But in three road starts against the Astros since joining the
Rockies in 1997, Astacio has a 2.59 ERA, bolstered by a three-hit,
one-run complete game at Enron Field three weeks ago. He hardly
looked like the same guy Monday, allowing nine hits (two homers)
and five walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to happen very often against Pedro,'' Bagwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros put the leadoff runner on base in each of the first
three innings, leading to one run in the first and three in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado also scored four runs through the first three innings,
starting in the second with the first of Helton's solo home runs.
Catcher Brent Mayne also drove in a run in the second, and two more
in the third with the second of his three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's two-run homer to straightaway center field broke the
tie in the fourth, and Ken Caminiti's sixth-inning solo shot
provided a three-run cushion for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel issued a leadoff walk to Curtis Goodwin in the sixth,
signaling the beginning of the end for the Astros righthander,
whose day was over after he walked Jeff Cirillo to give the Rockies
two on with one out. Dotel walked six batters, all in his final 3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin scored on Hammonds' pinch-hit single off Joe Slusarski
to cut the Astros' lead to 7-5. The run was charged to Dotel, as
Slusarski extended his scoreless-innings streak to 6. Goodwin drove
in a run in the seventh inning, during which the Rockies tied the
score on Mike Lansing's RBI single off Cabrera.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
