<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9345 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-30 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ Defeat can wear many faces, and the once-confident
Trail Blazers were a runway full of supermodels all decked out in
those silliest of get-ups that normal people wouldn't wear to a
cockfight.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen was dourly dashing while bemoaning the fact the
referees would not let him play his game. Rasheed Wallace wore a
snazzy sneer and defiant tone. Brian Grant, dreadlocks sagging like
his spirit, was trying to convince himself that it's still not
over, mon.
</P>
<P>
   But it is, and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   That much was written all over the face of team owner Paul
Allen, co-founder of Microsoft Corp., as he left his baseline seat
with equally depressed buddy Bill Gates, king of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Poor little rich boys.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, the highest payroll in the NBA _
$73.9 million _ has not been enough to get the Blazers a single win
on their own court in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Garden was turned into a house of thorns once again for
the home team.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago it was David Robinson, Tim Duncan and the Spurs who
rolled over Portland on their way to a championship. This time it
was Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and the Lakers who dropped the
hammer and left the Blazers befuddled.
</P>
<P>
   What had been a rowdy, ear-splitting, ``Beat LA!'' crowd Friday
night shuffled out in silence when Ron Harper hit the
difference-making jumper and Bryant blocked the last-ditch prayer
by Arvydas Sabonis.
</P>
<P>
   What had been hopeful nervousness and a glimmer of life Sunday
became muttering discontent when the Lakers put their arms on the
Blazers' windpipe.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called jackals who were whooping it up in a pack a week
ago after an upset win at the Staples Center now give the plaintive
wail of a lone coyote as they try to make everyone believe they can
do it again.
</P>
<P>
   It can happen, of course, this coming back from the near-dead
out of a 3-1 hole. We know this better than most in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It is a spark that can become a flame. Then the flame grows into
a roaring conflagration, and there is no firefighting team on the
planet that can put it out.
</P>
<P>
   But that spark must come from a leader, and that's what the
Blazers _ for all their moneyed pedigree _ are still without.
</P>
<P>
   They are a company with a dozen vice presidents and no CEO to
provide direction. They are a stable full of solid, hard-working
horses you can hitch to the plow, but there's not a single
Secretariat who can outrace everyone else to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Clyde Drexler left town, the Blazers have been
perspiration with no inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   For years now we have heard about the great depth of Portland's
roster, as if the game depended on how many players you can use
rather than how many players can use their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Dunleavy's rotation that regularly employs 10, 11,
even 12 men has been trumpeted as a strength, when in fact it is a
way to cover up a weakness. It is a cheap parlor trick that may
enable the Blazers to stay fresh and pile up wins during the long
regular season. But the 10th man on your bench does not win you a
title.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the playoffs, the game is all about stars,
about big-time players making big-time plays. And in that regard,
the Blazers' cupboard is bare.
</P>
<P>
   The big-time players in this series are all wearing the purple
and gold of the Lakers. From Shaq and Kobe to the veteran of the
Bulls' dynasty Harper to Glen Rice, who celebrated his 33rd
birthday by exploding in the third quarter of Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   To whom can the Blazers turn for any of that leadership in the
clutch?
</P>
<P>
   Surely not to Pippen, the ultimate character actor who could
never cut it as a marquee attraction. Every time Scottie tries to
pump himself up into the role, he only weighs himself down, which
is why Phil Jackson opened the series by playing mind games with
Pippen. On Sunday he scored just one basket in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has the talent to put his name up in lights. But his
always-on-the-brink-of-implosion demeanor in the heat of battle
makes him a character whom others are reluctant to follow. A leader
must always be cool, not on the verge of having a mental meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith is too mild-mannered. Arvydas Sabonis is too
lumbering. Damon Stoudamire is too inconsistent. Grant is too much
like the scenery. Bonzi Wells is too Bonzi Wells.
</P>
<P>
   All of which brings the Blazers back to the brink, with too much
and too little.
</P>
<P>
   Poor little rich boys.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
