<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9346 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-30 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN the Comets arrived at Compaq Center on Monday afternoon, they
wore their here-and-now game faces. Coach Van Chancellor swears
nobody in his locker room was giving an iota of thought to their
prospects of four-peating as WNBA champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about one thing,'' Chancellor said, ``nothing
else: Can we beat the New York Liberty in our first game?''
</P>
<P>
   But before they could play this season opener, there was some
unfinished business to address. The Comets had to receive their
three-peat rings from last summer, the sparkling, bejeweled symbols
of a grand triumph over real adversity, the life-and-death variety.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony would, of course, include a poignant memorial to
their fallen teammate, point guard Kim Perrot, who lost a gallant
battle with cancer shortly before the 1999 playoffs began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed it on the program,'' Chancellor said of the tribute
to Perrot, ``but it didn't really hit me until I walked out there.
The first person I saw was Kim's sister, and then her mother came
over and gave me a big hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Van cried unashamedly, as did Cynthia Cooper, Perrot's closest
friend. Chancellor admitted he was ``emotionally drained'' by
tipoff, and the Comets gave every indication they had misplaced
their hard edge, too.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 minutes, the Comets had missed 14 of 16 shots, incurred
six turnovers and pretty much let the New York Liberty dictate the
tempo, although the visitors' own erratic shooting kept the score
from getting out of hand. The Liberty never led by more than six.
</P>
<P>
   Then slowly, inevitably, the Comets got their groove back.
Cooper finally made a jumper drop after four bricks in a row, then
added two free throws and fed Tina Thompson with as slick a
needle-threading pass as you'll witness.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the only champions the WNBA has known were off on a
rip-roaring 13-2 run, doing all the little things _ plus the big
ones _ that will give them every opportunity to claim that fourth
ring. They collectively took a deep breath, coach included.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure when you've won three in a row,''
Chancellor argued later. ``Now, if I'd lost three in a row, I'd be
a nervous wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty, tough enough to have dragged the Comets into a
do-or-die showdown in last year's best-of-three Finals, would have
one tension-building second-half run left in them, trimming a
16-point margin to six with 7{ minutes to go. But the Comets'
wherewithal advantage with the outcome suddenly up for grabs made
sure the New Yorkers' last gasp went for naught. The Comets pulled
away for an 84-68 victory.
</P>
<P>
   So they're 4-for-4 in openers, the best possible way to head
toward being 4-for-4 in titles. Nobody knows how to win like they
do. In the WNBA, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a team, men or women, boys or girls, pro or
college, rise to the occasion like we do, when we absolutely have
to,'' Chancellor said. ``And I've never seen one play better
defense than we do, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The C's ``D'' was more imperfect than normal Monday, but they
picked their spots to make their stops, depriving the Liberty of
field goals on seven consecutive possessions after the Comets' lead
had shrunk to 66-60. And although New York is loaded with offensive
threats, none went off for more than the 15 points by Tamika
Whitmore, whose safe-like shape belies her delicate touch.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper and Sheryl Swoopes, ever the WNBA's most lethal one-two
punch, combined for 46 points in turn, serving to remind the
sellout crowd and national TV audience what makes the Comets such
heavenly bodies. The opposition has yet to figure out a way to
stymie either effectively, never mind both at once.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, with 19 points, surpassed 2,000 for her career, a WNBA
first, and Swoopes, eight years her junior, showed why she'll
probably end up with way more than Coop when all is said and won,
scoring 27. Chancellor may have lost a small piece of himself when
Perrot passed away, but he's quick to remind us he's very blessed
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the 78th birthday of his father, Winston. The
occasion prompted Van to mention the phone call he made to Dad when
he first visited Houston to interview with the Comets. Chancellor
pere warned Chancellor fils he'd be ``the dumbest man in
Mississippi if I accepted the job and walked away from all my
friends.'' After Van's meeting with owner Leslie Alexander,
however, they conversed again, and the subject of salary came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad asked me how much money we _ we _ would be turning down,''
Van recalls. ``When I told him it was about twice what I was
getting at Ole Miss, he said, `Boy, with your personality, you can
make a lot of new friends in Houston, Texas.'''
</P>
<P>
   And he has. We do love a winner.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
