<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, May 30.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-CAMPS Ain el Hilwe Camp, Lebanon) _ For the
300,000 Palestinians who have lived for half a century in squalid,
supposedly makeshift refugee camps in Lebanon, the Israeli troop
withdrawal last week proved a bittersweet experience. For them, the
moment was distinctly powerful: From the newly opened border area,
they could gaze on the hills of what they consider their land. For
an entire generation of Palestinians in Lebanon, it was the very
first glimpse, and suddenly, painfully, they felt both closer and
farther away than ever. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BABY-BOUNTY (Tokyo) _ While other Japanese companies give
congratulatory bonuses to child-bearing employees, the Bandai
Corp., a major toy maker, is offering to pay employees $10,000 for
every baby they have after their second child _ the largest baby
bounty ever in Japan, which is struggling to reduce record-low
birth rates that are threatening the country's long-term viability.
By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Lima, Peru) _ Analysis: The students have been
back in the streets, throwing molotov cocktails at the presidential
palace, and the police have been firing back, with tear gas and
water cannon. The army called for order. On the surface it appeared
so familiar, as President Alberto Fujimori rode to a third term
Sunday in an election so full of dirty tricks that Alejandro
Toledo, the opposition candidate, withdrew from the race. By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MITROVICA (Kosovska Mitrovica, Yugoslavia) _ The French
commander of this volatile town, Gen. Pierre de Saqui de Sannes,
told a visiting U.N. delegation recently that the place was calm.
Minutes later, the first stones were thrown in a weekend of street
violence that left six French soldiers and one U.N. police officer
injured, several buildings burned and dozens of foreign cars
damaged. It is the nature of Mitrovica, the last town in Kosovo
with a significant presence of Serbs, to explode without warning.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Washington) _ The wildfire that swept through Los
Alamos, N.M., earlier this month is setting off alarms across the
mountain West, where more and more Americans have chosen to live on
the forest's edge. Experts say those housing shifts have multiplied
the danger that other fires could kindle similar disasters. They
lie behind an urgent new congressional quest for millions of
dollars in emergency money to try to ease the risk. Across the
country, the damage caused by wildfire to homes and property
increased sixfold between the 1980s and 1990s, to a total of $3.2
billion over the last 10 years, federal officials say. In an
average year over the past decade, 1,200 homes have burned. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-POLITICS (Undated) _ Organized labor may have suffered a
bruising setback when the House of Representatives approved the
China trade bill last week, but there is widespread agreement, even
among labor's opponents, that the nation's unions are growing
stronger after years of decline. After steadily losing influence
for two decades, the labor movement has begun to rebound under John
Sweeney, the AFL-CIO's president, by reversing its membership slide
and by throwing its weight around far more in elections and on
Capitol Hill. Thomas Donohue, president of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, said it would be foolish to dismiss labor's power because
of the China trade vote. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SOUTHHAMPTON-TAX (Southampton, N.Y.) _ Behind the privet
hedges that shield the many monstrous mansions in this village by
the sea, something semi-revolutionary is brewing. The rich folks
who summer in the Village of Southampton are up in arms, in a
law-abiding kind of way, about an American principle for which
colonial patriots tossed tea into Boston Harbor: taxation without
representation. This village has been floating in a deep green sea
of property tax money since the 1890s, when plutocrats like W.K.
Vanderbilt began to erect gargantuan houses they called cottages.
Since then, more and more summer people have bought their way into
Southampton, and they pay about three-quarters of the property
taxes. The justice that summer people seek is the right to vote on
village matters while still keeping their permanent residences back
home. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-MUSEUM (North Adams, Mass.) _ Once one of the most down and
out of the New England milltowns, North Adams, Mass., has been
transformed into a Soho of the Berkshires. The unlikely catalyst of
this change was a gigantic museum in an abandoned factory featuring
trees growing upside down and sculptures made out of tons of
industrial debris. But before it could be born, itwas nearly hooted
out of existence as a $35 million state boondoggle.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WAITERS-RACE (New York) _ One reality has dominated the
city's enormous inventory of distinguished restaurants: a scarcity
of black waiters. Interviews with dozens of restaurant owners and
waiters, and with state, city and labor leaders reveal an industry
that acknowledges a dearth of black waiters, but offers several
reasons for their absence. By Glenn Collins with Monte Williams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-OLINE (Undated) _ The race is on to transform visits to
the doctor by providing a wealth of clinical information online for
physicians. Several top medical schools are preparing sites of
their own, and there are several commercially operated sites as
well. These Websites reinforce a doctor's knowledge, suggest
diagnoses and provide on-the-spot answers to patients' questions
about their symptoms. In the process, the new Websites and the
other medical information online have the potential to alter the
relationship between patient and doctor. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-APPLIANCES (San Francisco) _ Breaking ranks with the
powerful ``Wintel duopoly,'' based on Intel hardware and Microsoft
software, Gateway and America Online plan to announce on Tuesday
that they will use a processor from an upstart Silicon Valley chip
maker and a version of the Linux operating system in a new Internet
home appliance scheduled to go on sale later this year. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROBREWERS (Boston) _ The craze in the 1990s for craft-brewed
beers with a variety of interesting tastes (and names) suddenly
jammed store aisles with fanciful brews like Laughing Skull
Bohemian Pilsner, Long Trail Double Bag Ale, Rogue Shakespeare
Stout and Pig's Eye Pilsner. For consumers used to basic labels
like Coors and Bud, it was a bit too much. Some microbrewers
collided with distributors who refused to carry their products and
financiers who clamored for profits even as sales slowed. As a
consequence, for the first time, more microbreweries in the United
States closed last year than opened. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-SPRINT-ASSESS (Undated) _ As Worldcom Inc. continues to
negotiate for the Justice Department's approval for the company's
pending $115 billion acquisition of Sprint Corp., people close to
the talks say the discussions could lead to the sale of the Sprint
brand and its long-distance service. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   SUV-LIABILITY (Detroit) _ Although Ford Motor Co. recently
acknowledged that sport utility vehicles can be hazardous to other
motorists, law professors and plaintiff lawyers say it remains
difficult to win lawsuits based on the damage that sport utilities
inflict in crashes. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
