<P>
   SEQUELS-MEDIA (Undated) _ The film industry loves the
familiarity of sequels, so it won't spoil the ending of this column
to reveal that the Web sites for this year's roster of potential
summer box-office blockbusters are mostly formulaic rehashes of
past sites.
</P>
<P>
   GUY-MAGS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Can men's magazines find a male
market? Or is TV simply too big a distraction for the limited male
attention span? By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CENTENARIAN-WRITER (Undated) _ In the annals of publishing, few
people have had to wait as long as George Dawson to see their names
on a book jacket. Dawson is 102. But then he didn't begin to read
until he was 98. This year, Dawson, who now reads at about a
fourth-grade level, and Richard Glaubman, a 50-year-old elementary
schoolteacher from Washington state, published ``Life Is So Good''
(Random House), based on Dawson's account of life growing up in
East Texas among relatives who had been slaves. Both are listed as
authors. The story is told partly in Dawson's words as recorded by
Glaubman. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NEWMUSIC-CRI (New York) _ Increasingly, as the major classical
record labels undergo seismic reorganizations, followers of new
music are finding that independent boutique labels like CRI, New
World Records, and Bridge are becoming the only companies willing
to record new works. But in the last decade it is CRI especially
that has been a vital home for both traditionalists and listeners
with eclectic tastes, thanks to the efforts of Joseph Dalton, the
label's 37-year-old executive director. But recently Dalton
surprised much of the new-music world by abruptly announcing his
resignation. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
