<HEADLINE>
SUN SHINES ON MARINERS IN FOUR-RUN FIFTH AGAINST CHICACO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Playing at an unusual starting time of 5 p.m. on an
even rarer sunny holiday, the right fielders at Safeco Field faced
an enormous challenge Monday. With the bright sun often shining
straight into their eyes, it must have been like staring directly
into Rickey Henderson's jewelry cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Jay Buhner, who also homered, made a good catch on
a line drive in the second inning when he appeared to simply fling
his glove up at the last moment and hope for the best. He fought
off the sun a couple other times as well to make catches.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago right fielder Magglio Ordonez, however, didn't fare so
well on a crucial line drive in the fifth inning of Seattle's 5-4
victory.
</P>
<P>
   With Seattle trailing 3-1, two out and the bases loaded, Edgar
Martinez sent a low fly ball into right field. The ball likely
would have been a flyout under normal circumstances, but Ordonez
was unable to get a good read on the ball in the intense sunshine
and it dropped in for a game-tying two-run single. Another run
scored right after that on a wild pitch, giving Seattle the lead,
4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Lefty John Halama and the bullpen made the lead stand up as the
Mariners opened a long homestand and kept the lead in the crowded
American League West. If Memorial Day marks the traditional start
to summer, it should be a tight one in the division, where just 2{
games separate first from last.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners needed a well-pitched game after Sunday's debacle,
when starter Gil Meche went only five innings and became a
candidate for the disabled list with a ``dead arm'' (he was to be
examined before Monday's game by the team doctor), while reliever
Jose Mesa pitched so poorly _ nine runs allowed and one batter
retired _ that manager Lou Piniella resorted to using John Mabry.
Halama came through with seven strong innings, and the bullpen
finished up with two scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Undefeated this season, Halama has pitched well since a terrible
inning a couple weeks ago when he lost touch with the strike zone.
He threw an 87-pitch shutout two starts ago and gave the Mariners a
quality start against Baltimore last week, plus another one Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Halama is effective when he keeps batters driving the ball into
the ground. He was able to do so against the White Sox _ he struck
out none, walked one and retired 12 batters on grounders.
</P>
<P>
   The only runs he allowed Monday were on home runs. Ordonez hit a
three-run homer in the fourth inning, and Carlos Lee slammed a shot
that got over the left-field fence in a hurry in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Halama got some help from his fielders as well, which often
happens when you throw strikes and keep the defense on its toes.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's defense is much improved this season, even with the
departure of Ken Griffey Jr. In addition to Buhner's work in right
field, center fielder Mike Cameron, a former White Sox top
prospect, made a Junior-like catch in the fifth inning, leaping and
reaching beyond the center-field fence to rob Herbert Perry of a
home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners also received more effective relief pitching than
Sunday, which isn't difficult when you're only trying to better
Mesa and Mabry. Lefty Arthur Rhodes retired the three batters he
faced in the eighth and closer Kazu Sasaki pitched a scoreless
ninth inning for his seventh save.
</P>
<P>
   The four-run rally against Chicago starter Mike Sirotka wasn't
especially impressive. In addition to Martinez's single, Dan Wilson
reached on an error, Mark McLemore and Cameron walked, and
Rodriguez drove in the first run on a slow, two-out roller that
went for an infield single.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
