<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9350 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-30 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CONTINUE TO SEEK ANTIDOTE FOR POISON 'PEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's not known whether the Mariners have a
game-disaster plan.
</P>
<P>
   But if they do, putting position player John Mabry on the mound
to finish a game would have had to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching choice in the eighth inning of Sunday's game in
Tampa didn't come out of the book of baseball percentages. Unless
the book was titled, ``In case of emergency, break glass and
pull.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite June yet, so it's a tad embarrassing for a
division leader to resort to emergency staffing. But when the
previous pitcher gets every bit as undressed as Charlie Brown by
the worst team in baseball, shame is no longer an issue.
</P>
<P>
   After Jose Mesa gave up nine runs in one-third of an inning _
his single-game ERA is still being calculated by senior research
fellows at MIT _ the Mariners find themselves in an unusual place.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the franchise that over the past five years has
not only written the book on bullpen troubles, but done the movie
as well as syndicated the TV show to Europe, they were adrift in
the uncharted.
</P>
<P>
   Bad as relief pitching had been since 1995, the Mariners at
least had enough bad relievers. Boy, did they have enough bad
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, manager Lou Piniella found himself drained of what
was believed to have been be an inexhaustible supply.
</P>
<P>
   This was like Tonya Harding running out of purple eyeshadow,
Marlboros and bail bondsmen.
</P>
<P>
   Who woulda thunk?
</P>
<P>
   So Piniella resorted to Mabry, a versatile guy who pitched as
recently as high school, rather than subject another overworked
reliever to what became an 11-run debacle. He gave up three hits, a
walk and two runs and must tack an ERA of 27.00 onto his eternal
baseball card.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe not. He rates a few more innings. While he
won't be the first Mariners reliever to have an ERA almost matching
his age (29), he deserves another chance at least as much as Mesa
to put the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that isn't going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners aren't going to dump Mesa. But longtime fans knew
that. After the endless endurance developed watching the
late-edition Norm Charlton along with Bobby Ayala and Heathcliff
Slocumb, fans know that one little 11-run inning will not deter
this club from sticking with underachievers, as long as they are
veteran underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners soothed brows by beating the Central
Division-leading Chicago White Sox 5-4 with seven solid innings
from starter John Halama and one shutout inning each from relievers
Arthur Rhodes and Kazu Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   And pitching coach Bryan Price took Mesa out behind the barn.
Not for a whuppin', but for some instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Seems that Mesa, by throwing open the left side of his body too
soon, is giving hitters a long look at his grip on the ball, which
telegraphs the type of pitch.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the story from Price and the Mariners, and
they're sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still hope there's some magic in the body,'' said Price,
apparently not referring to the fans' request for the old
saw-in-half trick.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa aside, much of what is stalling the staff this season is
attributable to the accursed fates.
</P>
<P>
   Now that 21-year-old Gil Meche has developed a still-undiagnosed
``dead arm'' and is a looming candidate for the disabled list, only
two starters, Halama and Aaron Sele, will have kept their appointed
rounds in the first two months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 pitcher Jamie Moyer and No. 2 pitcher Freddy Garcia went
on the same April weekend, where they have remained. Brett Tomko, a
possible No. 5 starter, was injured during spring training and
started the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki, the heralded closer who ballooned to a 5.06 ERA before
Monday night, had been troubled by a bad back, thanks to a soft bed
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The only health break the Mariners have caught was by Paul
Abbott, and that was because he was only slightly instead of
seriously injured Thursday in Baltimore after stopping a splintered
bat with his face.
</P>
<P>
   Monday in the clubhouse, he looked like Chuck Wepner after a
bout with Ali. After treatment by some of the best cut men in the
fight game, he will start Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But he will be lucky to get through five innings, which gets to
the source of the train wreck Sunday that Piniella and his staff
have seen coming since the injuries to Moyer and Garcia: Too few
innings from starters giving too many innings to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Abbott gone from middle relief, we have a lot of
(short-inning) people in the 'pen,'' Piniella said. ``We need
someone who can give us two or three innings at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Mabry.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Mariners are contemplating bringing up Kevin Hodges
or Tom Davey from Tacoma, the persistent pitching injuries mean
that there is no room for failure among the handful of healthies.
That includes Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners insist on pursuing the magic. If found, it will be
a world-record rabbit pulled from a size-one hat.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
