<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-30 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN SHINES ON MARINERS IN FOUR-RUN FIFTH AGAINST CHICACO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Optional story, subs for previous.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fortunately for Seattle, this time John Mabry wasn't summoned to
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   One day after their ugliest loss of the season, things went
somewhat better for the Mariners Monday afternoon in a 5-4 victory
over the Chicago White Sox in Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Starter John Halama pitched seven solid innings, relievers
Arthur Rhodes and Kazu Sasaki pitched two scoreless innings, the
Mariners played excellent defense behind all three and _ most
important _ the pitchers mound was strictly a No Mabry Zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (his ERA) is going to stay where it is,'' manager Lou
Piniella said of Mabry, an M's utility player who now has a 27.00
ERA after his emergency relief outing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners needed a well-pitched game Monday after Sunday's
train crash in which a dead arm limited starter Gil Meche to five
innings and reliever Jose Mesa pitched so poorly _ nine runs
allowed and one batter retired _ that Piniella resorted to Mabry in
order to spare his bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Halama was very much aware of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (pitching coach Bryan Price) before the game that it
wouldn't hurt my ego to stay in and give up some runs,'' Halama
said. ``To save the bullpen and give them some innings, I'll eat
some runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a starter, I'm looking to go six, seven innings and keep
the game close. It's not magic. Just get your starter out there and
have him get in some innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama made sure they were quality innings as well, allowing
three earned runs in seven innings before turning things over to
Rhodes and Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he got some help from his fielders, which often
happens when you throw strikes, put the ball in play and keep the
defense on its toes as Halama does.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Mike Cameron robbed the White Sox of a home run,
Alex Rodriguez and Mark McLemore comined on some nifty doubleplays
and Jay Buhner played outstanding defense while facing down the
glare of the early evening sun.
</P>
<P>
   Combine an unusual late afternoon start with an even rarer sunny
holiday and playing right field was like staring directly into
Rickey Henderson's jewelry collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible,'' Buhner said. ``That time of day is the
worst it can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, who also homered, made a good catch on a line drive in
the second inning when he simply raised his glove at the last
moment and hoped for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just basically stared at it for as long as I could, then
basically the ball was gone,'' Buhner said. ``I just stuck out my
glove and it hit the thumb and I was able to snowcone it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago right fielder Magglio Ordonez, however, didn't fare so
well on a crucial line drive in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With Seattle trailing 3-1, two out and the bases loaded, Edgar
Martinez sent a low fly ball into right field. The ball likely
would have been a flyout under normal circumstances, but Ordonez
was unable to get a good read on the ball in the intense sunshine
and it dropped in for a game-tying, two-run single. If Ordonez had
made the catch, Chicago would have escaped the inning with a 3-1
lead. Instead, Seattle led 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had a chance,'' Martinez said. ``I didn't hit it
that good, and it was high enough to hang up there. The sun is
tough out there, so it could have been a combination of that and
him playing deep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the sun is really bad out there even when it doesn't
look like it's that bad,'' Buhner said. ``There are these hot spots
where the ball goes in and the sun gets bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron, a former White Sox top prospect, made a Junior-like
catch in the fifth inning, leaping and reaching beyond the center
field fence to rob Herbert Perry of a home run that would have put
Seattle down 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not an easy play to make even when you don't have to
fight the sun, and he had to,'' a much impressed McLemore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well defensively all year,'' Piniella said.
``It's one of the reasons we've been able to remain in first
place.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
