<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXMEX-WATER-WAR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOU H2O: MEXICO LEAVES TEXAS FARMERS HIGH AND DRY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 525-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The Rio Grande, which forms an 800-mile border between
the United States and Mexico, is usually shown as an ankle-deep
flow with lots of immigrants in it. But it does contain a fair
amount of water, which is often the only drinkable source for miles
around.
</P>
<P>
   Under a treaty of 1944, Mexico is meant to give Texas access to
at least 350,000 acre-feet of water each year from the river and
its tributaries. Now Mexico has fallen so far behind in its
promised deliveries that it owes the United States more than 1
million acre-feet.
</P>
<P>
   According to gasping Texan farmers, the trouble began in 1992,
when the Mexican government started hoarding water during a
regional drought. In a parched region, water-hoarding is a high
crime, especially when it allows Mexico to grow crops for export
that compete with America's.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials reply that the drought counts as an
``extraordinary'' exception under the treaty, and they are still in
a bad way.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Mexico, rainfall has been below average for the past
six years. The reservoirs are so low that they can barely supply
the needs of some northern Mexican cities, and production of maize
(for tortillas, the pillar of the Mexican diet) has dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Texan officials question the treaty's vague use of
``extraordinary.'' Meanwhile, as Mexico fails to make its water
deliveries, Texan farmers suffer.
</P>
<P>
   One study, by a consortium of businesses from the Lower Rio
Grande Valley, shows that farmers are losing about $400 million a
year because of Mexico's water debt to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   One underlying cause of the water war is explosive growth. Since
the signing of the North American Free-Trade Agreement (NAFTA),
foreign direct investment has poured into the region.
</P>
<P>
   The border population _ at present about 6.4 million on the
United States side and 5.6 million on the Mexican side _ is
expected to jump to 24 million by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   But, as in California, another problem is wasteful practice.
Farmers soak up about 85 percent of the border region's scarce
water, and on the semi-arid land on both sides they grow thirsty
cash crops like sugar cane.
</P>
<P>
   An ancient system of water rights means that many farmers pay
only modest amounts to obtain their annual allocations from the Rio
Grande, and poor pipelines and irrigation systems allow lots of
water to leak out.
</P>
<P>
   The United States government is now demanding that Mexico make a
good-faith effort to deliver the water owed for the current year as
well as a small part of the accumulated shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   By Oct. 2, it hopes to have wrung at least 400,000 acre-feet out
of its neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   As a gesture of goodwill, Mexico has transferred to American
ownership a total of 138,000 acre-feet of water in the Amistad and
Falcon international dams. And it has promised to give Texas all it
owes since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But when will it do so? That depends on the rain; and Texas
weathermen see few clouds coming for a very long time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
