<HEADER>
A9407 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MARIA-AZR &LR;      05-30 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENAGER DEALS WITH MANY CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (RETRANSMITTING TO ADD BYLINE)  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 BY MAUREEN WEST  
(PHOENIX) - Maria Elena Orozco is a shooting star, the first in her
family to graduate from high school and the first to attend
college.
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's one of the bright lights that flash from the Phoenix
area's barrios, where girls tend to marry young and where high
school dropout rates are among the highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Maria's family is amazed, and a little worried, following her
graduation last week from El Mirage's Dysart High School. She
enters unfamiliar territory next week when she begins classes at
Estrella Mountain Community College in Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   Her college adviser, Juanita Parra, suggested that Maria start
college classes right away instead of taking the summer off. Parra
has seen too many children of first-generation immigrants fail
because they stopped to take a breath, giving in to bad choices and
easy pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen-year-old Maria understands: ``We are at a very
dangerous moment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her 16- and 17-year-old brother and sister dropped out of high
school though they are bright and hold high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure of growing up Hispanic and female is sometimes
crushing: Hispanic girls lead teenage girls nationally in rates of
depression, substance abuse and pregnancy, all of which can be seen
as attempts to escape from overwhelming job, school and family
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Many Hispanic girls live in two worlds, a traditional one that
encourages dependence on the family and a modern American one that
values independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult carrying the world on your shoulders,'' Parra
said. ``In Anglo families, normally the girls are taken care of.
Hispanic families ask their teenagers: `What are you going to do to
help the family?''
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily, Maria faces questions about why she isn't more
interested in parties, boys and marriage. People wonder if she
isnt' setting herself up for disappointment by shooting so high.
Her friends sometimes encourage her to put down her books and call
in sick for work.
</P>
<P>
   What inoculates her from such temptations, she says, are her
dreams for herself, and her love and concern for her mother, who
married at 16 and now works as a housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Maria says her mother gives her unquestioning moral support and
encouragement even if she doesn't always understand Maria's goals.
Maria plans to study communications and wants to become a teacher
or a writer. &QL; 
JUGGLING JOBS, SCHOOL &QL; 
Getting where Maria is today has meant learning English at the age
of 14, working up to 30 hours a week and carrying a full load at
school.
</P>
<P>
   Through high school, she would start her days at 6 a.m. and work
until midnight, then study late into the night, sometimes by
flashlight so as not to wake two of her sisters, who share a
bedroom with her.
</P>
<P>
   Maria, the oldest of six children, has been a dishwasher,
cashier, table buser and waitress. She has changed or lost jobs
sometimes because she didn't want to make excuses for her very
complicated obligations and schedules.
</P>
<P>
   At inopportune times, she is called on to translate for her
parents and grandparents or baby-sit the younger children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers don't understand my responsibilities,'' Maria said.
She is now working at a conven ience store near her home in
Surprise. Her boss has tried to be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   The work and family demands facing Maria and many other Hispanic
students often put them out of the running for scholar ships that
require involvement in athletics, clubs and other activi ties.
</P>
<P>
   But through efforts by her teachers, Maria received a $1,000
scholarship from the Arizona Community Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Maria also had the help of Sun City West retiree Dick Orr, a
retired high school principal. Orr has been her one-on-one tutor
for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   What they share is a faith in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Orr shuttled Maria and several of her classmates to Estrella
Community College and helped them with their college registra tion.
He helped Maria get a used computer. It sits in the family's living
room like a shrine, and Maria's brothers and sisters are learning
to use it too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cares about me,'' Maria said of Orr, who wept on her last
day of high school and snapped photos at her graduation as though
she were his own daugh ter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not like other giggly girls looking for the next dance
partner. She'll reach her goals,'' said Orr, a former Marine, who
still wears a close-cropped hair cut. &QL; 
1-ON-1 ATTENTION
</P>
<P>
   One of Maria's teachers, Susan Fernandez, believes the
one-on-one attention that her 40 migrant students receive from Sun
Cities tutors like Orr keeps them engaged and in school. This year,
Fernandez had only three drop out, and they left because they
needed to work for their families to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez believes her stu dents' need to work so much is a
major barrier to academic suc cess.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the money Maria earns goes to the family. This
summer she may start a second job in order to contribute more.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the money Maria earns goes for the kinds of things every
teen-aged girl wants: a stereo, a phone and fashionable clothes.
She also pays to keep her old car running and insured, a constant
battle and expense in an area without meaningful public
transportation. &QL; 
AN INSPIRATION FOR ALL
</P>
<P>
   Maria's graduation party was the first-ever such event for her
family.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins, aunts and uncles came from around the Phoenix area and
even out of state to celebrate with a traditional Mexi can feast.
</P>
<P>
   Maria's mother, Virginia Perez, was filled with intense feelings
of happiness and pride.
</P>
<P>
   Her uncle, Homer Perez, said he is so inspired by Maria's
success that he may try to get his high school equivalency degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Maria can do it . . .,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   But even at the graduation party, old pressures were ap plied.
Other teen girls and rela tives asked: ``A good time to get married
now, Maria? You have finished your schooling, yes?''
</P>
<P>
   She told them firmly that she isn't done yet, she has a long way
to go. Adults nodded. Little ones treated her with admiration.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Maria's success may be catching. Maria
convinced her friend, Nora Car illo, who has been out of high
school for two years, to sign up for college with her.
</P>
<P>
   And Maria tutors her 10- and 13-year-old sisters, Ady and
Ibette, and other children in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A regular club of neighborhood kids gather around Maria's
grandparents' backyard picnic table for help with their home work.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to be a role model, showing them what's possible. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Mau reen.West &LR; ArizonaRepublic &QL; 
.com or (602) 444-8167. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
