<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN31-CO     05-30 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: In the eye of the beholder
 &HT;    For release May 31, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Many years ago, one of my wife's cousins gave her a gift
of old watch parts _ framed. She hung it on the wall in the
hallway. Shortly, my father came along, observed the framed watch
parts and told us that when the transmission falls out of his car,
he'll know what to do with it -- please save some wall space.
</P>
<P>
   Well, we didn't. But we found a place where an old auto
transmission can be considered art. It's the Georges Pompidou
Center, known to the French as Beauborg because the French don't
want to call things and places by the same name as the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   The Pompidou's exterior is rivaled by what's inside: you just
don't know what to make of it, and since all the placards are in
French, you get no help either. Ever been in one of those nouveau
California cuisine restaurants where everything in the ceiling _
the air conditioning pipes, ducts, conduit and whatnot -- are
exposed? Well, that's how the exterior of the Pompidou appears.
</P>
<P>
   The architecture of the interior is more conformist, but not
what hangs from the walls or occupies floor space. That's where my
wife and I stopped dead in our tracks upon entering the fourth
floor of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   My father was here. Set in front of us was the transmission, and
a whole bunch of other auto parts, all compacted into a singular
rectangular mass of crumpled steel defined as art but exactly like
you see when you go to an auto junk yard where old cars are pressed
into scrap metal for meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pompidou, this is art. So is something that candidly and
movingly portrays all the stages of the digestive system from
beginning to end, and I do mean end.
</P>
<P>
   I confess to not being a fan of modern art but I have been
trying. There is some that, while I cannot possibly translate what
the artist had in mind when he began flinging his paint or pieces
around, I can grudgingly appreciate as being decorative.
</P>
<P>
   Also within the weird walls of the Pompidou, you can gaze upon
work by Dali, Picasso, Chagal, Calder, Miro -- somewhat traditional
non-traditionalists compared to what is going on a floor below.
</P>
<P>
   The Pompidou is the last major Paris museum I have visited, this
being my sixth or seventh trip here. Several years ago, I decided
to have a try at it but was warded off by a pro-Bosnia
demonstration that was taking place in its courtyard. (Or was it an
anti-Bosnia demonstration?)
</P>
<P>
   This time, I persisted. It was there that the memory of my late
father was rekindled. My wife and I stared at the hunk of
compressed auto parts, then caught each other's eye in a gleeful,
knowing expression that, yes, Dad, your transmission made it to a
place far more exalted than our hallway wall.
</P>
<P>
   As we ambled along the aisles, we found even more interesting
things. Often, you are fooled. There were two obscured bodies under
blue blankets on the floor, their anatomies heaving in heavy, deep
sleep breath. Don't touch, it's art -- with a small compressor.
</P>
<P>
   There also was a mannequin clad in a dress made of dried meat.
Haute couture carpaccio? Or was it semi-formal beef jerky?
</P>
<P>
   We waited 10 minutes in line to see a special exhibit, of which
we had no prior knowledge. It reminded me of the mobilized field in
Homestead, Fla., immediately after the ravages of Hurricane Andrew
in 1992. A long line had assembled toward a field tent. I asked
someone waiting in it what he was waiting for. ``I don't know,'' he
answered, ``but there's something at the end of this line, and I'm
going to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was something at the end of the Pompidou line as well, but
once I got it, I didn't want it. Made to lie on the floor in a
round room, we observed a nine-minute, 360-degree film of the
encapsulated body of a young girl (clothed) in various known places
of the world (Times Square, Rome, Hong Kong, the pyramids of Giza,
etc.) No explanation, sometimes an occasional sound of car horns
for effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was that?'' I asked upon getting up and leaving. ``Art,''
I was told.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
