<HEADLINE>
THE `STOP DR. LAURA CAMPAIGN' INTENSIFIES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By CHUCK COLBERT  
 &HT;    The high-profile controversy surrounding ``Dr. Laura''
Schlessinger, the syndicated radio talk-show host and newspaper
columnist, came to Boston last week with a protest demonstration in
downtown.
 &HT;    The local protest_ one in a series of nationally coordinated
rallies that have been held in Atlanta, Chicago, Dallas, Los
Angeles and San Francisco _ comes at a time when the ``Stop Dr.
Laura Campaign'' is gaining considerable momentum.
 &HT;    ``Dr. Laura,''who holds a Ph.D. in physiology, but no degrees in
psychology or psychiatry,has rankled the gay community for some
time now, with her highly inflammatory, if not defamatory,
rhetoric. Schlessinger has referred to homosexuality as ``deviant''
behavior and a ``biological error.'' She also advocates
``reparative therapy,'' which attempts to ``cure'' people of
homosexuality.
 &HT;    Her current three-hour-long Dr. Laura Program is the one of the
most-listened-to radio programs in North America, with an estimated
18 million listeners on more than 450 stations in the United States
and Canada.
 &HT;    But a national gay and lesbian media watchdog group, as well as
Internet activists, public-relations executives and media
professionals, are asking Paramount Television to drop its plans
for Laura Schlessinger's one-hour TV program, scheduled to air this
fall. Gay activists nationwide are calling on various local TV
stations to drop the show, which stars Dr. Laura as the highly
directive advice-giver, who tells her listeners what to think and
what to do.
 &HT;    Spearheading the nationwide protests are the Gay &AMP; Lesbian
Alliance Against Defamation (GLAAD) and an Internet activist group,
StopDrLaura.com.
 &HT;    GLAAD (www.glaad.org),with its mission of promoting and ensuring
accurate and inclusive representation of gays in the media, has
been monitoring Schlessinger's insolent language for nearly two
years.
 &HT;    Advertisers have started taking the activists seriously. For
example, Proctor &AMP; Gamble, the nation's second-largest advertiser
(spending more than $2.6 billion annually), announced earlier this
week that it will not sponsor the TV show and will stop advertising
on her radio program, according to a report in The New York Times.
 &HT;    Proctor &AMP; Gamble, which sells household staples, such as
Charmin, Crest,Bounty, Pampers and Tide, is considered to be a
trend setter in mass-market advertising. So other advertisers are
expected to follow suit as the Stop Dr. Laura campaign intensifies.
 &HT;    Some already have. United Airlines has also announced that it
will no longer run ads for Schlessinger's radio show in its
in-flight magazine.
 &HT;    ``Other advertisers, such as More.com, Toysrus.com and Xerox,
have either withdrawn from her radio program, announced they would
not sponsor her TV program or both,'' writes Stuart Elliot of The
Times.
 &HT;    The protest rally in Boston also comes on the heels of a
full-page ad, sponsored by NOW, the National Conference for
Community and Justice, the National Mental Health Association,
GLAAD and People for the American Way, in the May 24th editions of
The Los Angeles Times and The New York Times. The headline reads,
``Ad time with `Dr. Laura' is for sale. Here's what you're
buying.''
 &HT;    What follows is a sampling from the ad of Dr. Laura thoughts
about gay men and lesbians:
 &HT;    ``I've always told people who opposed homosexuality that they
were homophobic, bad, bigoted and idiotic. I was wrong. It is
destructive.
 &HT;    ``The debate over gay rights _ Rights. Rights! Rights? For
sexual deviant, sexual behavior that are now rights? That's what I
am worried about with the pedophilia and the bestiality and the
sadomasochism and the cross-dressing. It's all going to be `rights'
too, to deviant sexual behavior? It's deviant sexual behavior. Why
does deviant sexual behavior get rights?''
 &HT;    If that's not enough insolence, here's what Dr. Laura said about
women: ``There is little reason left for society to respect women
as it once did. Women get knocked up. They don't marry. They have
abortions. They go to bars. They get knocked up again.''
 &HT;    The ad goes on to document more of Dr. Laura's hurtful comments.
Schlessinger thinks, for instance, that affirmative action for
women in the workplace ``has resulted in jamming many people into
roles that are unnatural for them and undesirable for the rest of
us.''
 &HT;    She's also said, ``It's downright criminal and immoral for any
woman to decideno matter how loving or nurturing she isthat she is
going to intentionally bring a child into the world with no father.
It's wrong ... It's like having a pet.''
 &HT;    Dr. Laura is a gas bag full of crude insults and hot air,
blowing directly on gay Americans and deriding matters of
importance to our community, including AIDS funding, gay and
lesbian parenting, gay civil rights, same-sex marriage, gay pride
and tolerance in the schools for gay youth.
 &HT;    ``It's just trash,'' said Wendy Kaminer, author of the book
``I'm Dysfunctional, You're Dysfunctional'' and a fellow at the
Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study, in an article in The Boston
Globe. ``It's the ravings of a highly prejudiced woman. She's not a
`doctor.' She's a pop psychologist. And as far as I am concerned,
not a very responsible one.''
 &HT;    It's time for responsible advertisers and television producers,
as well as radio-station managers nationwide, to put out the
garbageand along with it the ttrash-talking``Dr. Laura Program.'' 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert serves on the board of the National Lesbian and
Gay Journalists Association.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Chuck Colbert 
