<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9513 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-LATINO-HO     05-30 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-LATINO-HOCKEY-STAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING THE ICE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By VINCENT CINISOMO  
 &HT;    When Scott Gomez first laced up a pair of skates, he didn't
think that one day he would be blazing a trail for
Hispanic-Americans in the National Hockey League.
 &HT;    In fact, he didn't even want to play hockey.
 &HT;    But Gomez has helped make the New Jersey Devils a title
contender this year, leading all first-year NHL players in scoring
and helping his team compile one of the league's best records.
 &HT;    Earlier this season, he also became the first rookie to play in
the NHL's All-Star Game since 1996. And he's the leading candidate
for the Calder Trophy, the NHL's rookie of the year award.
 &HT;    Gomez, an Alaska-born Mexican-American, is the first native
Alaskan to score a point in the NHL. More significantly, he is the
first Hispanic-American to make it to the NHL.
 &HT;    As a kid, Gomez says, he didn't enjoy playing hockey much,
mostly because he wasn't very good at it.
 &HT;    ``I was always the one getting yelled at (by coaches and
parents),'' the 22-year-old player says.
 &HT;    But privately he fantasized about becoming great.
 &HT;    ``Playing in the NHL is something I dreamed about every day when
I was growing up,'' Gomez says.
 &HT;    At one low point, he was ready to give up the game when his dad
forced him to keep playing. Being the dutiful son, Scott did. It
wasn't that Carlos was a hockey fan or envisioned his son becoming
the Mexican Wayne Gretzky; rather, he had just bought his son a
new, expensive pair of skates and didn't want them to go unused.
 &HT;    Being Mexican-American and growing up in Alaska wasn't a big
deal, and no one focused on his ethnicity, Gomez remembers. Scott's
dad is a Mexican immigrant who moved to Anchorage to work on the
Alaska Pipeline. He met Scott's mom, Dahlia, a Colombian immigrant,
at a Hispanic dance.
 &HT;    Gomez knows some Spanish, but admits, ``I'm not really fluent
now because I haven't practiced, and I went to school in English
all the time.''
 &HT;    Plus, he says, ``My mom and dad were always fighting about which
dialect was best when we spoke at home. I couldn't decide which one
I was going to use.''
 &HT;    Today, he proudly acknowledges that he's a role model for young
Hispanics. But the very fact that he is in that position after just
one season in the NHL seems unreal to Gomez, who until last year
played Junior A hockey in British Columbia and for the Tri-City
Americans of the Western Hockey League.
 &HT;    Gomez has had success at every level of his career. He was a
two-time Alaska high school player of the year and tore up the
British Columbia junior league during his single season there. In
the Western Hockey League, an elite association made up of top NHL
draftees, Gomez had 30 goals and 78 assists in just 58 games in
1998-99.
 &HT;    At the beginning of this season, his only goal was to make the
team that he is now leading. And he hasn't stopped piling up the
points this season against the world's best hockey players. Through
48 games, Gomez led the Devils with 44 points on 13 goals and 31
assists.
 &HT;    Lou Lamoriello, the general manager for the Devils, couldn't be
happier for his Latino star. ``(Gomez) can see the ice as well as
anybody,'' Lamoriello says. ``He has a God-given ability to see
plays prior to them developing. It's not something that can be
taught.''
 &HT;    Gomez also is helping the league in its never-ending push to
``grow the game.'' Once seen as a northern, mostly Canadian sport,
hockey in recent years has successfully attracted children of
diverse ethnic backgrounds to its NHL/USA Hockey Diversity Task
Force.
 &HT;    Still, Gomez downplays his role in helping to change the game.
``I don't think of myself as being a Jackie Robinson or a Willie
O'Ree (the first African-American player in the NHL.) There's no
comparison between what those guys had to go through and how things
are for me today. I don't think of it as a racial thing. If any
kid, of any race or any color, sees me and wants to play hockey,
that's what it's all about,'' he says.
 &HT;    Kids who want to play hockey face steep price tags. It is much
more expensive to play this sport than, for example, basketball.
Skates, sticks, protective equipment and time on the ice rink all
cost money. Basketball simply requires a ball and a hoop. Hockey
also lacks the alluring presence of Latino superstars, especially
in urban areas such as New York.
 &HT;    The NHL's diversity program, which has 27 chapters in several
states, is designed to help economically disadvantaged children get
a chance to play the game _ a goal Gomez wholeheartedly supports.
 &HT;    In the meantime, he's inspiring those very kids by filling the
nets and fulfilling his dreams.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Vincent Cinisomo is a correspondent for the Associated Press.
Bruce Sach contributed to this story.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Hispanic magazine 
<TEXT>
