<HEADLINE>
KOREA'S PECULIAR INSTITUTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By DOUGLAS KIM  
 &HT;    In 1991, I wrote for KoreAm on Korean adoption. I'd been
involved in camps for Korean American youth since '76, and worked
with adoptees since '84. The article I wrote was titled ``Korean
Adoption: An Anachronism or an Expediency?'' But somehow it got
toned down to ``An Anachronism or a Necessity?'' I regretted that
because I meant ``expediency'' and wanted to convey the notion of
taking the easy way out.
 &HT;    After 10 years I'm wondering if Korea is still taking the easy
way out.
 &HT;    First a caveat: The foremost consideration approaching this
subject is that behind every statistic there is a precious,
innocent child. I admonish all who enter to remember that helpless,
tiny babies may ultimately pay the price for inquiries, criticisms
or politics brought to bear.
 &HT;    In the mid-1980s, 5,000 to 6,000 adoptees came to the United
States annually. This trend peaked in '86 at 6,275 adoptees. Then
the numbers dropped to under 2,000 a year from '91 to '98. What
happened to 4,000 children a year? Where did they go?
 &HT;    Did Korea suddenly eliminate two-thirds of its sources of
orphans? Had Korea's tolerance increased or social safety net
widened enough to account for this dramatic decline? Did Koreans
adopt those children, or were they institutionalized? Did they pay
the price for the political embarrassment that Korea's peculiar
institution drew from the Seoul 1988 Olympics?
 &HT;    Was it simply more expedient to institutionalize them rather
than face growing international scrutiny as several thousand
adoptees left each year? While I hope not (because there is no
question that any child is better off loved by an adoptive family
than a ward of the state), my suspicion is that political
expediency again won out over the best interests of the children.
 &HT;    Despite the severe downturn, Korea remains the third top
supplier of foreign adoptees. Since 1985, Koreans accounted for
30.2 percent (45,142) of all children adopted from abroad
(149,453).
 &HT;    While it's easy to dismiss these questions simply as criticisms
of Korea, we need to be cognizant of her development over the past
50 years. As Americans we tend to forget the struggles and changes
that took lifetimes in the United States: transitioning from
rural-based living to urban-based, from an agricultural to
industrial to information economy, from an extended to a nuclear
family and ongoing efforts for racial equality.
 &HT;    As Korean Americans we generally ignore that fact that much of
the access and equality we enjoy but take for granted was hard won
by Japanese Americans and African Americans. So it's not difficult
to understand why we _ myself included _ tend to judge Korea by
American standards.
 &HT;    Lack of sex education, stigma of out-of-wedlock birth,
unacceptableness of adopting outside one's bloodline and poor legal
protection for children of a divorce or separation, make adoption
the most viable option for many Korean women confronted with
unwanted pregnancy. The situation in Korean today is not unlike the
one in the United States in the '50s.
 &HT;    Korea has accomplished many dramatic changes that took
generations in the United States. Such rapid transition naturally
results in displacements. The ongoing supply of orphans shows that
change has outpaced society's ability to safeguard many of its
youngest members.
 &HT;    While we can rightly criticize Korea, we also need to know that
applying our standards to a foreign culture without understanding
the complexity of the society can be problematic. As one adoptee
explained, ``Korea can't turn on a dime.''
 &HT;    She can't change overnight attitudes that took decades to reform
in the United States. He pointed out that U.S. race relations are
still evolving _ over 135 years after America abolished its own
peculiar institution.
 &HT;    And we need to remember that for whatever other the reasons,
adoptions also continue because demand continues in the United
States _ creating beautiful, loving families. The end result _
placing a child in a family _ is far preferable to many
alternatives life in Korea would hold.
 &HT;    So where should Korean Americans come-down on this 45-year-old
practice? We need to encourage Korea to continue putting the
interests of children first _ not denying them access to loving
adoptive families abroad. We should challenge Korea to provide full
explanation why the numbers dropped in the 1990s, and to obtain
information about the whereabouts and lives of these children.
 &HT;    Promoting social change is a tall order, but somehow it doesn't
seem enough to simply acknowledge that our motherland is suffering
growing pains.
 &HT;    Recently the Korean government sponsored ``homeland'' tours for
older adoptees. While these gestures are well intentioned, I
question their worth. After 20 years working with Korean American
youth, I know identity is formed much earlier in life _ and not by
briefly being thrust into a foreign land amid strangers. Moreover,
the funds spent on tours may be better spent to help children in
the Korean system get better care, education or vocational
training. The funds could also be used for sex-education, or
protecting children's legal interests.
 &HT;    If Korea channeled her guilt and misgivings about current U.S.
adoptees into care and concern for children in their system now,
there may be less need for foreign adoption in the future.
 &HT;    It's interesting to speculate what changes may occur in 10
years. Let's hope that Korea's policy towards orphans will be
guided foremost by concern for their welfare and not on political
expediency. And that life for adopted kids in Korea will improve by
2010, but if not, that foreign adoption remains a realistic option.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Douglas Kim is a contributor to KoreAm Journal)
