<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9525 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0531-CO     05-30 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0531-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A day without politics is like a day with sunshine
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ My son has a saying: ``When Momma ain't
happy, ain't nobody happy.'' It's not original _ I think he read it
on a tee shirt in Myrtle Beach _ but it's true and right now, Momma
ain't too happy.
</P>
<P>
   The day got off to a bad start about two this morning when a
sudden north wind blasted me out of my summer sleeping habit _ a
Pawley's Island hammock on an upstairs screened porch. Blew the
comforters right off me and whipped the bamboo wind chimes into a
frenzy. Freaky weather, I grumbled as I picked up the cat and made
my way inside. She grumbled too.
</P>
<P>
   But it gets worse. I'm particularly tetchy this morning because
I have broken my own ``happy day'' rule by scanning the morning
paper before the coffee has finished perking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dueling presidential fund-raisers eclipse single-day record,''
is the first headline I see. Seems the Democrats pitched a blue
jeans, barbecue, and Bill appreciation shindig last night at a
downtown Washington sports arena, while a few blocks away
Republicans were hosting a more conventional black-tie dinner.
Between the two parties they managed to raise $40 million _ in one
evening.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of money, my friends, spent on chicken, peas, and a
whole lot of hot air, is obscene _ particularly when we know that
nary a suit there attended out of the simple desire to eat
Brunswick stew with some good ol' down-home folks, or to listen to
George W.'s daddy tell 'em how smart his kid really is _ in spite
of the dumb stuff he says when the dog eats his script.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue with Bill and Hill and Al and Tipper doesn't sound like
even five bucks worth of fun to me, much less the half-a-million
reportedly anted up by 10 unions and a few business executives for
the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Just how many shekels would you shell out to tip a glass of
politically correct merlot with the congressional leader of your
choice? Not much, although I would like the chance to ask one of
them for a list of who's in whose pocket so I could stop wasting my
time complaining to all the wrong people.
</P>
<P>
   ``China given full privileges'' is this morning's lead story,
and it's accompanied by a picture of Minority Whip David Bonior
(D., Mt. Clemens, Mich.) wearing a frown, Chinese dissident Wei
Jingsheng wearing an inscrutable look, and Rep. Marcy Kaptur of
Toledo wearing beads.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters President James P. Hoffa is against the bill, fearing
job losses for his members. Former Presidents Carter and Bush
strongly support the legislation, but it doesn't say exactly why.
</P>
<P>
   Then the news improves: ``Math solutions worth millions.'' This
headline makes some sense, I'm thinking, recalling high school days
when I would have offered up my entire fortune (35-cents lunch
money) for a solution to one of Verna Kimler's mind-bending
equations.
</P>
<P>
   For one New York minute I consider digging out an old college
algebra book (the one that looks like it's written in Sumerian
cuneiform) and having a go at cracking the Navier-Stokes Equations,
or solving the P versus NP Problem.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't be any worse than my monthly bout with the checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   On page 16, I stumble across a headline that could go either
way. ``Hormone offers hope of reviving lost youth.'' Definitely an
eye catcher. So I read on. In Philadelphia, a 60-year-old gentleman
is smearing himself with a
</P>
<P>
   testosterone gel that he swears gives him more energy, allows
him to stay up later, and in his own words, ``do pretty well in the
sack.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the casual reader cannot know what doing ``pretty
well'' in the sack may mean to one man, this news cannot be all
bad. In fact, for the 60-something ladies who wouldn't mind being
hit on by an energetic guy their own age, it could be all good _
unless the macho guys overdose, get aggressive, and in a fit of
he-man chest pounding trigger WW3.
</P>
<P>
   So the news isn't all bad _ but naturally, the good news has
nothing to do with politics.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9526 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN31-COX     05-30 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lord, he's _ a Pibber?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Youthful rebellion takes many forms. My first
coming-of-age rebellion was to hide in the ditch when the piano
teacher came. It was the beginning of the end of lessons I
detested.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, who didn't want to take swimming lessons in seventh
grade, defied her mother and got a two-piece suit to protest.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest son chose rebellion of a fashion as a middle-schooler.
He dyed his sandy hair auburn.
</P>
<P>
   None of this guaranteed, we told ourselves, that our youngest
son, now in the autumn of age 12, would ever fall to said
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he would disobey on occasion just like a kid. But he would
never make some sort of kooky symbolic statement that tossed
convention out into the slop or denounced his heritage. Not him.
</P>
<P>
   Then a few days ago he made the most jarring announcement ever
made in an ever-tranquil home.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Dr Pepper. Mr Pibb.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr Pibb? This cannot be so. My son and Dr Pepper have been
linked almost since birth, sharing the same birthplace: Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Before he could bite off ``c's'' and ``t's'' he was requesting
Dopper Pepper. Waco being the nation's per-capita Dr Pepper
consumption capital, he was contributing to the cause almost before
he consented to solid food.
</P>
<P>
   Two one-soda guys
</P>
<P>
   I loved Dr Pepper long before wings of fate delivered me to its
holy land. You can imagine how my heir's love affair with it
touched me.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot describe how his new dalliance pains me.
</P>
<P>
   We had a match for life, I assumed. My son, whose initials are
RC, would never be caught with any but DP. It was there for him in
good times and bad, for richer or poorer, for pizza party or
Amoxycillin.
</P>
<P>
   And then what happened in his sixth-grade year but a flirtatious
vending machine at school caught his eye. Based on a handsome and
blasphemous promotional contract, Waco schools vend no Dr Pepper;
Coke products exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was there that he tried this, this Mr Imposter. At first
I know it was in protest (I'd seen him turn up his nose at it in
restaurants). Then it came with less resistance. Then he was under
its spell.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who loves Dr Pepper is wise to the crafty attempts of
competitors in the industry to copycat the formula Charles Alderton
whipped up at the Old Corner Drug.
</P>
<P>
   The Dr Pepper Museum has an occasional display on these efforts,
showing all the Dr Fauxes and Dr Fakes.
</P>
<P>
   Fizzy forgeries
</P>
<P>
   Attempts at matching the Dr Pepper formula were made way before
the turn of the century. Maybe the first mass-consumed effort was
Dr Wells. Museum director Joe Cavanaugh blames Dr Wells for a
common misimpression about Dr Pepper. There's no prune juice in Dr
Pepper. None. But the imitator had it.
</P>
<P>
   Mr Pibb was Coke's venture into the field of Pepper imposters, a
field which continues to grow as super stores and grocery chains
make their own. A Dr Pepper Clone Page on the Internet lists 103
versions, from Dr A to Dr Zing. In between are such attempts as Dr
Perky, Dr Gulpster and Dr Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   And now my son has been seduced by one of them. When I sent him
away to school I figured all sorts of influences might change him.
He'd find ideas and and interests to which I'd not exposed him.
He'd find girls. But I never imagined that his schooling would lead
him into the arms of another soda.
</P>
<P>
   The indignity of it all. To think now that some of my
hard-earned cash is underwriting rank fakery of a national
treasure, here in Pepper heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Two can play this rebellion game. The next time he requests Mr
Pibb from me, I will dye my hair, wear a bikini and hide in a
ditch.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the editorial page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
