<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9536 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-ART-N     05-30 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: GREAT JOURNEYS IN WORDS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    The best travel writing is about a meaningful journey, not mere
escape. In light of that, here are five great journeys to take to
the beach, the lake or the armchair this summer.
 &HT;    ``Fresh Air Fiend: Travel Writings,'' by Paul Theroux (Houghton
Mifflin, 2000; $27), shows the master in great form. Whether he's
writing about solitary cross-country skiing in the Maine woods,
cruising down the Yangtze River in China or paddling his kayak off
Cape Cod, Thoreau is a trenchant observer of people and places.
 &HT;    Most of these pieces have already appeared in magazines and have
been resurrected here. That's good, because some of Theroux's best
pieces are his shorter ones.
 &HT;    In ``Dead Reckoning to Nantucket,'' Theroux challenges the
notion that to experience adventure, it's necessary to travel great
distances. So he sets off from Cape Cod, where he lives part of the
year, and attempts to paddle his kayak to Nantucket Island, across
a stretch of open ocean that's known to be treacherous.
 &HT;    ``It was dangerous, it was unlawful, it was foolhardy, it was
forbidden. Catnip, I thought. Who wouldn't choose to paddle to
Nantucket?''
 &HT;    What makes Theroux a great read, apart from his terrific prose,
is the fact this is not mere location reportage. In an essay
entitled ``Travel Writing: The Point of It,'' Theroux notes that
``the travel book performs a unique function. A book has the
capacity to express a country's heart, as long as it stays away
from vacations, holidays, sightseeing and the half-truths in
official handouts.''
 &HT;    ``In a Sunburned Country,'' by Bill Bryson (Broadway Books,
2000; $25), is the latest work from the class clown of travel
writers. Bryson, the author of ``A Walk in the Woods,'' turns his
sharp eye to Australia this time. He writes, ``The supreme
emptiness of Australia, the galling uselessness of such a mass of
land, was something it took the country's European settlers a long
time to adjust to.''
 &HT;    It takes Bryson quite a long time to adjust as well, as he
drives, flies, takes trains and gets chased by dogs through the
suburbs of Sydney. Along the way, he examines some of the more
popular myths about Australia.
 &HT;    ``The thing about Ayers Rock,'' he writes, ``is that by the time
you finally get there you are already a little sick of it. Even
when you are a thousand miles from it, you can't go a day in
Australia without seeing it four or five times _ on postcards, on
travel agents' posters, on the cover of souvenir picture books _
and as you get nearer the rock the frequency of exposure increases.
So you are aware ... that you have driven thirteen hundred miles to
look at a large, inert, loaf-shaped object that you have seen
photographically portrayed a thousand times already.''
 &HT;    Yet despite everything, Bryson is quickly won over by the site
of the rock, as well as by Australia. This is a sharp, funny book
by one of the few travel writers who can provoke belly laughter.
 &HT;    ``Frost On My Mustache: The Arctic Exploits of a Lord and a
Loafer,'' by Tim Moore (St. Martin's Press, 2000; $23.95), is the
first book by an English writer who is very much in the
self-deprecating Bryson mold.
 &HT;    Moore sets out to retrace the explorations of one Lord Dufferin,
a Victorian explorer who traveled throughout Iceland and the more
remote island of Norway and wrote a best-selling book about his
exploits. Seasickness, the Scandinavian diet and a bicycle trip
across Iceland are what Moore encounters.
 &HT;    ``I'm going to get into trouble for saying this, but Reykjavik
is not lovely ... a hundred yards in any direction and you're in an
off-the-peg Legoland suburb, traipsing forlornly through colorful
but soulless tenements or having your holiday face blown off in a
wind-tunnel underpass.''
 &HT;    Moore is of the woe-is-me school of travel writing, where he not
only observes but experiences virtually every unusual or unpleasant
aspect of a culture. It can make for hilarious reading, even as he
strains for effect.
 &HT;    But Moore's constant references to English culture can begin to
sound like inside jokes to those who aren't clued in to English
politics, football and television.
 &HT;    Also worth noting is ``Driving Over Lemons,'' by Chris Stewart
(Pantheon, 2000; $22). At 17, Stewart was the drummer for the rock
group Genesis, before being replaced by a then-unknown Phil
Collins. He had further stints as a sheep shearer and travel writer
before moving to southern Spain and purchasing a ramshackle farm
called El Valero.
 &HT;    In the manner of ``Under the Tuscan Sun,'' he and his wife Ana
started a new life among peasants and shepherds, dealing with
drought, animal husbandry and scorpions. Others have tried to write
this kind of story, but Stewart, who is self-effacing as well as
humorous, manages to succeed.
 &HT;    Finally, ``Passage to Juneau: A Sea and Its Meanings,'' by
Jonathan Raban (Pantheon, 1999; $26.50), remains one of the best
travel books of the year. Raban, who is one of the finest writers
around, sailed his ketch northward from Seattle to Juneau, giving
readers an eyeful of Northwest history, sea lore and his personal
travails. Grab it now, or wait for the paperback this fall. 
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on WAY TO GO!
and other features. &QL;
