<HEADER>
A9540 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-MATURE-ART-NYT     05-30 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MATURE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: DENVER'S DEALS, AND MORE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 PLEASE NOTE: We have included some optional trims in this article
to make cutting the piece for length an easier task. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    This summer, thrill-seeking mature travelers in search of some
excitement _ and a place to take their grandkids for a vacation
they'll never forget _ should head straight for Denver, where the
city's two best deals for seniors can be had at area amusement
parks.
 &HT;    Six Flags Elitch Gardens (299 Walnut) is the only theme park in
America located in the downtown area of a major city. The
$120-million attraction features more than 48 thrill rides,
including Mind Eraser, a mind-boggling inverted roller coaster that
travels up to 60 miles an hour.
 &HT;    For those who want to keep their to keep their feet planted
firmly on the ground, the park has elaborate flower gardens, a beer
garden and fun shows, including a Batman stunt show featuring
motorcycle stunts, high-speed chases and daring falls.
 &HT;    Admission is $30 for adults, $17 for seniors ages 55 to 69 and
free for those over ages 70. These prices also include entrance to
a water theme park with wave pools, tube rides, water slides and
raft float trips. For more information, call (303) 595-4386, or
visit www.sixflags.com on the Web.
 &HT;    Landlocked Denver is also home to the nation's largest water
theme park, Waterworld (1800 W. 89th Ave., Federal Heights), which
features more than 40 attractions on 64 landscaped acres.
 &HT;    Adults ages 60 and over enter free, compared to an adult
admission price of $22.95. For more information, call (303)
427-7873, or visit www.hylandhills.org on the Web.
 &HT;    Classical-music aficionados should take advantage of the
discounted ticket prices for a variety of performances scheduled
this summer at the Denver Performing Arts Complex, a group of nine
theaters that seat more than 10,800 people. Mature travelers ages
62 and older can see topnotch theater for half price at selected
performances, but must arrive one hour before the curtain rises.
 &HT;    Prices vary depending on the show and seat location. For more
information, call (800) 641-1222, or visit see www.denvercenter.org
on the Web.
 &HT;    The Colorado Symphony Orchestra also offers seniors a 10 percent
discount on its prices. Call (303) 893-4100, or visit
www.coloradosymphony.org on the Web.
 &HT;    In Denver, you're never far from nature _ whether your outside
or inside. A selection of zoos, aquariums and museums devoted to
the study of Planet Earth and the creatures that inhabit it will
fascinate the grandkids _ and maybe even the kid in you.
 &HT;    Ocean Journey, Colorado's new $93-million aquarium, is home to
more than 15,000 fish, plants and mammals. Visitors follow two
simulated river journeys. The Colorado River trip begins at 12,000
feet above sea level, with waterfalls and trout streams, and flows
through red-rock canyons to the Sea of Cortez. Along the way there
are flash floods as well as encounters with green moray eels and
exquisite schooling fish.
 &HT;    The simulated Kampar River journey also begins at 12,000 feet
above sea level in the lush tropical rain forests of Sumatra and
flows to a coral reef in Indonesia.
 &HT;    Seniors ages 65 and over receive a $2 discount off the $14.95
admission price. For more information, call (888) 561-4450, or
visit www.oceanjourney.org on the Web.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Other Denver museums that offer discounts of varying amounts to
mature travelers include:
 &HT;     _ Denver Museum of Natural History,  2001 Colorado Blvd., which
features one of the world's best collections of dinosaur skeletons.
 &HT;     _ The Denver Zoo,  23rd Avenue between Colorado and York
avenues, which just acquired precious polar bear cubs.
 &HT;     _ Butterfly Pavilion &AMP; Insect Center,  6252 W. 104th Ave. in
Westminster, a 16,000-square-foot glass-enclosed tropical rain
forest filled with 1,200 free-floating butterflies.
 &HT;     _ Denver Botanical Gardens,  909 York St., with a famed Rock
Alpine Garden that is considered one of the finest in America.
 &HT;     _ Colorado History Museum,  1300 Broadway, which tells the
story of Native-Americans, cowboys, soldiers, explorers, sodbusters
and cattle ranchers.
 &HT;     _ Buffalo Bill Museum,  on top of Lookout Mountain, which tells
the story of the West's most famous scout and showman, from his
days as a Pony Express rider to the famous ``Buffalo Bill's Wild
West Show.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Most hotels in the Denver metro area offer AARP discounts plus
special packages for mature travelers. For more information, visit
the Convention and Visitors Bureau's Web site at www.denver.org, or
call (800) 393-8559 for a free 154-page guide.
 &HT;    
 ACT FAST FOR HONG KONG DISCOUNTS  
 &HT;    This summer, Hong Kong welcomes mature travelers to witness its
beauty by distributing a special coupon book that offers discounted
or free travel experiences. You must call or write before the end
of June to get the book, but travel bonuses can be used anytime
until Jan. 23, 2001. For information, call (800) 282-4583.
 &HT;    With the coupon book, seniors ages 60 and older can take free,
self-guided walks that give participants a good sense of the city's
heritage and architecture. The walks usually cost $6.
 &HT;    The book also includes discounted tours, including one to
Kowloon, with a stop at the Peninsula Hotel, one of the oldest
surviving British colonial buildings. Another tour explores the New
Territories to celebrate the Hong Kong of 100 years ago. One
highlight: a visit to the Sam Tung Uk Museum, a restored
18th-century walled village.
 &HT;    The coupon book's ``freebies'' include admission to Ocean Park,
which normally costs $18, and a museum pass, normally $6, for
unlimited access to four museums.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Feng Shui tour costs $26 without lunch, $36 with lunch, when
using the senior discount booklet _ both $10 cheaper than the
regular adult prices. Tour-goers learn the methods of creating
harmonious environments for man and nature that are practiced in
modern Hong Kong. Stops include Stubbs Road Lookout, Repulse Bay
and Statue Square.
 &HT;    The Dragon Tale tour, which offers the same pricing structure
for coupon holders as the Feng Shui tour, takes mature travelers to
an authentic village home where they view demonstrations of old
customs.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 ORLANDO NEW DISCOUNTS  
 &HT;    Always a favorite for mature travelers, Orlando has a
vacation-planning kit that includes a ``Mature Traveler Guide''
listing discounts available to seniors at over 52 establishments.
The savings: up to $275! Most offers are good through Dec. 31,
2000.
 &HT;    Get your copy by calling the Orlando/Orange County Convention
and Visitors Bureau at (800) 972-3308, visiting www.Go2orlando.com
on the Web or stopping by the Visitor Center, which is located at
8723 International Drive.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Here's a sampling of the bargains, which are available to
seniors ages 55 and older:
 &HT;     _ Arnold Palmer's Golf Academy,  (800) 523-5999, will take 10
percent off any of its programs _ from a half-day to five days _
which range in price from $275 to $1,250.
 &HT;     _ The Ridgewood Lakes Golf &AMP; Country Club,  (863) 424-8688,
will take two-thirds off the regular rate of $75, provided you
begin playing before 9 a.m.
 &HT;     _ Blazing Pianos,  (800) 833-8181, offers a two-for-one-deal _
buy one admission and get a second one free.
 &HT;     _ Gatorland,  (800) 393-5297, gives a 20 percent discount off
its regular rate of $17.95.
 &HT;     _ Wet 'n Wild,  (800) 992-9453, offers a 50 percent discount. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    
