<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-CYBILL-COLUMN-     05-30 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-CYBILL-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBILL'S SAD TALE WILL CURE MARITAL BOREDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, May 30, or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER-COLUMN.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The target demographic for this column is married women in their
late 30s to early 50s. Middle-aged moms, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you're reading this early in the morning, before you head
off to work. Maybe you're flipping through the paper while you're
at home waiting for another load of laundry to dry, or at the
dentist's office while one of your kids finds out if she's going to
get those braces off any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe you're not having a great day, week, month. Nothing
catastrophic going on in your life-but nothing very exciting,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Your husband is a good solid guy, but after 20 years of marriage
things are a bit tepid. When you tell each other ``I love you'' at
the end of the night, it's often said with about the same amount of
passion used to utter, ``Did you remember to walk the dog?''
</P>
<P>
   So yours has not turned out to be a particularly glamorous life,
and you're having idle fantasies about roads not traveled,
adventures not attempted ...
</P>
<P>
   Men you never kissed.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if you'd actually trade your world for anybody
else's, but sometimes you wonder what it would have been like to
have a rich, sexy, wild, rollercoaster ride of a life.
</P>
<P>
   Well cheer up! I've got just the book for you, guaranteed to
make you feel eternally grateful for what you have.
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm not talking about one of those mystical self-help tomes
Oprah's always peddling. I'm talking about Cybill Shepard's life
story.
</P>
<P>
   That's right: by reading Cybill Disobedience, the sassy
autobiography from the fantabulously bounteous star of stage and
screen and tabloid, you'll be thrilled to have your relatively
mundane existence, I guarantee it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure Shepard intended for her book to be a cheeky romp,
chronicling her controversies and conquests through a wildly uneven
career that includes not only great movies such as ``The Last
Picture Show'' and ``Taxi Driver'' and the terrific
``Moonlighting'' on TV, but also some of the stinkiest bombs ever,
e.g., ``At Long Last Love'' and the television adaptation of ``Long
Hot Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   I've always kind of liked Shepard. She's a big, brassy,
beautiful blonde who speaks her mind, even when her mind doesn't
have that much to say.
</P>
<P>
   Kudos also go to Shepard for often naming names as she punctures
the bloated egos of such male co-stars and associates as Elvis
Presley, Bruce Willis, Ryan O'Neal and even Joey Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the book is about sex _ specifically Cybill's
tireless, relentless and apparently often joyless bed-hopping. I
paper-clipped every page where Shepard names a new lover, and by
the time I was through, Shepard's 292-page book was fanned out
fatter than Frankie Yankovich's accordion.
</P>
<P>
   Among her partners, some pseudonymous, some named:
</P>
<P>
   First boyfriend, ``Mike.'' Second boyfriend, Gray _ better known
today as Gov. Gray Davis of California.
</P>
<P>
   More early boyfriends, ``Sam'' and ``Lawrence.'' John Bruno, ``a
wealthy restaurateur.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bridges, on the set of ``The Last Picture Show.'' And then,
of course, Peter Bogdanovich on the same set.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Producer,'' while she was still with Bogdanovich.
(``Shuttling between two lovers did not preclude my taking a third,
or fourth, or fifth,'' adds Shepard.) ``The Director,'' described
as ``a craggy-faced man more than 25 years my senior who tended to
wear long gold chains and a thick gold ID bracelet and was married
to a famous actress.''
</P>
<P>
   A waiter at a resort where Shepard was singing. ``An agent ... a
married father of five.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Grodin.
</P>
<P>
   David Ford, who would marry Shepard. ``The Co-star'' on
Shepard's tour of the play ``Lunch Hour.'' Larry McMurtry, author
of ``The Last Picture Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Two stuntment who created a ``Cybill sandwich,'' in the author's
words.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's gynecologist. An 18-year-old, when Shepard was 35.
</P>
<P>
   Don Johnson. Another husband, Dr. Bruce Oppenheim. An Ayn
Rand-loving musician Shepard dubs ``Howard Roark.''
</P>
<P>
   Cybill even recounts her meeting with, you guessed it, then-Gov.
Bill Clinton, but she claims she told him, ``You know what? You're
entirely too attractive. You better stand on the other side of the
room.''
</P>
<P>
   No moral judgments here about Shepard's track record. If Geraldo
Rivera can write a piggish autobiography detailing his many sexual
escapades, a gal can do the same, right?
</P>
<P>
   It's just that there's something overwhelmingly desperate and
sad about nearly every encounter described by Ms. Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   So, target audience, read Cybill Disobedience, and I guarantee
you that life with Mister-Forgot-to-Put-Down-the-Toilet-Seat-Again
will suddenly seem like a fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least a hell of a lot more fulfilling than one star's love
life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for
the Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
RICHARD ROEPER column and other features. &QL;
