<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIA-SLEUTHING (San Antonio) _ Progress in finding and
identifying missing GIs has been slow on the Korean peninsula,
where tensions remain high 47 years after a shaky armistice brought
an end to the Korean war but no official peace. So far the remains
of five Air Force veterans of the Korean War who had been listed as
unaccounted for have been recovered and returned to the United
States for burial, while 324 of 674 airmen killed in Southeast Asia
have come home. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   DEA-CHIEF (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ Thomas Constantine, who retired
as head of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration to spend more
time with his family, apparently will resume his police career. The
Northern Ireland Police Federation is expected to announce soon
that Constantine, 60, will be appointed oversight commissioner for
the province's new police service, sources said. By MARV CERMAK.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-FOE (San Antonio) _ Jeffrey Wigand no longer travels
with an armed guard. The threats against his family have stopped.
The anxiety and paranoia have all but ended. But the fire remains.
The same angry conviction that spurred Wigand to blow the whistle
on the tobacco industry continues to compel him to rail against his
former bosses. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   CAVE-WRITING (San Antonio) _ An inscription discovered in a
Bandera County cave suggests Spaniards, possibly in search of
silver or native Americans to enslave, may have ventured through
the Hill Country years earlier than previously believed. If proven
authentic), it would be the earliest written inscription in Texas,
said Thomas Hester, a University of Texas anthropology professor,
who noted that the previously known Spanish records in Texas date
from the 1580s. By ZEKE MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-HORTON-HEAT (Undated) _ Guitarist, vocalist and songwriter
Jim Heath isn't really complaining about his life on the go. After
all, he's making his high-energy, revved-up, all-out
rockabilly-based music with Jimbo Wallace and Scott Churilla. The
trio is touring with a new album, ``Spend a Night in the Box.'' By
JIM BEAL Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Honda plans to beef up production of its
new Odyssey minivan to satisfy a U.S. market that can't seem to get
enough of these cars. Also, Ford Motor Co. has decided not to build
a 2000 model Mustang SVT Cobra, but plans to begin production of
the 2001 model in early fall. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CATS-COMPUTERS (San Francisco) _ The latest economic tumult
shivers the spines of Internet moneybags and Silicon Valley
kingpins, but ordinary American computer users have a lesser worry:
``How do I get my cat off the computer keyboard?'' Now a solution
has arrived _ a software program that ``knows'' when a cat is
walking on the keyboard. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   RAILROAD-PARK (Rusk, Texas) _ Blair Lavell, mechanical
superintendent with the Texas Parks &AMP; Wildlife Department, oversees
the collection of nearly four dozen cars and operating steam
locomotives that comprise the Texas State Railroad, which operates
between this sleepy Piney Woods town and Palestine, 25 miles away.
The Rusk and Palestine depots, as well as the miles of track and
low bridges that join them, comprise the Texas State Railroad State
Historical Park. By RON HENRY STRAIT.
</P>
<P>
   With RAILROAD-GLOSSARY.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BEER-WINE (San Antonio) _ More beer drinkers than ever are
beginning to learn that, given the wealth of beers available
nowadays, different styles of their favorite beverage can be just
as good with food as wine _ and, in some cases, even better. By
JOHN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-SOCCER-FANS (San Francisco) _ It is a mystery that defies
easy explanation. Somehow, millions of soccer players have vanished
without a trace. An estimated 18 million men and women play soccer
in this country. Add to that impressive number the millions who
have participated in the sport since the soccer boom began a
quarter of a century ago. Yet professional Major League Soccer,
which is played in 12 U.S. cities is averaging only 14,000 fans a
game, well below capacity. By FRANK BLACKMAN.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The most unusual place to find
a grandmother and mother of four, nursing a broken rib, would be 25
miles out at sea, captaining a 50-foot sportfishing vessel looking
for salmon. That is where you will find Jacqueline Douglas, the
first professional female skipper on the Pacific Coast, running her
boat seven days a week out of Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco.
By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ This is a city that eats grilled
radicchio and miso-glazed cod, but spits out its small businesses,
old people and children. Attention Mayor Willie Brown and the San
Francisco Board of Supervisors _ your city is disappearing.
Something has to be done, or this won't be a city at all, but a
shiny theme park for the rich and the childless. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Maybe by next year I'll decide
if I prefer the new ballpark when the Giants are at home or on the
road. All I know now is that _ in this, Pacific Bell Park's
inaugural season _ the cozy little red-brick baseball stadium makes
me feel like a teenager with a major crush. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-TOWN (San Francisco) _ San Francisco was once a Navy town,
but you'd never know it today. Not so long ago, tens of thousands
of bluejackets _ along with Marines, Coast Guardsmen and Merchant
Mariners _ swarmed our streets, drank our booze and hit on our
women (and our men, too, doubtlessly). White caps of sailors on
liberty were everywhere, but Market Street was the gangway into the
city and North Beach the galley. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
