<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-BRIEFS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HONDA TO ACCELERATE PRODUCTION OF MINIVAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Honda has heard from consumers hot for its new Odyssey minivan,
and is taking steps to beef-up production to satisfy a U.S. market
that can't seem to get enough of these cars.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waiting until April 2002 to open its new plant in
Alabama to build the Odyssey, Honda has moved start-up to late
2001, officials of American Honda said. The site, in Lincoln, Ala.,
will be Honda's second assembly plant for the Odyssey in North
America; the vehicles already are being built at Alliston, Ontario.
Honda builds cars in Marysville, Ohio, too, but has no plans to
build minivans there.
</P>
<P>
   Honda will spend about $800 million to build the Alabama plant,
which will be able to produce about 120,000 of the minivans yearly.
Combined with the Canadian plant, North American production
capacity for the Odyssey will be about 280,000 units a year, Honda
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that will cut the long wait for new Odyssey vans that
many consumers are experiencing now. Some customers reportedly are
waiting up to four months to get the vehicle they want.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Honda's first midsize sport-utility vehicle for
the U.S. market will go on sale this fall, branded as the Acura
MDX.
</P>
<P>
   The MDX will replace the Acura SLX, which is basically a
rebadged, high-end version of the Isuzu Trooper. There also could
be a Honda-branded version of the MDX to replace the Passport,
which is a rebadged Isuzu Rodeo. The only sport-utility that Honda
makes for itself now is the CR-V, a mini-SUV based on the Civic
chassis.
</P>
<P>
   The MDX that will appear this fall as a 2001 model will be
positioned to compete against the Lexus RX 300, Mercedes-Benz
M-class and Land Rover Discovery II, and will have a full-time
four-wheel-drive system. The vehicle, which debuted in April at the
New York Auto Show, will carry up to seven people.
</P>
<P>
   It will be powered by a 240-horsepower, 3.5-liter V-6 engine and
five-speed automatic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   FORD WON'T BUILD 2000-MODEL COBRA
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. has decided not to build a 2000 model Mustang SVT
Cobra, even though the company has about 900 orders for the cars,
company officials said. The company is still dealing with
complaints from buyers of the 1999 model Cobras that the cars don't
get the 320 horsepower that specifications call for.
</P>
<P>
   All is not lost for those expecting new Cobras, however. Ford
says it plans to begin production of the 2001 model in early fall,
and will offer the first of those to customers who have orders on
file. Those customers will get the vehicles at the prices set for
the 2000 models.
</P>
<P>
   Production for 2001 will be limited to 8,000 units. The Cobra
was designed by Ford's special vehicle team, which is given a free
hand to take regular Ford products and soup them up into special
high-performance models.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   LEXUS PLANS SPORTS SEDAN
</P>
<P>
   Lexus, Toyota's premium-car division, will roll out its all-new
IS 300 sports sedan on June 23 priced at $30,995, the company has
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The new sedan, expected to be more of a driver's car than other
Lexus models in the low $30,000s, will be equipped with a 3.0-liter
inline six-cylinder engine making 215 horsepower. It is expected to
compete against models such as the BMW 328i, which costs about
$34,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus expects to sell about 25,000 of the new model in the first
year. Standard equipment will include automatic climate control,
cruise control, traction control, power windows/mirrors/door locks,
17-inch sport wheels, and compact-disc changer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
