<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9573 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-BEER-WINE-HNS &LR;      05-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-WINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HAUTE CUISINE: TRY WASHING IT DOWN WITH BEER INSTEAD OF WINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GRIFFIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Much has been made of pairing the right wine with
certain dishes. Oenologists and chefs alike love to wax rhapsodic
about how, say, the elusive hints of tangy star fruit on a certain
chardonnay's finish would make it the perfect partner for a
cilantro-lobster flan on a golden tomato coulis. Or they gush over
a fruity old vines' zinfandel poured alongside a ginger-berry
compote with creme anglaise.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make a beer drinker choke on his Frito pie.
</P>
<P>
   If that's your impression of wine drinkers vs. beer drinkers,
you probably should modify your stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   More beer drinkers than ever are beginning to learn that, given
the wealth of beers available nowadays, different styles of their
favorite beverage can be just as good with food as wine _ and, in
some cases, even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 400 to 1,000 identified compounds in beer which
affect the flavor and how it's perceived,'' says Dan Hermes, food
and beverage director of the Faust Restaurant and Brewery in New
Braunfels, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right partnership will make both your beer and your
meal taste better. And that's what it's all about, anyway, isn't
it?
</P>
<P>
   This goes beyond having Budweiser after Budweiser throughout
dinner, regardless of what's being served. It involves some thought
about the flavor of the beer, its texture and overall nature and
how those characteristics match up with the food that's being
served.
</P>
<P>
   The vocabulary employed is akin to that of food and wine
pairings, and there are similarities. Both a pilsner and a
chardonnay are noted for their dryness, for example. In fact,
Michael Jackson, an author and authority on beer, says, ``A good
dry pilsner is like the chardonnay of the beer world.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, extend that comparison to what food you'd serve with
chardonnay _ fish, for example _ and you're off and running.
</P>
<P>
   Some pairings are easy. Yeasty beers of any sort go well with
bread. Tart Belgian ales, with undertones of citrus zest and
coriander, would be a natural with a salad sporting an oil and
vinegar dressing. Now, think of a dish of warm berry cobbler with a
raspberry ale on the side or a chocolate stout with a dense slice
of flourless chocolate cake. A rauchbier has, as the style's name
implies in German, a smokiness that makes it perfect for smoked
oysters or bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The next steps involve finding pairings that complement each
other but not in so obvious a manner. What, for example, goes with
a thick, juicy steak?
</P>
<P>
   As with wine, the final word is that what appeals to you most is
what works best. ``To each his own,'' says Joey Villareal, owner
and brewer at the Blue Star Brewing Co. in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to steak, Hermes prefers a brown ale, with its
host of roasted flavors. ``You're extending the same flavors,'' he
says. But don't order something too dark. ``An Irish stout would
dominate the steak.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson prefers pale ales with steak; in his authoritative
``Ultimate Beer'' (DK Publishing), he compares that style to ``the
fresh, fruit cabernets of the New World.''
</P>
<P>
   Villareal also likes a pale ale with steak, and he might have
the same with a spicy dish. ``I'd like a pilsner or a pale ale with
Mexican food,'' he says. ``Some spicy Chinese food is great with a
lager,'' especially a Sapporo.
</P>
<P>
   But with a hamburger, Villareal prefers a pilsner, because the
bread is so filling ``you want something lighter.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all a matter of giving the subject some thought beforehand
and being aware of what's happening. ``Once you become aware of
this fluid going across your tongue,'' you start tasting it
differently and begin to think of how it will work with certain
foods, Hermes says. ``That's not just food and wine _ or beer _ but
food to food, how everything on the plate goes together.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's also the wealth of beers to consider. Since the
microbrewery explosion of the late 1970s and an increase in
imported beers, American beer drinkers have been faced with
hundreds of options and styles. Back in the 1960s, who but world
travelers and beer nuts had ever heard of a Belgian abbey beer,
much less thought of matching one with Stilton or Roquefort cheese?
</P>
<P>
   Not all beer drinkers structure their beer and food pairings
analytically, but some have instinctively made choices about what
they like together. Paul Kahl, a real estate agent and beer
aficionado, hadn't given the concept much thought before being
asked about it, but he knows he loves ``a Heineken with fish and
shrimp, some of the foreign beers, like Pilsner Urquell.'' And with
``lighter foods, I want some lighter kind of cool to wash it down
with,'' he says, citing Bud Lite or Miller Lite as possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Most people will readily admit that they enjoy pairings that
complement each other. Jackson is quick to point out that ``I like
similar flavors because they extend the experience. I just enjoy
that very much.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that some contrasts can be beneficial, such as
a peppery porter or dry stout served up with salty oysters, long a
tradition in Jackson's home country, England. A hefeweizen, with
its residual sugars, is an exciting partner for a salty Caesar
salad or spicy Asian food.
</P>
<P>
   But don't take the contrast too far, Hermes warns, or you'll end
up with a combination that brings out the worst of both, much like
``toothpaste and orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a danger in too much discussion of pairings, Villareal
warns. Taking the topic too far gives beer the wrong image. ``The
wine industry ran into a snob problem,'' he says. ``I don't want
craft beer to face the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson feels the same way. ``It's not that I feel that whenever
you eat, you must have beer,'' says the self-proclaimed Beer
Hunter, who also has written extensively about single malt
scotches. ``But you don't always have to have wine.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact John Griffin by e-mail at jgriffin(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
