A9575 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MUSIC-HORTON-HEAT-HNS     05-30 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HORTON-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GUITARIST PROUD OF HIS ROCKABILLY BAND'S TEXAS SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM BEAL Jr.  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life on the road with a rock `n' roll band is nothing but
glamour. Just ask Jim Heath, guitarist, vocalist, songwriter and
front man with the Reverend Horton Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to wash my clothes,'' Heath yelled over the roar of
a clothes dryer somewhere in North Carolina. ``And this is a crummy
laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heath wasn't really complaining. After all, he's on the road
making his high-energy, revved-up, all-out rockabilly-based music
with Jimbo Wallace thumping the upright bass and Scott Churilla
pounding the drums.
</P>
<P>
   The trio is touring with a new album, ``Spend a Night in the
Box,'' on the Time Bomb label.
</P>
<P>
   The Reverend Horton Heat is based in Dallas. Heath spent the
first six years of his life in San Antonio and grew up in Corpus
Christi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived around the corner from this record store,'' he said.
``I could go over there and get blues stuff. I had some cousins who
liked to play music. That made me want to play. Then I started
seeing the Beatles and the Rolling Stones and Johnny Cash on
television and I really wanted to play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Reverend started recording in the early 1990s on
labels ranging from Sub Pop to Interscope to Time Bomb, the group
has played stripped-down music that bears more than a passing
resemblance to real-deal rockabilly but because of its energy and
attitude, also has attracted a large punk contingent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Reverend Horton Heat started, it was a solo thing,''
Heath said. ``It was rockabilly and bluesy, but the main audience
was punk/rock kids. I could have made some money playing blues, but
the alternative scene was more fun. It was nothing conscious. We
tried to be more authentic, but we decided that's been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Could this music have come from anywhere but Texas? Heath
laughed for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm pretty proud of the fact we do sound like we come
from Texas,'' he said. ``There are some pretty great players from
all over the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath describes the Reverend Horton Heat as a rockabilly band
that plays original music. The tunes on ``Spend a Night in the
Box'' were all penned by Heath save for one number that's a
Heath/Churilla effort. Heath loves the writing part of his gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my deal,'' he said. ``I write a lot of songs. Sometimes
I have to slow down because it confuses things. If I write 30 songs
and demo them, record labels like the ones that least sound like us
and that can change the whole theme.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath and those involved in the business end of music have not
always seen eye-to-eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at labels are always saying, `I love what you do. Let
me change you.' They try too hard to control the artist. But what
can you expect when all radio stations are owned by one person? We
just want to do our best and make our music,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides releasing a string of albums and living on the tour
road, Heath and the band have turned in an acting stint on ``The
Drew Carey Show.'' Heath also has appeared on the television show
``Homicide: Life on the Street'' and in the movie ``Love and a
.45.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Jim Beal Jr. by e-mail at jbeal(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
