<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9597 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-RAILROAD-PARK-HNS &LR;      05-30 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILROAD-PARK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS RAIL PARK TAKES PASSENGERS BACK IN TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: With: RAILROAD-GLOSSARY   
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RON HENRY STRAIT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSK, Texas _ Blair Lavell has been working on the railroad, in
one capacity or another, for more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   He has bought, sold and traded freight and passenger cars. He
once made a $1 deal for a 224-ton locomotive to save it from the
scrap-iron heap. He has built an inventory of old railroad cars and
a network of informants who keep him posted on the disposition of
others on their way to salvage yards. He saves what he can and
stores them here in his train maintenance yard.
</P>
<P>
   As a mechanical superintendent with the Texas Parks and Wildlife
Department, Lavell oversees 18 staffers and the collection of
nearly four dozen cars and operating steam locomotives that
comprise the Texas State Railroad, which operates between this
sleepy town and Palestine, 25 miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
   The Rusk and Palestine depots, as well as the miles of track and
low bridges that join them, comprise the Texas State Railroad State
Historical Park, 150 miles north of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The park, under manager Curtis Pruett, accommodates more than
200,000 visitors a year. Most of them come to admire and be a part
of the living legacy of railway history that Lavell has assembled.
</P>
<P>
   The state-owned railroad has operated since the original tracks
were laid in 1896. The first five miles linked the town of North
Rusk to an iron foundry operated by the state prison.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, iron ore and wood rolled to the penitentiary
smelter, and iron rolled out. In 1907, the Legislature authorized
extending the tracks to Palestine, and the Texas State Railroad
reached its present length.
</P>
<P>
   The prison foundry closed in 1913. The railroad operated for a
few years before deficits began to mount and the state was forced
to lease the line to forest-products haulers as part of the Texas
and New Orleans Railroad in late 1921.
</P>
<P>
   Private operators kept the short line leased until the early
1970s. When no new tenants took the railroad, the Legislature in
1972 turned the facility over to the Texas Parks and Wildlife
Department for conversion to a hike-and-bike trail. The 76-year-old
railroad itself was headed for the scrap heap.
</P>
<P>
   Railroad buffs, however, had different ideas. They stepped in
and persuaded the state to rehabilitate the line and run it as a
recreational passenger service, complete with vintage cars and
turn-of-the-century steam locomotives.
</P>
<P>
   The call went out for old cars and locomotives. The good old
days were about to return.
</P>
<P>
   The state historical park opened in 1977, with depots at each
end. Today, the railroad carries paying passengers on the
three-hour round trip between the two stations.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad has gained wider attention, too, as the bright
lights of Hollywood have come to visit often. Lavell's efforts to
assemble a collection of authentic steam railroad artifacts,
coupled with the area's rustic setting, has resulted in more than
20 movies, television programs and commercials being filmed on the
railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the parks in the state park system, the Texas State
Railroad park is unusual in the way it presents itself to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   While most historical exhibits are, by necessity, of the ``look,
don't touch'' variety, the state railroad is a ``climb aboard, move
around, bring the family and a picnic lunch'' kind of place.
</P>
<P>
   Because only steam engines run on the railroad, Lavell and his
crew work full time keeping the century-old iron horses ready to
run. Most of the time, they do it without instruction manuals.
</P>
<P>
   The four active locomotives undergo constant inspections.
Because of the age of the machinery, Lavell's machinists,
pipefitters and carpenters use their experiences to stay ahead of
most problems and maintain the engines and cars to federal
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The four locomotives date from the 1910s and earlier, when they
served to pull troop trains, heavy freight and passengers around
the United States. Lavell cares for a fifth locomotive, the Lima
No. 610, known as the Amon Carter Jr.
</P>
<P>
   At 224 tons, the engine is too large for use on the state
railroad. The cab stands more than 15 feet off the ground, and the
drivers _ the big wheels that push the engine along _ are nearly 4
feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Through Lavell's efforts and the help of railroad enthusiasts,
the magnificent No. 610 was bought at auction for $1 and moved to a
specially prepared shed at the Palestine Depot.
</P>
<P>
   As grand as the Lima locomotive is, engine No. 400 is more
typical of the railroad's efforts to represent the golden days of
steam locomotion.
</P>
<P>
   Made in 1917, the Baldwin No. 400 locomotive weighs 87 tons,
with a wheel configuration known as 2-8-2. The ``8'' refers to the
number of driver wheels, with two support wheels forward of the
drivers near the cow catcher and two others behind the drivers
supporting the cab. By comparison, the massive Lima No. 610 is a
2-10-4.
</P>
<P>
   Under the skilled handling of engineer Roger Graham and fireman
Martin Lazcano, Engine No. 400 can pull 300 tons of passengers and
cars from a dead stop to 25 mph and back to a stop, with barely a
bump in between.
</P>
<P>
   Although they keep a close eye on the gauges, a lot of what the
two men do in the locomotive cab is done by feel, letting off
steam, pouring on the fuel and fine-tuning the throttle in
anticipation of an incline or a stop.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Lazcano worked their way up through the railroad
ranks from helpers to hostlers, to life in the cab where the action
is. Now they watch the track ahead through narrow-slat windows and
roll with the rhythm of the rails.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is in charge. He controls the throttle, sounds the
whistle and constantly balances the engine's needs with gentle taps
from a gloved hand on a half-dozen knobs and handles.
</P>
<P>
   Lazcano fuels the diesel fire to keep the boiler steaming at
peak performance. He rings the bell, turns valves and, at one
point, has to climb out on the catwalk, nine-pound hammer in hand,
to adjust a disagreeable fitting.
</P>
<P>
   They are a team, using nods, hand signals and one-word sentences
to keep order in the smoky, noisy chaos of the cab and deliver a
smooth ride to the passengers behind them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For passengers, the ride is much more pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger cars have slide-open windows. On warm days, riders
experience the feel of the Piney Woods as the train rumbles along,
the cadence of the rails mixing with smoke from the boiler fire and
the clang of the big brass bell.
</P>
<P>
   The whistle screams at every crossing, and anyone standing near
the track gets a thousand waves from passengers as the train rolls
by.
</P>
<P>
   Trains roll from each end of the line at 11 a.m. and meet
half-way at the Mewshaw Siding. From June 1-July 30, the trains run
Thursday through Sunday. In the spring and fall, the trains run
weekends only.
</P>
<P>
   There are special runs for school groups in October and April.
The park also offers a nighttime run on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular time to make the trip is during the cool
months, when the East Texas humidity and temperatures are more
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The park also offers special-event days, such as the recent
presentation by the Texas Military Historical Society's of military
paraphernalia from colonial Texas through the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Call the park, 800-442-8951, for schedules and information on
special-event days.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9601 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-RAILROAD-GLOSSARY-HNS     05-30 0263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILROAD-GLOSSARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RAILROADING: WHAT IT ALL MEANS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some commonly used terms in railroading:
</P>
<P>
   Ballast: The fist-sized rocks that support and surround the ties
and rails to keep them from shifting and to keep them off the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Cow-catcher: The low-set grill at the front end of the
locomotive. Positioned just inches off the rail, it clears minor
debris off the rails.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers: The large wheels under the locomotive. They are linked
by drive rods to the steam pistons and are what actually set the
train in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Engineer: The person in charge of the locomotive. He sets train
speed by use of a hand throttle and sounds the whistle to warn of
train movement.
</P>
<P>
   Fireman: The person in charge of tending the fire and keeping
the pressure up in the boiler.
</P>
<P>
   High ball: When the passengers, baggage and mail are loaded, the
train is ready to high ball, or leave the station, thus the old
phrase, ``Let's high ball it out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostler: The person who tends the locomotive between runs, such
as when it's in the train yard.
</P>
<P>
   Sand dome: Atop the long boiler in front of the engineer's cabin
sit two domes. The forward dome is the sand dome. It contains
fine-grit sand that can be released directly onto the rails in
front of the driver wheels to increase traction.
</P>
<P>
   Steam dome: The other dome atop the boiler is the steam dome. It
contains a valve that the engineer adjusts to release more or less
steam and set the train's speed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
