<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AT 71, SHE IS THE MATRIARCH OF THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The most unusual place to find a grandmother and
mother of four, nursing a broken rib, would be 25 miles out at sea,
captaining a 50-foot sportfishing vessel looking for salmon.
</P>
<P>
   That is where you will find Jacqueline Douglas, the first
professional female skipper on the Pacific Coast, running her boat
seven days a week from Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Yet perhaps even more unusual is where you can find her
daughter, Diana Fischer. Married and a mom as well, she was
recently elected the first female commodore in the 114-year history
of the once all-male Corinthian Yacht Club of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   This mother-daughter team _ Douglas, 71, of San Francisco,
skipper of the party boat Wacky Jacky, and her daughter, Fisher,
51, the new Corinthian commodore _ are about as far removed from
being crusty salts as the North Pole is from the South Pole. They
are refined, intelligent, accomplished at their crafts, and have
not only won the respect of their peers, but their friendships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't believe I'm doing this,'' Douglas said while at
sea recently, still recovering from a rib broken in a fall. ``I get
on the ocean and I don't believe I'm me.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, married 52 years to George Douglas, first got the idea
of buying a party boat in the early 1970s when she was in her 40s.
By that time, she had already attracted considerable attention by
being Queen of the San Francisco 49ers on opening day in 1946 at
Kezar Stadium. After that she took time off, got married and raised
her four daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a customer on the old Carrie in the 1950s, going salmon
fishing, and never did I think about doing this, running a party
boat,'' Douglas said. She bought a boat, the New Florie S, in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   She took the Coast Guard operator tests, finagled a business
loan, and then opened business at Fisherman's Wharf. She was not an
overnight success. In fact, Douglas was initially spurned by many
old-timers in the Golden Gate Fleet, and many longtime fishermen
were suspicious of her intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't understand why a woman was doing this,'' Douglas
said. ``But I didn't care what anybody thought. I was so thrilled
by my job that I was blind to the friction about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband remembers how he was even confronted several times
at the dock and asked, ``What the hell does she think she's
doing?''
</P>
<P>
   But in the next few years, a funny thing happened. People who
went fishing with her found they were having a great time, and were
going home with salmon as well. It turns out that Douglas is a
great angler who has mastered her craft _ captains call the ocean
``an open book,'' and Douglas ``knows how to read the book'' _ and
her scores over the years have ranked high among all boats on the
Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   One recent day, for instance, she did it yet again, guiding a
group of 13 aboard her boat to southwest of Half Moon Bay. The
fishermen caught 26 salmon, limits for all aboard, with retired
skipper Taylor McGee, 81, catching a 17-pounder. Douglas runs one
of the most popular and successful operations in the Golden Gate
Fleet, supported by a wide-ranging clientele.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they board my boat, I want them to feel like they are
walking into my living room,'' Douglas said. ``And I love the
ocean, all the rhythms and experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Douglas has become an excellent naturalist, often finding and
describing seabirds, marine mammals and many ocean anomalies to her
customers. Her popularity is documented in the numbers: In the past
27 years, Douglas has taken an estimated 120,000 people from all
over the world fishing out the Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   When Douglas started, her oldest daughter, Diana, was paying
close attention. She went fishing as a teen-ager. She seemed to
have a natural attraction to the sea, just like her mom. As time
passed _ after she married, became Diana Fischer and had a child _
she found herself always around the water. She and her husband, Ed
Fischer, eventually bought a sailboat, a 27-foot Catalina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started at a very young age with my parents taking us to
Santa Cruz for the summer, living on the beach, going down and
swimming in the Pacific every day,'' Fischer said. ``This past
Sunday, I was just out on the Bay again, and just being on the
water, there's something energizing about it. I feel it at the
yacht club all the time, the vistas of the Bay, my love of San
Francisco, and it fills me up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
