   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, May 31:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Lisbon) _ The last time a U.S. president was in
Portugal, in 1985, the two big issues were trade disputes and
missile defense. As Clinton arrived there Tuesday for a weeklong
trip in Europe, the two big issues were again trade disputes and
missile defense. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-POLITICS (Miami) _ The party of former President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide has won control of Haiti's Senate, according
to partial returns from the elections last week. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-U.S. (Washington) _ On the U.S. response to the re-election
of President Alberto Fujimori of Peru. By Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ENTREPRENEUR (Shanghai) _ China's best known private
entrepreneur, Mou Qizhong, was sentenced Tuesday to life in prison
for fraud. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH (Bint Jabil) _ In southern Lebanon, Hezbollah
is beginning to provide municipal services much as a government
would. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-POLITICS (Paris) _ More corruption investigations are
underway at the Paris city hall, where 15 politicians have been
placed under judicial investigation for ballot stuffing in 1989,
when President Jacques Chirac was Paris mayor. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A roundup: The Supreme Court agrees to
take a second case on the Clean Air Act, this one that raises the
question of whether the act requires federal government to justify
any regulations with a cost-benefit analysis. In addition, the
Supreme Court takes a dispute between Virginia and Maryland over
water rights to the Potomac. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MILITARY (Denver) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is scheduled
to discuss military readiness with a group of veterans here. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ENVIRON (Milwaukee) _ Vice President Al Gore gives an
environmental speech. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ORE-ADOPT (Seattle) _ In Oregon, adoptees gain access to their
birth certificates on Tuesday under the state's 1998 adoption law.
By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   LA-WOMAN-SLAIN (Los Angeles) _ The granddaughter of Police Chief
Bernard Parks was shot to death in a restaurant parking lot by
gunman who was apparently aiming for her friend. By Barbara
Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   GEOGRAPHY-GENDER-GAP (New York) _ There were no girl finalists
at the National Geographic bee last week. The disparity reveals a
gender gap on geography that researchers have conflicting opinions
about. But it may say something about why men so stubbornly refuse
to ask for directions. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COWS-COPYRIGHT (New York) _ Remember those painted fiberglass
cows that will soon be distributed around New York City? They have
brought charges of copyright theft and corporate espionage. And
they have turned into a major embarrassment for the Swiss
government. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LABS-ASIANS (Undated) _ The Association of Asian Americans
Studies, a group representing 700 scholars, becomes the second
Asian American education group to urge scientists of Asian heritage
to boycott the national weapons labs. By James Glanz. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   UNITED-USAIR (Undated) _ Following developments in the deal
between United and US Airways. By Laurence Zuckerman and Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-CROSS-OWNERSHIP (Washington) _ As part of a congressionally
mandated biennial review, the Federal Communications Commission
makes recommendations about rules governing a number of important
broadcast ownership rules, including cross-ownership limits of
broadcast and newspaper properties in a single market. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   SARA-LEE (Undated) _ Sara Lee plans to sell some of it
businesses, including the leather company Coach and athletic
apparel maker Champion, to focus on food and beverages, intimates
and household products.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TELECOMS (London) _ A look at what comes next in the
rapidly changing European telecommunications market with the
acquisition of Orange of Britain by France Telecom. The new Orange
combines France Telecom's mobile operations with the British
business, and will continue to led by the Orange management team,
who have been highly praised by analysts. Plus the Vodafone
Airtouch earnings report. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S.-TELECOM (Tokyo) _ Senior members of the ruling party
have been pressing NTT to agree to a sharp cut in its network
access fees in order to end a stalemate on talks over
telecommunications deregulation between the U.S. and Japan. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NICE-BOSSES (Undated) _ Remember Chainsaw Al? Being a tough guy
might have worked a decade ago, when corporate America was
downsizing and laying off workers by the millions. But the day of
the chief executive who boasts about how many jobs he cuts to
bolster his company's stock price is over. With unemployment at a
30-year low, bosses realize that they have to do more than pay good
salaries and lavish perks on their employees if they want to keep
them. They also have to be nice to them. By Amy Zipkin.
</P>
<P>
   SLADE-BOSS (Undated) _ John H. Slade, 92, honorary chairman of
the executive committee, BearStearns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krugman's ``Reckonings'' and Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties.''
</P>
