<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCER-FANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOCCER HAS NO SHORTAGE OF PLAYERS, BUT WHITHER THE FANS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is a mystery that defies easy explanation.
Somehow, millions of soccer players have vanished without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 18 million men and women play soccer in this
country. Add to that impressive number the millions who have
participated in the sport since the soccer boom began 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet professional Major League Soccer (MLS), which is played in
12 U.S. cities, is averaging only 14,000 fans a game, well below
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you the reason, because I've thought the same
thing: Where the hell are they?'' Steve Negoesco, coach of the
University of San Francisco soccer team, said of the fans. ``For
the last 20 years, you've had youth soccer. In Northern California,
you've got 150,000 kids playing every year. And they get older and
older. And every year you get 20,000 to 30,000 graduating from
youth soccer. We should have no room in the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, there were bold predictions that it would take one
generation for the United States to embrace the most popular sport
on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence supposedly was there for anyone to see: Johnny and
Judy, driven to and from practice by their soccer moms, happily
kicked a ball instead of hitting, passing, or shooting it.
</P>
<P>
   So when Johnny and Judy and their friends grew up, Babe Ruth
would be knocked off his pedestal. It was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Only it never happened. The three major sports in this country
still are football, baseball and basketball. Hockey is a solid
fourth. Soccer, meanwhile, is barely a blip on the national sports
radar _ save for one-time-only events like last year's Women's
World Cup, when the U.S. team won the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Woodring, who played professionally in Germany and Denmark
before returning to the United States to play in the MLS, retired
two years ago at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is back in Marin County, Calif., working full-time in
financial management. He coaches youth soccer in his spare time and
remains devoted to the game. It remains a passion.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have an easy answer for why his generation played the
sport but won't pay to watch it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the ultimate question: Why aren't these stadiums full,
or at least more full?'' Woodring said. ``Part of it is all the
other things people have going on. Soccer is not a tradition in
this country. In other countries, it's a priority to watch their
teams play. We have too many other sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there are people who really love the game but don't find
this league attractive. It's too slow. They go once and don't
return. The avid soccer person will continue to follow the European
leagues because they are the elite.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys may play soccer while they are young, but as they get
older, the pressure becomes more intense for them to begin to play
traditional sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school, soccer wasn't in the mainstream,'' said John
Doyle, 34, an American who played soccer in Europe. ``A lot of good
athletes were lost to other sports. In high school, it's a
challenge not to play football, if only because the guys who play
football are around the cheerleaders and are more popular.''
</P>
<P>
   The pool of athletes shrinks, especially in the inner city. And
the remaining players, Negoesco contends, are not being coached in
a way that is conducive to producing world-class players who could
fill stadiums in this country.
</P>
<P>
   They are, he said, under pressure to win because parents ``don't
know the game. `What did you guys do today? We lost. Again?' So the
coach has to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The top U.S. players who persevere in the sport inevitably face
a new temptation, Negoesco said. They go to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle disagrees with the notion that an inferior brand of soccer
is being foisted on the public by the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's very unfair, actually,'' he said. ``I did play
in Europe at the highest level. Is the MLS as good as Bayren
Munich, Real Madrid or Manchester United? No. But those teams cost
millions upon millions of dollars to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``But look at what DC United did. They won a tournament
involving all of Mexico and Central America. And then they won a
tournament against all of South America, including Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say it's not good soccer, that's someone who's not
watching. The quality of the league is good. And the players are
getting better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Meterparel, the 31-year-old general manager of the
Earthquakes in San Jose, Calif., vigorously disputes that something
is wrong with the American pro league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sport that is growing,'' she said. ``We're in our
fifth year of existence now. This was not supposed to be an
overnight success. This is something that is going to build over
10, 15, 20 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
