<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-U.S.-TELECOM-62     05-30 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-TELECOM-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL MAY BE NEAR TO OPEN JAPAN'S PHONE MARKET AND COUNTER U.S.
CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Speculation is increasing among some informed Japanese
that a deal may be in the works to end a stalemate in talks between
Japan and the United States on telecommunications deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications executives and politicians have been saying
for the last week that senior members of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party, notably Hiromu Nonaka _ who is nominally the
party's secretary-general but practically the reigning kingmaker in
Japanese politics _ are pressing Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Corp. to agree to a sharp cut in fees that competing carriers must
pay to use its local network.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has dominated the deregulation talks because NTT
controls 99 percent of the lines that connect directly to Japanese
homes and offices. The price charged to use those lines is critical
to opening the telecommunications market here.
</P>
<P>
   At current rates, about 40 percent of the revenues of competing
carriers is used for fees paid to NTT, according to the Ministry of
Posts and Telecommunications, which regulates the market.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has threatened to take the matter to the World
Trade Organization. The threat carries special weight in Japan,
which is hosting a summit meeting of world leaders in July.
Japanese officials are working to ensure that the meeting, which
President Clinton will attend, will be as uneventful as a noh
theatrical performance, in which an actor can take half an hour to
cross the stage.
</P>
<P>
   A potential trade war runs counter to that goal. Thus even
politicians sympathetic to NTT, which has tremendous political
clout thanks to its legions of employees and strong trade union,
are trying to coax the former telephone monopoly to concede some
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Even the normally conservative Fair Trade Commission is
reportedly on the brink of publishing a report saying that Nippon
Telegraph's reorganization last year failed to enhance competition
in the telecommunications market here and urging sharper cuts in
access fees, according to the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading
business daily.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts worry that in exchange for such a concession,
NTT would be given even more power than it already has, which could
further hamper competition in Japan. Executives at competing
carriers, Japanese businessmen and politicians suspect that Nonaka
and other senior politicians are promising the telecommunications
firm that they will push for a sweeping revision of the restrictive
law governing its activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a move afoot to drastically revise, or even abolish
the NTT law,'' said Kei Hata, a member of the upper house of
parliament who is becoming one of the most vocal critics of the
government's regulation of Nippon Telegraph. ``I myself favor an
abolishment of the law, but only after we have secured conditions
for free and fair competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Hata and many others say those conditions do not yet exist in
Japan. Abolishing the NTT law would open the door for NTT East and
NTT West, the two regional fixed-line phone companies in the NTT
family, to provide long distance and international service. Many
worry that with the advantages of NTT's deep pockets and existing
technology, they would wipe out competitors that are only just
beginning to secure a toehold in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to think more about the implications of changing the
law,'' Hata said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has proposed cutting the fees the company charges
competing carriers by 22.5 percent over four years, saying further
cuts would damage NTT.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, however, wants immediate cuts of 41.1 percent
and contends that the telecommunications ministry is enabling NTT
to avoid a far-reaching overhaul of its business.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NTT's recent financial performance, which was far better than
the company had projected, undercut its contention that it would be
crippled by cuts of the magnitude demanded by the United States.
Both NTT East and NTT West vastly outperformed the expectations of
their parent company, which has given even NTT's supporters cause
to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Junichiro Miyazu, NTT's president, has not furthered his
company's cause by saying he could not explain the markedly better
performance. His insistence that declining profitability at the two
regional carriers was a trend also rang somewhat hollow against the
backdrop of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earnings of the regional carriers improved,'' Eita
Yashiro, the minister of posts and telecommunications, said at a
press conference Tuesday. ``It's very different from the initial
projections.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of that, Yashiro said, his agency would consider the
reduction in interconnection fees it has proposed, as well as the
proposed timetable for achieving those reductions.
</P>
</TEXT>
