<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC HOPES ARE RAISED BY ULSTER PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTRUSH, Northern Ireland _ Standing on the tee of the par-3,
cliff-hugging 14th hole at Royal Portrush Golf Club, overlooking a
foreboding 200-yard stretch aptly named ``Calamity,'' Dennis Ryan
abruptly stepped away from his ball and turned to gaze out over a
majestic piece of the North Antrim coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christ,'' he whispered, almost to himself, ``it's so beautiful
here. Why in God's name do people fight over this place?''
</P>
<P>
   As Northern Ireland and its people are gradually but inexorably
seduced by normality, it is finally becoming possible for those who
live here to realize what they have, and why the current peace
process is the only game in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people here realize just how good they have it
here,'' said Ryan, an investment banker from Tipperary who lives in
Toronto. ``There is a very high standard of living, a beautiful
countryside. Please, God, let's hope they can get it together and
really bring peace to this place, because once they do, there's no
stopping this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan is not the only one with money at his disposal who believes
that Northern Ireland is poised to become known for its booming
economy rather than its booming bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Without the strong backing of the business community here, the
Ulster Unionist Party would not have decided on Saturday to resume
a power-sharing government with Sinn Fein, the Irish Republican
Army's political wing.
</P>
<P>
   George Quigley, the chairman of Ulster Bank, was among many
business leaders who worked behind the scenes, persuading unionists
to put aside their hatred and suspicions of the IRA for the sake of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   While news accounts have focused on the narrow margin of victory
that Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble was able to secure on
Saturday, 53 to 47 percent, those accounts often fail to note that
the 860-member Ulster Unionist council, the party's ruling body, is
more hard-line than the middle-class Protestants who make up the
party itself, Northern Ireland's largest.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order, a Protestant fraternal organization that
stages some 3,000 parades each year, is outraged that the new
arrangements in Northern Ireland will deny it a chance to march
through Catholic neighborhoods where it is not wanted. Members say
they march to express their cultural identity. But Catholics see
the marches as bigoted triumphalism, a way for intolerant
Protestants to remind them of their place in a society described by
one prime minister as ``a Protestant state for a Protestant
people.''
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of the places on the Ulster Unionist's ruling
council are allocated to Orange Order members, a built-in minority
opposed to the power-sharing ethos of the Good Friday Agreement of
1998, the blueprint for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, an Orangeman himself, has said he wants to sever the
official links between his party and the Orange Order, but doing so
would probably provoke a huge split.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the de facto spilt within the party was in full display
Saturday as angry delegates stormed out of the Waterfront Hall in
Belfast, denouncing Trimble as the latest traitor to Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   While proclaiming himself to be a democrat, Willie Thompson, a
British parliamentarian and a vehement opponent of the Good Friday
Agreement, said he saw no contradiction in refusing to accept the
will of the majority of his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to fight,'' Thompson said, ``until Trimble
and this agreement are finished.''
</P>
<P>
   While petty politics and promising cooperation continue to
flourish simultaneously, most ordinary people simply get on with
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Homer Murphy, a building consultant from Warrenpoint who will
give you a finger-pointing lecture if you call him by his real
first name, Seamus, went to Casement Park in Belfast on Sunday with
his old friend Dennis Moynihan, a retired banker, to take in the
soccer match between Antrim and Down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day, isn't it?'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy had close friends from both sides of the divide who were
murdered. Ivan Toombes, a Protestant, was shot dead by the IRA.
Edmund Woolsey, a Catholic, was blown up.
</P>
<P>
   So, sitting in the sunshine of Casement Park was a treat, even
when, as is common here, the sky turned dark and hail and rain
poured down on the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up Down!'' Murphy yelled, cheering on County Down with the
ultimate contradiction in terms.
</P>
<P>
   But you would hardly find a Protestant in Casement Park, where
Gaelic games are played. In Northern Ireland, Protestants and
Catholics have their own separate sports. Catholics play Irish
football and hurling, while the women play camogie, a Gaelic mix of
hurling and field hockey. Protestants play soccer and rugby. That
is changing, but slowly.
</P>
<P>
   When a Catholic soccer team in West Belfast tried to play a team
from the Royal Ulster Constabulary last year, Sinn Fein organized a
protest that led to the game being canceled.
</P>
<P>
   While sports tend to bring people of different backgrounds
together, here they are just another way for people to focus on
their differences.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a tendency here in the north of Ireland to focus on
the negative. By any measure, life has improved. As Trimble
reminded his party on Saturday, last year was the first in 30 that
no member of the Royal Ulster Constabulary or the British Army was
killed in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   That, in this place, is progress.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the 18th fairway of Royal Portrush, the most
stunning course on the island of Ireland, Dennis Ryan took a 5-iron
and prepared to make his approach shot. Again, he turned away, took
one last glance at the coast and said something that people might
remind themselves of in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' he said, ``to be alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
