<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-COMMENCEMENT-     05-30 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COMMENCEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL COLLEGE SCORES A GRADUATION COUP: CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week from Saturday, Bill Clinton will don a cap
and gown for the last time in his presidency and deliver the
commencement address at little Carleton College in Northfield,
Minn.
</P>
<P>
   How he ended up there is a story _ and a bit of a mystery _ in
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for commencement addresses is a process rivaled only by
the preparation for the president's annual State of the Union
address. It begins months before graduation ceremonies unfold
across the country, as White House aides contemplate what Clinton
should say and where he should say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commencement speeches are one of the best chances a president
has to speak at length about a serious topic and not be guided or
constrained by the needs of an audience or the brevity you have to
have in the Rose Garden,'' said Michael Waldman, Clinton's former
chief speechwriter and an adjunct faculty member at the Kennedy
School of Government at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president especially enjoys schools that are a little more
off the beaten path,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Carleton, where on June 10, Clinton will
address the 423 graduates. The private liberal arts school, founded
in 1866, has never had a major commencement speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a phone call from the White House telling us President
Clinton was considering places to give his speech and would we be
interested in having the president visit,'' said Marla Holt, a
spokeswoman for Carleton College.
</P>
<P>
   During that call in early April, school officials were told that
if they were interested in having Clinton speak, they should invite
him.
</P>
<P>
   They did, and he accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Governor Jesse Ventura, a spokesman said, can't claim
credit for that coup, nor could the state's senior senator, Paul D.
Wellstone, a Democrat who taught political science at Carleton for
21 years before becoming a member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were informed after the fact,'' Ventura spokesman John
Wodele said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy they got him, but Wellstone wasn't involved,''
said Jim Farrell, the senator's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   One person who extolled the virtues of Carleton _ though White
House aides say it was after the school made Clinton's short list _
was Thomas Freedman, a senior adviser to the president and a 1985
graduate of Carleton.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, White House aides say, no one is sure exactly how
Clinton settled on Carleton.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cabinet officers pushing their favorite policy themes for
Clinton's State of the Union address, aides early in the year begin
promoting topics Clinton might want to explore for commencement and
schools where he might want to explore them.
</P>
<P>
   Aides sort through dozens of invitations from schools; in 1993,
the year Boston's Northeastern University was chosen, there were no
fewer that 200. Northeastern's prospects were boosted by personal
lobbying from such Bay Staters as Senator Edward M. Kennedy and
former governor Michael Dukakis. It didn't hurt that Massachusetts
handed Clinton one of the largest margins of victory over President
George Bush in the 1992 election.
</P>
<P>
   Geography is a factor in the selection, current and former White
House aides say, and so are Clinton's connections to a particular
school or promises he may have made to speak at a graduation.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Clinton chose New Hampshire Technical College
in Stratham for the first commencement address of his presidency,
he was making good on a promise to Greg Fuller, a student he met
while campaigning in the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, Clinton delivers three commencement addresses,
except in 1994, when he gave two plus the convocation at the
University of California at Los Angeles. Of the three speeches each
year, one is always at a military academy, chosen on a rotating
basis. Last year, he spoke to graduates at the US Air Force Academy
in Colorado Springs. On May 17, Clinton spoke at the US Coast Guard
Academy in New London, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a service academy, Clinton speaks at one private
college and one public university. ``He likes to go not just to the
Harvards and the Yales, but he will ask specifically to go to some
of the smaller schools,'' White House deputy press secretary Jake
Siewert said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Clinton has never delivered a commencement address at
Harvard or Yale. But Princeton served as the backdrop in 1996 for
Clinton to summon the spirit of the post-World War II GI Bill in
proposing a $1,500 tax credit to help the impoverished, and many
from the middle class, go to college. Congress later enacted the
Hope Scholarship program into law.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing, the
president used a commencement speech at Michigan State University,
located near a training site for militant antigovernment groups, to
admonish militia groups. It was where he uttered one of the more
memorable lines of his presidency: ``You can't love your country
and hate your government.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in 1997, the diverse campus at the University of California
at San Diego was the site for his call for America to deal with its
racial problem, a speech given shortly after the state had passed
an antiaffirmative action ballot initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some years, he goes in with an eye toward making news . . . or
to put himself in the middle of a news event,'' Siewert said.
``Sometimes what he says might not make headlines the next day, but
will stand up very well historically.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldman said Clinton agonizes over those speeches. ``He spends a
lot of time rewriting, poring over his own words and ideas, so you
can learn a lot about what is on his mind by what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   The frequency of Clinton's commencement addresses contrasts with
his two predecessors, though in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan gave only one commencement address a year, or
eight during his presidency _ four of them at military academies
and one at his alma mater, Eureka College in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was a comparative chatterbox, speaking at 20 college and
military commencements in just four years, compared with Clinton's
23 speeches in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Commencement speeches are a ``big showcase'' for presidents,
Waldman said. And for Clinton, whose speechwriters look for
thematic threads each year to link the addresses, that's especially
true. ``If you look at all the commencement speeches throughout his
term,'' Waldman said, ``they really do tell a story of his
presidency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-30 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY IS QUIETLY SETTING NEW AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ Here are some numbers you are unlikely to hear
discussed in the current mad dash to the ``center'' in national
politics. They come courtesy of Senator Edward M. Kennedy and form
the ingredients for what needs to become a national preoccupation
once the desultory presidential campaign is history.
</P>
<P>
   Between the end of the 1970s, when double-digit inflation had
the economy in a vise, and the mid-1990s, just before the current,
unprecedented expansion began to accelerate significantly, the
earnings of typical 25- to 34-year-olds who had never finished high
school fell by nearly a third.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period the earnings of people who had graduated
from four-year colleges shot up by a 133 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Working full time, year-round, at the minimum wage with not a
single day of vacation is a guarantee of abject poverty. You would
earn just under $11,000, or $3,500 below the poverty line for a
family of three, $6,300 below it for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Women continue to take in just 73 cents for every dollar earned
by a man. In terms of women of color, the figures are 63 percent
for an African-American, 53 cents for a Latina.
</P>
<P>
   The wage gap in terms of jobs of comparable worth is large and
growing. It deprives the average women $4,200 in income annually,
and the figure swells to $420,000 over a career. Wage inequality
costs the US economy as well as victimized females some $200
billion a year. If pay equity existed, poverty rates in the United
States would drop by more than half.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers exist after a record-setting economic expansion.
The fact is that the expansion hasn't begun to have an impact on
the earnings of average working families, much less the poor. When
Bill Clinton ran for president eight years ago, he declared
full-time employment at poverty wages an enemy, but it has proved a
durable one.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy in just the last week has twice zeroed in on what ought
to be the outrage of low-wage employment, meaning that
progressivism's most reliable leading indicator is once again
moving to define what should be on the country's next page. The
first instance was at his commencement appearance at Bentley
College; the second was at a meeting here that brought together
organizations as disparate as the Ford and Rockefeller foundations,
the AFL-CIO, and the National Association of Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's agenda is not radical. It starts with raising the
minimum wage, a goal that still eludes a gridlocked Congress. It
may be a familiar fight, but the fact remains that it is the
quickest way to lift 10 million workers stuck at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Investment in education and training is another way. Kennedy is
backing the front lines of this struggle _ the country's community
colleges _ as well as business-city partnerships and the public
schools themselves. Anyone who can manage at least a couple of
years schooling beyond high school is almost certain to end up
above the median in income. And no progress will be made in these
critical areas if precious resources are wasted on cutting the top
rates of income tax; we can either indulge ourselves or address the
country's unmet needs in a time of plenty. The fiscal resources do
not exist to do both.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that the best economic stimulus program would be to
put a fair wage in the pockets of the women currently being denied
one, Kennedy is pushing a long-overdue toughening of existing law
to ban wage discrimination affecting workers in equivalent jobs in
the same workplace and a toughening of remedies for women denied
equal pay.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also asserts that the landmark Family and Medical Leave
Act of seven years ago needs to be nudged beyond its present
guarantees of unpaid leave. He thinks it's time for responsibly
managed paid leave.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy notes that several states are already studying or
acting, including New Hampshire and Vermont, where the state Senate
recently passed legislation allowing its citizens to collect
unemployment compensation during parental leave; a similar
initiative has been introduced in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The monster gap that remains is health insurance. As Kennedy has
noted, lack of it is now the seventh-ranking ``and most
preventable'' of all causes of death in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Like Al Gore, Kennedy is a committed incrementalist, but there
are signs that he is beginning to think about a blueprint for
national health insurance that would include all the interim steps
that need to be taken to reach it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Massachusetts political world is focused on the
ballot access soap opera of a possible opponent to Kennedy this
fall or on elevating the state's Libertarian Party to a status it
has never earned from the voters.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, it's more interesting to focus on what Kennedy himself
is thinking and doing, because it always has far more relevance to
the state's working families.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
