<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9653 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CAPE-HOMELESS-ART-BOS     05-30 1657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPE-HOMELESS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CAPE FEAR: NO HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREWSTER, Mass. _ She waits on tables eight hours a day. She is
a soccer mom and a softball mom, proud of children who get A's in
school and she's usually there to help a mother who is ill. She
drives a station wagon and has the confident, sporty features of a
woman who probably turns a few heads when she drives through town.
</P>
<P>
   And she is homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Susan O'Donnell, more than four years without a permanent
residence, is living at a campsite in Nickerson State Park with her
three daughters. O'Donnell doesn't drink, she doesn't smoke, and
says she's too proud to accept public assistance. She earns $21,000
a year and much praise from managers at the Homeport Restaurant in
Orleans, where she has worked, with only a few days off, for the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear? Yes, sometimes the darkness scares me,'' the 39-year-old
mother explained the other night, seated in a lawn chair she had
salvaged from a dumpster and repaired. Only a hint of Thursday's
light remained on the western horizon, the kerosene lantern was not
yet lit. ``Mostly I fear that this won't end. I try so hard to be
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The O'Donnells and, by one homeless agency count last year, 67
other families _ including 122 children _ on quaint old Cape Cod
are caught in an affordable housing vacuum. Cape officials say
they've never seen it so severe. The homeless are doubled up with
other families, or living in cars or tents. This year, the
caseloads are running about 30 ahead of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Skyrocketing real estate prices have dramatically reduced the
number of homes available for year-round rental. Houses that were
once rented to members of the labor force on which the Cape tourism
industry depends are being sold at an unprededented rate, the
owners cashing in on investments that appreciated more than 20
percent just last year.
</P>
<P>
   New owners with money to spare are demolishing those houses,
building what around here are known as ``starter castles,'' then
leaving them vacant during the off season. Meanwhile, a seasonal
rental for less than $1,500 a week is considered a steal.``What
we've got here is a classic case of the rich getting richer, while
the poor suck air,'' said Todd Holland, treasurer of the Orleans
Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   To make ends meet today, a single adult with no children on Cape
Cod must earn an annual salary of approximately $40,000, according
to William Zammer Jr., owner of the Coonamessett Inn and two other
restaurants in Falmouth. The starting salary down the street at the
White Hen Pantry is $7 an hour, which amounts to less than $15,000
a year. The ``Help Wanted'' sign has been in the convenience store
window for two years, according to owner Lois Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   She sometimes has to work all three shifts without a break,
``which was not what I envisioned when I moved to this paradise,''
said Kendall, 54.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's hard to find a restaurant, inn, or gas station on
the Cape without a ``Help Wanted'' sign in the window. Four weeks
ago, Zammer purchased the old Hotel Falmouth so he could rent
accommodations to 70 employees to help him survive the summer
season. Cape employers have guaranteed the US government jobs for
3,122 people from other countries this summer if work visas are
granted. Last summer, 2,800 workers from 30 countries filled the
jobs. Some resort owners are busing help in daily from New Bedford.
Peter Hall, owner of Van Rensselaer's Restaurant in Wellfleet, just
added a fifth mobile home to his employee camp to accommodate a
host of Eastern European waiters.
</P>
<P>
   On Martha's Vineyard, the shortage of housing for summer help is
so acute that plans are underway to build 200-bed dormitory at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's a drop in the bucket. It could be 2,000 beds, and
it still would not be enough,'' said Herbert Putnam, a business
owner who is spearheading the project.
</P>
<P>
   On the Cape, about 5 percent of the housing stock is classified
affordable, according to the Cape Cod Commission; that's half the
state's recommended minimum. Many units are occupied by the elderly
or persons with disabilities. As one fisherman put it, drawing on
an image of his trade, ``the Cape is being gutted of the middle
class.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who grew up here, work here, and make the Cape what it
is, simply can't live here anymore,'' said Roger Cahoon, owner of
the 7 Cs Fish Market in West Yarmouth. ``So what? So you're losing
the soul of the place, not to mention the hands that feed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan O'Donnell is struggling to make sure her soul is not among
the lost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell lives in an old camper that broke down four times on
its way into Nickerson. Melissa, 14, Lindsay, 11, and Emily, 4,
live in a tent under a large tarp that Melissa takes pride in
helping erect because she had to climb 15 feet up one tree to
fasten an end.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell estimates at least a half-dozen homeless are legally
camped at Nickerson _ people shower in campsite washrooms, cook on
barbecue grills, sleep in brightly colored tents, wash clothes in
the laundromat, and laugh with their children like the vacationers
staying at the 418-site campground that is fully booked this
Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum camping stay at Nickerson is two weeks, for $12 a
night. O'Donnell will get a six-week camping permit at no charge
when the season's official meter starts ticking June 15 because she
has agreed to clean the campground toilets. There will be no more
extensions; she does not know what she will do when her permit
expires.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, one woman caught camping illegally became the stuff
of local homeless legend when she subsequently slipped into a
bank-possessed house in Eastham. She convinced the cable company
and utilities to resume service, but got caught a month later only
because she kept mowing the lawn. The place looked conspicuously
tidy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell moved to Nickerson last week because the house she had
been renting off season for $680 a month will be sold June 1. The
same thing happened with a different house the year before, and the
year before that in yet another house. Each summer began at
Nickerson, then continued in the driveways of friends or relatives
until she could find an affordable off-season rental. But, as real
estate agents point out, fewer homeowners are renting homes after
they leave in the fall because in this economy, the rental money is
not worth the trouble of packing up. She fears that this year her
camper existence may extend beyond the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 989 people applied for housing help at the Interfaith
Council for the Homeless, an Orleans-based advocacy organization
serving eight communites on the Lower Cape. Almost 400 people
applied for help in the first quarter of this year. A few get
housing, many get shelter help. The agency did not have placement
figures available.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this community, a lot of people don't understand that you
don't have to be pushing a shopping cart of belongings to be
homeless. For the most part, they're invisible,'' said Christine
Austin, the program director at Interfaith. It irks her that the
wealthy destroy cottages to make way for bigger homes, when those
cottages could be relocated for affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, who is divorced, moved to the Cape 11 years ago from
Medfield to be with her brother, two sisters, and mother. ``We all
have support systems. I could never leave the Cape, because I could
never leave my mother, brother, and sisters,'' O'Donnell said. But
she said her siblings have too many children to share a house with
four more people.
</P>
<P>
   A typical day: She's up to clean toilets at dawn, then gets the
children ready for school. Melissa goes to Nauset Middle School,
where she is in the honors program. Lindsay is ``on the verge'' of
honors at the Cape Cod Lighthouse Charter School in Orleans. Emily
stays with her grandmother, who has not been well. O'Donnell goes
to work until about 3 p.m., then she picks up the children to
attend the various after-school sporting events. Often she also
helps her mother with chores. She is home by 6 p.m. to cook supper
either on the grill or a Coleman stove. The kerosene lights go out
around 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, the children go to their grandmother's early so
O'Donnell can get to work by 5:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Off season, the camper sits in a friend's driveway.
</P>
<P>
   And what will she do when her six-week permit expires? ``I don't
know,'' she replied. In the near darkness, Melissa has been
assembling the myriad pieces of a geodesic dome from a kit. It will
become the children's play area. The directions are the kind that
might ruin Christmas morning for a parent. Her cocked head as she
worked suggested she was listening.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell has friends in the construction business, some of them
also living at campsites. ``How strange it is,'' she remarked,
``that so many houses sit empty all winter, and so many people
can't find a place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a hard day. Most of the previous week had been
rainy, and she spent the afternoon at the doctor's office. Three of
the four O'Donnells had been diagnosed with strep throat. The smoke
from the campfire could not have been helping sore throats, but its
glow was warming.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell was asked if she had any heroes. She thought for a
moment, then melted into tears, apologizing profusely for letting
down the facade of strength that gets her from day to day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids,'' she sobbed. ``They are my heroes. I don't know how
they put up with this, but they do. I try to never let them see me
cry.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the geodesic dome erected, Melissa came over and
put her arm around her mother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
