<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Friendly' policy
</P>
<P>
   Colonial Williamsburg is offering a new ``family-friendly''
admission policy. Visitors now have an option to purchase a general
admission ticket or an annual pass. Each will allow admission to
all exhibition buildings, daytime programs and museums throughout
Colonial Williamsburg and Carter's Grove, for the duration of the
visitor's ticket. The annual pass also includes history walks,
other benefits, and some special discounts, as well as free
parking, while the general admission ticket will not. A one-day
adult ticket is $30, with additional days at $5 each; the annual
pass is $65 per adult. Prices for children are lower. Guests
staying at Colonial Williamsburg hotels pay $30 for the duration of
their stay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lyme warning
</P>
<P>
   Vacationers headed to wooded, bushy, or overgrown grassy areas
might consider the new vaccine for Lyme disease, an infection
caused by bacteria transmitted via the bite of ticks that live on
deer or white-footed mice. ``But, the new vaccine might prove
tricky for travelers who do not plan their trips far in advance,''
said Dr. Cliff Dacso with the Travel Medicine Service at Baylor
College of Medicine in Houston. ``Recommendations call for vaccine
doses to be given in three injections over the course of a year.
Booster shots may be needed over time.'' Dacso noted that no
vaccine offers perfect protection so he encourages nature
enthusiasts to practice standard preventive measures such as
wearing protective clothing, using tick repellent, and removing
attached ticks as quickly as possible. Caught early, Lyme disease
is highly treatable. Left untreated, in rare cases the illness can
lead to a disabling arthritis and neurological problems.
Individuals who are at high risk are those who live or play in the
Northeast or Mid-Atlantic states, particularly along the coastal
areas from Maine to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Free stuff
</P>
