<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHO-GAMES-ART-BOS &LR;      05-30 1668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHO-GAMES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY FIGHTS FOR $20 BILLION VIEDO GAME MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The video game industry, purveyor of graphic fight
games, is headed for its own real-life carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Girding for the battle are four Titans lined up in a bid for the
next-generation game console market: Sony Computer Entertainment,
Sega Enterprises Ltd., Nintendo Co., and the industry's newest
entrant, Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The prize: a $20 billion annual market worldwide that analysts
say is growing more rapidly than the film or music industries.
</P>
<P>
   With two in every five US households owning game consoles, the
video game business has turned into a high-stakes business that's
no longer just about fun and games. For companies such as Sony and
Microsoft, it has become a deadly serious quest to be the dominant
entertainment hub for the world's living rooms, positioning the
survivors to sell movies, music, and other forms of digital
entertainment over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Behind their cheerful mascots is a brutal economic calculus
where billions are invested in each generation of consoles for a
market that has room for only one or two winners. In a race to
penetrate as many households as quickly as possible, most console
makers lose money for each machine they sell in the hopes that they
can make up for the losses in future software sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ugly business,'' said Peter Moore, president of Sega
of America Dreamcast Inc., a subsidiary of the Japanese company.
``Hardware is sold at cost or below to get a large installed base.
There is tremendous carnage involved in getting to that installed
base.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all is dire in the video game business. The good news is
that gaming is no longer just a pastime for adolescent boys. Women
and older consumers are increasingly embracing video games, drawn
by their hyper-realistic graphics and a growing genre of programs,
from puzzle games to ``edutainment'' software.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, US video game sales now rival Hollywood box-office
revenues. More people than ever are playing video games and
spending more time doing it. More than 40 percent of US households
now have at least one game console, according to estimates from
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is also converging with the Internet. Aside from
e-mail, game playing is rapidly becoming one of the Web's most
popular uses. The gaming industry is exploiting that popularity by
making a built-in modem a standard feature for next-generation
consoles.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers eventually will be able to download games, movies and
music via their consoles, opening up a whole new source of revenue.
And many consumers will pay monthly fees to participate in
``massively multiplayer'' games, such as Ultima, a popular online
fantasy game that can accommodate thousands of players at once.
</P>
<P>
   To get there, however, console makers must win the race for
getting the most number of machines into consumers' hands over the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been this riveting,'' said Matt Gravett, game
analyst at PC Data, a market research firm in Reston, Va. ``The
market is larger than it's even been, so the stakes are a lot
higher than they've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Each round in the console game wars has lasted about five years,
and the business is now poised to enter a new round. The four
contestants are pursuing distinct console strategies and
introducing markedly different products.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Computer Entertainment. After making its debut with the
PlayStation console in 1995, Sony emerged as the undisputed winner
of the last round. Last year, Sony captured 54 percent of the US
game hardware market and 68 percent of the software gaming market,
according to the NPD Group Inc., an industry tracking firm in Port
Washington, N.Y. One in four US households currently has a
PlayStation.
</P>
<P>
   Sony is hoping to repeat its success with PlayStation 2, which
is set to hit store shelves in late October. The new console, which
doubles as a digital video disk (or DVD) player, is wildly popular
in Japan, where Sony has sold nearly 2 million units since
launching PlayStation 2 there in March.
</P>
<P>
   Sony also has the most ambitious plans for its console. The
entertainment giant is looking to use the machines as a potential
platform for distributing other products over the Internet,
including its own movies and music and those of other companies,
according to Molly Smith, spokeswoman for Sony's American division.
</P>
<P>
   But success is not a foregone conclusion for Sony. For one
thing, PlayStation 2, at $299 each, is relatively costly. Rival
machines cost between $99 and $199. Another potential drawback is
the relatively sparse number of new games available for PlayStation
2, said Charles Gray, publisher of Happy Puppy, an online gaming
site based in New York. Game developers say that is partly because
the new machine is so complex that it's tough to write games for
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that what sells consoles are games,'' said Gray.
Referring to the Sony booth at the annual trade show in Los Angeles
earlier this month, he said, ``Sony had a pretty underwhelming show
on the software side.''
</P>
<P>
   Sega Enterprises Ltd. The comeback kid of the video game
business, Sega crashed to earth in the mid-1990s with its Saturn
console, a dismal failure that followed its popular Genesis system.
But Sega surprised many in the industry with its Dreamcast machine,
rolled out last fall. Sega has sold more than 2 million Dreamcasts
and snagged a 14 percent share of the US game hardware market in
1999, according to NPD figures.
</P>
<P>
   Sega has shrewdly nurtured Dreamcast sales by courting outside
software developers who help keep the pipeline full of new games,
including Crazy Taxi, Resident Evil, and Quake III Arena. Moore,
the San Francisco-based president of Sega of America, estimates
another 170 games for the coming holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   With Sega.com set to launch this fall, Sega will be the first
company to actually have a live online gaming site for its
consoles. But the strategy is risky, analysts say, because it asks
consumers to fork over $21.95 a month for Internet access to the
Sega site. To make the pill go down more smoothly, Sega is offering
a $200 rebate to anyone who signs up for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``it's a bit steep,'' said Gravett of PC Data.
</P>
<P>
   Also working against Sega is the impending introduction of more
powerful machines, such as the PlayStation 2. Moore dismisses the
threat, saying, ``Power is relative. It's not what you've got; it's
how you use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo Co. The grandfather of the video game business,
Nintendo has built an empire from inexpensive machines and games
that feature well-known characters from Pokemon to Mario. The
company dominates the list of best-selling games in spite of the
fact that its current machine, the Nintendo 64, is based on old,
costly cartridge technology rather than CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nintendo took 33 percent of the hardware market and
28 percent of the software market, according to the NPD Group.
(Those figures don't include sales of Game Boy, Nintendo's wildly
popular portable gaming device, which controls the lion's share of
the hand-held market category.)
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo's next-generation console _ code-named Dolphin _ is due
out some time next year. The console will use DVD technology and
sport a 400-megahertz IBM copper microprocessor twice as fast as
the Dreamcast and one-third faster than the PlayStation 2. But
aside from the chip, Nintendo isn't revealing much about its new
console.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is that so little is known about it,''
said Schelley Olhava, analyst with IDC in Mountain View, Calif.
``The longer they hold out information, the more the window of
opportunity closes for them. People are evaluating their purchasing
options now, and Nintendo needs to give these consumers more to go
by.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. The newest kid on the block and the sole US
challenger to three Japanese players, Microsoft is working hard to
break into the console market. It's part of the Redmond, Wash.,
company's overall strategy to expand beyond the realm of desktop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Though not scheduled to hit store shelves until fall 2001, the
company's prototype _ the X-Box _ was unveiled in March by
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates. The X-Box towers above its
competitors in sheer computing power. It will have a 733-megahertz
Pentium III processor, a built-in broadband modem, 64 megabytes of
memory, and an internal hard disk drive, something no other console
has to date.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft knows that its success hinges upon games, and that
means winning the loyalty of game developers. Right now, the
company is busy touting the X-Box's developer-friendly platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building a console based on PC technology that is very
familiar to developers and artists,'' said Ed Fries, vice president
of games publishing at Microsoft. ``This will allow developers to
focus on making great games, instead of struggling to figure out
how the machine works.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft isn't exactly new to games. The company is the world's
fifth-largest publisher of PC games and has operated an online
gaming site, called Zone.com, for four years. Nor is Microsoft new
to hardware; its joysticks and game pads outsell all other brands.
</P>
<P>
   But console gaming is an entirely different beast. PC games tend
to sell poorly in the console market, and Microsoft knows that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be developing a completely different set of games for
the X-Box,'' Fries said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Microsoft and its rivals know that consoles are
empty vessels that must be filled with compelling games in order to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are just boxes,'' said Moore. ``The bottom line is that
it's all about the software inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the games begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
