<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ESTONIA-PAST-BOS &LR;      05-30 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTONIA-PAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING JUSTICE, NOT REVENGE IN ESTONIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLINN, Estonia _ On a summer morning just before dawn, Lennart
Meri, 12, woke to the sound of stomping jackboots and strangers
shouting in Russian. When he opened his eyes, he saw two
bayonet-wielding Red Army soldiers standing over his bed.
</P>
<P>
   They ordered Meri, his parents, and his younger brother to dress
quickly and pack a suitcase. They then drove the family to a
railway depot where cargo trains waited, bound for Siberian labor
camps.
</P>
<P>
   The date was June 14, 1941, less than a year after Soviet forces
had invaded Estonia, a small country on the Baltic sea roughly the
size of Vermont and New Hampshire combined.
</P>
<P>
   Today that boy is president of Estonia, less than a decade after
the country regained its freedom from Moscow. His story is very
much Estonia's story, one of invasion, occupation and repression _
and a belated attempt to come to terms with a painful past. It is a
past whose details many Estonians have sought in the now-opened
files of the KGB, the former Soviet secret police.
</P>
<P>
   On the same June day, in what some here call the start of a
1940s version of ethnic cleansing, Soviet authorities deported
10,000 Estonians to Siberia. Three-fourths of them died in the
harsh Russian winter.
</P>
<P>
   This history is very much a part of Estonia's present. As most
of Europe was celebrating the 55th anniversary of the end of World
War II earlier this month, Estonia was subdued. Here, the war was a
lose-lose affair.
</P>
<P>
   Estonia was overrun three times by two of the past century's
most nefarious regimes, once by Hitler's Germany and twice by
Stalin's Russia _ and was forcibly absorbed into the Soviet Union
after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Soviets deported more than 30,000 Estonians to
Siberian labor camps in the 1940s. Nearly every family in the
country was affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were cattle carriages with small windows and iron bars.
Behind these bars I saw human faces, children weeping, women
weeping,'' Meri said in an interview at his home. A Soviet officer
told Meri's father, Georg, a prominent Estonian diplomat, that he
would be taken on a separate train.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father clasped my shoulder and said to me, `From now on you
are the eldest man in the family, so take care of your mother,' ''
Meri said.
</P>
<P>
   Now 71, Meri said that ``to build a free democratic future''
Estonia must ``shed the bright light of truth'' on its tragic past,
no matter how painful. ``We must do this for ourselves. We are
building a state based on the rule of law, and our citizens are
interested in addressing this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the Nazi and Soviet occupations equally odious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot compare two evils. Evil is like love, either it
exists or it does not exist,'' Meri said.
</P>
<P>
   But while thousands of Nazi war criminals were prosecuted after
the war, those responsible for Soviet repression in Estonia had
gone unpunished _ until recently. Last year, law-enforcement
officials began prosecuting former Estonian and ethnic Russian
officials for ordering the arrests, deportations, and executions
that became the hallmark of Soviet rule here.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1999, meanwhile, a presidential commission has
been investigating crimes against humanity committed in Estonia
under Nazi and Soviet rule. The commission, whose members come from
the United States, Germany, Russia, Finland, and Denmark, is
expected to report in December.
</P>
<P>
   Meri and other officials said that in reckoning with its past,
Estonia must take extra care not to be vindictive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being dogmatic always results in a terrible tragedy for any
nation,'' Meri said. ``We are very much aware that in such a
situation, one wrong step can lead to a horrible dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Mart Laar, 40, Estonia's prime minister, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very easy for us to decide that this one or that
one is guilty. But if we did that, we would be acting just like the
Nazi and the communist dictatorships. We are interested in being
different,'' said Laar, who lost relatives to both the Nazis and
the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   Most deportees tell stories similar to Meri's.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests of those suspected of not being loyal enough to
Moscow usually were made in the small hours of the morning. Soviet
officers gave people minutes to pack before marching them to
waiting trains. Fathers were often separated from their families.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the deportations and immigration of Russians
loyal to Moscow, Estonia's ethnic mix changed dramatically. Before
the war, 95 percent of the population was Estonian; today, 65
percent are.
</P>
<P>
   While Meri and his family survived and were united after the
war, many others were not so fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement of Estonia's State Archive building, rows of
neatly stacked KGB files tell the stories of thousands of destroyed
lives. A deportation order for an entire family, including a
3-year-old girl. A 78-year-old man deported for owning a farm. A
21-year-old man executed for once belonging to the Young Eagles, an
organization similar to the Boy Scouts. A 17-year-old boy
imprisoned for wearing a ``forbidden'' high school pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, this is history, but it is also evidence _ evidence of
criminal deportations and executions,'' said an archive historian,
Indrek Jurjo, as he pointed at the stack of manila folders on his
desk.
</P>
<P>
   One file told the story of Leo Oispuu's family, like Meri's,
deported on June 14, 1941. Oispuu, now 69, was 10 years old at the
time. His father Magnus, his mother Kersti, and his brother Felix
all died in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   The KGB archives have been open to the public since 1994, and
every year hundreds of people come to investigate the fate of their
loved ones. They are also one of the main sources of evidence for
Estonian law-enforcement officials as they prepare cases against
Soviet-era officials.
</P>
<P>
   The process, according to Hannes Kont, a spokesman for Estonia's
Security Police, is tedious. Investigators pore through archives,
matching Soviet officials' signatures on deportation and execution
orders with death certificates to see who is still alive to face
trial. Since both the victims and the perpetrators are elderly,
finding living witnesses is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only convict a person if you have real evidence, not
just somebody making a speech saying he is guilty,'' Kont said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Estonian courts have convicted four former secret police
officials for organizing deportations and politically motivated
executions. All received suspended sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main idea is to get the courts to prove that the Soviet
regime committed crimes against humanity,'' Kont said. ``This is
not a question of revenge, but a question of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to neighboring Latvia, where trials of former Soviet
officials have sparked angry protests from the Russian minority,
the process is proceeding quietly in Estonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Estonians are going about this very wisely,'' said Sergei
Ivanov, an ethnic Russian who sits in Estonia's parliament. ``It is
necessary to evaluate what happened. There are people alive who saw
and experienced injustice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
