<HEADLINE>
NARROWLY NAVIGATING THE STRAITS OF USAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Strait is the gate, and narrow is the way which leadeth unto
life,'' according to Matthew in the King James Bible. But the path
of strait through the centuries has been a long and winding road;
hence the puzzlement of several readers at my use of strait and
narrow a few weeks ago. ``I always thought it was straight,'' wrote
Dorothy Teehan of Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   Not always, but it is today. The accepted idiom has become
straight and narrow, meaning the path of rectitude, or sometimes
the path of small-minded conventionality. That's the version
dictionaries endorse, and you can use it without fear of reproach
even from straitlaced usage cops.
</P>
<P>
   But straight and narrow is a condensation of the biblical
caution, and writers who remember that _ and who fear the loss of
straitjacket and straitened and straitlaced to the encroaching
straight variations _ still sometimes use the original form. More
than one country music reviewer has found it handy when dealing
with singer George Strait. (Don't ask why more than one takes a
singular verb; our language soars above mere literalism.) Strait
and narrow is fairly frequent in the English press, and even in
America, it gets pretty good play in the South _ the Sun-Sentinel
in Fort Lauderdale, the Times-Picayune in New Orleans, the Houston
Chronicle, and especially the Dallas Morning News all have writers
(or editors) who remember their New Testament and stick with
strait.
</P>
<P>
   Where did it all start? With two entirely different words:
Strait, from the Latin for ``tighten, bind,'' is related to strict
and stringent. It's been an English word since the 1200s, with
various meanings related to limitation: Straitlaced means squinched
into a laced corset, like Scarlett O'Hara, or as stiff as if you
were; straitjacketed means tightly restrained, whether literally or
figuratively. And the person in straitened circumstances has
nowhere to turn, financially speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Straight, on the other hand, derives from the Middle English for
stretched, and in the 1300s is being used to mean both ``direct''
and ``not crooked'' _ the meanings that have migrated to our
contemporary straight and narrow.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see how such an evolution would proceed; straight
in the sense of ``righteous'' overlaps with the sense of strait,
``confined,'' and in less orthographically correct centuries, the
spellings were often interchanged even when the senses were clearly
distinct. There's even a logical rationale for straight and narrow:
Once we've condensed the quotation from Matthew to strait and
narrow, it's redundant. Strait means constricted, and so does
narrow, but nothing about the original image suggests directness;
the path may well be full of twists and turns. Change it to
straight and narrow, and your image of the way to salvation _ or
merely to avoiding jail _ is more like a tightrope than a dark and
tortuous trail. Not as poetic, perhaps, as what Matthew had in
mind, but the straight and narrow, whether you use it to mean
conventional dullness or effortful virtue, is a useful
modification.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, it's officially the idiom now, despite the
sentimental attachment of some word watchers to the older form. So
go ahead and use straight and narrow; just keep those other
expressions strait, if you please.
</P>
<P>
   Dialectally challenged
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, I wrote that berm was ``dialectically''
used in New England as a term for the curbside planting strip.
Philip Sawyer of New York e-mailed to point out that I'd been swept
up from the sidewalk into the realm of philosophy: What I should
have written was dialectally. ``The former term refers to the
dialectic (thesis, antithesis, synthesis) rather than to matters
related to speech,'' he notes. And it's true; Hegelian logic and
Marxist dialectical materialism have nothing to do with our names
for that streetside plot. Dialectally may not have the same snap,
but for a word maven sticking to the straight and narrow, it's the
only adverbial form on the books.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to
her at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
