<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCERDRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKING THE ROOT OF CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laura B. Smith had one of the bad breast cancers, the ones that
recur and spread and defy even the harshest chemotherapy drugs
reserved for desperate cases.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, after the disease spread to her neck, ``the doctor
said I had three to five years,'' said Smith, a 38-year-old mother
of three who lives near Indianapolis. ``I told her I needed another
15 or 20 years, so she better find a way to get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Smith, who is a registered nurse, entered a clinical
trial of anti-VEGF, one of the new cancer drugs known as
angiogenesis inhibitors that are supposed to strangle tumors' blood
supply lifelines and cause fewer punishing side effects than
traditional chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she says, the cancer in her neck is undetectable, and she
has suffered minimal side effects from the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful,'' said Smith, whose religious faith earned her
the nickname ``Miracle Child'' among the staff, adding, ``I`m so
blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is among five of 59 patients with advanced breast cancer
whose tumors have responded to the drug, made by Genentech Inc., in
toxicity testing, according to a sobering report at last week's
meeting of the American Society for Clinical Oncology. And no one
knows whether the drug will continue to keep her tumor in check.
</P>
<P>
   Still, hopeful anecdotes such as Smith's are beginning to emerge
from early testing of some angiogenesis inhibitors, which many
specialists (and patients) believe is the most exciting front in
the war against cancer. Perhaps $4 billion has been spent in
research on this new class of cancer treatments, and about 6,500
cancer patients have received some sort of therapy, according to
the Boston-based Angiogenesis Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's far too soon to write an overall report card on
the drugs, dozens of which are now undergoing human trials. And
many of the trials are still in Phase I, in which the drugs are
pitted against out-of-control cancers in very sick patients,
creating a formidable challenge for any new drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we have some good leads. We have some drugs that
are clearly not producing side effects in patients,'' said David
Cheresh, an angiogenesis researcher at the Scripps Clinic and
Research Foundation in California.
</P>
<P>
   Moreoever, he said, cancers are being slowed or halted in some
patients, ``and I see that as a remarkable success in drugs that
have no side effects. If we can simply hold tumors at bay, we've
accomplished a major, major goal,'' Cheresh said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say that some terminally ill patients who received
anti-angiogenesis drugs are still alive between one and two years
later, when they otherwise would have died long ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, the drugs haven't even slowed some types of cancer. For
example, when the drug thalidomide, a sedative that has some
anti-angiogenic traits) was given to 17 patients with metastatic
head and neck cancer, one patient soon died and the tumors
continued to grow in the other 16.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the drugs have caused serious, even lethal, side
effects in other patients. Most alarming, in a trial of 99 patients
with advanced lung cancer given the same anti-VEGF drug taken by
Smith, six patients suddenly began coughing up blood and four died.
The drug also apparently caused strokes in a few patients with
colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The angiogenesis field, pioneered by Dr. Judah Folkman at
Harvard Medical School and Children's Hospital in Boston, has been
awash in high expectations since some of the drugs have obliterated
huge tumors in animals at little cost in side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes have been particularly high for endostatin, discovered in
Folkman's lab, because it proved so powerful and nontoxic in animal
experiments. But a senior official at the National Cancer
Institute, which is overseeing two endostatin trials, recently said
he has seen no dramatic benefits from endostatin after seven months
of testing.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman countered at last week's conference in New Orleans that
he was ``very pleased'' by the initial tests _ which show the drug
seems free of toxicity _ and suggested it is too early to judge
endostatin's effects on cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But, while researchers spar publicly over extremely preliminary
results on endostatin, other angiogenesis inhibitors such as
anti-VEGF and a few others provide a better reality check, since
they are well into the second phase of the three-stage human
testing process. However, these drugs are less potent than
endostatin is in animals.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Phase I studies, which concentrate on safety, in
Phase II, researchers look for signs that the drug works.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Li, who heads the Angiogenesis Foundation that
promotes research and application of the drugs, said that this
year's American Society of Clinical Oncology meeting was the first
to have a large number of reports from human trials of angiogenesis
inhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   While encouraged by some of the results, Li noted that ``many
people have believed that all solid tumors are dependent on
angiogenesis (recruiting a new blood supply) and therefore that
they would all respond'' to inhibitors. ``However, in human
clinical studies we've generally not seen the consistent
spectacular results that we've seen in mice,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind these drugs is elegantly simple. Instead of
trying to pulverize cancer cells, the way standard chemotherapy and
radiation do, angiogenesis inhibitors aim to shut off tumors' blood
supply. If tumors can't attract new blood vessels to fuel them,
they can't grow or spread.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, angiogenesis _ the formation of new blood vessels _
isn't always harmful. The body needs to turn on blood vessel growth
to repair wounds and to form the blood-rich lining of the uterus
during menstruation and pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The antiangiogenic drugs work by blocking the many chemical
signals that tumors send out to nearby blood vessels, which may
respond by sending out tiny blood vessels that grow toward the
tumor. Tumor cells attacked by conventional chemotherapy drugs
eventually mutate into resistant cells, thwarting the treatment.
Angiogenesis blockers don't have the problem because they bypass
tumors and focus just on the blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Angiogenesis inhibitors may not kill tumors, but there are good
reasons to think they could hold cancer in check for years _ as
long as they are free of side-effects. Natural anti-angiogenesis
substances in the body, such as endostatin, probably keep many tiny
tumors from ever becoming troublesome, Folkman believes.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans meeting included reports on other new
``targeted'' therapies, drugs designed to attack weak points in
cancer cells by focusing on specific molecules. Some of those are
showing similar encouraging progress.
</P>
<P>
   As for anti-angiogenesis drugs, there were about 40 reports
including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Genentech's anti-VEGF, combined with a standard chemotherapy
drug, stalled the disease in advanced colon cancer patients and
extended survival to an average of at least 17 months, compared to
13.8 months in those who got only the chemo. Side effects included
strokes, high blood pressure, fever and chills.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 99 patients with the most common form of lung cancer,
anti-VEGF along with chemo slowed the disease enough to add a few
months of survival. ``That may not seem like a long time, but it's
as big an improvement as we've ever seen,'' said Dr. Russell DeVore
of Vanderbilt University.
</P>
<P>
   However, the lung bleeding that killed four patients was a total
surprise, DeVore said, noting that they all occurred among patients
with a specific type of the disease, squamous cell lung cancer. One
possible explanation advanced by other researchers is that the
anti-VEGF drug destroyed weakened blood vessels in and around the
tumor that had been supporting lung tissue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thalidomide, the once-banned sedative that caused tragic birth
defects, yielded ``stunning'' results in treating multiple myeloma,
a form of bone marrow cancer, reported Dr. Bart Barlogie of the
Arkansas Cancer Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Thalidomide also showed some activity in patients with recurring
brain tumors, stabilized disease in inoperable liver cancer.
However, it was ineffective in patients with head and neck cancers
and in lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ An antiogenic drug named SU5416, made by Sugen, Inc., combined
with standard chemo, showed promise in patients with advanced colon
cancer, and was tolerated by patients at every dosage level. In 28
patients the drug shrank just one tumor completely, partially
shrank tumors in five others, and held the disease in check in 9
patients. It had no effect in four others.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin, made by EntreMed Inc. of Rockville, Md., is in Phase
I trials in Boston; Madison, Wisc.; and Houston. At one point, the
researchers thought they might report some data at the oncology
conference, but then said they hadn't analyzed enough results yet.
Despite unanswered questions about its effectiveness, the company
plans to go on to Phase II trials.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joanna Horobin, an EntreMed vice president, said last week
that a new trial is planned to begin in Europe using portable pumps
to administer endostatin continuously at low doses, instead of the
once-daily infusions patients have been getting thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Horobin said researchers are rapidly analyzing ``an
enormous amount'' of data from the Phase I trials in Boston, being
carried out by Dana-Farber/Partners Cancer Care. The material
includes blood and urine samples, biopsy tissues and different
kinds of imaging scans.
</P>
<P>
   When all the data is sifted, she said, it will be possible to
draw some conclusions about the drug's Phase 1 performance. At
present, said Horobin, ``It's like a puzzle: we have a lot of
pieces but, we don't quite know what the picture on the front of
the box looks like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
