<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHAPES OF GALAXIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What causes galaxies to form into different shapes such as
the elliptical or spiral shape?
</P>
<P>
   N.D., Plymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is that nobody really knows. In general, when
you have a lot of bodies with not much overall rotation, galaxies
tend to get pulled into a spherical shape by gravity, much as the
stars and planets all got pulled into roughly spherical shapes by
their own gravity. It's easy to see that if mountains weren't so
stiff, they'd just collapse into puddles, and if you start off with
a sphere with lots of lumps on the surface, they will eventually
collapse under the action of gravity and leave you with a perfect
sphere.
</P>
<P>
   If there's some rotation, the galaxy tends to flatten out, just
like a disk of pizza dough thrown in the air spinning: The middle
gets pushed out by centrifugal force.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem with understanding the details is that we've
looked at rotating galaxies and, if we assume that we know how
gravity works on very large distance scales (and most people think
this is the case) and we measure the speed with which stars go
about the center of the galaxy, we should be able to calculate how
much matter is in the galaxy. But when we count up what we can see
directly with telescopes, we find we only get about 10 percent of
what we calculated.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, 90 percent of the matter in galaxies seems to be
invisible ``dark matter.'' We don't know what it is, and since we
don't know what 90 percent of the matter in galaxies is, we're not
really in a very good position to understand in detail why they
take the shapes they do. There are lots of ideas about what the
dark matter may be, and lots of experiments underway to find it,
but so far it's all very mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Knowledge answers your questions about health and science
each week. E-mail the doctor at drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send
fax to: 617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The
Boston Globe, Health/Science Section, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
