<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-BUGS-BOS &LR;      05-30 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING INSECTS TO SOLVE CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The worms go in.
</P>
<P>
   The worms go out.
</P>
<P>
   The worms play pinochle on your snout.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the old children's rhyme about death claimed,
anyway. But, it turns out, it's not just the worms.
</P>
<P>
   A new breed of forensic scientists has discovered that they can
actually solve crimes by studying the insect demolition crew that
dismantles the human body after death.
</P>
<P>
   Maggots, the eggs of flies that can infest a corpse within
minutes, are prolific snitches, revealing the time of death, if the
body has been moved, whether a victim had been taking drugs, and
sometimes, even, who did it.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the wrong impression, the maggots aren't the only
stool pigeons. A veritable Cosa Nostra of creepy crawlies gather at
the scene of the crime, from hide beetles to wasps to ants, each
with a special role to play as the body decomposes.
</P>
<P>
   And their life cycles are so predictable that those who
understand them can provide police with clues beyond the reach of
conventional methods _ especially if the victim has been dead for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of forensic entolomogy is constantly growing,'' said
William Rodriguez, a forensic anthropologist with the Armed Forces
Institute of Pathology in Washington D.C. ``The percentage of cases
may not be that large, but after 20 to 42 hours, insects are the
best scientific method we have for determining the post mortem
interval.''
</P>
<P>
   These new crime investigators remain a tiny fraternity _ there
are just 15 members of the American Board of Forensic Entomology _
but their often-grisly work is about to become a good deal better
known thanks to the deliciously disgusting new book, ``A Fly for
the Prosecution'' (Harvard University Press, $22.95).
</P>
<P>
   Author M. Lee Goff, professor of entomology at the University of
Hawaii, believes that his field will always represent a relatively
small percentage of cases. Since most bodies are recovered quickly,
the medical examiner can estimate time of death without assistance.
Goff, for instance, handles only about 15 to 20 cases a year, and,
with Hawaii's low homicide rate, much of the work comes from other
places _ Florida, Tennessee, Nevada, even Europe and Central and
South America.
</P>
<P>
   But when forensic entomology is needed _ when bodies have been
lying out in the elements and tissues are degraded _ the results
can be dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case on New Year's Eve, 1998, when police called Goff
to a murder scene in Oahu, Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The swashbuckling bug man hopped on his Harley Davidson
motorcycle and motored to an area of scrub and brush near the ocean
and a golf course. There, behind yellow crime scene tape was a
corpse bundled up tightly in blankets.
</P>
<P>
   Before disturbing the body, Goff swept the area with an insect
net to collect samples. Once these had been placed in containers,
the body was unwrapped from the brown blanket, which had been
sealed shut at both ends by Ace elastic bandages. Another layer was
discovered: the body was also wrapped in a white blanket. There
were no obvious signs of trauma.
</P>
<P>
   But there were plenty of signs that the elaborate choreography
of decomposition was underway. Goff found blow fly eggs as well as
pupae _ the casings from which mature flies emerge _ on the outer
and inner blankets. He found predatory hister beetles feeding on
the blow fly maggots, who already had fed and were moving away from
the corpse. On the body itself, there were more maggots and pupae.
</P>
<P>
   Then, armed with insect and soils samples, Goff raced off to
start processing samples and to clean up for a New Year's Eve
party.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out there were four species of blow fly in different
stages of development. Because there were no empty pupal cases, it
appeared that Goff was working with the first generation of flies
to hit the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Goff reared pupae in the lab for identification _ it's hard to
tell one species from another when in maggot form, but raised to
adulthood, they can be named _ and used weather information from
that area to formulate the onset of insect activity.
</P>
<P>
   Goff determined that insects started their work 10 and a half
days before the body was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   But the victim had last been seen alive 13 days earlier, in the
company of her estranged husband. And, at that time, neighbors had
heard some gasping and thumping noises.
</P>
<P>
   Goff reasoned that the insect activity on the corpse was delayed
by two and a half days due to the blanket barrier. And his report
was accepted by the authorities. But the defense attorney for the
husband pressed Goff to be more conclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Goff went further, conducting an experiment with a 50-pound pig
(considered the best simulation of human remains) and two blankets.
Setting the decomposing pig in a blanket out in his own backyeard,
Goff discovered that it did, indeed, take 2.5 days for the flies to
penetrate the wrapping. With that detailed evidence, the husband
was convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Other times, the job can be far less difficult. In one odd case
from Texas in 1985, Goff reports that a mangled grasshopper was
found on a female victim. Later, the missing leg from the
grasshopper was discovered in the cuff of a suspect's pants. He was
convicted, partially from that evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the insects can harbor traces of drugs long gone
from degraded tissue. And bugs particular to one area can give
clues to movement _ the body's or the perpetrator's. In one
instance Goff cites, tiny scabs on the suspect's legs helped
establish that he had been at the chigger-infested scene where the
murder victim was found.
</P>
<P>
   Goff's meticulous work ``has been real important in certain
cases,'' said Dr. Alvin Omori, the chief medical examiner in
Honolulu, who has worked on about four or five cases a year with
Goff for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic entomology emerged as a science in the 1980s, but the
concept has been around a lot longer. In 13th-century China, after
a man was slashed to death by a sickle in a rural village, the
local magistrate ordered farmers with sickles to appear before him.
In the hot summer sun, flies swarmed to the one that had blood and
tissue residue on it. And the farmer confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the entire field of forensics is enjoying a popular
renaissance in the wake of the O.J. Simpson case, as well as movies
such as ``The Bone Collector,'' and the wildly popular novels of
Patricia Cornwell featuring the sleuthing medical examiner, Kay
Scarpetta.
</P>
<P>
   Like the autopsies performed by Cornwell's protagonist, however,
the work of Goff and his colleagues is not for the faint of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Goff said that at a lecture he attended early in his career, an
expert presented slides of some of the decomposition studies he had
done with pigs. After a few images clicked by, the man next to Goff
whispered, ``that's one funny looking pig.''
</P>
<P>
   And Goff corrected him, ``That's a human.''
</P>
<P>
   The colleague and about a quarter of the room, stampeded out of
the lecture hall, some headed for the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Though Goff is respectful of the dead, he doesn't allow those
feelings to interfere with his science. And his book is filled with
medical details that aren't everyone's cup of tea. He tells about
grisly subjects such as the drip zone and skin slippage, as well as
the five stages of decomposition _ fresh, bloated, decay,
post-decay, and skeletal. And Goff encounters skulls polished by
the scraping mandibles of beetle larvae as well as a cranial vault
that housed an ant colony.
</P>
<P>
   For Goff, bugs and bodies are a perfect professional fit. He is
an entomologist who did a stint in the army in a military morgue.
But he laughs at the romantic way most forensic work is portrayed
in TV shows and films. There are many tedious hours, Goff said,
spent counting eyes, wing veins, and hairs or bristles on various
parts of the insects bodies.
</P>
<P>
   And the forensic entomologists are so specialized that there is
no one to help them answer important questions. In one case from
1984, Goff submitted specimens of rove beetles for identification
to the USDA. A full 12 years later, he received the report: no one
at the lab could identify them.
</P>
<P>
   For all the film noir aspects of what he does, Goff pointed out
that forensic entomology is really about hard science. And, as with
any science, it still holds more unsolved mysteries than Hollywood
could ever plot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
