<HEADLINE>
EULOGIZING THE LATE, GREAT SMASHING PUMPKINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With summer almost upon us, I thought it might be a fine time to
finish up my spring cleaning:
</P>
<P>
   That grating, bratty whine of a voice. That Uncle Festus chrome
dome. Those shredded screams. Those pretentious Big Rock
pronouncements. Those endlessly ambitious songs.
</P>
<P>
   I'm really going to miss Smashing Pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   There was a discernible pang of loss last week when fearless
Pumpkins leader Billy Corgan announced that his band will call it
quits at year's end. After 12 years, Corgan said the band _
guitarist James Iha, drummer Jimmy Chamberlin, and bassist Melissa
Auf Der Maur (who replaced original Pumpkins bassist D'Arcy Wretzky
last year) _ had reached the ``end of our road emotionally,
spiritually, and musically,'' and deep down ``our fans knew that
this was the end.'' Perhaps Billy's right. Their latest CD,
``Machina/The Machines of God,'' never caught fire, probably
because it wasn't a particularly interesting record.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, there was ``The Everlasting Gaze'' _ which was really
just a rip-off of their own superior ``Zero'' _ but what else was
there? The album has sold only 500,000 copies, a pittance for a
major band, since its late February release, and it's nowhere to be
found on the charts. None of this, of course, takes away from the
fact that the Pumpkins were one of the best bands of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In such offerings as 1991's ``Gish,'' their 1993 breakthrough
``Siamese Dream,'' and their creative highpoint, 1995's double-CD
``Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness,'' the Pumpkins,
especially Corgan, understood the healing and redemptive powers of
rock perhaps better than just about any artist of his generation.
It was his manna, and he believed in its potential to salve
society's wounds even when he was railing at the gods. From
``Crush,'' ``Disarm,'' and ``Tonight, Tonight'' to ``Cherub Rock''
to ``Bullet With Butterfly Wings'' to ``Today'' to ``1979,'' at
their best, the Pumpkins could make you feel whole and mighty. Such
songs were baptisms of fire to make you thrash, cry, dance, or
laugh with abandon. Carrying out Billy's vision, the Pumpkins were
annoying and amazing, beautiful and bombastic, cliched and so damn
daring, sometimes it was like they invented this whole rock thing
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There will be solo albums and such, of course. But it won't
quite be the same. There was just something soothing in knowing
that, even though we were rats in that cage Billy once sang about,
we had the Pumpkins' music to illuminate all our rage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So do you think Bobby Brown's recent legal troubles _ he's in a
Broward County, Fla. jail at least until mid-June awaiting a
hearing on a probation violation _ will hurt his career? Oh, wait a
minute _ these days, getting in legal trouble is his career.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admit it: you were wickedly happy when John ``Scientology is not
a cult'' Travolta's Scientology cult movie, ``Battlefield Earth''
died a big ol' noisy death at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cruise, Tom Snooze: Make no mistake, ``Mission: Impossible
2'' is the new John Woo movie, period. You could cast Cartman from
``South Park'' as superspy Ethan Hunt, and so long as Woo was
behind the camera, it would be worth the price of admission. And
speaking of Nicole Kidman's husband, is there any other star who,
in TV interviews, seems more sincere and phony at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm jonesing something fierce for Tony, Carmela, Livia, Paulie
Walnuts, and the rest of the ``Sopranos'' gang. March 2001 can't
come fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas band Dynamite Hack's wacky white-boy cover of N.W.A's
``Boyz-N-Tha-Hood'' _ gentle folk-rock vocals and acoustic guitar
accompanying the original straight-outta-Compton lyrics by Dr. Dre,
Ice Cube, and the late Eazy-E _ is so absurd, it's almost
brilliant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
