<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-SMART-CAMERAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUPED-UP SURVEILLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   READING, Mass. _ From supermarkets to banks to office parks, the
world is full of thousands of surveillance cameras. But generally
speaking, they're only as good as the sometimes glassy-eyed
security officers watching them.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, however, you had a surveillance camera that would
automatically detect suspicious behavior, sound an alarm, and begin
recording an incident for later review by security officials.
</P>
<P>
   That's the concept behind a new system being developed here by
TASC Inc., a unit of defense and intelligence contractor Litton
Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting technology used for battlefields and counterespionage,
TASC engineers have developed a system that will be installed later
this year to improve video surveillance at a retail chain and a
casino. Elements of the system are also being used by TASC to
upgrade security on Capitol Hill, under a $5 million contract with
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   By linking movement- and behavior-recognizing systems with
advanced digital video cameras made by Loronix Information Systems
Inc. of Durango, Colo., TASC's system could flash and sound an
alert at a guard's computer screen if someone is running rather
than walking to the exit, or a clerk leaves a cash register drawer
open, or a casino croupier seems to have his hands under the table
too often.
</P>
<P>
   Based on staggering amounts of math, the technology, simply put,
tries to figure out when an object being monitored is a human
being, and when the human being is acting in ways that can be
defined as suspicious or worth being taped for later review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closed-circuit TV is just an extension of people's eyes,''
says Bradley C. Lynch, security systems account manager for TASC,
which traces its roots to a Pentagon contractor founded in
Winchester 34 years ago. ``We looked at this and said, `Let's make
this an extension of people's minds.' With our system, video is
more than just a picture. It's information.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether a souped-up camera can determine when people are
doing bad things, of course, depends on how precisely operators can
define for the camera what bad behavior is _ and on little things
such as keeping the cameras clean.
</P>
<P>
   TASC officials acknowledge the system has the potential for
spurring false alarms. When a warning flashes at a security TV
monitor, it merely alerts the guards to pay attention to something
on the screen. The guards must use discretion in determining
whether the alert was prompted by a fleeing grocery thief or a
toddler sprinting in the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some TASC officials think their biggest markets in the
near term could be monitoring for problems other than shoplifters
or crooked employees.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Insurance Information Institute estimates that
American businesses lose $30 billion a year in slip-and-fall
accidents, including some number of phony spills staged by willing
``victims'' looking to sue.
</P>
<P>
   TASC's technology can identify a spill by the way it looks on
the floor and the way it slowly grows irregularly in shape. With a
camera trained on the detergent and cooking-oil aisles, the system
could send an alarm to supermarket managers that there's a puddle
that needs to be cleaned up. Meanwhile, it would begin making a
digital video archive that could help a supermarket defend itself
against an accident suit _ or prove the plaintiff dumped the pool
of Tide that made him sprain his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Or, by identifying and counting carts, the system could detect
that five or more shoppers are backed up in a checkout line. It
could then send an alert by pager to the overworked store manager
telling her she needs to open up another register.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond preventing problems, the system might be used to gather
valuable information for store owners: How many people come into
the store each hour? Where do they go first? How long do they spend
in each department? What aisle displays catch their eyes?
</P>
<P>
   A system that prevented a multimillion-dollar slip-and-fall tort
claim might pay for itself. Officials expect the system would cost
around $75,000 for the digital cameras needed in an average-size
supermarket, plus $5,000 per ``module,'' or monitoring add-on
dedicated to looking for a specific problem, such as spills or
people running or checkout line backups.
</P>
<P>
   While TASC executives admit it may sound Big Brother-y, they
gamely suggest some people might be more comfortable knowing they
are being watched by an objective piece of software rather than
another person who could be fascinated by their efforts to readjust
their underwear in the pasta aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer just doesn't care that Joe Customer is scratching
himself in aisle 6,'' said Stuart E. Peskoe, TASC's director of
transportation systems.
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at howe(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
