<HEADLINE>
INSIDE THE BODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Second in an occasional series on millennial London.
</P>
<P>
   Here we go into the belly of The Body. Watch out _ the gastric
juices are flowing and a whole lot more is going on!
</P>
<P>
   The Body is a shimmering seven-story structure inside London's
Millennium Dome. The structure, worthy of an art museum, depicts a
male and female figure in a gentle, reclining embrace. Visitors
walk through enclosed spaces, up an escalator, and then down and
out, visiting arms, legs, a pumping heart, and even a wisecracking,
fez-wearing brain along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Body is one of 14 exhibit-filled ``zones'' within the Dome,
which will be open this year only. The multimillion-dollar
attraction was greeted with withering reviews from the British
press, but word of mouth has been kinder. Every attraction may not
be a stunner, but at the Dome you can explore the future,
experience visual tricks such as watching yourself grow older, gaze
at a 21-karat blue diamond, and _ in the center of all the activity
_ see a live show with 200 performers that includes fireworks,
bungee jumpers on stilts, and a graceful ballet high in the sky.
Here are a few fab facts:
</P>
<P>
   --The Dome has the world's biggest roof, measuring some 25
acres. It is, in fact, the largest domed structure in the world _
twice the size of the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   --The inside volume of more than 6 million square feet would
hold 12.8 million barrels of beer, or 18,000 double-decker buses.
If inverted under Niagara Falls, the Dome would take more than 10
minutes to fill with water.
</P>
<P>
   --Its futuristic masts lean at three times the angle of the
Tower of Pisa and are 131 feet taller.
</P>
<P>
   --With 1 million square feet of fabric, it is the largest fabric
structure in the world. It is also the strongest fabric building,
able to support a jumbo jet _ or the force of James Bond plummeting
from the sky onto the Dome roof in the movie ``The World Is Not
Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dome tickets are about $32 for adults and $26 for children
5-15; children younger than 5 are free. Tickets are sold in a
number of places and are part of many travel packages. There are
various ways to get to the Dome, which is in Greenwich, but one of
the most pleasant is a 45-minute riverboat ride down the Thames,
beginning near the London Eye, passing by Big Ben and the Tower of
London, and going under the Tower Bridge. Round-trip tickets are
about $13 for adults and $9 for children. For more information
about the Dome or all of London, call the British Tourist Authority
at 800-462-2748 or visit www.LondonTown.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: Which African nation's capital is named after a
US president? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   In a name: In Australia, poker machines, slot machines, and
other gambling machines are known collectively as pokies.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``The fool who traveled is better off than the wise
man who stayed home'' _ Rashi, an 11th-century scholar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today &LR; 's loopy law: Carrizozo, N.M., forbids women to appear in
public with unshaven legs (or faces, if needed).
</P>
<P>
   Who knew? When celebrities are publicizing a movie or play in
London, they want to be recognized and stay in a high-profile
hotel. But when they want to escape from it all, some stay at the
Cliveden Town House, a lushly landscaped 35-room hotel at Cadogen
Gardens. Sometimes the stars are recognizable, but at other times,
we're told, the celebs look so different that few would know them.
(And, no, the hotel won't tell you who stays there.) For more
information about Cliveden Town House, visit www.
</P>
<P>
   clivedenhouse.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Fascinating fact: Because of Denver's mile-high altitude, water
boils at 202 degrees instead of 212. Thus it takes four minutes to
boil a three-minute egg.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide Web site: TicketPlanet.com specializes in discounted
air fares for destinations around the world, and offers plans that
include multiple stops. For instance, a package that begins at
$1,497 through Oct. 1 takes you from Boston to Bali to Bangkok to
Nepal to a choice of European cities, then back to Boston. The site
is www.ticketplanet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Netting a first: Pennsylvania became the first state in the
country to put the state's Web site _ www.state.pa.us _ on license
plates. But it surely won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   Take a bathrobe home . . . legally: There's nothing rocky about
the Rockresorts Experience Package, available in June and July at
four luxury resorts. Each adult guest who stays at least three
nights will receive a Rockresorts signature bathrobe. The nightly
double occupancy rate is from $139 at Cheeca Lodge in the Florida
Keys, $300 at CuisinArt Resort &AMP; Spa in Anguilla, $179 at La Posada
de Santa Fe Resort &AMP; Spa, and $195 at Rosario Resort &AMP; Spa in the
San Juan Islands of the Pacific Northwest. For more information,
call 800-223-7637 or visit www.rockresorts.com.
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? Monrovia, Liberia, named after James Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Tidbits is compiled from wire-service reports, news
releases, books, magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of
the author's mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits,
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to
carpenter(at)globe.com. Include your name and community.
</P>
</TEXT>
