<HEADLINE>
MONTOYA CROSSES BRIDGE BETWEEN RIVAL FACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ For a moment Sunday, it seemed the hostilities
between Championship Auto Racing Teams and the Indy Racing League
had been put aside.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the squabble between open-wheel series
came together and recognized the extraordinary talent of Juan
Montoya after the 24-year-old Colombian, the reigning CART FedEx
Series champion, won the 84th Indianapolis 500 in his first
appearance at the fabled Brickyard.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Montoya won over his IRL peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid's a hell of a race driver,'' said car owner A.J. Foyt,
a four-time Indy 500 winner who has long been a proponent of the
IRL.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hat's off to him, because he's a really, really, really
good race car driver,'' said runner-up Buddy Lazier, the 1996 Indy
500 winner who subjected Montoya to a hot pursuit only to get
caught in traffic. ``This was one of the hardest races in my eight
starts here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have compared him to Ayrton Senna, and maybe he
will be,'' said Chilean Eliseo Salazar, who finished third. ``But
he's an awesome race car driver.''
</P>
<P>
   And for one unforgettable race, Montoya was one of them.
Although Lazier said IRL drivers had joked among themselves that
``we can't let these CART guys win,'' Montoya clearly shared their
desire to win the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were here just like any other IRL team, believe me,'' said
Montoya, who became the first rookie since Graham Hill in 1996 and
seventh overall to win the 500. ``We're not here with any CART
flags or anything like that. Right now, in my position, (team
owner) Chip (Ganassi) decided to have an IRL team for the 500 and
that's the way we took it. I look at myself like any other driver
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard work submitted by Montoya and members of the
Target/Chip Ganassi Racing crew, which has won the last four CART
championships, was as impressive as it was expansive. From the time
they took possession of their G-Force chassis and
Comp-Tech-prepared Oldsmobile Aurora engines three months ago, Team
Target began its two-car assault on the Indy 500, all the while
struggling to win its first CART race of the season.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, Montoya, Vasser, and their respective
crews were subjected to difficult working conditions by Mother
Nature. A race in Motegi, Japan, was rained out, causing a delay in
their arrival at Indy for the time trials. A CART race at Nazareth,
Pa., that was snowed out April 9 and rescheduled for the day before
the Indy 500 added to Team Target's workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked an awful lot of our teams in the last two months,''
said Ganassi, who visited Victory Lane at Indy for the first time
as a car owner. ``Whether it was testing an IRL car, jumping past a
lot of the drivers, jumping back and forth between IRL to CART,
CART to IRL . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, that's a lot of work, and when you're in a
position of management sometimes you ask yourself, `Are you asking
too much of your people?' The rewards like this, I guess, taste
that much sweeter to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Will this be the first trickle in a flood of CART teams
returning to Indy? Will Ganassi even come back next year? Or, for
that matter, Montoya, who is rumored to be on his way to Formula
One?
</P>
<P>
   ``All week everybody was always interested in the political side
of things and I was not into that, and I'm still not,'' Ganassi
said. ``This is still a big race. When we walked out this morning
through Gasoline Alley with Jimmy and Juan, I was keyed up. This is
still the biggest race in the world and it's the biggest win in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now that's what it means to me and it's obviously going
to mean a lot more as time passes.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it mean enough to want to do it all over again as
defending champion next year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that our team is going to be able to do the right
thing, whatever that entails as the future comes,'' said Ganassi.
``Certainly, I'm going to run here. So, I just hope we can do the
right thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
