<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CASTAWAYS-PREVIEW-LAD     05-30 1736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTAWAYS-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME IT'S REAL CASTAWAYS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box and cast list below; ``tonight'' refers to Wed., May
31.) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For ``Survivor,'' which debuts tonight on CBS, 16 contestants
were unceremoniously dumped on the remote, virtually deserted
island Pulau Tiga in the South China Sea back in March. There, they
spent 39 days building crude huts, scrapping for food, bickering
with one another and engaging in contests for meager amenities (a
map to fresh water, waterproof matches, a cell-phone call home).
</P>
<P>
   Rats nibbled their dried skin while they slept (and lured
rat-eating snakes near the compounds); contestants reciprocated by
feasting on the vermin when other food supplies dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Cordy, a 38-year-old mother of two and former Air Force
survival instructor who was one of the show's participants, reports
that not only is rat as a delicacy pretty much as unpleasant as it
sounds _ ``They smell really gamy, like something you would not
want to put in your mouth, but after they're cooked, when you're
really hungry, they're not so bad'' _ but it was scarcely worth the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``A buffalo wing has 10 times more meat on it,'' she says.
``When you consider all the calories it takes catching and cleaning
them, they're not really that nourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   For all that, however, in Mark Burnett's estimation, his
rough-and- ready game show/reality series _ ``dramality'' is the
term his crew devised for it _ turned out to be more Campaign 2000
than ``Lord of the Flies.''
</P>
<P>
   The final contestant left on the island won $1 million (CBS is
trying to keep the winner's identity a secret) _ but competitors
weren't whittled away through attrition or cannibalism. Every three
days, the group assembled for a ``tribal council'' and voted to
bounce one of the castaways. Ousters could occur because someone
wasn't contributing meaningfully, or because someone didn't like
his or her looks. Forget the pythons and the venomous sea snakes _
the tribal councils were where the real cutthroat activity
occurred. Burnett was amazed by the venal politics at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven weeks in a row, my jaw dropped; I was dumbfounded at who
got voted off,'' Burnett says. ``There was a lot at stake, and it
involved the best or worst of office politics. People were
duplicitous, but very few people win anything or rise in their job
by being 100 percent on the straight and narrow. I gained an
enormous respect for their duplicity. These people are playing
against one another and some people forgot that. It was fascinating
to watch how clever some of them were at playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' based on a European TV series (like CBS' other
upcoming orgy of voyeurism, ``Big Brother''), will run 13 weeks.
Burnett says the participants underwent intense psychological and
physical scrutiny to ascertain whether they had the mettle to
endure not only the island's unforgiving primitivism, but also the
potential for being embarrassed on national television through
getting voted out of the contest. (One contestant in the European
version, whom Burnett claims had psychological problems before
appearing on the series, committed suicide after leaving the
island.)
</P>
<P>
   Burnett says that even though contestant arguments account for a
lot of the show's drama, he didn't cast the survivors with an eye
towards skirmishes. ``I did the opposite of that,'' he says. ``I
knew I would get conflicts without turning it into a `Jerry
Springer' kind of show that nobody would want to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   His cast of castaways turned out to be tougher than he expected.
``I was afraid they'd find the island offered too much suffering
and there'd be mass quitting,'' he says. ``One time, after five or
six days of nonstop rain, I got soft and gave them a map for fruit
_ and they were offended. They said, `Screw you, keep your map.'
They had crossed that line, they were taking it very seriously.''
When contestants were voted off, he reports, they merely shrugged,
laughed and asked for a beer.
</P>
<P>
   There was one problem: ``Some people thought it was cool to be
nude all the time,'' Burnett says. ``When people wanted to walk
around nude to an annoying level, I heard a producer told them to
put their clothes on, and I yelled at him. Our only rules were: No
violence, and no colluding to split the million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you'll see tonight: A mile off the coast of Pulau
Tiga, the contestants were abruptly given two minutes to abandon
the fishing boat transporting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some jumped off in one second, and didn't take anything;
others spent a little time gathering things like fruit or an extra
knife,'' Burnett _ or, as the contestants called him, the Marquis
de Sade _ recalls. ``There were two rafts behind the boat, and some
large boxes of provisions, which were enormous trouble to bring to
shore. It was the first test of group dynamics.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordy says the abandon-ship edict was virtually the only time
she really wondered what she had gotten herself into.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked someone to hold the raft so people could throw
things off,'' Cordy remembers. ``When we threw the mandatory box
onto the raft, it broke open, and a couple of us jumped into the
water to retrieve the stuff. It was sinking, and it was all
disorganized and chaotic, as if it was a real sinking ship. It was
very realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordy was in the water, pulling a chest toward the raft. ``Then
I saw this big black thing in the water coming toward me, and I was
hoping to God it was just a shadow. I got to thinking of the
Discovery Channel's Shark Week, and wondered, `Is this gonna end
right here?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so embarrassed _ as it got closer and closer and closer,
I realized it was a cameraman underwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordy admits that although her stint in the Air Force came in
handy _ she was able to start fires using a team member's
eyeglasses _ it also ``overprepared me a bit. When we first got
there, we took inventory of what we had _ we had thrown cans of
food onto the raft, and rice. My big thing was, `We're not eating
this stuff. We don't need to. We need to save the food for as long
as can. That was kind of a battle between us, and we ended up with
more food than I thought we would.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramona (one of the survivors) wanted to open a can of beans,
and I said, `We need to save this.' She and I were unhappy with
each other. When we got back home, I sent her a 10-pound can of
beans.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first couple of weeks, some of the competitions Burnett
staged were ``immunity challenges'' _ the prize was an ``immunity
idol,'' a token declaring that no one from the winning team could
be voted off the island during the tribal council. Later, when the
teams consolidated, individuals won the right to immunity,
symbolized by an immunity necklace.
</P>
<P>
   For Cordy, the tribal councils were some of the most trying
times. ``I thought I wouldn't bond with people, but I really liked
everybody,'' she says. ``Everyone had something to offer. I was
never concerned with the physical challenges or lack of food. For
me, that was easy part. What I hadn't prepared for was to put
someone's life or reputation in my own hands. It got ludicrous _ I
would hope someone ticked me off just before the council meeting so
I'd have someone to vote off.''
</P>
<P>
   A contest airing on tonight's episode involves a race to set a
giant burning-man statue afire, while keeping a string of tiki
torches lit on a raft in the ocean and on the land. In another
competition, the survivors had to retrieve treasure chests filled
with useful items from the ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   But Burnett says what viewers will most remember are the
colorful characters populating Pulau Tiga. ``There are a couple of
people you'll never forget,'' he says. ``I can imagine a couple of
them coming on David Letterman regularly, offering their views on
life. A couple should be turned into little dolls _ when you press
it, it comes out with its sayings.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Cordy's favorites was Gervase, a Philadelphia basketball
coach who had never roughed it before _ except, of course, in
Philadelphia, which is no picnic. ``He impressed me very much,''
she says. ``Right off, when we were jumping off the ship and our
box broke and things were falling in the water, he jumped in after
them, even though he had only had four weeks of swimming lessons.
Right off the bat, he was really ready to give this a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supplies we had _ for Gervase, they were nothing, but I'd
think, `Wow, we have a machete'; I knew what we could do with it.
Every time I thought that something would throw him, he'd work
harder. The heat was oppressive to him, so he'd get up earlier in
morning and work harder. He hadn't been camping before, and there
he was, sleeping under the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only would Cordy return for another round of ``Survivor'' _
in a ``heartbeat'' _ but she thinks Burnett could franchise the
series as a sort of amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it could become one of those things that rich people pay
big bucks for,'' she suggests. ``They'll pay Mark well to treat
them badly.'' &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The show: ``Survivor.'' &QL; 
What: Reality contest placing participants on a deserted island and
forcing them to fend for themselves. &QL; 
Where: CBS (Channel 2). &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Wednesdays, starting tonight &QL; 
Contestants:
</P>
<P>
   - Kelley, 22 (single), river guide, Las Vegas, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   - Dirk, 23 (single), substitute teacher, Spring Green, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   - Rudy, 72 (married), retired Navy SEAL, Virginia Beach, Va.
</P>
<P>
   - Sean, 30 (single), neurologist, Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   - Susan, 38 (married), truck driver, Palmyra, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   - Stacey, 27 (single), attorney, San Francisco, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   - Richard, 38 (single), corporate trainer, Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   - Sonja, 62 (single), musician, cancer survivor, Walnut Creek,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   - Greg, 24 (single), journeyman, Gold Hill, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   - Jenna, 22 (single), college student, Franklin, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   - Gervase, 30 (single), youth basketball coach, Philadelphia,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   - Joel, 27 (single), traveling salesman, Sherwood, Alaska
</P>
<P>
   - Colleen, 23 (single), college student, Miami Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   - Ramona, 28 (single), biochemist, Edison, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   - B.B., 64 (married), retired contractor, Mission Hills, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   - Gretchen Cordy, 38 (married), homemaker, former Air Force
survival instructor, Clarksville, Tenn. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
