<HEADER>
A9697 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-30 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S MARCH TO THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a famous inside-Boston story: how developers in the late
1960s, intent on building the city's first downtown skyscraper
since the 1920s, trooped from lender to lender with their plans.
</P>
<P>
   The local money men all said no. They knew Boston had been
declining for 75 years, that its central business district was
complete, the Custom House Tower its single tall centerpiece. The
Prudential building, which had gone up on an empty rail yard in the
early 1960s, was an anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   The only prosperous businesses left to speak of in the city were
its law firms and money managers. They would never leave their
tradition-bound offices along State Street, the city's
pre-Revolutionary thoroughfare, for a sterile tower.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Edinburgh, a money-management center quite like Boston
in many respects, did the developers find lenders willing to defy
the local conventional wisdom. The canny Scots put up the money for
225 Franklin Street.
</P>
<P>
   And when construction finally did begin on the the eastern side
of Post Office Square, across the street from what was then the
Federal Reserve Bank, tenants flocked to sign long-term leases at
lofty prices. Boston's staid First National Bank soon would follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
   The city's downtown has been moving toward the waterfront ever
since. But too little attention has been paid to how Boston will
change once its new South Boston Waterfront district is built.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to recognize is that the neigborhood across Fort
Point Channel already has its anchor tenant. It is the new federal
courthouse, an enormous building of H.H. Richardsonian proportions
that perches at the Fan Pier's edge.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the city's prosperous law firms remain scattered in a
270-degree arc around the old WPA-style courthouse in Post Office
Square, half a mile away. In all likelihood, they'll begin moving
to the vicinity of the new federal building, singly or in groups,
as soon as new office towers around the waterfront are ready to
accommodate them.
</P>
<P>
   Across the wasteland of present-day parking lots to the west are
the dot-com lofts and artists' studios of the old Leather District.
Around the corner will be the new convention center in due course.
But the law firms will provide a solid commercial organizing
principle for the new district.
</P>
<P>
   The second thing to recognize about the South Boston Waterfront
is that it will be at the foot of the newly extended Massachusetts
Turnpike _ a straight shot to the office towers' underground
parking garage, especially from the suburban west. The weak link is
the MBTA's ``Silver Line,'' which so far is little more than a bus
route. The problem of mass transit doesn't have to be solved at
once, but it remains a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The third thing is to understand that the new district has
virtually nothing to do with South Boston, aside from the current
jockeying over legislative clout. Another 10 years and the
waterfront will be a second little city nestled next to the first,
presumably with its own representation on the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the waterfront will grow out to the Reserve Channel
on the east and to West Broadway on the south. Clever Edward C.
``Ned'' Johnson of Fidelity Investments already has nailed down the
middle of the district, with his World Trade Center, a hotel, and
an office building. There's plenty of room for housing away from
the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   What will grow up in the rest of the thousand acres, where a
miscellany of fish-packing plants, bakeries, steel fabrication
facilities, and health clubs now nestle cheek by jowl, is anybody's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   It is important that it not somehow become a gated community in
an urban setting, as critics fear; important, too, to recognize the
pressure it will put on South Boston to gentrify. But this much is
clear already: Boston's glorious urban mansion is about to add a
grand new wing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
