<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-ART-37     05-30 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-ART-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BEGINS WEEK-LONG EUROPE VISIT IN PORTUGAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton began the last scheduled European trip of his
presidency Tuesday in Portugal, the first visit there by a U.S.
president in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio formally welcomed Clinton
before the two leaders sat down for discussions at the Belem
Palace, on the outskirts of Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   In his welcoming speech, Sampaio said: ``Globalization requires
the international community to take responsibility for the future
of our planet. The United States of America has a decisive role in
this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the 16th-century Tower of Belem, at the mouth of
Lisbon's harbor, Clinton said that Portuguese explorers had sailed
past the monument on their voyages to discover the New World. He
described Portugal as leading the way to ``a new voyage of
discovery'' over horizons ranging from the Internet to world
poverty and the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was greeted at the airport by about 150 U.S. and
Portuguese schoolchildren. He also reviewed an honor guard of
Portuguese soldiers, some of whom will be taking up peacekeeping
duties in East Timor, a former Portuguese colony claimed by
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The president was scheduled to meet Portugal's prime minister,
Antonio Guterrez, later Tuesday to discuss political and trade
issues.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton is expected to again take up trade
differences when meeting with Sampaio and senior officials of the
European Union. Portugal currently holds the rotating presidency of
the 15-member body.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan was the last U.S. president to visit Portugal, in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   After Portugal, Clinton's weeklong tour of four countries will
take him to Germany, Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   The trip will consist primarily of bilateral meetings on trade
and other issues, with no breakthrough expected with Russia on arms
control issues.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and U.S. officials announced Tuesday that Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak would fly to Berlin Thursday to meet with
Clinton and discuss the latest developments in the Middle East.
Barak planned to meet Clinton in Washington last week but postponed
the trip because of the Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon
and outbreaks of violence in Palestinian territories.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A statement issued by Barak's office in Jerusalem said, ``The
two men will discuss the Middle East peace process in general and
the implications of the withdrawal from Lebanon and ways to advance
the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations in particular.'' The closed
negotiations broke off in Stockholm earlier this month, and the
Palestinian side, complaining of lack of progress, wants them to be
relocated closer to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Portugal, Clinton is scheduled to fly to Germany,
where he will give a foreign policy speech in Aachen on Europe's
future and receive a prize for contributing to world peace and
European unity.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday and Saturday, Clinton will attend a conference in
Berlin on so-called ``third way'' politics that offer alternatives
to free market capitalism and welfare-state liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   The high point of Clinton's trip is expected to be his address
to the Duma, the lower house of the Russian parliament. He is also
scheduled to meet with President Vladimir Putin on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to stop in Kiev on Monday to see the president of
Ukraine, Leonid Kuchma, and urge the former Soviet republic to push
ahead with economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is being accompanied by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Commerce Secretary William Daley and the White House
national security adviser, Sandy Berger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
