</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BARAK-0531-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO MEET WITH BARAK, BEGINS WEEK OF POLITICAL TALKS,
SUMMITRY IN EUROPE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON _ Hoping to rescue the Middle East peace process amid a
series of fast-moving events, President Clinton will meet Thursday
in Berlin with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, the White House
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders will assess how the prospects for peace have
been affected by Israel's surprise pull-out from southern Lebanon
and a spate of renewed violence between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the president and the prime minister believe that it is
important for them to meet at this time,'' White House spokesman
Joseph Lockhart said in a statement released Tuesday to reporters
traveling here with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in Lisbon Tuesday, where he was greeted with a
21-gun salute from one of three Portuguese navy ships lying at
anchor off the white stone Tower of Belem.
</P>
<P>
   The 16th Century fortress is a symbol of Portugal's past glory
as an imperial seafaring power. It stands near the launch site of
dozens of 15th Century Portuguese explorations, including those of
such adventurers as Vasco da Gama and Ferdinand Magellan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our increasingly globalized world owes a lot to their deeds,''
said President Jorge Sampaio, as Clinton stood at his side beneath
cloudless skies on a spectacular spring morning.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed Portugal's mariners for leading ``an entire
continent to see beyond the horizon,'' and called for all of Europe
to join a 21st Century age of medical discovery and search for
affordable ways to rid the developing world of AIDS, tuberculosis
and malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton intends to build on that theme on Wednesday, when he
meets here with his counterparts from the 15-member European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has asked Congress for $325 million to combat AIDS
overseas and another $1 billion in tax credits to promote private
AIDS-related research, will propose that the EU adopt similar
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we'll come out of that meeting with a common approach
to the health crisis,'' Clinton told a group of scientists and
researchers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a solemn responsibility,'' he said, ``to take the
benefits of the information economy, of the explosion in biomedical
discoveries, and use them to give every young person in the world
the chance to live up to their God-given potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, in particular, has long experience working on the AIDS
problem in Africa through its five former colonies there, Angola,
Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, Cape Verde, and Sao Tome and Principe.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration recently announced it now regards the
world AIDS epidemic, which is particularly acute in Africa, as a
threat to U.S. national security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces EU resistance, however, over a number of issues
dividing the United States and Europe, including trade flaps over
U.S. beef exports _ the EU is resisting meat treated with hormone
additives _ European subsidies for the Airbus airliner
manufacturing company and European policies that discriminate
against Caribbean bananas.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked Clinton whether he will solve long-running
US-European Union trade disputes over beef and bananas, Clinton
replied: ``I hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton travels on Thursday to Germany, where he is to meet with
a host of international leaders at a governance conference. Barak,
who will also attend the conference, will meet separately with
Clinton before the conference begins Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Palestinian and Israeli negotiators set to return to
Stockholm Thursday to resume talks on developing a road map toward
a final peace accord, Clinton hopes to pull together a summer
summit among himself, Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had been scheduled to meet with Clinton last week in
Washington. The visit was called off, however, in the wake of the
worst clashes in more than three years between Israelis and
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, Barak stunned regional actors by pulling out of
southern Lebanon, ordering his troops to end, in an overnight
withdrawal, Israel's 18-year occupation of a swath of Lebanese
land.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat have set a September 13 deadline for resolving
the tough issues that stand between them and a permanent peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes a Barak-Arafat summit in the weeks ahead will nail
down a framework agreement, or blueprint, outlining the issues
remaining to be resolved. Among those are the future of Jerusalem,
the question of Palestinian statehood and the right of Palestinian
refugees to return to Israeli-occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to convene a meeting with the president, Prime
Minister Barak and Chairman Arafat when the time is right,'' said
White House spokesman P.J. Crowley. ``Between now and September 13,
we hope to move the process along with a framework agreement, and
that's what we are working on now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to Portugal begins a weeklong swing through
Europe that will also take him to Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
