<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CIBA-VISION-STREET &LR;      05-30 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIBA-VISION-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIBA VISION TO BUY WESLEY JESSEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN KOO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than two months of dueling with Bausch &AMP; Lomb
(BOL:NYSE), specialty contact lens maker Wesley Jessen VisionCare
(WJCO:Nasdaq) rebuffed the takeover bid of the No. 1 maker of soft
contact lenses by market share, signing on Tuesday to be bought by
Ciba Vision for about $785 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The move will form the second-largest contact lens company in
the world by revenue behind Johnson &AMP; Johnson (JNJ:NYSE).
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition cancels the March 20 all-stock merger agreement
between Wesley Jessen and Ocular Sciences (OCLR:Nasdaq), which was
valued at $552 million on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ciba Vision, the eye care unit of Novartis (NVS:NYSE ADR), the
fourth-largest pharmaceutical company in the world, based in Basel,
Switzerland, trumped Bausch &AMP; Lomb by agreeing to pay $38.50 a
share for Wesley Jessen, based in Des Plaines, Ill., a premium of 8
percent to Bausch &AMP; Lomb's final bid. The offer is also a 16
percent premium to Wesley Jessen's closing price Friday of 33 3/16
and a 55 percent premium to its closing price on March 22, the day
before Bausch &AMP; Lomb made its first offer.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close in the third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Days after Wesley Jessen agreed to buy Ocular Sciences, Bausch &AMP;
Lomb swooped in with an offer of $34 a share in cash for Wesley
Jessen. Wesley Jessen rejected both that offer and the subsequent
offer of $35.55 a share in cash, at the same time that it announced
discussions with a third party that would conceivably consider
buying Wesley Jessen as well as Ocular Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Ocular Sciences, though left in the cold, is $25 million richer
after collecting the breakup fee from Wesley Jessen.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Jessen is the largest maker of cosmetic lenses that
change or enhance a wearer's eye color, the second-largest growth
segment for contact lenses. Meanwhile, Ciba Vision makes contact
lenses, lens care products and drugs for the eyes. The two
companies had pro forma sales of $1.4 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
