<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9762 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-30 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO LOSING ITS FAMILY FEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This is a city that eats grilled radicchio and
miso-glazed cod, but spits out its small businesses, old people and
children.
</P>
<P>
   Attention Mayor Willie Brown and the San Francisco Board of
Supervisors _ your city is disappearing. Something has to be done,
or this won't be a city at all, but a shiny theme park for the rich
and the childless.
</P>
<P>
   Families can't make the rent or buy homes. Just on Friday, the
Pani-E-Dolci bakery, in the once-obscure San Francisco neighborhood
of Dogpatch, and the Garden Juice Bar, near the heart of the
Tenderloin, closed because the owners couldn't pay huge rent
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Now a preschool and 50 kids are being evicted.
</P>
<P>
   On May 10, the Montessori Children's Center received a notice of
eviction saying the school has until June 30 to be out of the
building it has occupied for 24 years on the grounds of the huge
Parkmerced housing development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if this is something like a hairdresser's shop and
you can pack up your things and go,'' said Judith Flynn, the
director of the school. ``You can't just go to a storefront and
open a school. We're licensed by the Department of Social Services,
and it would take at least two years. You're dealing with children
here. You're dealing with human lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-four years, and the school gets 50 days notice it has
to move,'' said Kathy Jones, whose 41/2-year-old daughter, Jessica,
was scheduled to be promoted to kindergarten at the school in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 50 children with nowhere to go,'' said Jones. ``It's
past the deadline to apply to another school. I'll have to
home-school her, but I'm not a teacher. She's about to start
reading, and she needs to be around other children.''
</P>
<P>
   Even over the phone, it was clear Jones was shaking with anger,
but she stayed level and understated the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is unfriendly to families,''she said.
</P>
<P>
   Parkmerced was bought last July by Carmel Companies, a real
estate firm with offices in Denver and San Francisco, for a figure
that was reported to be more than $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bert Polacci, the chief operating officer in
California for Carmel, told The Examiner, ``We're proud to have
this storied piece of San Francisco history.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the previous ownership of that storied piece of San
Francisco history, the little school on the grounds was listed in
brochures as one of the pluses of living at Parkmerced.
</P>
<P>
   Polacci said the sole reason Carmel is evicting the Montessori
Children's Center is because it's an insurance liability. ``If
someone sues them, you know who they're coming after,'' Polacci
said.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said that in the 24 years of the school's history, no one
has ever sued. She offered to raise the insurance coverage to $15
million, but Carmel still wants them gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them how long an extension they wanted, but they came
back with two years, and that seemed like an incredible request,''
said Polacci.
</P>
<P>
   Come fall, the kids will be out on the street, in the home, or
wherever little kids go when they don't have a school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if this is a private school, that's 50
places for kids gone,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Polacci said he's a native San Franciscan who knows how tough
the real estate market is, and how hard it is to put kids through
school. But he's adamant that liability is a problem for the
school, which pays $500 a month for a building originally designed
as a rec center.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd love to build a real state-of-the-art school at
Parkmerced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they come say that to us?'' said Flynn. ``It would
be my dream.''
</P>
<P>
   A school is a little world within a world, and the Montessori
Children's Center is a little world of 50 kids from 14 different
ethnic groups, a small mirror of the city outside. Now the kids
suffer the economic problems of the city outside, and something new
in San Francisco _ school-lessness.
</P>
<P>
   Young Rebecca Wright, daughter of Kathy Jones and her husband
David Wright, faces involuntary home-schooling in a home her
parents have to rent because they can't afford to buy. And Rebecca
is one of the lucky ones, because her mom is able to stay at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just one small period in the big picture,'' said Flynn
of the Montessori school, ``a picture that encompasses Carmel and
Parkmerced, as well as San Francisco. We need to really look at
what's happening in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this going to be a city that's a real community? Or is it
going to be friendly only to dot-commers and those with big
money?'' Flynn asked.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night at 7 p.m., the parents and staff of the
Montessori Children's Center will meet at the school to discuss
what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent invitations to city officials and officers of the
Carmel Company, but we haven't heard back,'' said Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be there, and I think a few city officials may show up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
