<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9772 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-30 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SHE LOVES THE NEW SAN FRANCISCO BASEBALL STADIUM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By STEPHANIE SALTER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C.2000 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Maybe by next year I'll decide if I prefer the
new ballpark when the Giants are at home or on the road.
</P>
<P>
   All I know now is that _ in this, Pacific Bell Park's inaugural
season _ the cozy little red-brick baseball stadium makes me feel
like a teenager with a major crush:
</P>
<P>
   Rain, shine, game days or no, I just wanna be near the object of
my affection.
</P>
<P>
   Not even two months into the Giants' first season at Pac Bell,
sets of encyclopedia already have been written about the
40,000-seat park. Even the most jaded sports writers and no-growth
environmentalists seem to love the place.
</P>
<P>
   But almost all of the reviews have come from people who actually
go into the park to watch baseball. Although I've been to one game,
I'm in love with Pacific Bell Park from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   I like everything about it. The way it occupies space, casts
shadows, reflects light and somehow excites the eye as it soothes.
</P>
<P>
   I like looking at it from blocks away, south on China Basin
Street, or from close up, beside the deep-green steel supports of
its scoreboard and light banks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, I like the life that now emanates from the
junction of Third and King streets, even when there's no game going
on.
</P>
<P>
   People come down to Pac Bell just to hang around. Alone or in
family clusters, they walk along its wide bayside promenade,
rollerblade or bike among its instant groves of giant palm trees,
peer through the ``knothole'' section at the grounds crews, or just
stand and stare up at the marvelous statue of Willie Mays _ about
to take the first steps of an exuberant home-run trot around the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   I know about people hanging out at Pac Bell because the park has
become the centerpiece of a running route I have been pounding (off
and on) for close to two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Back when I began _ when a downtown baseball stadium was but a
gleam in the eye of former Giants owner Bob Lurie _ the whole China
Basin area was remote, rundown and not a little spooky.
</P>
<P>
   My kind of place.
</P>
<P>
   The streets were wide and griddle flat, car and truck traffic
was minimal, and parking was an embarrassment of riches.
</P>
<P>
   Starting off somewhere around Mariposa and Illinois streets, I'd
head north for as long a loop as my legs and lungs would take me _
Pier 23 on a good day, South Beach Marina on a normal one.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the run was always when I'd thump across the
wooden pedestrian sidewalk of Lefty O'Doul Bridge at Third Street.
</P>
<P>
   A long look to the right was rewarded with the ever-changing
color of San Francisco Bay, then the Oakland skyline and hills
beyond. Just past the bridge, as I rounded the corner of King
Street, I'd brace for the smell of vinegar that seeped from an old
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on game days anyway, I brace myself for the olfactory jolt
of Gilroy Garlic Fries.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard that a major league baseball stadium was going to
be built in the middle of my beloved, spooky China Basin, I was
positive I would hate it. The haunting, timeless quiet of the old
waterside area would be wrecked forever, I knew.
</P>
<P>
   So, for more than a year, I just stopped going down there. I
wanted to remember everything the way it was.
</P>
<P>
   Silly me.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how the architects and builders did it, but Pacific
Bell Park hasn't taken anything away from China Basin. (Multi-media
Gulch and the dot-com invasion already took the parking.) It has
only enhanced it.
</P>
<P>
   Whether I drive by, roll up on Muni or _ best of all _ run
around it on my own two legs _ I always do the same thing: Offer up
a great big ``Thank you!'' to every pair of hands that helped make
this fabulous little baseball park a reality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
