<HEADER>
A9786 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-NAVY-TOWN-HNS &LR;      05-30 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-TOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     S.F. TO HONOR ITS HERITAGE AS A NAVY TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco was once a Navy town, but you'd
never know it today. Not so long ago, tens of thousands of
bluejackets _ along with Marines, Coast Guardsmen and Merchant
Mariners _ swarmed our streets, drank our booze and hit on our
women (and our men, too, doubtlessly).
</P>
<P>
   White caps of sailors on liberty were everywhere, but Market
Street was the gangway into the city and North Beach the galley.
</P>
<P>
   There were naval air stations in Alameda and Mountain View,
naval shipyards in Hunters Point and at Mare Island, a Navy supply
center in Oakland, a Coast Guard training station in Alameda, a
major Navy base at Treasure Island and other outposts of the four
sea services around the Golden Gate.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, artifacts of the fleet were everywhere. In the
`70s, you could buy old pea coats at Rosalie's on Columbus for $5,
and genuine woolen bell bottoms for $3 in the Mission.
</P>
<P>
   Now if you find anything that's genuine old Navy, it's made in
Sri Lanka and sold in a store on Market Street, or available on
eBay, with bids starting at $50.
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing about these bygone seafarers was that they didn't
look militaristic. They looked like people doing their duty without
enthusiasm, maybe, but with a sense of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   One of them may have been my uncle, Sidney, who saw action in
the Mediterranean and the Far East, and told stories about what
he'd seen and done in North Africa, the Bay of Naples and the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Sid was about 5 foot 7, 150 pounds, a terrific baseball player
and very unwarlike. He was a Navy swabbie, maybe the quintessential
citizen-sailor. I have crystalline half-century-old Kodak slides of
him in his white cap and pea coat, hands thrust into his pockets,
smiling shyly.
</P>
<P>
   You can read his mind. He's thinking, ``I guess I have to deal
with this.'' That, I imagine, is the way millions of men and women
in uniform felt.
</P>
<P>
   And yet they managed to defeat our enemies in World War II,
these befuddled, frightened, skeptical Cincinnatuses of the city
and the country, these ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   But you wouldn't have known it, hiking around the Bay Area on
Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Trione of Santa Rosa, Calif., and Jackson Schultz of
Hillsborough, Calif., are about to change that.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of $2 million in private funds, they plan to erect by
Memorial Day 2001 a 7-foot bronze statue of a sailor with his
duffel bag, standing at a dock. It will be placed at Vista Point,
at the northern (Marin County) end of the Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial, created by artist Stanley Bleifeld, will be a
replica of Bleifeld's U.S. Navy Memorial statue on Pennsylvania
Avenue in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Washington memorial and others elsewhere in the
nation, the San Francisco Lone Sailor Memorial will be the first
dedicated to all four sea services. Vista Point, overlooking the
Gate, the city and the Bay, is the perfect site.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate is more than a symbol of the Bay Area. It's a
symbol of our nation. It was a portal to and from their homeland
for millions of Americans sent overseas. During World War II alone,
more than 1.5 million men and women in uniform shipped out from
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You leave here to go overseas and you go under the bridge and
get your last view of the city and it's a sinking feeling; you're
leaving home behind. That's the last you'll see of the U.S.,'' said
Schultz, a retired Navy captain and former bank executive
co-chairing the project with Trione, a World War II Navy lieutenant
turned mortgage broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bridge is so unique,'' Schultz added. ``Then when you
come back, waiting for the first sight of home after two weeks at
sea, you finally see land, then the bridge, then you know: That's
home! That's San Francisco! And the whole city unfolds . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Trione, a member of the United States Navy
Memorial Foundation in Washington, D.C., pitched the idea to
Schultz of having a similar monument here. Both men also fed the
kitty from the start _ Trione to the extent of $100,000 (all
contributions are tax deductible).
</P>
<P>
   The best place for the statue, they knew right away, was Vista
Point. The problem: It's part of the Golden Gate National
Recreation Area, and the National Park Service has a policy against
memorials. Trione and Schultz went to work on Brian O'Neill,
superintendent of the GGNRA, and then on Robert Stanton, head of
the Park Service. Both decided to make an exception to the rule.
</P>
<P>
   I asked if any anti-military opposition had emerged yet,
remembering the fierce resistance to then-Mayor Dianne Feinstein's
plan to homeport the USS Missouri in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   None at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Vietnam,'' Schultz said. ``This is a timeless
statue, a sailor over the last century in San Francisco; it is
recognizing the role of the sea services.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Trione: ``I think people regret the fact that the Missouri
isn't in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco office of the U.S. Navy Memorial Foundation is
handling the fund raising for the Lone Sailor Memorial. It's at
3450 Sacramento St., 531, in San Francisco, 94118. The Web address
is www.lonesailor.bigstep.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
