<HEADER>
A9798 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CAVE-WRITING-HNS &LR;      05-30 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAVE-WRITING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS DISCOVERY POINTS TO EARLY VISITS BY SPANISH EXPLORERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANDERA, Texas _ An inscription discovered in a cave suggests
that Spaniards, possibly in search of silver or American Indians to
enslave, may have ventured through the Texas Hill Country years
earlier than previously believed.
</P>
<P>
   The notation ``1577 JH'' was found chiseled into the wall of a
cave near Tarpley, a Bandera County community northwest of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance would be, if it could be proven (to be
authentic), is that it is the earliest written inscription in
Texas,'' said Thomas Hester, a University of Texas anthropology
professor, who noted that the previously known Spanish records in
Texas date from the 1580s.
</P>
<P>
   Hester, director of the Texas Archaeological Research Lab in
Austin, was alerted last fall to the markings in what he described
as ``a little shelter or cave.''
</P>
<P>
   What he saw at the site sparked his interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is completely different from any other carvings I've
seen,'' he said Thursday. ``The way it is carved, too, is
important; it has beveled edges.''
</P>
<P>
   The location of the cave, which is on private property, is being
kept confidential to protect it from vandals and artifact
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the ``JH'' superscript was a mystery to
Hester until he mentioned it to Maria Wade, a fellow
anthropologist, who told him 16th-century Jesuits used the letters
as an abbreviation for ``Jesus Jehovah,'' much in the way AD is
short for anno Domini (in the year of our Lord).
</P>
<P>
   That would be consistent with the theory that the marks were
left by associates of Luis De Carvajal, a Portuguese-born Spanish
explorer who attended Jesuit schools as a youth.
</P>
<P>
   Carvajal sailed for ``New Spain'' (Mexico) in 1567 and was
awarded a vast land grant that reached across the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carvajal's jurisdiction extended north to the site of San
Antonio, Texas, and west to include almost all of the Mexican
states of Zacatecas and Durango,'' according to ``Spanish Texas
1519-1821,'' a book by Dr. Donald E. Chipman, a history professor
at the University of North Texas in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   Carvajal is recognized as the first European to cross the Lower
Rio Grande into Texas, according to ``The New Handbook of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as what he was after, we have the words of other people
that he was out-and-out slave-raiding,'' said Robert S. Weddle, who
wrote the handbook entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The date is certainly compatible with his exploits,'' the
79-year-old historian and author said Friday. ``We know of nobody
else who might have done it at that date.''
</P>
<P>
   ``LaSalle claims to have found in 1685 the date of 1588 carved
in a post at an Indian village near the lower Guadalupe River, but
nobody in modern times ever saw that,'' he said. ``So far as we
know, that's the earliest recorded mention of a European
inscription on rocks or trees in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Carvajal's activities inside Texas are not well documented
because he apparently did more than ``pacify'' the Indians and
establish new settlements, as ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to Wade, any people he sent out would not have filed
any reports because they were doing silver exploration in an area
where the king of Spain had prohibited it,'' Hester said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that what appears to be an abandoned mine is only a
mile from the cave in Tarpley.
</P>
<P>
   Carvajal was recalled to Mexico in 1578 to answer accusations
that he had concentrated on slave-trading and silver prospecting
rather than his assigned duties.
</P>
<P>
   He was acquitted, but convicted of heresy a decade later and
died in 1590 in a prison in Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
