<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARM SPICED PINEAPPLE TART 
</HEADLINE>
  (This is the sixth of eight columns by Wylie Dufresne, the chef of
71 Clinton Fresh Food. They are written with Jack Bishop.) 
 By JACK BISHOP    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I don't have an extensive background in pastry, so I
knew that dessert would be the toughest course to develop on my
menu. My shoe-box-size kitchen ruled out any complicated
last-minute preparations. I needed basic recipes.
</P>
<P>
   My warm spiced pineapple tart is a streamlined version of tarte
Tatin. I've kept the caramelized fruit and pastry but simplified
the preparation and improved the presentation. It's good enough to
serve at a restaurant and easy to make at home.
</P>
<P>
   There are two reasons this recipe succeeds. First, pineapple
(especially the golden-skinned variety) is almost always a good
fruit. Second, any tart that starts with puff pastry is a breeze to
assemble. Commercial puff pastry saves a tremendous amount of time
and effort without any sacrifice in quality. (Like many chefs, I
use Dufour, an all-butter brand sold in specialty markets.)
</P>
<P>
   I cut the puff pastry into four-inch circles with a ring mold
and then punch out a hole from the center of each to make the
pastry look like a pineapple ring. Pineapple pieces poached in a
spiced orange syrup are laid over the pastry. Then I bake the tarts
and serve them with coconut ice cream and a drizzle of sauce, made
by reducing the poaching liquid until it has the consistency of a
thin caramel sauce.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like overly sweet desserts, and a sauce made from a
concentrated poaching liquid can become cloying. That's why I cook
four spices with the orange syrup. Cinnamon and vanilla beans add
depth of flavor, while cracked black peppercorns and grated ginger
provide heat. The sauce tastes sweet at first but burns a bit at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple can stand up to these strong flavors, but this tart
could be made with other fruits, especially apricots or plums. Cut
each peeled and pitted fruit into six or eight wedges, then poach
them until tender. Sliced bananas are another possibility and are
even easier: they need no poaching. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WARM SPICED PINEAPPLE TART
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   2 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   2 vanilla beans
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons unsalted butter, cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons finely grated ginger
</P>
<P>
   Generous pinch cracked black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 medium ripe pineapple
</P>
<P>
   Flour for dusting
</P>
<P>
   1 sheet puff pastry (about 14 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   Coconut, vanilla or ginger ice cream
</P>
<P>
   1. Wrap cinnamon in towel and crack with mallet into rough
pieces. Place in dry skillet over medium heat, and toast, shaking
occasionally, until fragrant, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Transfer cinnamon to medium saucepan. With paring knife,
split vanilla beans lengthwise and scrape out seeds. Place beans
and seeds in pan; add butter, ginger, pepper, sugar and juice.
Bring to boil over high heat, whisking to dissolve sugar. Remove
from heat, cover and steep 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Trim top and bottom from pineapple. Cut in half lengthwise;
reserve half for another use. Peel remainder, and cut in half again
lengthwise. Cut away core, and cut each piece crosswise into
\-inch-thick pieces.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add pineapple to syrup, and return to a boil. Reduce heat,
and simmer gently until tender, 5 minutes. (Don't overcook.) Remove
from heat; cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   5. Unfold puff pastry, and roll on floured surface into
13-by-9-inch rectangle. Punch out six 4-inch disks, then cut out a
1-inch circle from center of each. Prick pastry with tines of fork.
Place on parchment-lined baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   6. Use slotted spoon to lift pineapple onto paper towels to blot
dry. (Reserve syrup in saucepan.) Discard any large cinnamon bits.
Arrange pineapple pieces over pastry, 6 or 7 pieces on each ring,
with narrow end of pieces pointing inward. If necessary, trim
pineapple so that pieces fit on pastry rings. Refrigerate baking
sheet until tarts are well chilled, 2 to 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   7. Strain syrup through fine sieve into clean saucepan. Bring to
a boil, and cook until sauce turns golden brown and reduces to 1\
cups, about 12 minutes. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   8. About 30 minutes before serving, heat oven to 425 degrees.
Bake tarts until golden brown and puffed, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   9. While tarts are baking, warm sauce over low heat; do not let
sauce boil.
</P>
<P>
   10. Transfer baked tarts to individual plates. Place small scoop
of ice cream in center of each. Drizzle 2 tablespoons warmed sauce
over each, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
