<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 4)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAHORS TURNS `SENSITIVE' FOR ITS ARTS FESTIVAL
</P>
<P>
   From June 16 through July 2, the medieval city of Cahors in the
Lot region of France, north of Toulouse, swings into summer with
its annual Printemps de Cahors arts festival. This avant-garde
event attracted 100,000 visitors in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The theme for the 2000 festival is ``Sensitive,'' but Cahors,
famed for its rough-edged black wine, has inspired 32 international
artists to import a defiantly earthy vintage of videos, photo
exhibits, installations and performance art to this quiet town. On
June 16, 17, 23 and 24, the exhibitions _ emphasizing sensation and
emotion rather than reason _ will be open till 1 a.m., with music
and dance events integrated with lighting displays and special
effects.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the historic sites of Cahors transformed into impromptu
indoor and outdoor galleries, visitors will encounter fanciful
egg-tipped cacti created by the Belgian sculptor Michel Francois
and an imaginary hockey match installed by Roderick Buchanan of
Scotland. The French artist Fabrice Hybert will introduce ``Arbres
Fruitiers dans la Ville,'' which replaces the city's existing flora
with fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe Leonard, a New York photographer, is presenting pictures
where tree foliage has been replaced by plastic shopping bags,
while Via Lewandowsky of Germany showcases his ``Never Been There''
series of computer-generated photographs suggesting idealized
African landscapes. The composer Simon Fisher Turner, the
choreographer Olivia Granville and the Compagnie EDNA dance
ensemble will perform.
</P>
<P>
   All events are free. Information: (33-5) 65.53.94.75 and
www.printempsdecahors.com.
</P>
<P>
   BY BUCKINGHAM PALACE, A PLACE FOR PAMPERING
</P>
<P>
   The place for royal treatment in London is Buckingham Palace, of
course. Wrong lineage? Well, 41, a new hotel just down the street
at 41 Buckingham Palace Road, may be the next best option.
</P>
<P>
   This 20-room club-style hotel on the top floor of a five-story
Victorian building across from the Royal Mews has been designed as
a home-office away from home for movers and shakers. The room rate
covers the services of the two staff butlers who are always on duty
and a 24-hour buffet of salads, sandwiches, pasta, pizzas and
drinks in a mahogany and leather lounge.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 rooms and 4 split-level suites are decorated in
power-broker black and white, including the marble and tile baths.
Most rooms have working fireplaces, and each has a fully stocked
minibar (no extra charge); high-speed Internet access with wireless
keyboard and mouse; a fax-scanner-printer, and DVD and CD players.
There is also a business center.
</P>
<P>
   The rates at 41, at $1.50 to the pound, are $520 a night, and
$705 and $925 for suites, and include a full breakfast, afternoon
tea, and laundry and dry-cleaning services.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations: (800) 552-6844; the phone number for 41 is (44-20)
7300-0041, the fax (44-20) 7300-0141. The Web address is
www.redcarnationhotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   THREE AIRLINES ADD WAYS TO EARN MILES
</P>
<P>
   Continental, America West and Delta Airlines have developed new
partnerships allowing customers to earn frequent flier miles
without leaving terra firma.
</P>
<P>
   Continental has formed an alliance with DLJdirect, an online
brokerage, allowing participants in the OnePass program to earn
miles while investing. Members earn 10,000 miles when they open and
activate a DLJdirect account with a minimum $10,000 transfer or
deposit. More information is available at (713) 952-1630,
www.continental.com or www.DLJdirect.com.
</P>
<P>
   Wyndham Hotels and Resorts is the newest partner in America
West's frequent flier program, FlightFund. Members earn 500 miles
for each stay at a Wyndham property, with triple miles through June
30. Wyndham information and reservations: (800) 996-3426 or
www.wyndham.com.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also has a new hotel affiliate _ Sol Melia Hotels and
Resorts. SkyMiles members earn 500 miles per stay at Melia and
Paradisus hotels and 250 miles at Sol Hotels. Double miles will be
awarded through Aug. 31. Hotel information and reservations: (800)
336-3542 or www.solmelia.com.
</P>
<P>
   2 GUIDES CAN HELP FIND AFRICAN-AMERICAN SITES
</P>
<P>
   Two new guides showcase contributions of African-Americans to
the history and culture of North Carolina and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   One, ``The Rich Heritage of African Americans in North
Carolina,'' offers a brief history, a guide to historic and
cultural sites, a sampling of cultural events throughout the state,
and profiles of African-American musicians and artists. The
historical section starts with the introduction of slaves in the
16th century and covers events through the Civil Rights movements
of the 1950s and 1960s. A directory of historic and cultural places
includes museums, churches, markets, hospitals and schools.
Festivals and other annual events are catalogued by location. The
52-page guide is free from the North Carolina Division of Tourism,
(800) 847-4862, or can be read at www.visitnc.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida Black Heritage Trail'' is a 32-page glossy book with
descriptions of more than 140 historical places and profiles of
civil rights activists, educators, musicians and other black
Floridians. A schedule of annual festivals and three self-guided
driving tours are included.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet version is available at
www.flheritage.com/magazine/bht. The printed version costs $3.95
plus tax and shipping, from Florida History Associates, 500 South
Bronough Street, Tallahassee, Fla. 32399; (850) 488-1484.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
