<HEADLINE>
WHO TURNED ON THE NOISE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Curt Peoples, of Toronto, went to Myrtle Beach, S.C., with a
friend for a weekend of golf last month. He was taken aback to
discover they had arrived in the midst of a huge convergence called
Harley-Davidson Week. Peoples said that from his hotel, the
Caribbean Resort on Ocean Boulevard, he could hear the parade of
bikes making its way around the Route 17 loop until 1 a.m. nightly.
Sleep was elusive, Peoples said, and the drive back to the
Charlotte, N.C., airport, a trip that normally takes three hours,
took four and a half because of the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The local Harley-Davidson shop estimates that 250,000 machines
were in town for the week. The Myrtle Beach Grand Strand area has
60,000 rooms for rent, including condominiums for six or eight
people, according to Jennifer Coons at the Chamber of Commerce, and
she considers the figure of a quarter of a million motorcycles
quite plausible. Last year, it was 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples said he does not consider himself anti-biker, but he and
his golfing friend would plan their trip differently next year.
</P>
<P>
   The experience brings up the question: What steps can the
leisure traveler seeking a quiet getaway take to avoid sleepless
nights and choked highways that may develop around unanticipated
conventions? Here are some thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   First, avoid large numbers of internal combustion engines. The
bikers' week that Peoples' encountered is actually considered a
tranquil respite in the biking community. ``They mostly come to
ride around and admire each other's bikes,'' said Dale Coyner of
Communicast, a producer of live Web events in Herndon, Va., and
author of ``Motorcycle Journeys Through the Appalachians''
(Whitehorse Press).
</P>
<P>
   Coyner said that the Myrtle Beach week had a family quality
because it has been fostered by the Blue Knights, an organization
of bikers who are current or retired law officers. He said this was
unlike a week in Sturgis, S.D., which he said was ``notorious''
(this year's rally is scheduled for Aug. 7 to 13).
</P>
<P>
   For Myrtle Beach, he said, the carefully maintained bikes are
brought in on trailers lest they get scratched or dirty on the
highway. This was part of the congestion on the route to Charlotte.
Moreover, the Myrtle Beach week, he said, is a tiny shadow of the
Daytona Beach week, which in March was reported to have attracted
600,000 motorcycles. The Daytona 200 race is run then.
</P>
<P>
   Asking a hotel or convention and visitors bureau what events are
scheduled for the week in the area you plan a visit is one step
travelers can take. Really big events, like Daytona, soak up the
available rooms a year in advance and drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague who covers auto races said that the sound of a drag
race can be heard five miles off. Reber said this was perfectly
likely, and that, worse, because the sound is not steady, it would
be much more irritating than, say, the hum of an air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Again, to participants, the racket is part of the attraction.
The National Hot Rod Association recently reiterated that an upper
limit of 95 decibels, as measured 50 feet from the engine, was set
on Jan. 1 for all stock and superstock vehicles competing in
organization events, but the ``vast majority'' had chosen to ignore
the rule. Moreover, these vehicles are quieter than the
5,000-horsepower top fuel dragsters that are part of the mythology.
</P>
<P>
   The hot rod association and two other groups have about 50
events scheduled between now and October.In the cold weather, these
are in the South, but by August they are in Norwalk, Ohio, and
Indianapolis. The schedule is maintained at www.bmracing.com.
</P>
<P>
   There are other noises that can wreck a vacation. Unless you
face on a courtyard, a room in the French Quarter of New Orleans is
not likely to be restful any night of the year, particularly
holidays. But most people who want quiet in Louisiana do not pick
the French Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Events designed to bring in tourists to celebrate in the streets
_ Fiesta in San Antonio, for example _ also have their own distant
early warnings in high hotel prices and limited availability. In
addition, there are holidays unique to some states, traffic-halting
marathon races and nationality parades across the country. Local
hotel clerks and tourist bureaus know about these, and they should
be asked for a schedule. Holidays overseas may bring noise in the
street, or the opposite: shuttered banks, museums, stores and
information bureaus. It is worthwhile to check guidebooks for these
lists, especially if they are religious holidays that may shift
with a lunar calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel rooms just above the disco are an awful problem, and if
the room is rented early in the day, the situation may not be
apparent. When making reservations, ask about the location of any
late-night clubs. Other hazards are the swimming pool, the parking
lot and the place where trash is picked up early in the morning.
Lately the Travel section has received a rash of letters
complaining of hotel construction, a byproduct of a booming
economy, or reconstruction in the Caribbean after hurricane damage.
This is less of a late evening problem than one for early in the
morning. If there are dropcloths and Dumpsters about, ask for
another floor. When renting a vacation house, ask the agent if the
view from the porch is likely to include a construction crew during
your stay.
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year, it is nearly impossible to avoid
graduation parties and wedding receptions. Samuel F. Pryor III, a
partner at Davis, Polk &AMP; Wardwell in New York, related that he
arrived in Durango, Colo., at the time of a major bikers' gathering
last year. ``They were parked head-in as far as you could see,'' he
said. But the noise was not such a problem, ``We were attending a
wedding,'' he said, ``making some of our own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
