r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     05-30 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THABO MBEKI HAS BIG SHOES TO FILL, BUT DON'T WRITE HIM OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Thabo Mbeki demonstrated political savvy by
making a stop here during his first official visit to the United
States as president of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, San Francisco, even Atlanta are expected stops on
the itinerary of a new president looking to forge investment
partnerships with American corporations. But this capital in the
Hill Country is a double whammy: Mbeki meets with the CEOs of
Fortune 500 companies and the Republican presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old head of state denied mingling in American
politics during his six-day visit here, but his meeting with Gov.
George W. Bush served a twofold purpose: establish ties with a
governor whose state represents tremendous economic opportunity for
Mbeki's struggling sub-Saharan nation, and meet with the man who
might be sitting in the White House come January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we must come to Texas, to pay a courtesy call on
the governor and to interact certainly with the business
community,'' Mbeki said Thursday during a 40-minute meeting with
editorial writers from the state's five largest newspapers. ``Texas
is an important economic and power center. We wanted to expose our
sizable business delegation to your companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizable, indeed. Mbeki's entourage took up 120 rooms at the Four
Seasons Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the president, few of the questions asked by
the Texas journalists had anything to do with economics or trade.
Mbeki's controversial and widely reported fascination with two U.S.
scientists who reject the idea that the HIV virus causes AIDS
begged clarification.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most frequently asked question in the United
States,'' Mbeki said. ``There is a serious AIDS problem in South
Africa and sub-Saharan Africa. And the view of the South African
government is that we indeed have to deal with this matter with the
greatest possible vigor.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Mbeki went on to reiterate his statements that the
entire scientific community _ including those researchers labeled
dissidents by the mainstream _ must continue to study the specifics
of how the disease is transmitted, and how best to get actual
results in fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth of South Africa's adult population is estimated to be
HIV-positive, according to the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists have different views about the elements of HIV/AIDS
_ we're not just talking about evidence of HIV/AIDS,'' he said.
``Why is there heterosexual transmission of HIV in some parts of
the world and homosexual transmission in others? If we can get an
answer to that, you are then able to make the kind of focused,
specific response to whatever might be the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A question about ongoing conflicts in Sierra Leone, Zimbabwe and
between Eritrea and Ethiopia and their impacts on South Africa
elicited a quick geography lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a bad moment,'' Mbeki admitted, ``but it is also
necessary to somewhat disaggregate the African continent. If you do
that, it becomes possible to see that these negative things in,
say, Eritrea do not in reality define altogether what is happening
on the African continent.''
</P>
<P>
   Addis Ababa, the capital of Ethiopia, is a five-hour plane ride
from Johannesburg, Mbeki said. Although the two nations are on the
same continent, what is occurring that far away has little to no
impact on the economic opportunities that exist for American
companies interested in investing in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like saying that conflict in Yugoslavia between
the Serbs and the Muslims, the Albanians and the Kosovars sent
ripples through the Irish and the Scots and the Brits,'' he said.
``It didn't happen, but for some strange reason when that conflict
breaks out in Africa .... You must look at Africa in the
disaggregate.''
</P>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of former President Nelson Mandela
would not be an easy job for anyone, but it has fallen to Mbeki to
deliver on the promises made six years ago when a government led by
the African National Congress took power. Those promises included
housing, water and electricity for all South Africans. Yet when
asked about a report issued last week by his own officials
indicating that 3 million families still lack proper housing, Mbeki
was unapologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised that it is so few, the 3 million, given where
we've come from,'' Mbeki said. ``What happened in '94 is that we
said that we would aim to have something in the order of 1 million
houses in a period of five years. We didn't quite get to that
million, but as far as I can remember _ I'm trying to remember the
exact statistics _ it was in the upper 800,000s by the end of that
five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be big backlogs, if you will understand where we
came from. There will be big backlogs in housing, electrification,
rural roads, water supply _ in anything. But it is the goal to
sustain that housing program and obviously try and speed it up. I
think a lot of progress has been made. But the backlog is big _
very big.''
</P>
<P>
   The president will have been in office only a year as of June
16, but he's learned the art of the dodge well. When asked what he
would consider to be the highlight of his administration thus far,
Mbeki exhibited a decidedly un-American political trait: He
deflected the chance to blow his own horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is unfair,'' he said to a nervous giggle from the
writer. (Even seasoned journalists can get flustered.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure. No, because I mean, if I praise myself, if I say to you
I am a spectacular president (laughter from the room), you would
say: `What's wrong with that silly fellow?' I couldn't answer that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I would ask you that question. And you would answer me
honestly and say, `Well, to tell you the truth, nothing. I haven't
seen anything worth considering an achievement.' And it's probably
true. But I could not answer that question, could I?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You choose not to, so it's all right, sir,'' the writer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it would be impossible to answer,'' Mbeki continued.
``Well, I submit that it is not impossible. I can answer. I can say
that I've demonstrated that I'm much better than the United States
president. (Laughter from the room.) Ask another question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, what is the ... well ... I guess I'm so used to United
States presidents answering that question that I'm taken aback.''
(Laughter from the room.)
</P>
<P>
   Politically savvy and a sense of humor. Another double whammy.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and a columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
