<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9821 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-ASBESTOS-WITNESS-SPI &LR;      05-30 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-WITNESS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASBESTOS INDUSTRY PAYS CRAYOLA'S EXPERT MILLIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 and CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``independent'' expert that Crayola hired to check its
crayons for asbestos has been paid millions of dollars by the
asbestos industry for testimony on its behalf in personal-injury
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lee, president of the RJ Lee Group in Pittsburgh,
testified under oath in March in a personal-injury asbestos trial
in Abbeville, La., that he had been a witness more that 250 times
for asbestos companies like W.R. Grace &AMP; Co., United States
Mineral, Owens Corning and others.
</P>
<P>
   For his services, he testified, he has billed asbestos companies
about $7 million, often at $350 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   After the Seattle Post-Intelligencer published a story last week
disclosing that tests had found asbestos in its tests of Crayola
and two other crayon brands, Binney &AMP; Smith, makers of Crayola,
hired Lee to do another test.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Lee and the crayon company announced his tests showed
no asbestos in the two Crayolas he tested.
</P>
<P>
   Binney &AMP; Smith was asked Friday if Lee's involvement with the
asbestos and talc industries met its definition of independent. The
company has not answered that question.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he examined the crayons and the raw talc using
polarized light microscopy (PLM), transmission electron microscopy
(TEM) and scanning electron microscopy (SEM).
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of those techniques, which definitely
determine whether or not asbestos is present, confirmed that the
talc used in Crayola crayons and the finished products do not
contain asbestos,'' said Lee in a statement issued by Crayola.
</P>
<P>
   The three tests that Lee mentioned were the same methods used by
the two Seattle labs that did the analysis for the P-I _ Lab/Cor
Inc, and Pacific Rim Environmental Inc. Those tests detected
asbestos _ tremolite and anthophyllite _ in 32 of 40 Crayola, Prang
and Rose Art crayons tested. Other tests of crayons commissioned by
ABC News found tremolite fibers at concentrations which exceeded 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lee suggested last week that the labs used by the P-I
misidentified the asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been common in the past for labs to misidentify talc
fibers and cleavage minerals as asbestos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both labs that examined the crayons for the P-I stand by their
analyses, which showed tremolite and anthophyllite fibers with a
length and width and chemical composition that meets the definition
of asbestos used by government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This laboratory, under the supervision of John Harris, uses
analytical protocols for asbestos analysis as set down by the EPA.
We have been doing this for years,'' said Dr. Robert Fisher,
Lab/Cor's president and chief scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our proficiency for this work is evaluated regularly through
round-robin analysis of blind samples and on-site monitoring by
highly qualified scientists under a program administered by the
National Institutes of Science and Technology. We have always
passed,'' said Fisher, who is also a research professor of
materials science and engineering at the University of Washington
and a past president of the Microscopy Society of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is unmistakably some asbestos at low levels in some of
the crayons we tested,'' said Fred Golloway, director at Pacific
Rim Environmental Labs. ``The PLM method that we use here can
differentiate between fibrous and non-fibrous tremolite. We do it
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, Harris and Golloway _ the three scientists who analyzed
samples for the P-I _ all said they have never testified in
asbestos litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Crayola, the P-I and ABC News all have provided some test
results to the Consumer Product Safety Commission, which is
conducting its own tests. The agency expects initial results this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Germine examined a microscope photograph of one of the
crayon samples Lab/Cor had analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's a typical fiber of tremolite asbestos,'' the
California physician said.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old general practitioner and psychiatrist also has a
master's degree in geology and worked as a geologist for the state
of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fiber has the features that could be inhaled and could
cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fiber in this sample is identical to the type that has
caused cancer in humans in many studies,'' Germine said.
</P>
<P>
   Germine, who has been battling the government and industry over
the definition of tremolite since he found the fibers in play sand
in 1987, has also examined other consumer products for asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Germine e-mailed a microscope photograph taken of
tremolite asbestos in crayons he analyzed, along with a description
of the methods he used, to Crayola and CPSC. Neither could be
reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
