<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-FOOD-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-     05-30 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOOR MARKETS INSIDE THE KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open-air markets where farmers sell freshly dug
potatoes, fragrant herbs and dewy berries enrich the fabric of many
cities. Paris has 62 outdoor markets, which have long been anchors
of their neighborhoods. In New York, the 28 Greenmarkets, a network
begun in 1976, have changed the city's food scene.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two new lavishly photographed books celebrate these
cornucopias: ``Paris in a Basket: Markets _ The Food and the
People'' by Nicolle Aimee Meyer and Amanda Pilar Smith (Konemann,
$19.95) and ``The Greenmarket Cookbook: Recipes, Tips and Lore From
the World Famous Urban Farmer's Market'' by Joel Patraker (the
markets' assistant director) and Joan Schwartz (Viking, $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   The French book is the more focused and rewarding. The authors
spent a year walking in Paris, and their book tours the markets by
arrondissement. It puts personalities behind the farmers,
fishermen, butchers, cheese mongers, bakers and other food
producers who set up shop in stalls. They are people like Daniel
and Monique Letard, who sell poultry and game in the Joinville
market and who recommend putting some farmer cheese in the cavity
of a pheasant before roasting to keep it from drying out.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Greenmarkets in New York, not all the vendors in
Paris produce their own wares. Some gather cheeses, for example,
from sources in Normandy, or seafood from fishermen in Brittany.
The markets operate year round and offer foods that can include,
depending on the neighborhood, Chinese teas, Spanish oranges and
Indian spices. They represent a tradition that predates grocery
stores and supermarkets, and they often serve as colorful
substitutes for the more antiseptic stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paris in a Basket'' sketches the surroundings of each market,
including food shops, a few restaurants and historic sights, making
it worthwhile for the food-loving tourist. Throughout the book
appear brief excursions on subjects like oysters, olives, organic
farming and butchers. Unfortunately, there is no index, so finding
any of these nuggets easily is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Each section of the book includes a few fairly classic recipes,
like moules marinieres, vinaigrette salads, onion soup, potato
gratin, apple cake and duck breast with port, most of which can be
found in many other books. I loved the silky, cumin-scented avocado
vichyssoise, a more unusual recipe. But even it needed a spritz of
lemon juice to bring up the flavor, and I found it impossible to
cram all the ingredients into my blender at once. As good as the
recipes may be, they are basically beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenmarket book, by contrast, is filled with recipes. But
it is more valuable for listing produce and other foods by season,
along with helpful charts describing the varieties of apples,
squashes, potatoes, peppers, tomatoes, herbs and other foods.
</P>
<P>
   The book tells how Barry Benepe, a Hudson Valley urban planner,
conceived of the Greenmarkets as a way for growers in the region to
sell their produce in the city and keep their farms alive. It
profiles farmers, fishermen and cheesemakers who sell their wares
today. Unfortunately, it is not clear where a shopper can find
those sellers among the markets. The book also lacks a guide to
market sites and schedules, but that may be because they often
change.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes come from chefs, farmers, food writers and
Greenmarket shoppers. Some are quick to make, like baked Jerusalem
artichoke chips, green beans with savory and bacon, and tomato
salad with chilies and feta. Others, like duck salad with fresh
peas and radishes, are complex.
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes I tried needed fine-tuning, and a fellow reporter
had the same problem. That duck salad recipe does not say how long
it takes to roast the legs, and there was too much oil in a beet,
pear and Gorgonzola salad. A roasted strawberry clafoutis was heavy
and dense, no match for the custardy cherry clafoutis in the French
book.
</P>
<P>
   As in the French book, all the ingredients for a cool soup, this
time made with cucumbers, did not fit into my blender. But unlike
the recipes in the French book, which is more a Baedeker, the
Greenmarket recipes are the main feature. That's the problem.
</P>
<P>
   AVOCADO VICHYSSOISE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Paris in a Basket''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus chilling
</P>
<P>
   1\ pounds medium boiling potatoes, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   2 Hass avocados, peeled, pitted and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chilled, defatted chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cilantro leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1. Place potatoes in a saucepan of salted water, and cook until
tender. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place half the potatoes and half the avocados in a blender
with 1 cup chicken stock, cumin and lemon juice. Process to smooth
puree, gradually adding another cup of stock, and transfer to a
bowl. Puree the remaining potatoes and avocados with the remaining
stock, and combine with the first batch. Season to taste with salt
and pepper. Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   3. Serve garnished with a few cilantro leaves. Yield: 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   ALAN HARDING'S CHILLED CUCUMBER SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Greenmarket Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   8 medium cucumbers, peeled
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon fresh-ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1. Chop all but one of the cucumbers. Place half of chopped
cucumbers in blender with lemon juice, salt, pepper, vinegar, curry
powder, cardamom and cayenne. Puree. Transfer to bowl. Puree
remaining chopped cucumbers, and mix with first batch. Stir in
yogurt. Chill until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   2. Quarter the remaining cucumber lengthwise, remove seeds and
slice thin. Adjust seasoning of soup if necessary, and serve
garnished with cucumber slices.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
