 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, May 31. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ASSESS (Jakarta) _ A news analysis: Investigators who
are struggling to break through a mental fog as they question
former President Suharto are searching for something that is
perhaps more valuable than the billions of dollars he is said to
have stolen from his country. They are fighting to reclaim a piece
of their nation's history. The fitful interrogations of the ailing
78-year-old former president, who was placed under house arrest on
Monday, are one part of a broad campaign by President Abdurrahman
Wahid to dig into a past that is filled with hidden abuses. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Lisbon, Portugal) _ Opening his last scheduled
trip to Europe as President, President Clinton on Tuesday stood
near the spot where Portuguese explorers set sail for the New World
five centuries ago, praising them for their global adventures and
calling for ``a new voyage of discovery.'' By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-POLITICS (Miami) _ Former President Jean-Bertrand
Aristide's party has won control of Haiti's Senate, according to
partial returns from last week's election. The first results,
released Monday by Electoral Council spokesman Jean-Gardy Lorcy,
showed the Lavalas Family Party winning 14 of the 27 seats in the
Senate. The results of the May 21 vote suggested strong support for
the former priest who is expected to run for president again this
fall. (Summary from wires) By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ORE-ADOPT (Seattle) _ In Oregon, adoptees gain access to their
birth certificates on Tuesday under the state's 1998 adoption law.
By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S.-SPY (Miami) _ A U.S. immigration official was found
guilty of espionage Tuesday after getting caught in a government
sting passing secret information to a friend with ties to Cuba.
Mariano Faget, 54, a naturalized U.S. citizen who came from Cuba as
a teen-ager, showed no reaction when the federal jury convicted him
of all four counts, including violating the Espionage Act. The
charges carry a possible prison term of five to six years. (Summary
from wires) By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   GEOGRAPHY-GENDER-GAP (New York) _ There were no girl finalists
at the National Geographic bee last week. The disparity reveals a
gender gap on geography that researchers have conflicting opinions
about. But it may say something about why men so stubbornly refuse
to ask for directions. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock prices surged Tuesday, a move some
traders said could signal the start of a summer rally. But the
gains, which amounted to two percentage points or more in major
market indexes, were achieved on light, post-holiday trading
volume. The Dow Jones industrial average was up nearly 220 points;
the S&AMP;P 500 index was up more than 40 points; and the Nasdaq
composite index was up 255 points, or nearly 7 percent. By Kenneth
N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-CROSS-OWNERSHIP (Washington) _ As part of a congressionally
mandated biennial review, the Federal Communications Commission
makes recommendations about rules governing a number of important
broadcast ownership rules, including cross-ownership limits of
broadcast and newspaper properties in a single market. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
