<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A NEW BIRTH CERTIFICATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I was born in Kansas in the early '70s. My birth certificate
was lost when my mother went to a nursing home. How can I replace
it?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.H., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: To get a copy of your birth certificate, contact the vital
statistics office for the state you were born in.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, a birth certificate costs $10 from the Office of
Vital Statistics, 900 S.W. Jackson, Room 151, Topeka, KS
66612-2221.
</P>
<P>
   Include the following information with your request: your full
name with the last name capitalized, mailing address, driver's
license number and the state that issued it, date and place of
birth, mother's maiden name, father's name, signature and the
reason you are requesting the certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Call (785) 296-1400 or visit the Web site
www.kdhe.state.ks.us/vital for more information.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, birth records are available from the Bureau of Vital
Statistics. Call (512) 458-7111 or visit the Web site
www.tdh.state.tx.us/bvs on the Web for details.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which major leaguer is the all-time leader in striking out?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.S., Templeton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Reggie Jackson tops the list, with 2,597 strikeouts in 9,864
career at-bats, a .263 average. By comparison, his lifetime batting
average was .262.
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 Hall of Fame inductee played for five teams in a
21-year career, winning five World Series championships. He's No. 6
on the lifetime home run list with 563 and No. 17 in RBIs with
1,702.
</P>
<P>
   Among active players, Jose Canseco of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
leads with 1,802 strikeouts through May 16. That puts the 16-year
player in sixth place, and he's likely to reach second place if he
plays through the 2001 season, passing Willie Stargell at 1,936
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What poem includes the words ``If I had loved you less or
played you slyly,/I might have held you for a summer more''?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.S.N., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a sonnet by Edna St. Vincent Millay from her 1931 book
``Fatal Interview,'' a 52-poem collection inspired by a love
affair.
</P>
<P>
   The poem is sometimes reprinted under the titles ``Loss'' or
``Well, I Have Lost You, and Lost You Fairly,'' which is its first
line.
</P>
<P>
   Millay, who lived from 1892 to 1950, was one of the most popular
American poets of the 1920s. She won the 1923 Pulitzer Prize for
her collection ``The Ballad of the Harp-Weaver.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
