<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNS OF ANCIENT CIVILIZATION COULD BE NEARER THAN YOU THINK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Archaeologists from the University of Chicago have discovered a
6,000-year-old city in Syria. It appears to have been a full-blown
city and not just a small town or village. They've uncovered huge
cooking ovens, which for me is only evidence that there were
growing boys in the area; however, they found some other things
which indicate that this was a settlement of sophisticated people.
</P>
<P>
   The interesting thing about this discovery is that scholars had
previously believed that the development of cities began around
3100 B.C. This finding pushes that date back about 900 years to
4000 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that got me to thinking. It's just a vague recollection
but I kind of think that I had my own life before these children
arrived. It may have been a primitive existence, but there is
evidence that I haven't always avoided buying clothing that says
``dry clean only.''
</P>
<P>
   I began my search for self in my wallet but there was nothing in
there except pictures of my family, insurance cards, library cards
and faded credit cards. I looked in my closet but there was no
evidence of my past life there, either.
</P>
<P>
   Then I remembered the attic. I rushed to the hall, pulled the
ladder down and climbed up to the entrance. The single light bulb
failed to illuminate much of the room so I went and got a
flashlight and a bat.
</P>
<P>
   Inside that dim, hot room I found some incredible things. Buried
underneath a mountain of old, broken furniture, sleeping bags and
Christmas decorations were three boxes of artifacts from my life
before I discovered elastic waistbands.
</P>
<P>
   In one box, I found a calendar from 15 years ago. I was amazed
to see page after page of completely blank dates! It was as if I
had nothing to do beyond the usual tasks of my daily routine. My
organizer is so full now that by the middle of the month, I have to
use a sticky note if I want to add anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I found an old photo album. Inside were pictures of my
husband and me. In several of the pictures, we were just lying on a
beach or sitting on the patio of a restaurant doing nothing. There
were always a bunch of empty glasses and bottles near us, as if
we'd been doing nothing for a while.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a caricature of us at Six Flags. I cannot believe
that I went to Six Flags and sat still long enough for someone to
actually draw a picture of the two of us. Now, when we take the
kids to the amusement park, we barely pause at the entry gate long
enough to take a snapshot. After that, we sprint through the park
like it's going to close at any minute. If I want to eat, I have to
start on my hot dog 10 minutes before the boys start theirs. They
don't chew; they simply inhale their food and say, ``Let's go, Mom.
We want to ride the roller coaster again.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing I unearthed was proof positive that I had a life
of my own before my darling babies took it over. In a far corner of
the attic, partially hidden underneath the insulation, I found a
very, very small purse.
</P>
<P>
   It was barely big enough to hold a tube of lipstick, one car key
and a folded dollar bill. For years, that was my purse of choice.
It held everything I needed to get through the day. My current
wallet is larger than that purse. I could never get mints and
bandages and the schedules for 16 sporting events in that teeny
purse.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that did it for me. I got my bat and headed for the exit.
Suddenly, I saw a shadow and heard an eerie noise. I took a Ken
Griffey Jr. swing at what turned out to be my husband's head
peeking through the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the heck are you doing?'' he yelled, ducking his head in
the nick of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops. Sorry. I was looking for the beginnings of
civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well hurry up and find it and come on. The kids are ready to
go to Six Flags.''
</P>
<P>
   With one last backward glance, I started to leave the attic.
Then I went back to that corner and retrieved that teeny purse. If
I cut off the strap, the boys can keep their marbles in it. Hey,
life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can write her in care of the Arlington
Star-Telegram' at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
