<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9841 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      05-30 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    (RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS. MOVING IN
THE ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES)
</HEADLINE>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENON'S `NEW &AMP; NOTABLE' COLUMN(a)  &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``THE SPECIAL PRISONER''
</P>
<P>
   By JIM LEHRER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   There are 13 previous books by Lehrer listed before the title
page of this one, all written while he wasn't busy anchoring ``The
Newshour With Jim Lehrer'' on PBS. We think he should slow down.
There's a hurried feel to this novel, the story of Methodist bishop
John Quincy Watson, who in a crowded airport catches a glimpse of a
man he believes to be the Japanese officer who brutalized him in a
prison camp during World War II. Watson follows ``the Hyena,'' as
prisoners called him, to San Diego, where he corners him in his
hotel and proceeds to have a remarkably civilized talk with him, in
between bouts of tussling that go mysteriously unheard by guests in
surrounding rooms. These chapters, alternated with Watson's
memories of the camp, are tense and suspenseful. Unfortunately,
Lehrer places his real climax in the middle of the book, and
follows it with a section involving a murder trial, lots of moral
pondering and a ludicrous ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE SECRET LIVES OF WORDS'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By PAUL WEST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harcourt, $24)
</P>
<P>
   New &AMP; Notable falls hard for books like this. Novelist West
(''The Dry Danube,'' ``Life With Swan'') has assembled a list of
words he has kept over the years that are notable for no other
reason than that he was curious about them. They are here
alphabetically, with information on their etymologies and remarks
from the bemused author on their modern usage. The only
disappointment is that our own favorite words (discombobulate,
melancholy, spellbinding) are not here. Among those that are:
dunderhead, bungalow, grievous, italics, sad, blizzard, gremlin,
escape, serendipity and a few obscenities that are treated with the
same affectionate civility as all the rest. West describes his
delightful book as ``a short homage to words, and the devious route
they have taken in coming usefully to us - some 400 in particular,
most of whom I propose to treat as honored guests, invited in (or
out) for a drink, a handshake, and, in some cases, an exchange of
blue movies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``SHAKESPEARE'S LANGUAGE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By FRANK KERMODE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (FSG, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Kermode throws out the welcome mat in his preface when
he addresses this book not to scholars but ``to a non-professional
audience with an interest in Shakespeare that has not, I believe,
been well served by modern critics, who on the whole seem to have
little time for his language; they tend to talk past it in
technicalities or down to it in arcanely expressed platitudes.
Every other aspect of Shakespeare is studied almost to death, but
the fact that he was a poet has somehow dropped out of
consideration.'' There you have it: Poetic language is the focus
here, and if you have always wanted to be more interested in
Shakespeare than you are, if you've needed permission to be
discriminating rather than reverential toward his most famous
works, Kermode is here to light your way. His book is literary
criticism, to be sure, and not for the faint of heart. But it is
also unabashedly inviting and invigorating - you will want to
revisit the plays armed with all that you have learned. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   RED MAFIYA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By ROBERT FRIEDMAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Little, Brown, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   Friedman begins his book by offering his most impressive
credential, the news that Russian mobsters have threatened several
times to kill him, slowly and in as grisly a fashion as possible.
The Russians, it seems, make the Italian Mafia look like pikers. To
the Russians, murder is blood sport - they will shoot you, a cop
told Friedman, ``just to see if the gun works.'' Now that we've
mentioned this, you'll be pleased to know that these people have
global reach, vast financial assets and an ever-growing presence in
the United States. Friedman has written about them for Vanity Fair
and other magazines (hence the death threats) and now offers this
energetic book, in which he tells anecdote after anecdote in his
effort to portray the Russian mob as the most savage and vicious
bunch of thugs ever to reach American shores. He includes photos,
and judging from the look of these guys (they appear both alive and
lying in pools of blood) a Russian version of The Sopranos can't be
far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE FEAST OF LOVE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By CHARLES BAXTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Pantheon, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Its title doesn't begin to describe all of the things this novel
is, or hint at the skill and daring Baxter shows in writing it. He
is, in fact, his own character - the book begins with an insomniac
writer named Charlie taking an after-midnight walk on a summer
night. On a park bench he sees Bradley, his neighbor and fellow
member of ``the insomnia army.'' They talk aimlessly at first,
about Bradley's history in love and marriage, but suddenly Bradley
has an idea: Charlie should talk to real people, listen to the
human beings around him as inspiration for his fiction.
``Everybody's got a story,'' he says, ``and we'll just start
telling you the stories we have.'' So begins a chorus of voices,
all connected somehow to Bradley, and all of them talking about
love, longing and loss. As the best of them, a streetwise girl
named Chloe, says, ``You can't figure out love without figuring out
death, too, but the effort it takes can knock the wind out of
you.'' This funny, wistful novel is a stage for Baxter's
virtuosity, and a reader's feast indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``IN A SUNBURNED COUNTRY'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By BILL BRYSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame that this perfectly charming book about Australia
has to follow A Walk in the Woods, Bryson's hilarious chronicle of
his hike on the Appalachian Trail. That book afforded him a comic
foil in his none-too-refined hiking partner, Katz. Here he has only
himself, and the laughs are not as frequent or as incapacitating.
Still, he seems to feel an obligation to be funny, as in a lengthy
description of himself napping (he is not, he says, ``a discreet
and fetching sleeper''). The book is best when he does not push the
limits of his persona - that of a curious, witty, friendly,
informative and very British (he is American, actually, but lived
in England for years, as is evident in his writing style and his
accent) tourist set loose in one of the most underpublicized
countries in the world. Bryson's travels include Sydney, Canberra,
the forbidding and huge Nullarbor Plain (its name is a corruption
of the Latin for ``no trees'') and the odd and unfathomable
outback. It's not hilarious, but it's a great trip anyway.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDILOCKS AND THE THREE BEARS: A TALE MODERNE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By STEVEM GUARNACCIA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Abrams, $15.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the three bears had lived as Guarnaccia imagines, Goldilocks
would have bolted before she crossed the threshold, driven off by
the embarrassing surfeit of style. These bears have far-flung
tastes. In addition to a Charles Ennie Mackintosh ``Ladderback''
chair (1902), they own a George Nelson ``Asterisk'' clock (1950),
an Alvar Aalto ``Savoy'' vase (1936), an Isamu Noguchi chess table
(1947), an Arne Jacobsen ``Egg'' chair (1957), a Marianne Westman
``Picknick'' casserole (1956), a Charles and Ray Eames ``LCW''
chair (1946) and many other dysfunctional-looking objects. Our
favorite is a blow-up bed, designed by an Italian whose name we do
not know. Goldilocks makes short work of it, and leaves its carcass
for Mama Bear to find. Goldilocks, by the way, looks like a refugee
from ``The Jetsons,'' and Mama Bear's mouth is on the side of her
face, under her right eye. We found that to be disconcerting, but
there's no accounting for taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``HIDE YOUR ASSETS AND DISAPPEAR''
</P>
<P>
   By EDMUND J. PANKAU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Regan, $14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If someone had sent us this when it came out in hardcover, we'd
be gone by now. Ah, but we jest - Pankau's book, new in paperback,
is actually quite depressing, because it is based on the premise
that you hate everyone you know including your spouse and children
(how they feel about you is another book, maybe two). First, we
must tell you that he advises leaving the country if you want to
disappear, although he does give guidelines for remaining in the
United States incognito. Second, he likes to say unnerving things
like ``Three can keep a secret if two of them are dead,'' just to
scare you into silence. He suggests that you consider faking your
own death and erasing your tattoos. He also names countries that
make choice settings for a new life, and rates them (Costa Rica is
a winner) on things like weather, legal systems and extradition
policies. Even if you're not a felon, there's a certain
entertainment value to all of this, and you never know when
something will come in handy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
