<HEADLINE>
CHRONIC HEARTBURN MAY INDICATE MORE SERIOUS DISORDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Chronic heartburn was not a great concern for Baseball
Hall of Fame pitcher Jim Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   He says he self-medicated with Tums or Rolaids and got enough
symptom relief to win the Cy Young Award three times.
</P>
<P>
   But, after 21 years with the Baltimore Orioles, when he retired
from baseball to become a television sports commentator and
celebrity spokesman, the ``heartburn'' became a real problem. It
began affecting his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had frequent and persistent heartburn for many years during
my baseball career,'' Palmer said during a recent visit to Dallas.
``I thought it was normal _ from eating late at night after a game,
the stress of the game itself, or the kind of stuff I was eating.
There are no health-food restaurants open when the game's over at
11 at night.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 10 years after retiring from baseball, Palmer was on a
media tour to promote ``Together We Were 11 Foot 9 Inches,'' the
book he wrote with his Baltimore Orioles manager, Earl Weaver _ a
major cause of heartburn, Palmer jokes _ when he totally lost his
voice.
</P>
<P>
   He knew it could mean an end to his career as a play-by-play
sports announcer and baseball analyst for ABC and ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, my livelihood was at stake,,' recalls Palmer.
``No voice. No job.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw an ear, nose and throat specialist who diagnosed acid
reflux and referred him to a gastroenterologist, who used an
endoscope through the nose to examine his vocal cords and agreed
that gastroesophageal reflux disease, or GERD, was the cause of
Palmer's heartburn and hoarseness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoarseness and irritation and was clearing my throat all
the time,'' Palmer recalls. His doctor prescribed medication to
block the production of stomach acid and recommended lifestyle
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer elevated the head of his bed, began exercise to speed up
his metabolism, stopped eating within three hours of going to sleep
and cut back on high-fat, spicy food and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   More than 21 million Americans suffer from GERD. Surveys among
older people show that diabetes, hypertension, depression and GERD
are their biggest health problems, Palmer says.
</P>
<P>
   He now takes Prilosec, the first of a new class of drugs known
as ``proton pump inhibitors,'' to prevent the symptoms of GERD and
is traveling under sponsorship of the pharmaceutical company that
makes the drug, talking primarily with groups of doctors about the
seriousness of the disease and medications available to deal with
it.
</P>
<P>
   Gastrointestinal drugs are the biggest category in the
prescription drug market. Prilosec, which now has two competitors,
had more than $5.9 billion in sales worldwide last year, more than
any other prescription medicine.
</P>
<P>
   GERD occurs when the sphincter between the esophagus, or
swallowing tube, is not strong enough to prevent strong acid from
the stomach from escaping back up into the delicate tissue of the
esophagus. The only cure for GERD is surgery in which the top of
the stomach is wrapped around the esophagus, creating an envelope
that acts as a valve to keep the acid in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is visiting 25 cities as spokesman for a campaign, ``Two
strikes and you're in ... the doctor's office,'' sponsored by the
International Foundation for Functional Gastrointestinal Disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, if you have frequent and persistent heartburn _
as often as twice a week _ you should be talking with your
doctor,'' Palmer says. ``You really need to think control.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Foundation for Functional Gastrointestinal
Disorders is offering a free diary to help patients keep track of
their symptoms to facilitate discussions with their doctors. To
order a diary, call the foundation's hot line at (888) 964-2001.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on digestive disorders, symptoms, diagnosis
and treatment options, visit the official Web site of the American
Gastroenterological Association, www.gastro.org.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
