<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT TO CONSIDER CLEAN AIR ACT AND ITS ECONOMIC IMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday expanded its ongoing
review of the Clean Air Act by agreeing to decide whether the
statute requires looking beyond the public health benefits of
reducing air pollution to considering the economic costs as well.
</P>
<P>
   The court's action raised the stakes even higher in a case to be
argued next fall that already promised to be one of the most
important environmental and administrative law cases in years.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the justices agreed to hear the Clinton
administration's appeal of a ruling by the federal appeals court in
Washington that the Clean Air Act, as interpreted by the
Environmental Protection Agency, handed such broad,
legislative-like authority to the administrative agency as to
amount to an unconstitutional ``delegation'' by Congress of its
lawmaking power.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Tuesday in the same case, the court granted a separate
appeal filed by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and a group of
regulated industries that asked the justices to examine the Clean
Air Act from a different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   If the court were to read a broad cost-benefit requirement into
the agency's rule-making authority, the business groups said, the
whole delegation question could be avoided because the cost-benefit
requirement ``could functionally serve as the necessary
intelligible principle'' to preserve the Clean Air Act's
constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had argued against granting the
business groups' appeal, characterizing it as an invitation to a
judicial override of a choice that Congress had already made. In
enacting the Clean Air Act, the administration told the court,
Congress ``reasonably concluded'' that pollution standards ``should
be based on health and welfare considerations alone so that
Congress and the public know that EPA's judgments on the health and
welfare threats posed by particular criteria pollutants are not
compromised by considerations of economic and technical
feasibility.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case are new standards for ozone and small
airborne particles that the agency issued in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
