<HEADER>
A9852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEN-CHILDCARE-NYT &LR;      05-30 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-CHILDCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FEAR OF TAKING PATERNITY LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Md., N.Y.)   By MELINDA LIGOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James M. Strauss does not consider himself a wimp.
But Strauss, a Manhattan lawyer, was not going to take an extended
leave of absence when his son Evan was born last June. One of the
reasons: He feared that his co-workers would question his machismo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had said that I was planning to take more than two weeks
off, people would have looked at me askance,'' said Strauss, an
associate at Putney, Twombly, Hall &AMP; Hirson. Instead, he took just
three days of vacation to help his wife with their newborn.
``There's definitely a perception out there that child care is a
burden that's still expected to fall on women,'' Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been seven years since the enactment of the
Family and Medical Leave Act, which requires companies with more
than 50 employees to provide up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave for new
parents, most men do not take advantage of this legal right. Some
decline for economic reasons, but for others, it is fear that keeps
them in the workplace _ fear of being ridiculed, fear of being
discriminated against, even fear of losing their jobs _ some
specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are terrified to take parental leave,'' said Suzanne Braun
Levine, a former editor of Ms. Magazine and author of ``Father
Courage: What Happens When Men Put Family First'' (Harcourt, 2000).
``While their organizations may profess to be family-friendly,
their bosses are giving them the message that men who take leave
are not very manly, or are somehow letting down the team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the message that a former South Carolina state trooper,
David Roberts, says he got when he asked for six weeks off to care
for his newborn daughter, Cindy, in 1996. Roberts, who at the time
had been with the state police for nine years, says he made the
request because his wife was still in nursing school. He says his
superiors responded by telling him that ``a man's job was to work,
not stay home with the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my bosses told me this long story about how he had
never let his wife work _ even though they had so little money that
they had to eat beanie weenies to make ends meet,'' Roberts said.
``Basically, he said I was less of a man for wanting to care for my
child.'' Roberts said he was intimidated into withdrawing his
request and was later dismissed in retaliation for making it in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit
against the South Carolina Department of Public Safety on his
behalf. The department's lawyer, Vance J. Bettis, has filed a
motion to dismiss the lawsuit, and said that Roberts' accusations
``just aren't true.''
</P>
<P>
   The former trooper, Bettis said, ``was terminated for reasons
unrelated to his requesting leave.''
</P>
<P>
   In a strikingly similar case, also brought by the ACLU, a jury
awarded a former Maryland state trooper, Kevin Knussman, $375,000
in February 1999 for the first-ever sex-discrimination verdict in
conjunction with the 1993 federal family leave law. Knussman
contends that his supervisors told him that ``God made women to
breast-feed babies, and men can't fulfill that role.'' That case is
being appealed, and Betty Stemley Sconion, principal counsel for
the Maryland State Police, says that Knussman was not discriminated
against. ``He made a mountain out of a molehill,'' Stemley Sconion
said. ``His superiors made an attempt to accommodate his request
for leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Mandelbaum, a Manhattan lawyer who represents both Roberts
and Knussman for the ACLU, says accusations of bias against
family-oriented fathers is not confined to blue-collar male
bastions like law enforcement. ``We hear about situations like this
all the time in the white-collar world, although sometimes the
message is more subtle,'' Mandelbaum said. `I often hear from men
on Wall Street, or from lawyers, who say their bosses have hinted
that they wouldn't get promoted if they took an extended leave for
nurturing purposes.`
</P>
<P>
   Paula Rayman, director of the Radcliffe Public Policy Center,
which studies workplace issues, says a Harvard professor recently
confided that his boss told him he would never get tenure if he
took time out from work to care for a new baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies like to put on a family-friendly front,'' Rayman
said, ``but behind the scenes, managers are sending out a totally
different message.''
</P>
<P>
   In researching her book, Braun Levine says she interviewed a
human-resources manager for a major company who said he advised
male colleagues to take a combination of sick leave and vacation
time to avoid having the words ``parental leave'' emblazoned in
their employee records. ``He seemed to feel that taking paternity
leave would be a strike against you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even at some companies where parental leave is encouraged,
human-resources managers say they see few male takers. ``Very few
men here take more than a week off for the birth of a baby, and
usually, they just use vacation time,'' said Donna Klein, a vice
president at Marriott International in Bethesda, Md. ``If you're a
man, there's still somewhat of a stigma attached to taking
paternity leave per se.''
</P>
<P>
   The only companies that see larger numbers of men taking
parental leave are the ones that offer paid leave _ and even there,
senior executives have to set an example first, according to
workplace experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a big difference if you've got a manager to lead the
way,'' said Marcia Brumit Kropf, vice president for research and
information services for Catalyst, a New York-based research group
that studies women's issues.
</P>
<P>
   Such a manager may have made the difference for Joseph J.
Kelleher, an associate at Milbank, Tweed, Hadley &AMP; McCloy, a
Manhattan law firm that offers both male and female employees a
full month of paid leave after the birth of a child. Kelleher took
advantage of the firm's policy after both of his daughters, now 3
and 5, were born. ``I didn't feel funny about it, mainly because
there are several folks here who have children and have done the
same thing,'' Kelleher said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Christine Wagner, director of legal personnel for
the firm, more than 80 percent of eligible men have taken advantage
of the policy since its inception in 1993, including several
partners. But Wagner knows her firm is in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of firms offer some kind of leave policy, but their
managers don't walk the talk,'' she said. ``Here, our male partners
did _ and it's really opened the floodgates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
