<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ITALIAN RED BUILDS MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ISAAC ASIMOV    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Valpolicella, the light-bodied red wine made in
northeastern Italy, is blessed with a name that easily rolls off
the tongue. All too often, though, the wine fell flat, to the point
where the word Valpolicella no longer signified a supple,
inexpensive, easy-to-enjoy wine but became synonymous with thin,
mass-produced wine of little character.
</P>
<P>
   You can still find those insipid Valpolicellas in wine shops,
but in the last two decades, small winemakers in the region have
taken great strides toward rehabilitating the Valpolicella name,
producing fruity wines that range from lightly likable to elegant.
</P>
<P>
   Valpolicellas are blends, primarily of three grapes unfamiliar
to Americans: rondinella, molinara and corvina. By law, wines made
on a wide swath of land in the Veneto region, including terraced
hillsides and large flat expanses, are permitted to be called
Valpolicella, but the best wines generally come from the hillside
vineyards in the oldest part of the Valpolicella zone and are
labeled ``classico.'' Those wines called superiore are aged for at
least a year and usually have a slightly higher alcohol level.
</P>
<P>
   Valpolicella's big appeal continues to be its light-bodied
friendliness, which makes it a perfect summer red, served a tad
chilled with anything from burgers to fish to pizza. Good examples
of these fragrant wines can be found for $10 to $15 from producers
like Masi and Allegrini.
</P>
<P>
   Even more exciting are Valpolicellas that have reached new
levels of richness (and price) and muscularity but are not
overbearing. Giuseppe Quintarelli continues to turn out
idiosyncratic wines that are aged at least six years before they
are bottled. Quintarelli's son-in-law, Celentino Gaspari, seems to
be poised to carry on the family tradition, having made the
excellent Valpolicella Superiore 1996 for Marion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARION, SUPERIORE, 1996 $39.50
</P>
<P>
   Concentrated, with herbal, pine and berry aromas, sweet and
fruity.
</P>
<P>
   GIUSEPPE QUINTARELLI, CLASSICO SUPERIORE , 1992 $35
</P>
<P>
   Anise aromas, medium-bodied and mouthfilling.
</P>
<P>
   MASI, CLASSICO SUPERIORE, SEREGO ALIGHIERI , 1998 $12
</P>
<P>
   Ripe aromas of berries and cherries, a rich mouthful of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   LUIGI RIGHETTI, CLASSICO SUPERIORE, CAMPOLIETI, 1997 $13.50
</P>
<P>
   Unusual herbal, almost woodsy bouquet, cedar-licorice flavors.
</P>
<P>
   ALLEGRINI, CLASSICO SUPERIORE, PALAZZO DELLA TORRE, 1996 $17
</P>
<P>
   Big and robust, complex flavors wrapped around a core of
sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   SANTI, CLASSICO, SOLANE, 1998 $10
</P>
<P>
   Light-bodied with whiffs of cherry and tar, easy to drink.
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.
</P>
</TEXT>
