<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-BRITAIN-FOOD-SCIENCE-     05-30 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-FOOD-SCIENCE-ART-1,150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MATH: A CHEF ADDS SCIENCE TO THE SAUCEPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1,2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAY, England _ Brillat-Savarin admonished chefs 175 years ago
that ``certain things which you do without thinking, and only
because you have seen others do them, derive nonetheless from the
highest scientific principles.''
</P>
<P>
   He should have met Heston Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   An exuberant, crew-cut 33-year-old chef, Blumenthal runs the Fat
Duck, a restaurant in this idyllic village on the Thames, 35 miles
west of London, where science joins art in the endless search for
better flavor. He has allied himself with Peter Barham, a
49-year-old physicist at the University of Bristol, with remarkable
results. In only a few years, the Duck has waddled to the top of
several lists of England's best restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   As described on the menu, many of Blumenthal's dishes sound
preposterously complicated, just too rococo for words. Perfecting
the recipes has, in fact, required endless experimentation, and the
actual preparation is unusually exacting and exhausting. But what
finally emerges from Blumenthal's kitchen-cum-laboratory looks
beautiful and tastes perfectly balanced and integrated _ almost
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, what he calls ``cuttlefish cannelloni of duck
and maple syrup, parsley broth.''
</P>
<P>
   Making it, Blumenthal first cuts cuttlefish bodies into
rectangles and then freezes them, which, he told me, breaks down
molecules and makes them more tender. These are then cut into small
squares, which are filled with a stuffing of preserved duck, duck
ham, foie gras, cuttlefish and just a touch of maple syrup; rolled;
steamed slightly; and served on a soupy, spectacularly herbal and
intensely green puree of parsley. Wowee! Who would have thought
those disparate ingredients could unite in such flavor fireworks?
</P>
<P>
   The cuttlefish dish is typical of the Fat Duck's food in several
ways. It involves a scientific insight: the tenderizing effects of
freezing. It balances salty and sweet ingredients, as does
Blumenthal's bavarois of butternut squash with goat's milk ice
cream. It matches fish with meat, like his dishes of sweetbreads
with cockles and langoustine with pig's trotter.
</P>
<P>
   My wife Betsey and I ate our Easter dinner at the Fat Duck this
year, and in keeping with the season, Blumenthal suggested that we
order some lamb as a main course. As it turned out, we were the
designated guinea pigs for one of his latest experiments, an
innovative way of cooking lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, ``doneness'' in meat, the point at which it ceases to
be raw, is related to temperature, and browning it first is an
almost universal technique. But Blumenthal wanted to see what would
happen if fillets cut from a lamb T-bone were cooked for 45 or 50
minutes over very low heat _ say, 80 to 85 degrees _ in a pan
barely slicked with oil, and turned every minute or two, so they
never ``seized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't sizzle or anything,'' he reported. ``It sat there
and soaked up the heat. It never got that shock that ties the
fibers up.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think it would make me give up my rosemary-scented
gigot, with its rich roasting juices, any more than ceviche made me
abandon garlic-scented scallops bathed in beurre blanc. I'm too
piggy for that.
</P>
<P>
   But this new technique was a revelation. The lamb had an
exquisite tenderness, and something of the texture of carpaccio. It
was incredibly moist. The rosy color was uniform right through,
with no pink center or crusty exterior. And to my surprise, the
absence of browning had in no way robbed the meat of flavor; we
felt as if we were tasting the very essence of lamb, with no
gaminess, a taste of fresh air and spring pastures.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be no culinary shibboleth that Blumenthal will
not challenge, and no limit to his search for a better way.
Convinced that salting the water in which vegetables are cooked,
which has been standard procedure since the Stone Age, only
toughens them, he has stopped doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've experimented, with and without salt,'' he said. ``It
makes no visible difference. It certainly doesn't keep the beans
greener.''
</P>
<P>
   What does make a difference, Blumenthal found, is the quantity
of calcium in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Tap water in Bray is rich in calcium, which makes it good to
drink but bad for cooking, he said. Cooked with Evian, which has
little calcium, Blumenthal's beans stayed green; cooked in vodka,
which has none, they stayed greener. But simmering them in booze
was no better for beans than for humans, the chef said: ``One, it
costs too much, and two, the vodka tends to ignite.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer seems to be a water filtration system or, until that
can be installed, distilled water. But the investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   So does the hunt for some way to keep dry white beans from
cracking when boiled _ a result, Blumenthal thinks, of a hardening
of the beans' skins by chemicals in the water. And so does the foie
gras inquiry. Blumenthal finds that cutting foie gras in different
directions affects its texture, but until now he has been unable to
discover why, even with the help of scientists at the Royal
Veterinary College.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they saw no difference when they looked at the stuff
under a microscope,'' the chef said. ``They thought I was quite
mad.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of Barham, Blumenthal has finally succeeded in
making a sweet-sharp pineapple and chili jelly to serve with his
spice-cake ice cream _ no mean feat, since the enzymes in pineapple
fight the jelling agent, as almost every chef knows. Only a cook as
cerebral and as obsessive as this one would even try to attack such
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Jellies have preoccupied the Barham-Blumenthal team of late,
partly because of their use by Ferran Adria at El Bulli, the
Michelin three-star restaurant in Catalonia. He and Michel Bras at
Laguiole in southwestern France, which also has three stars, are
two of Europe's most original chefs, both fervently admired by
Blumenthal. A jelly of mead, an old English fermented drink that is
made from honey, gave a big lift to a ballottine of foie gras and
smoked eel that was my favorite dish on a previous visit to the
Duck.
</P>
<P>
   A manic, energetic man whose interests spill over the boundaries
of his academic specialty, polymer physics, Barham has traveled
twice to Antarctica because, he confessed, ``my wife and I are
basically obsessed by penguins.'' You can hear that same wacky
passion as he tries to explain that jelly need not be limited to
what we put on our toast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' he said, ``there's no reason you couldn't take two
glasses of liquid, one containing a red, alkaline liquid, with the
juice of red cabbage and fruit pectin in it, and the other a clear
liquid, basically citric acid, and put them on the table. The guest
could pour them together and over a dish of ice cream. In a flash,
the liquid would turn blue and form a gel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All great fun. But of course Heston would have to figure out
some way to make it taste good.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The two meet fairly regularly, either in Bristol, an hour or so
west of here by train or motorway, or at the restaurant. Some of
the things they talk about, like a Brie souffle or that jellied
blue sauce for ice cream, will probably never make their way onto
the Fat Duck's menu. But they also do specific research on things
like the feuillantine of crab that Blumenthal now uses in his
best-known appetizer, paired with marinated salmon, roasted foie
gras, crystallized seaweed and oyster vinaigrette _ another of
those dishes that sound a little like a woman wearing one too many
pieces of jewelry but astound almost everybody bold enough to order
them.
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the success of the dish is the tuilelike texture of
the feuillantine, which is based on crab essence. The chef said he
wanted ``something like a brandy snap, thin and shiny and
crackling,'' but when he first made it, the feuillantine came out
too biscuity, and he couldn't figure out how to add crunch. He
tried increasing the oven temperature, reducing the moisture,
adding gelatin and fiddling with the pH factor, all to little
avail.
</P>
<P>
   What finally did the trick was maple syrup, again. Blumenthal
says it worked because it introduced a different kind of
carbohydrate to the equation. Barham says, ``I don't really
understand the science here.'' But the result tastes great and
crackles to a fare-thee-well.
</P>
<P>
   Barham takes part in a conference held every two years at Erice,
in western Sicily, where like-minded spirits gather to discuss
``The Molecular and Physical Aspects of Gastronomy.'' Among other
regular participants are Alan Davidson, the Oxford food scholar,
and Harold McGee, whose book ``On Food and Cooking'' (Scribner,
1984) helped set Blumenthal on his path.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to get chefs to pose questions that we can answer,''
Barham said. ``Heston is the perfect chef from our point of view.
He has an open mind. He actually uses the research, whereas most
chefs pick up the bits that reinforce their preconceptions and just
ignore the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal fell in love with good cooking on a trip with his
parents to the south of France in 1975, when he was a mere
teen-ager. Like a thousand and one others, he found the food and
the setting magical at Raymond Thuilier's great restaurant, the
Baumaniere. Unlike most, he knew at once that he had found his
vocation. He worked at various restaurants in London and, for a
brief time, at the Manoir aux Quat'Saisons, near Oxford, where he
met a youngster named Marco Pierre White, who went on, as the
enfant terrible of London restaurateurs, to win three Michelin
stars. They remain good friends, one sunny, the other turbulent,
and White is the godfather of one of Blumenthal's children.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing to start a restaurant in Bray took a lot of nerve. The
Fat Duck is just a few blocks from the Waterside Inn, the gilded
stage on which Michel Roux, a great French classicist, has for many
years done his three-star turn. At first, Blumenthal stuck with
simple things _ rillettes of salmon, steak frites, lemon tart _ but
what a tart, and what frites! Chubby little things, fried to crisp
perfection, stacked like Lincoln Logs. They still arrive with the
veal kidney roasted in its own fat.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, Blumenthal turned to new twists on old dishes and to
more exotic ingredients, and the menu is full of them now, from
pollen to chlorophyll to piquillo peppers. He makes a bastilla of
pigeon but adds cherries and unsweetened Manjari chocolate, as if
it came from Mexico, not Morocco. With his fillet of venison he
serves a traditional sauce poivrade but also a potato gratin hyped
with snappy St.-Nectaire cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The service has grown more polished with the years, and now,
under Nigel Sutcliffe (the ``sort-of manager,'' Blumenthal calls
him), waiters can explain the most complex dishes quickly and
clearly. The wine list is full of grand names these days (including
scarce items like Harlan, Turley and Araujo cabernet sauvignons
from California), but also affordable bottles from Austria, Alsace,
Australia and Italy, including off-dry whites that go very well
with Blumenthal's food.
</P>
<P>
   I had planned to start our Easter celebration with a Condrieu,
pricey but promising, but the charming, laid-back wine waiter,
Gilles Manvieu, had a far better idea. He served us an
unprepossessing vin de pays _ same region, same grape (viognier) _
that cost half as much and drank better.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Duck itself has remained unchanged _ two plain
rooms, no tablecloths, stainless-steel cutlery, beamed ceilings,
wrought-iron tables and chairs, and a long, shiny copper bar. Too
plain, some say, for the prices. Dinner can easily run $85, without
wine or tip, although there is a far from meager three-course set
lunch for $37.50.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in decor are on the way, including, to my great regret,
the elimination of the bar to make room for a place for pre- and
post-dinner drinks. That was inevitable, I guess; although this
year's Good Food Guide ranks the Fat Duck among the top dozen
country restaurants in England, and one of its inspectors reported
that the three best meals that he ate in 1999 were all at the Duck,
Michelin still gives it only one lonely star. For larger
constellations, the red M demands a certain degree of luxury.
</P>
<P>
   GOAT'S MILK ICE CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Fat Duck, Bray, England
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes plus cooling, chilling and freezing
</P>
<P>
   3\ cups goats' milk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 and two/thirds cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   seven-eights cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1. In a heavy-bottomed saucepan combine the goats' milk, cream
and half of the sugar; bring the mixture to a simmer. Meanwhile,
whisk together the egg yolks and the remaining sugar in another
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove cream mixture from the heat and add a little to the
egg yolk mixture to warm it, stirring constantly to keep the yolks
from cooking. Pour the egg yolk mixture into the saucepan and cook
it over low heat, stirring constantly with a wooden spoon, until it
thickens very slightly, about 3 to 4 minutes. Strain the mixture
into a bowl and let cool completely. Chill until thoroughly cold,
at least 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Freeze in an ice cream maker according to the manufacturer's
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 1{ quarts. &QL;
</P>
