</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, May 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heat and humidity will spread from the southern and central
Plains into the interior East on Wednesday and Thursday. Strong
high pressure extending to 30,000 feet over the Tennessee Valley
will support the summery weather by suppressing clouds over most of
the Mississippi Valley and Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Fast jet stream winds will propel a series of disturbances from
the northern Rockies to the Great Lakes states, resulting in
widespread inclement weather. Cold rain will fall in Montana as
moist low-level winds ascend the sloping terrain. Farther east,
showers and some strong thunderstorms will streak along a wavering
front from the northern Plains to the central and southern Great
Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will turn milder than recent days. Onshore breezes
from southern New England to the Carolinas will keep coastal areas
several degrees cooler than the interior.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DERECHO
</P>
<P>
   Violent wind gusts of more than 90 mph tore across western
Nebraska on Monday afternoon. The winds resulted from a cluster of
thunderstorms that produced what meteorologists call a derecho. The
word ``derecho'' comes from the Spanish for ``straight ahead.''
Powerful straight-line wind gusts, not the twisting currents of
tornadoes, are the derecho's primary arsenal for damage. The
turbulent gusts develop as downdrafts within the thunderstorms
accelerate rapidly toward earth, spreading out in a destructive
barrage upon reaching the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
