<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9885 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER31-COX     05-30 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush, on the military
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush accused the Clinton administration today of
leaving the military unprepared and low in morale, saying the
performance ``cries out for a new sign on the Pentagon that says
`Under new management.' '' Bush, speaking in Denver at the nation's
oldest Veterans of Foreign Wars post, said the Democrats have
presided over a military in which some units are no longer at the
highest state of combat readiness, recruitment has fallen short,
and thousands of soldiers are on food stamps. He promised to honor
veterans by assuring the military is prepared.
</P>
<P>
   GORE, ON THE ENVIRONMENT
</P>
<P>
   Receiving the endorsement of the League of Conservation Voters
today, Al Gore vowed in Wisconsin to protect the environment while
maintaining economic growth. He said he'd stand firm against any
rollbacks of federal protections for clean air and water, promised
to clean up air pollution from the dirtiest power plants, called
for protecting pristine roadless areas in national forests, and
restated his opposition to oil drilling in the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO'S OFFICIAL NOW
</P>
<P>
   About 400 New York Republicans gathered in Buffalo today to
nominate Rick Lazio to take over the battle to keep Hillary Clinton
out of the Senate. Rudy Giuliani's withdrawal from the race less
than two weeks ago to deal with prostate cancer opened the door for
the four-term congressman from Long Island. His candidacy was
quickly supported by Gov. George Pataki and other Republican
leaders. The open Senate seat belongs to Democrat Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   THE FALL AND RISE OF RICK LAZIO
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio tripped and fell face down onto the pavement at a
Memorial Day parade in Babylon, N.Y., splitting his lip. But the
eager Senate candidate dusted himself off and finished the route
before going to the hospital, getting eight stitches and then
marching in a second parade, in Queens County, alongside the man he
replaced in the race, New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   SEND OUT FOR THE POPSICLES
</P>
<P>
   It was a Norman Rockwell scene for Hillary Clinton. She
surprised her new hometown by marching in Chappaqua, N.Y.'s
Memorial Day parade and then lingering to chat with her neighbors
and pose for pictures. Despite a few hecklers, she delighted the
crowd as she marched holding hands with two Scouts. ``Years ago, I
was a Brownie and a Girl Scout,'' Clinton told the girls. ``When we
marched, we used to end up in the park and get Popsicles at the end
of the parade.''
</P>
<P>
   PATRIOTISM OVER POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   As presidential politics took a back seat to patriotism on
Memorial Day, Al Gore, in Elizabeth, Pa., recalled his Army tour in
Vietnam with nostalgia and some humility while George W. Bush
looked ahead to the future without mentioning his own military
service. ``I know that my service doesn't in any way match that of
the heroes that we honor on this day,'' Gore said. Bush stayed
closer to home, telling people in Killeen, Texas, next to Fort
Hood, that veterans' sacrifices must be honored always.
</P>
<P>
   THAT PART OF THE STRAIGHT TALK?
</P>
<P>
   John McCain made ending big political donations a centerpiece of
his White House bid. But now he's campaigning for several
Republicans who oppose his plan and trying to defeat Democrats who
support it. Eight of the 17 congressional candidates McCain has
endorsed or campaigned for do not support his legislation to end
``soft money'' donations. Two of them, Reps. Clay Shaw of Florida
and Jim Rogan of California, actually voted against the House
version of his bill. On the other hand, 16 of 17 Democrats in those
races support McCain's position on a soft money ban.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAME DANFORTH COMES FORTH
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine reported over the weekend that ex-Sen. John
Danforth of Missouri figures heavily in George W. Bush's
calculations about whom to tap for the Republican vice presidential
nomination. At least on paper, Danforth, a 63-year-old ordained
Episcopal priest, fits several of Bush's needs: He's firmly opposed
to abortion, but more moderate on the rest of his politics.
Danforth came to national prominence with his all-out defense of
Clarence Thomas during the Supreme Court nomination fight in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   UNPIERCED AT ANY SPEED
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader's anti-corporate, pro-environment message, coupled
with his consumer credentials, is fusing audiences of blue-collar
workers and young people into a ``blue-green'' alliance. At a
recent rally on Boston Common to protest controversial state
educational testing, Nader elicited lusty cheers from young people.
Surrounded by teenagers after his speech, the 66-year-old consumer
activist studied a body-pierced, leather-attired young woman with
pink hair. ``I hope,'' he said, ``the dye was at least organic.''
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICAN IN-FIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   The longest-serving woman in Congress is battling a state
lawmaker who claims she's too liberal. Rep. Marge Roukema of New
Jersey is being challenged again in the state's Republican primary
by state Assemblyman Scott Garrett, 40, who came within 1,700 votes
of defeating her in 1998. If Roukema, 70, first elected in 1980,
keeps her seat, she could become the first woman to head a major
House committee: the House Banking Committee if the GOP retains
control of the House. The winner of the Roukema-Garrett contest on
June 6 will be favored against Democrat Linda Mercurio.
</P>
<P>
   IF TEXAS IS ANY INDICATION _
</P>
<P>
   Even as George W. Bush moves ahead in opinion polls with health
care one of his big campaign issues, the large number of Texans
without health insurance is emerging as an issue that could become
a political liability for him. Texas ranks No. 1 in the nation in
terms of the percentage of its population _ 24.5 percent, or nearly
5 million people _ lacking health insurance. With 1.4 million
children uninsured _ one out of every four _ the state is at the
bottom of the heap nationally, second only to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
