<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BODIES-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     05-30 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODIES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BODIES IN MOTION AND AT REST': A POET OF REALITY PRIES OPEN THE
LID 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Funerals and poetry are very similar, says Thomas Lynch,
possibly the only person on the planet who combines the two,
vocationally speaking. ``Whenever funeral directors get together
they talk about the fact that no one likes funerals,'' Lynch writes
in ``Bodies in Motion and at Rest,'' his richly idiosyncratic new
book of essays. ``Whenever poets get together they talk about the
fact that no one likes poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   It is fair to say that Lynch likes both funerals and poetry and
that he is good at both. His first book of essays, ``The
Undertaking: Life Studies From the Dismal Trade,'' introduced this
unusual writer to a public mostly unaware of the lyrical reflection
that can be involved in the necessary and wholesome task of burying
your fellow citizens. Lynch extends some of the themes that he
introduced in that book, adding, for example, that ``good poems and
good funerals are stories well told.'' In so doing he demonstrates
once again his quizzical, gently cantankerous, free-minded Yeatsean
charm. As he comments on the big and the small things of life Lynch
engages the reader with a mixture of poetic and funerary elements,
of ephemera and durables both.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book Lynch fills in some painful personal detail that
was missing from the first, like the battle with alcoholism he
fought for many years, a wrenching divorce, and the mostly
pleasurable tribulations he experienced in raising four children
largely by himself. ``Bodies in Motion and at Rest'' is less
thematically focused than ``The Undertaking'' and it is angrier in
places, as if Lynch has now decided to relax his hold on avuncular
bemusement and confide to us his private agony. His description of
alcoholism and the alcoholism of one of his sons makes for some
searing and powerfully affecting passages. But those of Lynch's
readers who are hoping for some striking new departures, some
entirely new themes, will not find them in this book. They will
find the pungent compassion, the unabashed lyricism and the
homespun repudiation of vanity and banality that bathed Lynch's
earlier writings in their considerable glow.
</P>
<P>
   The essays here are on a considerable variety of subjects, many
of them prompted by some item in the news, which leads Lynch to a
recollection of bygone days or to some meditation on what he sees
as the spiritual flatness of the end of the millennium. (The essays
were all written before the year 2000). In one of the longer
sections of a book of generally brief and pithy chapters, for
example, Lynch uses his hatred of a particular house cat to bring
him into a reminiscence of the collapse of his first marriage.
There, he freely reveals the fury and hurt that he experienced _ he
describes a poem he wrote about the experience as ``venom done up
as carefully off-rhymed birthday greetings.'' But as with all these
essays, there is a moral foundation, a probing for some lesson
about the essential condition of things, in this case the
uselessness of pretending that divorce does not harm children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most divorces are difficult choices in a world that applauds
the exercise of choice, even the bad ones,'' Lynch writes. ``And to
have good reasons for divorce _ as I did, as my former spouse
would, no doubt, say she did, as we always do _ does not make
divorcing good. It is the children who pay, for the two sets of
parents and households, holidays and disciplines. However equal and
amicable they might be, they are always separate, covertly at odds,
subtly competing, quietly instructing in the separate and
subversive dialects of love.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch discourses, often with a kind of sulfuric humor, on the
possibility that human life spans might soon be doubled by science;
on the similarities, as he sees it, of coffins and condoms; on
writer's block; on abortion; and on the contemporary value placed
on having choices, options, endless possibilities. But an
underlying philosophy is not difficult to detect. Lynch is an
eloquent but old-fashioned moralist. He has a capacious
understanding of human foibles and great tolerance for them. But he
knows that it is easy to be distracted from the verities _ by
rampant materialism, by fake piety, by all the cant that can be
produced in an age of electronic reproduction. That our humanity
can be diluted as a consequence is Lynch's underlying message.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the networks offer us,'' he declares at one point, ``is
the therapy of spectacle, excess and sedation _ our humanity dulled
by megadoses, like too much pornography dulls real sex, too much
volume eventually deafens, and too much information dulls the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm not sure about the phrase about information. It
seems to me that we suffer not from too much information but from
not enough. One can argue with Lynch as he rambles eloquently and
judgmentally through his life and ours. But it is impossible not to
take him seriously, since he is deeply thoughtful and his thoughts
have been hammered out on the anvil of experience. It is also
impossible not to like him, because his voice is rich and generous.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BODIES IN MOTION AND AT REST'
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Lynch  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 277 pages. W.W. Norton. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
