<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-NCR-BOOK-COX     05-30 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCR-BOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipe book serves up NCR history
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ NCR is usually considered a company of metal and
machines, not Cheddar Mac Salad and Petite Apple Tarts. Local
historian Curt Dalton has put together a book that probably won't
change that, but Delicious Recipes and Food for Thought goes far to
shed light on the character of John H. Patterson, NCR's founder, a
socially conscious businessman whose activism found outlets in some
unusual but effective ways.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton is a historian and assistant archivist at the Montgomery
County Historical Society with several publications under his belt:
Breweries of Dayton, Greater Dayton Drive-In Theatres and When
Dayton Went to the Movies, to name three.
</P>
<P>
   ``My primary job right now is going through the 1.5 million
negatives from the NCR Archives,'' Dalton said. ``Whenever
(Patterson) sold a cash register, he took a picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Those images offer a wealth of information about Dayton:
Patterson kept detailed records about the pictures, making a
relatively easy job for folks such as Dalton. Dalton's interest was
piqued by several pictures of beautiful dining rooms and kitchens.
A little digging revealed that Patterson, in an effort to improve
the working conditions for the women at NCR, began a lunch program
of hot soup and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   That program soon grew into a full-fledged daily
company-sponsored hot luncheon, with the first women's dining room
opened in 1896 on the fourth floor of Building No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Patterson) had seen that the women who worked for him seemed
to get ill often,'' Dalton said, ``and he attributed it partially
to food, diet and the conditions they lived in. He noticed the hot
lunches helped curb the illnesses, and the women came to work more
often.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson's insistence on keeping records of nearly everything
he did made it easy for Dalton to piece together the story of the
NCR dining rooms and the food served there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept a copy of everything they printed, so all the books
and pamphlets were available. He put out a lot of books _ one, from
1913, was called Human Efficiency Hints for Busy People.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1890s he began a publication for his workers. It
would include recipes and things going on in Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalton pulled the recipes for his new book from this publication
_ all the photos and text were taken from NCR publications spanning
100 years. They offer an insight to the times, such as the cook's
comment prefacing the He-Man Beef Stew: ``If `your man' is looking
for some recipes to try his hand, turn him loose with the
following.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some really fattening recipes _ some, like the Ham
Toastwich, call for a quarter-cup of butter, eggs, shortening ...''
Dalton said. ``But there are some health-conscious ones, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things people are buying it for is the
not-so-secret secret recipe for coconut macaroons that NCR has
served since 1903,'' he added. ``People have told me they'd lost
the recipe. That's the most popular recipe in there. I've made
them, and they're pretty darn good.''
</P>
<P>
   Delicious Recipes &AMP; Food for Thought also offers a tantalizing
preview of what the NCR Archives will offer to the public when it
opens next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Laura Dempsey at lauradempsey(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
