<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9891 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MIA-SLEUTHING-HNS &LR;      05-30 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIA-SLEUTHING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW SCIENTIFIC METHODS MAY HELP IDENTIFY REMAINS OF MIA
SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Air Force 1st Lt. Grady L. Hinson was attacking a
railroad tunnel May 16, 1953, when a wing on his F-84 Thunderjet
sheared off under intense ground fire, causing the craft to explode
and spin into the earth east of Pyongyang, North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Hinson didn't bail out.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow pilots heard nothing but static on their radios as they
called for him. They circled the wreckage, but they never saw him
again.
</P>
<P>
   Days later in Little Rock, Ark., World War I veteran Bedford
Grady Hinson and his wife, Virginia Louise, recoiled in shock as
they got word of their son's apparent death.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was on sick leave at the time from his job and he never
went back to work,'' recalled Hinson's sister, Mary Burrow of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He retired immediately. We called him (Grady) Bud, and he had
sent Dad a (bamboo) fishing pole. And his response was, `He sent
this to me and I'm going to use it.'''
</P>
<P>
   At 25, Hinson was listed as killed in action by an Air Force
casualty report. But his body was never found, and the elder
Hinsons went to their graves without ever having said goodbye to
their only son.
</P>
<P>
   For them the world stopped the moment Hinson vanished from the
radar screen. But Burrow, 74, may yet find closure _ thanks to
science, a Pentagon program and a thawing of relations between the
United States and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department's Prisoner of War/Missing Personnel
Office has fielded teams in Korea and Vietnam to find the remains
of more than 10,400 troops listed as unaccounted for _ those killed
in action in those countries and other Cold War clashes but never
found.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a $12 million annual budget, the Washington-based
office actively negotiates with the governments of Vietnam and
North Korea to gain access to excavation sites and state records
and to meet witnesses. Over the past decade the office has
coordinated the efforts of 500 Defense Department military and
civilian workers worldwide who have searched for the remains of
troops killed in action since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   A staggering 88,000 American soldiers, sailors, airmen and
Marines are now classified as missing in action and presumed dead.
More than 78,000 of those troops were lost in World War II, said
Larry Greer, a spokesman for the POW/Missing Personnel Office.
</P>
<P>
   Each service has offices that help search for lost soldiers and
continue contact with their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   At Randolph Air Force Base near New Braunfels, Texas., the Air
Force Personnel Center's Personnel Accountability Directorate
tracks 1,651 airmen lost in the Korean War, Vietnam War and Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   It works with forensic anthropologists in the field, a Honolulu
lab that identifies remains, a Brooks AFB life sciences office here
that evaluates such items as ejection seats found at crash scenes
and a DNA laboratory in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Progress has been slow on the Korean peninsula, where tensions
remain high 47 years after a shaky armistice brought an end to the
war but no official peace.
</P>
<P>
   So far the remains of five Air Force veterans of the Korean War
who had been listed as unaccounted for have been recovered and
returned to the United States for burial, while 324 of 674 airmen
killed in Southeast Asia have come home. Four of 57 airmen lost in
Cold War incidents, most of them reconnaissance missions behind the
Iron Curtain, also have been identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is the enemy, physics is the enemy,'' Greer said. ``And
there's another factor in the Vietnam cases: Most of the ones that
we are searching for now (were involved in) high-speed jet crashes.
Oftentimes the skeletal fragments have been eroded so badly or are
nonexistent due to erosion that sometimes it makes identification
extremely difficult to confirm. Time is the enemy in the case of
Korea because family lineage is often gone, and that's important
for DNA testing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Randolph directorate's missing persons branch chief, Jim
Russell, concurred, noting that 50 years after the war's start on
June 25, 1950, ``it would be difficult from an investigatory
standpoint to try to find people who are still around.''
</P>
<P>
   That difficulty has been compounded by seesaw relations between
Washington and Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   North Korean President Kim Il Sung agreed in 1994 to the joint
recovery of remains, a major breakthrough. But his government also
demanded $4 million for 162 sets of remains returned in 1993-94.
The United States refused, but it later agreed to pay North Korean
workers involved with recovery efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 1996, the Central Identification Laboratory in Hawaii
has led 12 recovery operations in North Korea that have turned up
42 sets of remains. While strained relations have been a hallmark
of relations between the United States and North Korea, slowing
progress, Greer said the communist government of Kim Jong Il has
agreed to resume negotiations early next month.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a cooperative North Korea, some cases, among them the
losses of Capt. James Arch Foulks Jr., may well defy any simple
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Foulks guided a B-29 Superfortress badly damaged by fighter and
ground fire toward the coast after a daylight bombing mission over
an enemy base on the Yalu River.
</P>
<P>
   Then he gave the order to bail out.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 13-member crew apparently escaped the crippled
bomber, six of the men were never seen again, perhaps lost at sea,
taken alive by the enemy or falling into the hands of fishermen or
villagers. A gunner whom Foulks found frozen with fear in his
turret bailed out and was rescued by a British destroyer. Another
man was killed, and five others were taken prisoner. Foulks, 30,
was the last to bail out that day in October 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sad, but I've gotten over that sad feeling,'' said his
widow, Alma Fields, 79, of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral isn't likely so many years after the death of her
husband, who trained in the B-29 at Randolph AFB. But Fields, who
later married a Houston neurologist, believes there is still hope.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago Air Force officials went to the home of one of Foulks'
sisters and took a DNA sample.
</P>
<P>
   If a future search team finds remains of American airmen in the
area, the case may be resolved by the Hawaii lab, using tests
conducted by the Armed Forces DNA Identification Laboratory in
Maryland. The Hawaii lab matches samples taken from the maternal
bloodline of soldiers with the mitochondrial DNA taken from the
remains. Such DNA is found in teeth and bone, typically the only
remains that are recovered by U.S. teams.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, blood samples have been taken from 2,000 family
members of the 8,100-plus who served in the Korean War and are
unaccounted for, Greer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has obtained DNA samples from 48 percent of the
920 airmen who remain unaccounted for in Korea, said Col. Roger
Corbin, who heads the Personnel Accountability Directorate. It's
also in the second year of a six-year contract with an El Paso firm
to put more than 5 million Air Force documents about the 1,651
airmen still unaccounted for into a database.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Reserve Col. Ronald Tipton, one of three
contract workers at Randolph scanning in the documents, envisions
the day when relatives of the airmen can log onto the Internet,
punch in a secret code and get access to official service records.
That, he said, will reduce the demand for copies that must now be
mailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
