A9900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-440&AMP;     05-30 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIA SAYS IT WILL WITHDRAW FROM RECENTLY CAPTURED TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EGALI, Eritrea _ Even as artillery shells plopped into dusty
fields here Tuesday, Ethiopia took a big step toward ending the war
with its neighbor Eritrea by saying it would withdraw troops from
territory it has captured in western Eritrea over the last 18 days.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia made the announcement as peace talks, aimed at ending
the two-year-long war between the nations, opened Tuesday in
Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department weighed in on the conflict Tuesday,
saying it had verified that Eritrea had also pulled back from
territory that Ethiopia claims as its own. ``We have confirmed that
Eritrea has done so,'' the State Department said in a statement
issued in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare situation since the conflict began, each nation has
now made what appears to be a public concession to the other. And
while there is no guarantee the war will be over soon, it would be
far harder to end without the announced withdrawal of troops on
each side.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bitterness and distrust that has characterized this
war, which began as a border dispute in May 1998, was on full
display Tuesday. The Eritrean government denied that Ethiopia had
pulled back its troops from areas it has captured in the west since
it began a major, and largely successful, offensive on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Yemane Ghebremeskel, a spokesman for the Eritrean government,
said the Ethiopians had in fact taken another Eritrean town,
Teseney, near the border with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange way of withdrawing,'' Ghebremeskel said.
</P>
<P>
   But Selome Taddesse, an Ethiopian spokeswoman, insisted that the
withdrawal was real, although she denied that it was a gesture
toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we have said all along,'' Taddesse said, denying
also that Ethiopians had captured any new towns. ``The only reason
we were in Eritrea was toward our main objective, and that is to
regain our territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The land Ethiopia said it has left was captured only since the
offensive began this month, reaching north from the Eritrean border
to the town of Barentu.
</P>
<P>
   The land that Eritrea says it has now abandoned was taken in
1998, when border skirmishes between the two countries became full
warfare that has claimed tens of thousands of lives in sporadic
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea gained its independence from Ethiopia only in 1993, and
many of the problems have stemmed from the fact that the nations'
620-mile border was never officially marked. What is still
unsettled is the territory here along the central front, about 60
miles south of the Eritrean capital, Asmara, and the main target of
the Ethiopian offensive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ethiopia has pushed its way into Eritrean territory, it says,
only as a temporary strategic position. Both sides have reported
major battles in the last week, though the fighting has been less
fierce in the last three days.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrean soldiers hidden in crevices along the mountains here
Tuesday watched as shells landed from the Ethiopian front, near the
town of Senafe, and blasted out from positions here.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia says it pushed the Eritreans back by military force,
though the Eritreans here say they have moved rearward waiting for
a good place to fight. Whether the war goes on, even as their
leaders discuss peace, is ``their choice,'' said Col. Habtu
Gebrendras, a local commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they withdraw from our country, good,'' he said. ``If they
don't withdraw from our country we will continue to defend it and
return our territories to ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
