<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-VISAS31-COX     05-30 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech visa debate raises number of workplace issues
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the pell mell push to pass pending legislation to enlarge the
supply of visas for technical workers, many experts believe that
there is an urgent side issue.
</P>
<P>
   That is the need to protect the employees _ both Americans
subject to being replaced by overseas talent, as well as the
foreign workers lured here for new opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   There is a strong view among many technology specialists that
the need for more foreign workers is exaggerated. Others think the
campaign for more technology workers is nothing more or less than a
quest for cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   But many respected sources, ranging from science policy-makers
to the Labor Department, hold that we cannot fill the need for
technology talent domestically, and have no choice but to recruit
overseas talent _ at least for the short term.
</P>
<P>
   One study, funded by the National Science Foundation and the
Computing Research Association, found that the shortage exists, and
published a paper found at the following Web site:
www.cra.org/reports/wits
</P>
<P>
   /execsummary.html
</P>
<P>
   In the study, the authors make the point that the term
``technology workers'' is too vague, and that any examination of
the talent supply needs to differentiate information technology
workers, with little more than a two-year degree, from the likes of
advanced computer engineers.
</P>
<P>
   But on the whole, the study said, ``the preponderance of
evidence suggests that there is a shortage of IT workers, or at
least a tight labor market.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the issue is more complicated than that, and that
there is abuse of American workers by some companies or
institutions who shove older, more expensive talent aside in favor
of eager young foreign workers who get paid less.
</P>
<P>
   And to get around laws that prohibit such abuse, foreign workers
are often retained by third-party firms, which then are contracted
by companies to do the work.
</P>
<P>
   Often companies or research labs will simply push aside the
people who give them problems and hire younger, more compliant
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Computing Research Association study concluded that many of
the problems of talent supply revolve around the uniqueness of
technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has its own constraints,'' the study said. ``For
example, companies are forced by short product life and short
product development cycles to hire new employees or reassign
existing workers in ways that do not require a lot of break-in
training before they can be productive.''
</P>
<P>
   And in another passage, the study said:
</P>
<P>
   ``It may also be true that older workers are underrepresented in
the IT work force. There is certainly a widespread perception that
programming is an activity for the young, and that IT workers tend
to get burned out and leave the field by the age of 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics would hold that these ``older'' workers don't flee, they
get pushed.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of areas of non-technical work are renewed on the fly, with
younger folks replacing older, less agile workers.
</P>
<P>
   But a difference where high technology is concerned is that
foreign workers are well prepared for the work at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the United States must, by whatever
means necessary, increase the production of smart, qualified
performers in the technology area.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia State University's Paula Stephan, who has done work in
labor issues as they relate to science, said her studies show that
at the Ph.D. level, foreign scientists have made contributions
beyond their numbers in our society.
</P>
<P>
   And their presence and force within academia and research
probably has displaced Americans, because of the value of their
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their work has displaced Americans, and may be a
discouragement factor, preventing some Americans from going into
science fields,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And so while there are good arguments to consider protection
provisions in any long-term authorization to extend and increase
tech visas, there is an even more urgent need to emphasize more
rapid training of scientists and technologists at home.
</P>
<P>
   The pool of talent must be enlarged.
</P>
<P>
   The Computer Research study emphasized that if women,
African-American, Hispanic and Native American technology workers
were fully represented in the industry, ``this country would have
more than an adequate supply of workers to fill even the most dire
estimates of a shortage.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-BRITAIN-ABSINTHE-ART-     05-30 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ABSINTHE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODERN ABSINTHE EXPERIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In the decades since it was banned, absinthe, a spirit
flavored with anise and wormwood, has been inflated with tremendous
allure. It was said to make people wickedly drunk and to unleash
the creativity in their souls. It was hedonism distilled into a
liqueur the color of a pea leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Absinthe was also supposed to be hallucinogenic and was blamed
for causing insanity, which is why it was banned in most of Western
Europe and the United States. Then in 1998, a group of curious
Londoners uncovered a surprising detail: absinthe was never legally
banned in Britain. They soon began importing it. It was an instant
hit among the young bar crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Until I went to London last week, it was still legend for me. I
went to soak up the absinthe scene, which, as it turned out, was
already fading. But I wondered, What is absinthe really like, this
spirit that mesmerized Rimbaud, Verlaine, van Gogh and
Toulouse-Lautrec. Oscar Wilde described it: ``After the first
glass, you see things as you wish they were. After the second, you
see things as they are not. Finally you see things as they really
are, and that is the most horrible thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   I started at Pharmacy in Notting Hill, one of the first bars to
carry absinthe. I went at 6, post-work, pre-dinner, l'heure verte,
the green hour as it was called a century ago, when Parisians could
be found at cafes smoking, staring, sipping absinthe.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the tradition was lost. The place was empty, save for a
man hunched over a newspaper and a beer. When I ordered, the
bartender raised his brow. ``You know it's very strong, right?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   He gave me a small taste of it straight. I swirled the liquid,
green as mouthwash, in the glass. It shimmered in a soft eddy. I
had intended to taste it like wine, breathing it in and letting it
sit and roll around my mouth. But somehow, it shot down my throat
like a bullet. I seem to recall it went something like this: first,
there was a scream of anise and herbs, then what felt like a
steaming hot cotton swab spread over my tongue, and a flash of heat
raced to my stomach. My tongue was numb, and within a minute my
limbs were leaden.
</P>
<P>
   Was it the power of a legend, or just that of a spirit that's
140 proof?
</P>
<P>
   The bartender then made the traditional drink, a measured
procedure that looks a lot like a drug ritual. He poured a finger
of the spirit into a tumbler, then dipped a spoon with a sugar cube
into it until it was soaked. He lighted the spoon, making a great
blue flame. He let it burn over the glass, then swirled the
bubbling sugar into the absinthe and topped it with water, stirring
it into a pale green, milky liquid.
</P>
<P>
   This was tamer, creamier and softer, like pastis, but much
sweeter. I became numb from my eyebrows down.
</P>
<P>
   I moved on to a few more bars, including Woody's, a new bar in
northwest London with tall vermilion banquettes, moss green walls
and an enormous glossy Mario Testino photo of people standing
around in their underwear. There, I was told I could have absinthe
the traditional way, but that very few people ordered it like that.
Puzzled, I ordered one of the house's absinthe cocktails, a
Dragon's Breath, made with cherry liqueur, vodka and lime juice.
</P>
<P>
   It came in a shot glass with a frosty liquid on the bottom and a
viscous layer of pale green absinthe on top. Where the two met,
they curdled. If it did that in the glass, what would happen once
it hit my stomach? Unfortunately, I can tell you: it was like
drinking tomato sauce after eating ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   No one else had ordered absinthe that night, which was a good
thing, since I got the last shot that was left. They had run out of
it over the weekend, Tony Rweyemamu, the bartender, told me. That's
when people drink it, he said, usually a quick shot between beers
or other mixed drinks, to speed up the lubrication process.
</P>
<P>
   Jans Ende, a bartender at the Met, a private club, said he
wasn't serving it as much anymore. ``It's not that good,'' he said.
``It's not the legend that absinthe was.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you happen upon a bottle that has been preserved, it is
impossible to know exactly how it is different, or even whether it
was good in its day. Before the general ban early in the 20th
century, absinthe had been produced for more than a century. As
Barnaby Conrad III states in ``Absinthe: History in a Bottle''
(Chronicle, 1988), it was created in Switzerland and originally
issued as a tonic for French soldiers to fight fevers. It was so
popular that it became an everyday drink for soldiers and
civilians. Which isn't to say that it was good, but it was cheap _
as cheap as wine, at least, and with much more bang for the franc.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 20th century, though, absinthe became the scapegoat
for many social problems. The French government's anti-absinthe
campaign included claims that it caused impotence. When people died
of syphilis, doctors would name absinthe abuse as the cause of
death to save them the embarrassment of the illness.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland, Belgium and the United States were the first to ban
absinthe. Eventually, the French government prohibited absinthe in
1914, and the Pernod company developed pastis to replace it. Pastis
was still flavored with anise but not wormwood, but it is much
different from absinthe in subtle but significant ways. Its alcohol
content is much lower, and it has a less complex flavor. It can't
be substituted for absinthe in cocktails. Its greatest similarity,
really, is that it is affordable, as absinthe once was.
</P>
<P>
   Today's absinthe, however, is the wealthy urbanite's drink.
Classic absinthe, with sugar and water, averages $9; cocktails cost
more. When I ordered it at Three Three Three in Shoreditch, where
many young artists live, the bartender made sure I knew it was
expensive before she poured.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the price is partly intentional, partly
unavoidable. In Britain, import taxes are based on alcohol content,
absinthe's primary component. And Green Bohemia, the first
distributor of absinthe, had the marketing tactics of Absolut Vodka
in mind. The distributor wanted it to be expensive and difficult to
get, as Absolut was early on, knowing that the difficulty would
make Londoners want it even more.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to import absinthe began with an article in an
underground literary magazine called The Idler: Those Who Live to
Loaf. The writer, John Moore, is a musician whose band, Black Box
Recorder, was traveling through Eastern Europe, where absinthe is
legal. The two men behind The Idler, Gavin Pretor-Pinney and Tom
Hodgkinson, were intrigued. ``We, like most people, had sort of
heard of this drink, that it was this kind of naughty drink,''
Pretor-Pinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Over several meetings with Moore in a pub, they explored the
idea of importing it. After many letters to agencies dealing with
health and with agriculture and fisheries, they confirmed that it
was, in fact, legal. They sought out an importer of spirits in the
Czech Republic, where absinthe has always been available, and they
formed an alliance with Hill's Absinthe.
</P>
<P>
   They called the new importing company Green Bohemia and
introduced absinthe in Britain in November 1998. In less than a
year, it took London by storm, beginning in Soho bars, then
spreading to private clubs and bars throughout the city. Now, even
the staid, formal Library Bar in the Lanesborough Hotel serves it,
and so do many ordinary pubs.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bohemia is run out of The Idler office, a loft in
Clerkenwell strewn with music magazines, coffee cups, skateboards
and computer equipment. Pretor-Pinney and Hodgkinson said that
selling absinthe is a kind of pleasant distraction for them. They
try to promote it as an artists' drink but realize that it has
taken on a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   There are now more than eight brands, all made in Europe, from
Spain to Bulgaria. Some are sweeter than others, but all contain
scant amounts of wormwood, the ingredient responsible for
absinthe's supposed hallucinogenic effects. Even the original had
very little, and modern studies have concluded that whatever
extreme effects people had from absinthe were most likely caused by
the high alcohol content, not the wormwood. Today, the European
Union limits thujone, the drug in wormwood, to 10 milligrams a
kilogram of the spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The flavor of Hill's is the most austere, resembling vodka, with
a milder licorice flavor. Salvatore Calabrese, the bar manager at
the Library Bar, has tasted an old bottle of the original, and he
said Hill's is the closest in flavor.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense. Hill's tends toward the bitter more than the
sweet, which is why the ritual of adding sugar to the drink
evolved. Many of the other absinthes are so sweet that by the time
the sugar is added, it is like drinking syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Making my way around London in search of the absinthe scene was
like chasing an elusive criminal. It was easy to find people who
had drunk absinthe but difficult to find anyone drinking it. Ben
Hoyle, Nick Chapman and Sebastian Boyd, all young professionals in
jeans and sneakers, were at the Bluu Cafe on Hoxton Square having
beers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first flush of novelty has definitely gone out,'' Chapman
said. It has been around for a whole year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   But they knew absinthe and all of its effects, having drunk it
often during the last year. ``It's a really good laugh,'' said
Hoyle, a management consultant. ``But it has a kind of depth-charge
effect, because after two or three, you don't think it's working,
then later, one and a half hours after, you feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   None of them has hallucinated, but it has made them, they said,
do things out of the ordinary. Hoyle, who rarely dances, danced
salsa for three hours straight after an absinthe binge. One took a
chicken from the refrigerator and beat it with a hammer. Another
set a table on fire.
</P>
<P>
   They don't drink it to savor it. ``It gets the job done,'' said
Boyd, a journalist. And they try not to drink it during the week.
``They were obviously more hard core in the 19th century,'' Hoyle
added, ``Now we have jobs to go to.''
</P>
<P>
   I also stopped in at the Long Bar in the Sanderson Hotel, a more
self-conscious scene in a new hotel designed by Ian Schrager. They
didn't have absinthe, as it turned out. ``I don't want people
burning things at the bar,'' said Ben Pundole, the bars executive
for Schrager's hotels. ``It's a classic bar.'' When Pundole was the
bar manager at the Met, he made sure that it was one of the first
to have absinthe on its shelf.
</P>
<P>
   More unfortunate, though, was the emerging truth that after all
these years, absinthe was being reduced to a fad.
</P>
<P>
   I still hadn't had enough to feel its effects, other than a numb
tongue. It was time. At Alphabet in Soho, I ordered three classic
absinthes and drank them within half an hour. Then _ clearly the
absinthe was working _ I decided to have a beer. At first, the back
of my head felt as if it would burn off, then the heat descended to
the ends of my limbs, making them feel as heavy as if I had just
gone swimming in a denim suit. I had no desire to beat a chicken. I
did not see green fairies. But I was breathlessly drunk. The next
morning had that familiar haze.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the romance. It's no wonder the fashionable crowd
has turned its back on absinthe. The genie is out of the bottle,
and no one wants to think of van Gogh lying in bed with the spins. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
