<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HORSES-WORKPLACE-ART-     05-30 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSES-WORKPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNSENTIMENTAL HORSE WHISPERER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (Sam Brown, 60, is a horse trainer, seller and riding instructor,
at Montclair Riding Academy in New Jersey and at Cedar Lane Stables
in Brooklyn. This was written with Joe Sharkey.)  
 By SAM BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Keep in mind that a horse has a little brain. You and
I, as the intelligent ones, we have to come down to this horse's
level. We have to try to get into this animal's head.
</P>
<P>
   When giving beginner lessons, if I sense there's some fear in
you, we're going to stop and have a five-minute chat:
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you fear?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I fear getting thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, some horses will never throw you, and if you're a
beginner, that's probably the kind of horse you'll be on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear getting kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you can't get kicked being on top of the horse. It is
physically impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   With proper instruction, anyone can ride with confidence,
knowing what to do in case a horse is going and he moves laterally,
which can pop you out of the saddle. I mean actually getting into
this animal, actually riding this horse, toe always up, heel always
down, a nice seat you work from the waist-down to ride.
</P>
<P>
   I learned to ride in Central Park in Manhattan. I used to go
down on the weekend, and I'd clean the stables and brush the horses
and what-not. And my mother, she used to tear into me. She would
say, ``Where'd you get this money?'' and I'd say, ``Ma, I worked
for it.'' And she'd say, ``What's that smell?'' I'd come home
smelling of stables.
</P>
<P>
   How I got started riding, I was shining shoes down there. And I
saw this guy wearing beautiful paddock boots, English boots, and I
said, ``Mister, can I give you a shine?'' and he said, ``Son, all
you going to do is mess up these new boots.'' Then I said, ``What
you do?'' He said, ``I ride, I train horses.'' I said, ``Maybe
you'll take me out to ride on a horse?'' He said, ``OK, how about
tomorrow?'' I said, ``I can't go tomorrow, tomorrow's school.''
</P>
<P>
   It's different if a kid stays out of school today. Back then, if
a kid stayed out of school, the truant officer came to the house.
But that one time I played hooky, I went riding with this guy, and
he says, ``Kid, you're a natural.'' That was the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The rich at that time were different than the rich of today.
They were not as snobbish as today, they could recognize, ``That's
young Sam, he rides here, and he's a good kid.'' That wouldn't
happen today to a kid like me who just wanted to ride in Central
Park. The rich today, they're too much into protecting their turf.
</P>
<P>
   I love horses. I understand them. I don't sentimentalize them. I
don't kiss a horse. Every now and then I'll give them a little pat.
A horse has no emotions, no nothing, he's just a beast of burden
with a little brain the size of a walnut. I don't want to get
attached to that animal because I get attached I'll never sell him.
But I do keep a scrapbook with pictures of most of the horses I
have owned in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9911 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0529-COX     05-30 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0529-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WWII generation felt every life is worth honoring
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even today, John Souther knows the desert passes of
North Africa about as well as he knows his way around Gainesville.
He can name and spell each of those historic passes _ Kasserine,
Maknassey, Sbeitla, Faid, Lassouda.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, when he was 80, Souther published a book about
his World War II experiences. ``War Not Forgotten'' is in its
second printing.
</P>
<P>
   Souther, like my late father-in-law, William T. Ezzard,
commanded a platoon of about 65 men in the Army's 1st Armored
Division, which was sent to Tunisia in the winter of 1943 to help
fight the forces of Field Marshal Erwin Rommel, ``the Desert Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1942, when we invaded North Africa, we were the first to go
into combat, and looking back we were just pitifully unprepared,''
Souther said. The division lost about 3,000 men near Lassouda Pass
on Feb. 14, 1943 _ which Souther calls ``the worst day of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in a scout car when American tanks all around him
starting getting picked off by German artillery. His platoon,
assigned to reconnaissance, was looking for ``camel trails'' _
places to cross the dry stream gullies in the desert _ when enemy
fire blew the motor out of his vehicle. Souther ended up stuck in
one of the deep gullies. He sent his platoon ahead with his
second-in-command and stayed behind alone in the gully, radioing
the division command of the precise location of the German
artillery.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much (fire) do you need?'' they asked.'' He chuckled at
the recollection. ``I told 'em, 'All you got.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That same day, on the other side of Lassouda Pass, about 4,000
troops were surrounded by Rommel's forces _ including my
father-in-law. In his book, Souther describes how Lt. Ezzard
escaped in the middle of the night, leading most of his men to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Souther managed to get back to his platoon after hiding several
hours in the gully and was awarded a Silver Star for bravery. Lt.
Ezzard got a Silver Star, too, for his courage behind enemy lines.
</P>
<P>
   About a month after American troops were ``walloped by Rommel,''
as Souther puts it, Lt. Ezzard was wounded trying to disarm a land
mine near Sbeitla. He carried some of those tiny steel balls in his
chest all of his life. (My husband cherishes the flak jacket with
the burned holes in it his father wore that fateful day.)
</P>
<P>
   Souther said he originally asked to extend his ROTC commission
for just one year in 1940 when he graduated from the University of
Georgia with a degree in forestry. He did it, he said, because the
Army paid him $125 a month, compared with $75 for a forestry job.
Both Souther and my father-in-law ended up staying in the Army
after the war, mainly because it was the best way to make a living
for their children. Both retired as lieutenant colonels.
</P>
<P>
   As I talked with Souther, I was reminded of qualities he, my
father-in-law and their uncommon generation shared. Their brushes
with death made them honor life so intensely. A story about my
father-in-law speaks to the point.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral procession was passing by the farm in North Georgia
where he raised vegetables and blueberries after his retirement.
The colonel was on his tractor in the fields, but he got down, took
off his hat and held it over his heart until the procession passed.
It wasn't anyone Col. Ezzard knew. It was his way of saying every
life is worth honoring.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Souther talks proudly about his grandson, who holds a
Ph.D. in history, he worries about how to protect a new generation
of Americans from the threats of technology, nuclear terrorists and
the rest. ``We old men just sit around drinking coffee now, and we
say, `Well, we can die, but what about our grandchildren?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
