<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-NCAA-PREVIEW _ Story setting up NCAA golf tourney in
Opelika, Ala. Georgia is the defending champion. Georgia Tech is
ranked No. 1 entering the tournament, and the biggest surprise is
that Georgia State also made the field. (Awtrey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   SEC-MEETINGS _ Story setting up what will be on the agenda at
the SEC Meetings in Destin, Fla. Likely among the topics, the
reconfiguration of the SEC football schedule that we first reported
two weeks ago. (Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FBC-VOLS _ Normally, this is a time of celebration for the fans
of Tennessee football. Coach Phil Fulmer is making his annual tour
of booster clubs, known as the Big Orange Caravan, where he fires
up the Volunteers faithful and gets them excited about another
season. But this year there is an air of uncertainty and uneasiness
at the school. It was bad enough that the Vols lost nine starters,
including five underclassmen, to the NFL draft. Now there are
additional charges from an English professor of academic fraud in
the way the athletes are tutored. The charged were first raised
last fall, but were thought to have been put to rest by an internal
audit. Those results were approved by the NCAA and all thought the
matter was closed. But the same professor has released her findings
concering 39 UT athletes which she says were put through a
hodge-podge of courses to keep them eligible. Those records are
being studied by the Faculty Senate and the NCAA plans a return
visit. Tennessee could be guilty of no NCAA violations but the
negative media attention from the episode could ultimlatey have an
adverse affect on the football program. It happened at Georgia in
1985. (Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   With chronology and a Q&AMP;A with the English professor. (Barnhart,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRACK AND FIELD
</P>
<P>
   RUN-NCAA-PREVIEW _ Story setting up the NCAA track championships
in Durham, N.C., where several Olympic hopefuls will compete.
(Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   RUN-TEXAS _ They simply weren't hungry enough. Texas men's and
women's track and field teams gear up for the NCAA outdoor
championships next week. They have the talent, but didn't show much
desire. Especially the women. (Riggs, Austin American-Statesman).
51.
</P>
