<HEADER>
A9920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SLADE-BOSS-ART-NYT &LR;      05-30 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLADE-BOSS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NICEST MAN ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (EDS: John H. Slade is honorary chairman of the executive committee
at Bear Stearns. This was written with Melinda Ligos.)  
 By JOHN H. SLADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week I celebrated my 92nd birthday, and I feel like the
luckiest man in the world.
</P>
<P>
   My good fortune started when I came to the United States on
March 26, 1936. I was 27 years old and had had been living in
Frankfurt, where I'd been hoping to make the field hockey team for
the German Olympics. But one day, the club I played for didn't
invite me to play in one of its games. The club's president told me
the team we were playing against didn't want any Jews on our team.
I took that as a sign and decided to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I got a lucky career break. A former boss at a bank
where I'd worked as an apprentice gave me an introduction to his
nephew who worked at Bear Stearns in New York. So the first day I
came here, I got a job as a runner for the firm, making $15 a week.
</P>
<P>
   I soon realized that in order to get ahead, you have to produce
commissions, so I began meeting the boats carrying the German
refugees as they arrived into New York. I often recognized the
names of some of the passengers, and brought customers to the firm
that way. I became the foreign bond trader at the firm, and later
started the risk arbitrage department.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the war started, I was fortunate enough to be able
to save my whole family by bringing them to the United States. In
1942, I left the firm to join the Army and spent three years on the
front lines of the war, interrogating POWs.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned from Europe at the end of 1945, I rejoined Bear
Stearns. In 1948, I returned to Europe, but this time as part of
the U.S. Olympic field hockey team. While I was in Europe, the firm
gave me permission to develop an international department.
</P>
<P>
   By 1949, I ran the international department, the international
trading department, the risk arbitrage department and the
convertible bond department. In 1951, I was made a partner of Bear
Stearns. When the firm went public in 1985, I became an executive
vice president and director.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what position I've held, I've had the same management
philosophy: Every employee is a human being. I've never screamed at
anybody at work, and I've never fired anybody. I treat people as
I'd like to be treated. That's my style.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't just been lucky in my career _ I've been lucky in
love, too. In 1977, while on a train to Switzerland, I met a
Hungarian couple, and we talked. The woman said she had a sister
who lived in New York, and I asked the gentleman, ``Is you
sister-in-law as attractive as your wife?'' And he said, ``And
how!'' And I asked for her name and address. Marianne and I were
married on the Concorde two months later.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago I decided to make room for the younger people at
the firm, so I'm now the the honorary chairman of the executive
committee, and the honorary director, which means I can attend all
the meetings but I have no vote. I'm lucky to be with a firm where
I'm permitted to work at my age.
</P>
<P>
   Though my job title has changed, I still keep busy. I wake up
every day at 5 a.m. and ride my electric bicycle for 25 minutes
while I watch the business news. Four days a week (Marianne doesn't
want me to work five days), I walk the mile from my home to the
office.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never retire because I love this job. For me, the whole
profession is a sport. Nobody can really predict what will happen
with the market. Every day, I have visitors from all over the world
come into my office and ask my opinion on various investments. And
I always tell them they can have my opinion, but it's just a guess.
I've been real lucky in the past, but who the hell knows what's
going to happen tomorrow?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
