<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PERSONALS: The Guns That Go Bang  
 (Eds: Repeating for all needing. This story also moved in the 
 ``l'' lifestyle news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Royal Navy recruits training at a gunnery school in Plymouth,
England, have been ordered to save money by lining up targets,
aiming their guns and shouting ``bang'' instead of shooting, which
uses up expensive shells. The school is scheduled to close in April
of next year, says a report forwarded by  &UR; Mark &LR; 
 &UR; Steinberg &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the armed forces' continuing efforts to
achieve the best possible value for money,'' a navy spokesman told
the Daily Telegraph of England.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Michael Jackson &LR; , who was in London and attended  &UR; Elizabeth &LR; 
 &UR; Taylor &LR; 's AIDS concert last week, insisted, reports Sunday People:
that he and Taylor be protected by 27 bodyguards at the Royal
Albert Hall; that all seats in his box be covered with plastic
sheeting replaced when anyone got up; that a humidifier pump air
into his box so he wouldn't catch germs; and that he be solely
responsible for pushing Taylor's wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Mike Tyson &LR;  told friends that he's getting divorced from
 &UR; Monica Turner &LR;  after three years of marriage and that he uses a
camera in his bedroom to protect himself against rape charges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MIDNIGHT AT AN OASIS &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter No. 4 _ the name of the book is being kept under
wraps _ will go on sale July 8, after months of top-secret
maneuvering. A Clean Well-Lighted Place for Books is planning to
start selling the book just after midnight on the morning of the
8th, keeping the store open until 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the secrecy is that before No. 3 came
out, entrepreneurs were making big bucks off pins and other
memorabilia they'd created from images they'd gotten in giveaway
materials. The publisher, Scholastic, wants to make sure that
hustlers ``don't sell things they don't have the rights to sell,''
said the bookstore's  &UR; Neil Sofman &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Morrow printed 5,000 bandannas to promote  &UR; Sonny &LR; 
 &UR; Barger &LR; 's memoir, ``Hell's Angel,'' but the author forced a recall.
``Sonny said to me, `We're Hell's Angels. We beat people up for
wearing that patch,''' Angel lawyer  &UR; Fritz Clapp &LR;  told
Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE FOOD CHAIN &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ So you stopped eating spotted owl stew and you thought you
were a hero? What about endangered herbs? Natural Health magazine
describes the work of United Plant Savers, which tries to protect
medicinal plants at risk of extinction. Unlike health food
advocates who recommend eating free-range chickens over those grown
for slaughter, the group urges consumers to buy only herbs that
have been cultivated for sale by a purveyor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roll Call reports that in an effort to lobby members of
Congress before last week's vote on normalizing trade with China,
the Business Roundtable sent every representative a package of
American goods that will be making their way to China. Hit the
deck, Beijing: Pringles potato chips are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE TIE SCORE &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In answer to his plea for ties to be worn by students graduating
from James Lick Middle School, Personals readers sent nearly 700
ties to teacher  &UR; Andrew Grimstad &LR; . The supply was so overwhelming
that he dispersed:
</P>
<P>
   Ties to Hoover, Francisco and Aptos middle schools, to be worn
by graduating students; ties to be worn by the band members at
Aptos, and chorus or band members at Lick; ties to be worn by
graduates presenting their portfolios (middle school theses) at
Lick; ties reserved for members of the Lick basketball team to wear
on game days. Extra ties (those in the worst condition) will be
made into quilts and used for other projects at school.
</P>
<P>
   And thank you to tie-givers from New York to San Francisco, to
the alum who sent a check and to the two tie manufacturers whose
offers were appreciated but unneeded because of the huge response.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I just made `The Caveman's Valentine,' where I play the &LR; 
 &UR; lover of a homeless Samuel Jackson, so we have a nude scene &LR; 
 &UR; together. Jackson told me he was looking forward to the bedroom &LR; 
 &UR; scene because he had never kissed anyone on screen before. More &LR; 
 &UR; money has been grossed by Samuel Jackson films in the last &LR; 
 &UR; decade than any single other actor, more than Mel Gibson, Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Cruise and Harrison Ford, and still his agent couldn't get him a &LR; 
 &UR; single sex scene!'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; Ann Magnuson &LR;  to Personals spy  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  at the New York
opening of ``Groove,'' which is set in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
