A9935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-U.S.-TELECOM-1S     05-30 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-TELECOM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL MAY BE NEAR TO OPEN JAPAN'S PHONE MARKET AND COUNTER U.S.
CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to recast lede and restructure; deletes grafs 1-4 of original
and inserts new grafs 1-5; subs grafs 6-9 to clarify; moves two
grafs before optional end to end of text, bgng `Japan has
proposed...')  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Senior members of Japan's ruling party are pressing the
dominant telecommunications company to cut sharply the high
connection fees charged to competitors, an issue that has caused
deep trade friction with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications executives and politicians have been saying
that in the last week members of the Liberal Democratic Party, most
notably its influential secretary-general, Hiromu Nonaka, have been
talking to the Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. about the fees,
which make the cost of doing business here exceedingly expensive
for other telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   The fees are the main reason for a stalemate in talks on
telecommunications deregulation between the United States and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing speculation that a deal is in the works to end
the stalemate and avoid a major trade dispute before Japan plays
host to a summit meeting of leaders from the richest industrialized
nations in less than two months.
</P>
<P>
   NTT, the former telephone monopoly in Japan and still its
biggest telephone company, controls 99 percent of the lines that
connect directly to homes and offices here. The price it charges
others to use those lines is critical to opening the
telecommunications market in Japan. At current rates, about 40
percent of the revenues of competing carriers is used for fees paid
to NTT, according to the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications,
which regulates the market.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has threatened to take the matter to the World
Trade Organization, signaling a potential escalation in the dispute
at a time when Japan's government is working to ensure a smooth
summit meeting, which President Clinton will attend.
</P>
<P>
   Even politicians sympathetic to NTT, which has tremendous
political influence because of its legions of employees and strong
trade union, are trying to coax the former telephone monopoly to
make some concessions on the fees.
</P>
<P>
   The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading business daily, said
the normally conservative Fair Trade Commission was about to
publish a report saying that Nippon Telegraph's reorganization last
year failed to enhance competition in the telecommunications market
here and urging sharper cuts in access fees.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts worry that in exchange for such cuts NTT may
get even more power than it already has and further hamper
competition here. Executives at competing carriers, Japanese
businessmen and politicians suspect that Nonaka and other senior
politicians are promising the telecommunications firm that they
will push for a sweeping revision of the restrictive law governing
its activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a move afoot to drastically revise, or even abolish
the NTT law,'' said Kei Hata, a member of the upper house of
parliament who is becoming one of the most vocal critics of the
government's regulation of Nippon Telegraph. ``I myself favor an
abolishment of the law, but only after we have secured conditions
for free and fair competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Hata and many others say those conditions do not yet exist in
Japan. Abolishing the NTT law would open the door for NTT East and
NTT West, the two regional fixed-line phone companies in the NTT
family, to provide long distance and international service. Many
worry that with the advantages of NTT's deep pockets and existing
technology, they would wipe out competitors that are only just
beginning to secure a toehold in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to think more about the implications of changing the
law,'' Hata said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NTT's recent financial performance, which was far better than
the company had projected, undercut its contention that it would be
crippled by cuts of the magnitude demanded by the United States.
Both NTT East and NTT West vastly outperformed the expectations of
their parent company, which has given even NTT's supporters cause
to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Junichiro Miyazu, NTT's president, has not furthered his
company's cause by saying he could not explain the markedly better
performance. His insistence that declining profitability at the two
regional carriers was a trend also rang somewhat hollow against the
backdrop of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earnings of the regional carriers improved,'' Eita
Yashiro, the minister of posts and telecommunications, said at a
press conference Tuesday. ``It's very different from the initial
projections.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of that, Yashiro said, his agency would consider the
reduction in interconnection fees it has proposed, as well as the
proposed timetable for achieving those reductions. Japan has
proposed cutting the fees by 22.5 percent over four years, saying
further cuts would damage NTT.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, however, wants cuts of 41.1 percent
immediately and has said the ministry is helping NTT avoid a
far-reaching overhaul of its business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
