<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-4     05-30 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK AND ARAFAT HOPE TO RESTART PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian Authority
leader Yasser Arafat are taking steps to revive their stalled peace
talks, which had been overshadowed for the past week by Israel's
abrupt withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is scheduled to fly to Germany on Thursday to meet with
President Clinton and discuss the ``implications'' of the
withdrawal and ``ways to advance the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations in particular,'' the prime minister's office announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, meanwhile, has restrained the often violent Palestinian
protest demonstrations of recent weeks, which are what had prompted
Israel to suspend the talks. His emissaries were working Tuesday
night to persuade hunger-striking Palestinian prisoners in Israeli
jails to resume eating in exchange for concessions on visitation
rights and other issues, Palestinian sources said. Officials on
both sides fear that the death of a hunger striker could detonate a
new round of violence in Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are expected to resume this weekend or sooner,
though it is not yet clear where. Nor is it clear what new
concessions either side is willing to make to break what Arafat on
Monday termed the ``impasse'' in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   But right-wing opposition leaders and one disgruntled Barak
cabinet minister asserted Tuesday that Barak is prepared to give
the Palestinians up to 95 percent of the West Bank, including
fertile Jordan valley lands extending to the edge of the Dead Sea.
Israel would retain Jewish-settled West Bank lands near its present
eastern border, plus a narrow sliver of the West Bank border zone
with Jordan for security purposes, according to opponents of the
reported proposal. Israel currently controls more than half of the
West Bank, which it seized from Jordan in the 1967 Arab-Israeli
war.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Natan Sharansky sent Barak a letter demanding
a security cabinet discussion of the alleged new negotiating offer,
a ministry spokesman said Tuesday night. Sharansky, who has
repeatedly threatened to quit the government over territorial
concessions in peace talks, said in his letter that the reported
new proposal would require up to 50,000 Jewish settlers to be
relocated into Israel and award the Palestinians sovereign control
over border crossings into Jordan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak's spokesman, Gadi Baltianski, said the position
ascribed to the prime minister ``does not represent the
government's posture or the agreement that we are working on.'' A
spokesman for Sharansky replied that the interior minister ``is
confident that his information is accurate.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Negotiations in Stockholm aimed at drafting an outline for a
final peace settlement were suspended last week following violent
protests in Gaza and the West Bank on behalf of the Palestinian
prisoners. The elastic deadline for the so-called framework
agreement was most recently extended to June 23, but negotiators on
both sides have expressed skepticism that they could resolve all
outstanding issues in the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat said last week's sudden Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon
has made it harder for him to compromise on territorial claims and
the highly sensitive issues of Palestinian refugees and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``My public sees Hezbollah'' _ the guerrilla movement that
fought against Israel's presence in southern Lebanon _ ``as heroes
who succeeded in getting the Israeli army out of Lebanon, and
believes that that is the route we should take as well,'' he told
Dalia Izik, Israel's Environment Minister, in a meeting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his effort to end the hunger strikes by the prisoners _ and
by their protesting sympathizers in West Bank and Gaza plazas _ is
clearly intended to pave the way for a return to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's Palestinian critics say he has further quelled dissent
by trampling on civil liberties: A Ramallah television station was
closed down by Palestinian police this morning after airing
repeated reports about the hunger strikers, and earlier this week
the police arrested local leaders of the dissident Palestinian
Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has quietly acknowledged Arafat's renewed control of his
internal security situation, lifting a week-long ban on travel by
Israelis and foreign tourists to Palestinian areas it imposed
following the firebombing of an Israeli car in Jericho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
