<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9937 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CACTUSCASH-TEX     05-30 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CACTUSCASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG A COSTLY BANE TO RANCHERS, THE PRICKLY PEAR IS NOW PROVIDING
PROFITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WORTH WREN JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Pity the poor prickly pear cactus no more.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of Texans have condemned it for pilfering moisture
from the prairie grasses that sustain cattle across this
drought-pestered state.
</P>
<P>
   But now the cactus is gaining a new image. New products,
including insect repellent and a skin-care moisturizing gel, are
being made from the extract of the prolific prickly pear.
</P>
<P>
   Since being introduced in the Caribbean islands in 1997, sales
of Cactus Juice products have gone national and are expected to top
$4 million this year, says the manufacturer, Safe Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which started its factory in Rowlett, transferred
operations to Dallas before relocating deep in Texas ranching and
farming country this year. Safe Solutions, with 20 employees, is
now based in Seymour, about 130 miles west of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Texas native Rob Gibson started the company after moving to
Roatan, one of the Bay Islands off the Honduras coast, where he
desperately needed relief from tropical insects and sun.
</P>
<P>
   He had retired early from partnerships in a string of auto
repair shops and gone in search of nirvana. Instead, he found a new
business career. Through a friend, he learned about the
possibilities of products made from cactus juice and decided to
test some of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to say, `It's going to be the next aloe,''' said
Gibson, referring to widely sold products made from the aloe vera
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Cactus Juice brand products are now sold in Kmart, Sam's Club,
some supermarket chains and other retail stores after their U.S.
debut this year.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the only way the prickly pear is losing its
pasture-pest reputation.
</P>
<P>
   From a long history as a food and feed source in Mexico and
Central and South America, cactus farming is snagging interest in
Africa, Israel, Sicily, southern Italy, Southern California and
other regions.
</P>
<P>
   And cactus is being used for a variety of foods from salsa to
wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beginning to get respectable,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Research on human health benefits of cactus extract has begun,
said Jonas Wilson, Safe Solutions' marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   The French are even showing an interest in its uses for skin
care, said Jim Moss, a free-lance technical writer and editor of
the Professional Association for Cactus Development Journal, based
in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters tout cactus vitamins, fiber and other nutrients. In
fact, cactus product claims are becoming so numerous that
scientists are urging caution for consumers. A cactus pill touted
for its health benefits was proved worthless, Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's move into the cactus product business was based on
research by another Texan, Richard Kunkel, who lived for many years
in Tarrant County and died last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kunkel, a retired industrial chemist whose son is a friend of
Gibson, had studied cactus extract. After testing it for use as an
insect repellent in Central America, Gibson and his partners found
a way to mass produce it. Hence, Safe Solutions Cactus Juice Insect
Protection and Cactus Juice Miracle Gel.
</P>
<P>
   Safe Solutions contracts ranchers to harvest the native cactus,
which in the past was sprayed with herbicide, burned or bulldozed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not traditional agriculture,'' said David Eppele,
director of Arizona Cactus and Succulent Research, a 14-year-old
nonprofit botanical garden in Bisbee, Ariz., in the Chihuahuan
desert on the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Eppele said, most North Americans have
stubbornly refused to believe in the commercial possibilities of
cultivating common prickly pear cactus for human foods, skin-care
products and livestock feeds. The cactus needles are easily singed
off. Or, Eppele said, a grower can choose from 17 naturally
spineless varieties with varying degrees of cold tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Cactus is nutritious, and it might even benefit diabetics, based
on early research, Eppele said.
</P>
<P>
   He cites centuries of American Indians and then Hispanics using
cactus juice to soothe and heal burned and scraped skin. They would
use both the green cactus ears and the plant's red, yellow or
purple fruit for food and livestock feed.
</P>
<P>
   As a cultivated crop south of the Rio Grande, the young green
ears, called ``nopalitos,'' are a venerable staple in Hispanic
cooking and steadily becoming sampled more often by Anglos north of
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nopalitos. That's yuppie food in Santa Fe, Sausalito and Fort
Worth,'' Eppele said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also rapidly becoming a U.S. staple. Eppele said U.S.
border officials at Nogales, Ariz., alone reported 138,000 tons of
imported prickly pear cactus in cans, jars and bulk fresh loads
crossing last year.
</P>
<P>
   A cactus margarita has been served on the San Antonio Riverwalk.
And although he hasn't sampled it yet, Wilson said, prickly pear
wine has been made. ``It's supposed to be pretty interesting,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of West Texas ranch wives have made jellies, jams
and relishes from ``cactus apples,'' the fruit. Now those
specialties and cactus candies and salsas are beginning to pop up
in more retail outlets, Gibson said. There are even kosher dill and
sweet-and-hot cactus salsas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could row crop it from here to Las Cruces,'' Eppele said.
``We can do this for free.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the desert plant doesn't need fertilizers, pesticides or
supplemental water. In some arid parts of Texas, New Mexico and
Arizona, producers could reap 50 tons per acre per year with no
costs other than the harvest work, he said. ``We've got to save our
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Eppele is pushing prickly pear for a major, cheaper role in
cattle feed, touting a mix of 75 percent cactus ears for fiber,
water and nutrients and 25 percent grain, molasses or cottonseed
byproducts, hay and minerals for a complete ration.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Seymour, the coming of the Cactus Juice factory has
created jobs in a town of about 3,100 people where most young
residents have been leaving to find work in the big cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're part of a rural renewal project,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
