<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9939 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SMOKING-FOE-HNS &LR;      05-30 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-FOE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHISTLE-BLOWER CONTINUES TO ATTACK TOBACCO INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By NICOLE FOY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Jeffrey Wigand no longer travels with an armed
guard. The threats against his family have stopped. The anxiety and
paranoia have all but ended.
</P>
<P>
   But the fire remains.
</P>
<P>
   The same angry conviction that spurred Wigand to blow the
whistle on the tobacco industry continues to compel him to rail
against his former bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week he detailed his high-stakes fight against Big Tobacco
for about 4,000 physicians attending the Texas Medical Foundation
annual conference at the Convention Center here.
</P>
<P>
   Wigand now works with a nonprofit anti-smoking group that
educates kids about the dangers of tobacco. He urged doctors to
closely track the Texas legislature's spending of the state's
recent $17 billion settlement with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should convince the legislature to get more involved (in
anti-tobacco efforts) and see that your kids' inheritance isn't
wasted on prisons, roads and bridges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once an obscure scientist for Brown &AMP; Williamson Corp., the
nation's third largest tobacco company, Wigand enjoyed a brush with
celebrity after actor Russell Crowe portrayed him in the Academy
Awards nominated movie ``The Insider.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the notoriety has come with a price, he said during an
interview that he would do it all again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being followed wasn't fun. Being threatened wasn't fun,''
Wigand said dryly. ``But I know what I'm doing is the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wigand, who holds a doctorate in biochemistry, worked for the
tobacco company from 1989 until 1993. He said he began the
$300,000-a-year job with the goal of using his knowledge to develop
a safer cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   But Wigand said he soon learned ``the lawyers were going to tell
me what to think about science'' in order to hide the fact the
company knew about the risks of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   As the evidence mounted that tobacco company executives were
hiding evidence nicotine was addictive, Wigand acknowledged he
chose to look the other way. The money and health benefits were too
precious to abandon, especially since his daughter has spina
bifida, he said. (In the movie, she suffered from asthma.)
</P>
<P>
   But after he recommended that the company remove from its pipe
tobacco an additive suspected of causing cancer, Wigand was fired.
He was, however, given health care benefits and a severance
package.
</P>
<P>
   He also had to sign a confidentiality agreement vowing not to
reveal anything about his work with the company. What executives
wanted to hide, Wigand said, was that cigarettes are manipulated to
enhance their addictive nature, then marketed to children.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for his former employer have claimed Wigand's
allegations are false and that they stem from the vengeance he felt
after losing his job.
</P>
<P>
   Wigand said he later became infuriated when the CEOs of the
nation's seven top tobacco companies testified before Congress that
cigarettes were not addictive or dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to grant an interview to CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' and in
it, he spilled secrets about his former company's research into the
addictive nature of tobacco. But the piece CBS broadcast was
heavily edited. Executives cited a threatened Brown &AMP; Williamson
lawsuit over Wigand's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Wigand also noted that at the time, CBS was controlled by
Laurence Tisch's Loews Corp., which also owned Lorillard, a firm
then working with Brown &AMP; Williamson on a deal with billion-dollar
implications.
</P>
<P>
   Wigand's eventual testimony in the first state lawsuit against
Big Tobacco helped lead to the 1998 national settlement between the
industry and 46 states. The $206 billion deal settled state
lawsuits filed against cigarette makers to recover Medicaid money
spent treating diseases related to smoking.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the industry has agreed to pay $246 billion over 25
years to settle lawsuits in the four other states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
