<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts and travel articles this week for release
Sunday, June 4, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moving in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-OVERVIEW (New York) _ With the Tony awards just hours
away, New York Times theater critic Ben Brantley reviews the
theater season and concludes there is much to toast.
</P>
<P>
   TONYS-TV _ (New York) _ Anita Gates reports that the one-hour
preshow of the Tony Awards on Sunday night on PBS is gaining equal
footing with the two-hour ceremony on CBS. The title of the hour is
``The First 10 Awards: Tonys 2000'' For the first time, Rosie
O'Donnell _ who is returning as host of the overall telecast _ will
be acting as live host of the first hour, and she'll have Nathan
Lane as a co-host.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TONYS-HERSCHER (New York) _ After a 50-year theatrical life
spanning several careers _ as a general manager, a producer, a
music publisher, an agent _ Sylvia Herscher, 86, is retired.
Composer Jerry Herman describes her as the offstage embodiment of
his greatest leading lady, Dolly Levi herself. Barry Singer
profiles Herscher as she prepares to step into the spotlight Sunday
night to receive a Tony award for excellence.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-MUSICALS (Undated) _ Playwright Wendy Wasserstein believes
that movie musicals defined romance and American exuberance and are
among the top ten reasons to live. She hopes Kenneth Branagh's
musical version of Shakespeare's ``Love's Labour's Lost'' will
introduce a new generation of moviegoers to one of the best
romantic comedies and some of the best songs ever written.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-IMMIGRATION (New York) _ ``A Well-Founded Fear'' penetrates
the Immigration and Naturalization Service's confidential system of
granting or denying asylum to refugees. Samuel G. Freedman
interviews the filmmakers Michael Camerini and Shari Robertson,
whose two-hour documentary received its first critical acclaim at
Sundance last January leading to its broadcast Monday night on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARYSHNIKOV-RAINER-DANCE (Undated) _ Superstars Mikhail
Baryshnikov, the prince of Russian ballet, and Yvonne Rainer, the
high priestess of the American avant-garde, are rehearsing together
for a season of the White Oak Dance Project. How did it happen that
Baryshnikov asked Rainer, who had not choreographed a dance in
decades, to contribute to this program? Wendy Perron writes about
the commissioning of ``After Many a Summer Dies the Swan.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RAVE-FILM-MUSIC (Undated) ``Better Living Through Circuitry,''
is the latest of three new films, along with the recently released
``Human Traffic'' and ``Groove'' to celebrate the rave scene. A new
crop of moviemakers are attempting to portray the rave subculture
in all its optimistic blissed-out, trippy glee. By David Bahr.
</P>
<P>
   YOGA-MUSIC (New York) _ Krishna Das is the icon of kirtan, the
trend to organized chanting sessions. Yoga Journal recently called
him ``The Pavarotti of Kirtan.'' His most popular album, ``Pilgrim
Heart'' (1996), has sold nearly 50,000 copies. He has sung with
Sting and given instruction to Madonna. ``I think it's perfectly
natural that a Westerner should go to India, soak it up and come
back and then work with the forms they've absorbed in this
lifetime, which for me was Little Anthony and the Imperials and
rock 'n' roll,'' said the artist who was born Jeffrey Kagel in Long
Island in 1947. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HAYNES-DRUMS-MUSIC (Undated) _ Ben Ratliff profiles drummer Roy
Haynes, 75, who has seen 50 years' of change in jazz from the best
vantage point _ the back of the bandstand, the rhythm section. He
has played with practically everybody of major significance since
the 1940s _ from Louis Armstrong to Pat Metheny.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-BRAZIL (Sao Paulo) _ In the largest city in Latin America's
largest country, cultural and business leaders wanted to
commemorate the 500th Anniversary of the Portuguese colonization of
Brazil and make a bold, sweeping statement about the state of the
arts in Brazil. They have. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, June 4, The New York Times Travel section highlights
travel in New England.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COOLIDGE-VERMONT (Undated) _ Christopher S. Wren visits
Plymouth Notch, the town known as Vermont's Brigadoon. This
community of clapboard farmhouses and weathered barns seems to have
changed little since Calvin Coolidge was sworn in here as president
on Aug. 23, 1923.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MAINE-WILDERNESS (Undated) _ Carey Goldberg asked the
question, ``How deep of a wilderness experience can be had in
Maine?'' and finds the answer. ``Pretty Deep.'' He writes of hiking
eight miles without meeting another person, flying over lakes of
pristine water, moose safaris and falling asleep in a yurt to the
sounds ``a chorus of clacks and cheeps and peeps and hoots ...''
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PARKS-SMOG (Undated) _ As smog season begins, it is
likely that some of the country's most popular national parks,
especially in the east, will once again be troubled by haze and
smog rivaling the levels in crowded metropolitan areas. By John H.
Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Paul Freireich answers readers questions
on how to find a flight simulator, tickets to cricket matches in
London and botanical gardens with wheelchair access.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGAINS (Undated) _ Deals on travel to Japan, Los Cabos
in Mexico, barge trips in France and the Four Seasons Hotels.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Printemps de Cahors arts festival in
France; a club style hotel in London; an online brokerage offers
frequent flier mileage; new guides to African-American sites in
North Carolina and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ There are steps leisure travelers
can take to avoid traffic jams and noise. Among other things, Betsy
Wade advises that the practical traveler should avoid large numbers
of internal combustion engines such as the 250,000 motorcylists who
rolled into Myrtle Beach, S.C. for Harley-Davidson Week.
</P>
