<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, May 31,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Updates: CLINTON-BARAK, TEACHER-FUNERAL (No photos for NYT
clients)
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BARAK _ LISBON, Portugal _ White House officials said
Tuesday that President Clinton will take time out of a European
summit to discuss Middle East peace with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak when the two leaders are in Berlin later this week. They
will meet on Thursday, said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart,
when Clinton is scheduled to participate in a summit with other
world leaders in Berlin. The summit on ``third way'' politics seeks
alternatives to the traditional liberal and conservative approaches
to government. Will wrapo in other news of the day. (Deans, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-PRISON _ BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Until she her release during
the Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon, Journalism student Cosette
Ibrihim spent 9 months in the notorious Al-Khaim prison, run by
Israel's allies, the South Lebanon Army. She said that as a
Christian and the objects of an international human rights cause,
she received ``lenient treatment'' a month of interrogations and
beatings, no trials or lawyers. ``Here,'' here captors told her,
``You defend yourself.'' Lebanese are debating whether to turn the
hill top prison into a museum or turn it into a prison for
collaborators. Inmates there in the '80s describe days chained to
electrical posts, sessions of dowsings with extremely hot or
extremely cold water. While her country celebrates Israel's
withdrawal, Ibrihim is suffering from stress, aggravated ulcers and
exhaustion. She's bitter and unsure of what to do with her life.
Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: RE-SENDING for those papers that have not used it
previously.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO-SENATE _ BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Coverage of Rick Lazio's
nomination for the Senate at the New York GOP convention.
(Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Nomination begins at 4 p.m.; acceptance speech follows.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-FUNERAL _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A memorial service was
held Tuesday for a teacher who was shot to death allegedly by a
13-year-old boy who had been sent home from school on the last day
of classes for throwing water balloons. (Palm Beach Post). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The Palm Beach Post will have an early version of this
story ready by 6:30 p.m. EDT. An updated version of the story
including reports from a 7 p.m. candlelight vigil will be available
later via the budget tool for Cox papers.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-TRIAL _ ATLANTA _ Lewis trial begins its second week of
testimony Tuesday as prosecutors try to stop the bleeding. The limo
passenger they struck a deal with seems to be the best thing
they've got coming up _ maybe today. (Rankin/Torpy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   OHAIR-TRIAL _ AUSTIN _ Closing statements in Gary Karr's trial,
then jurors begin deliberating. Verdict today possible. (Ball,
Austin American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKIES-BEARS _ GATLINBURG, Tenn. _ There was trepidation among
a few hikers in Tennessee and North Carolina in the wake of the
first fatal bear attack in the history of the Great Smoky Mountains
national park. Mostly, though, it seems like business as usual in
the Smokies. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
