<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      05-30 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: INDONESIA RECLAIMS ITS HISTORY BY INVESTIGATING PAST
ABUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Investigators who are struggling to break
through the mental fog of former President Suharto as they question
him are searching for something that is perhaps more valuable than
the billions of dollars he is said to have stolen from his country.
</P>
<P>
   They are fighting to reclaim a piece of their nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The fitful interrogations of the ailing 78-year-old former
president, who was placed under house arrest on Monday, are one
part of a broad campaign by President Abdurrahman Wahid to dig into
a past that is filled with hidden abuses.
</P>
<P>
   As with the national treasury, which Suharto used as his
personal bank account, he ravaged his country and then concealed
the evidence _ from shady business deals to dirty political tricks
to military massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wahid is pushing to dig up the bones of the past in a series
of investigations and trials. In response, he is receiving mostly
abuse, either from people who shout that he is moving too slowly or
from others who fear instability or personal exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main motivation is a hunger to explore this period of
Suharto's government,'' said Adam Schwarz, the author of ``A Nation
in Waiting'' (Allen &AMP; Unwin, 1999), the basic history of
Indonesia's recent past. ``I don't think it's really about the
money, and it's only partly about issues of justice. What is really
driving this is a strong desire for an accounting of what happened
in the past, whether in the case of human rights violations,
judicial misconduct or corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positive thing is that Indonesians will to some extent be
able to put the past behind them. The negative is that a lot of bad
things will be dragged back up to the surface and confronted.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Indonesia's most powerful people are resisting this
process. Most of those who prospered during the 32 years of
Suharto's rule were complicit to some degree in the abuses or
corruption that were the order of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are really serious,'' said one victim of a violent
raid on an opposition party office in 1997, ``then the police
headquarters would be empty, because everyone was involved.''
</P>
<P>
   As they push to uncover the truth about past abuses, the
investigations go beyond a simple exploration of the past. They
also have become a battleground of contemporary politics, enabling
Wahid to keep some of his opponents from the Suharto years on the
defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Some powerful people apparently are fighting back, instigating
violent incidents in an attempt to derail Wahid's government and
the threat it poses to them. Defense Minister Juwono Sudarsono, who
was also a Cabinet member in the previous government, said he knows
of several former civilian and military officials who are paying to
foment unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have noted that on several occasions when a new
investigation is opened or new charges are brought, a riot erupts
or bombs go off somewhere in this volatile nation.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Suharto did not begin in earnest until
Wahid took office last October. During the previous 17 months,
after Suharto's forced resignation in May 1998, the interim
government of President B.J. Habibie _ stocked with Suharto
loyalists _ protected him.
</P>
<P>
   The interrogations are moving slowly now because Suharto's mind
has been affected by three strokes. The disability is apparently
being maximized by his team of lawyers, and perhaps by Suharto
himself, to hamper the questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid and his attorney general, Marzuki Darusman, are also
meeting resistance as they probe a number of other difficult areas
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The most startlingly successful initiative so far, perhaps
because it was politically insulated, was the trial and conviction
on May 18 of 24 soldiers and a civilian for the massacre of an
Islamic teacher and more than 50 students last year in the province
of Aceh. The defendants received jail terms of up to 10 years each
_ although human rights campaigners now ask why none of their
superiors have been charged in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   It will be much more politically difficult to complete an
investigation into the campaign of violence last year in East Timor
after that former Indonesian province voted for independence.
Wiranto, the former military chief, formally resigned his Cabinet
post this month as he continued to undergo questioning as one of 21
high-ranking officers and civilians implicated by a government
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Opening another highly sensitive investigation this month, the
National Commission on Human Rights began summoning former generals
for questioning about the killings of at least 50 Muslim protesters
in the Tanjung Priok district of Jakarta in 1984. Among those
questioned were the former military chief, Benny Murdani, and a
former vice-president, Try Sutrisno.
</P>
<P>
   So far there has been no full-scale investigation into the riots
in May 1998 that helped bring down Suharto. It was clear from many
accounts by witnesses that much of that violence was instigated and
that a campaign of rapes of ethnic Chinese women was orchestrated
and involved members of the military.
</P>
<P>
   And although Wahid has raised the issue, there has been no
formal investigation yet into the massacres that began it all: the
killings of 500,000 people and the jailing without trial of
hundreds of thousands more in an anti-communist purge that began in
1965.
</P>
<P>
   The origins and responsibility for those atrocities have never
been fully explored, but their ultimate outcome was clear: Suharto
became president of Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9966 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-RIVER-HNS &LR;      05-30 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-RIVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT TO SETTLE RIVER FIGHT BETWEEN VIRGINIA AND MARYLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stepping into a territorial deal dating to 1632,
the U.S. Supreme Court agreed Tuesday to referee a dispute between
Virginia and Maryland over the Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Constitution and federal law, the justices are the
only ones who can settle lawsuits between states, but historically
they have accepted only cases they believe are important and cannot
be resolved otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The interstate feud began four years ago when Maryland blocked a
plan by the Fairfax County Water Authority in Fairfax, Va., to
extend a drinking-water intake pipe from Virginia's shore to the
middle of the river.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, a plant along the riverbank uses a pipe that opens
only a few feet from the riverbank to supply water to 1.2 million
Northern Virginia residents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Virginia officials, concerned about muddied water and
the build-up of sediment around the pipe, proposed extending the
pipe 725 feet into the center of the river to collect cleaner
water.
</P>
<P>
   But Maryland, which owns the entire Potomac under a 1632 land
grant from King Charles I of England, refused to issue a
construction permit for the new pipe until the completion of a
state-ordered study on the environmental impact of the project.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief to the court, Virginia Attorney General Mark L.
Earley argued that the pipe extension is needed to secure a
``reliable'' water supply and to protect residents from toxic
by-products that can't be removed from muddy water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are serious public health issues that militate against
further delay,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Earley said the delay in building the extension
costs Virginia several hundred thousand dollars a year because of
the expense involved in straining sediment out of the water that
comes into the existing pipe.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that several interstate agreements give Virginia
rights to the water in the river and allow the state to build out
from its shoreline without asking Maryland's permission. Earley
also claimed that an appeal to a Maryland administrative law judge,
which was filed in 1997 after Maryland denied the permit, has been
needlessly delayed and embroiled in politics. The appeal process no
longer offers a fair way of resolving the dispute, he argued.
``Maryland will continue to delay for years and ultimately deny
Virginia its permit and the Maryland courts will uphold that
determination,'' Earley wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland responds that Virginia is responsible for the very
problem that Earley is complaining about.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia created its problem by allowing rampant residential and
industrial development, which has increased pollution and sediment
run-off into the river.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Byrnie, a spokeswoman for Maryland Gov. Parris N.
Glendening, said in a statement Tuesday that her state has
``serious concerns'' about the environmental impact of a new water
intake pipe that must be addressed before the extension could be
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is confident that the Supreme Court will
recognize that Maryland has taken reasonable and appropriate action
to address those concerns,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said environmentalists worry that the new pipe would allow
Fairfax County to draw more water and would feed even more growth
in Virginia, further damaging water quality.
</P>
<P>
   The Potomac River is only one of several boundary rivers being
fought over by states. The others are Alabama, Arizona, California,
Florida, Georgia, Kansas and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court already is considering whether to look into a
case brought by California and Arizona against the federal
government and an Indian tribe over rights to Colorado River water.
The court has not yet decided whether to take the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Quechan tribe wants more water to irrigate its Fort Yuma
Indian Reservation, which straddles the river where it flows
between the two states. The tribe claims the water under an 1893
treaty that promised irrigation benefits that never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   But both states contend the Quechan relinquished their claim in
a $15 million settlement over disputed land and water in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The high court also may be called on to resolve other disputes
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Nebraska, state Attorney General Don Stenberg has asked the
high court to settle his state's legal war with Kansas over the use
of water from the Republican River basin. Kansas accuses Nebraska
of violating a 1943 interstate compact by allowing farmers to
divert more than their legal share of the river's water for private
use.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Georgia, Alabama and Florida have said that unless
a deal can be worked in the next few months over two river basins,
they also will ask the court to settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   They are wrangling over the Alabama-Coosa-Tallapoosa and
Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint river basins, both of which
originate in Georgia. Georgia relies on the rivers for drinking
water and hydroelectric power, especially in the growing metro area
of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But downstream, Alabama and Florida are asking for assurances
that enough water will be available for their needs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
