<SLUG> BC-SEC-MEETINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC tees up scheduling change
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ Over the next few days, the 12 members of the SEC
will gather at this resort for their annual ritual.
</P>
<P>
   They will engage in some R&AMP;R after hard year's work, and they
will get a check from the conference office to take back home. This
year, each school's share of television revenues is expected to be
between $5 million and $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, when SEC commissioner Roy Kramer ends the meetings
Friday, the conference also will have put in place a major change
in the way it schedules football games.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC will change its schedule format for the first time since
it expanded to 12 teams in 1992. The purpose is to give more
variety to the schedule and to please television, which provides
the largess.
</P>
<P>
   Because teams play just eight conference games, a rotation
determines the schedules. Under the old system, such games as
Alabama-Georgia, Alabama-Florida and Auburn-Tennessee came along
only twice in eight years. Under the new format, which will begin
in 2002, such games will come along twice every six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had to sacrifice a little to make this happen,''
Kramer said, ``but I think it's a big step forward for the
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Other hot topics during this week's meetings will include the
recent decision by the NCAA to eliminate summer basketball
recruiting in 2001. The coaches don't like it, but key college
administrators, including Kramer, are insisting some changes be
made.
</P>
<P>
   Some early decisions on which SEC football games will be
televised this fall also are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
