A9980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-ENTREPRENEUR-(T     05-30 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ENTREPRENEUR-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-FLYING CHINESE CAPITALIST GETS LIFE SENTENCE FOR FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China's most celebrated private entrepreneur,
Mou Qizhong, will end his days in a prison cell, a Chinese court
decided Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Intermediate People's Court in Wuhan, an industrial city,
sentenced Mou to life in the country's bleak penal system, ending a
remarkable chapter in China's fitful march toward a market economy.
China's state press reported that Mou said he would appeal, but
appeals in such high-profile cases are rarely granted and almost
never successful if they are heard.
</P>
<P>
   Mou, 58, became the very model of the new Chinese capitalist in
the early 1990s, after Deng Xiaoping kicked off a fresh wave of
high economic growth and easy credit. Mou, a master at
self-promotion, delighted the Western and Chinese press with his
claims of great wealth and his crazy investment schemes, like a
string of private satellites to be launched from neighboring
Kazakhstan _ little of which any journalists took the trouble to
substantiate.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of the media hype, Mou insisted that his Land
Economic Group was worth as much as $240 million, and Forbes
magazine listed him as the fourth wealthiest man in China. Now it
appears more likely that he was the most indebted man in China
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Mou's rise and fall say as much about Western misperceptions of
China's development as they do about the deep flaws in China's
hybrid socialist-market economy. It seems now that Mou was more a
symbol of how far an opportunist can get on China's political
favoritism and lack of transparency, rather than an example of
capitalistic entrepreneurship. And his case is a stark illustration
of the poor monitoring of China's leaky banking system, which is
swamped with bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Wuhan court said Mou defrauded the Bank of China's Wuhan
branch by drawing $75 million on a letter of credit that was
supposed to pay for computer equipment imported from Australia. Mou
apparently spent the money on satellite investments that generated
no revenue. When in 1996 Beijing finally told state banks to call
in their loans to Mou, his debts exceeded his assets by about $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing reporters with colorful copy _ Mou's
outlandish proposals included blasting a hole in the Himalayas to
let warm moist air flow in from India and turn the arid Tibetan
plateau into an oasis _ he had a compelling story. The son of poor
farmers, Mou spent four years in jail during the 1970s for
criticizing the leaders of China's disastrous Cultural Revolution
in a book titled, ``Where is China Headed?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He rose to prominence in 1989, when he openly supported the
government's crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in Tiananmen
Square. China's leaders rewarded him with public recognition, which
allowed him the freedom to operate in what is still a tiny, tightly
circumscribed private sector.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he brokered a barter between Russia and his home
province of Sichuan, swapping a few hundred railroad cars of canned
pork, garments and electronic goods for four used Tupolev-154
passenger jets. The deal reportedly netted him $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mou was a charmed man _ for a while. Banks readily loaned him
money. He was toasted as China's new breed of capitalist at the
World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland. But the barter deal may
have been the only profitable business he ever conducted. He
ricocheted from one dubious project to another, including the
proposed purchase of an aircraft carrier for China's navy. By 1995
he was working on the satellite deal and his political capital was
running out.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu Rongji, then China's deputy prime minister, had begun an
austerity drive to tame double-digit inflation and rein in bank
lending. Suddenly Mou's high profile drew scrutiny from more sober
eyes. In 1996, when he was unable to repay the bank loans, the
government began seizing his assets and confiscated his passport.
He was formally arrested in January last year and charged with
fraud in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
