<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, May 31 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Lisbon, Portugal) _ Opening his last scheduled
trip to Europe as President, President Clinton on Tuesday stood
near the spot where Portuguese explorers set sail for the New World
five centuries ago, praising them for their global adventures and
calling for ``a new voyage of discovery.'' By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-CROSS-OWNERSHIP (Washington) _ The Federal Communications
Commission is expected to recommend easing somewhat the
restrictions that have prevented newspapers from owning radio and
televisions stations in the same cities. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NKOREA (Yanji, China) _ Like hundreds of thousands of
hungry North Koreans have sneaked into neighboring China to find
food, escaping a deadly famine in their homeland. But now, Chinese
police have sharply increased their efforts to expel the North
Koreans living undercover in China, creating a climate of fear
along the border and fueling a potentially explosive international
refugee crisis. The number of ``food migrants'' sent back has at
least doubled this year, up to about 2,000 a month, aid groups on
the border say. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MASSACRE-DAILY (Louisville, Ky.) _ Edward Daily seemed to
have the resume of a true American hero. When the Associated Press
began investigating reports that the unit he said he was with had
massacred hundreds of South Koreans nearly 50 years ago, Daily, 69,
seemed an ideal guide. The story led to a Pulitzer for the AP and
the unmasking of Daily. As the Army and other reporters began to
study the records, it became clear that Daily was neither the war
criminal nor war hero he claimed to be. He was never at the scene
of the massacre or even with the unit. And interviews with veterans
show that Daily, who had been chatting them up for years to develop
books, may have airbrushed himself into their memories of the war.
By Michael Moss.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ALTHORP (Great Brington, England) _ It is spelled simply
enough, in just two syllables, with no strange or gimmicky
combinations of letters. But for centuries it has been grievously
mispronounced by everyone who is not anyone. And no wonder. Why
would the average person know that the word ``Althorp'' is supposed
to be pronounced AWL-trupp? That is exactly the question Earl
Spencer, brother of the late Diana, Princess of Wales, and the
owner of Althorp, the family's impressive ancestral estate next to
this tiny village, asked himself recently. In a highly
unaristocratic move, the earl announced that ``Althorp'' should
henceforth be known the way common people might think it should be
known. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH (Bint Jbail, Lebanon) _ After liberating
southern Lebanon with rockets and bombs, the Hezbollah militia is
back here in force _ this time with an army of doctors, nurses,
veterinarians, bulldozers, agronomists and engineers. One week
after the last Israeli soldiers retreated from the rocky hillside
villages that they controlled for nearly 18 years, the business of
keeping the water pumping and the hospitals running for an
estimated 75,000 Lebanese civilians has been taken on by Hezbollah.
By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
