<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ULSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER PROGRESS, PITFALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government of Northern Ireland is up and running once again,
thanks to a narrow vote of support by the Ulster Unionist Council.
But the two great sectarian factions of the North remain at odds
over symbolic and substantive issues.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists were barely mollified by the Irish Republican Army's
promise May 6 to put its weapons beyond use. The IRA must give
international monitors every opportunity to examine its arms dumps
and verify that the guns are safely buried.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Friday agreement, under which the government was
formed, is based on the belief that both sides can find a way
around ancient differences. This approach ought to guide a
compromise on the issue of whether government ministers from Sinn
Fein, the IRA's party, will fly British flags above their ministry
buildings. Ministers ought to have the option of substituting a
flag based on the emblem of the Northern Ireland Assembly _ a bunch
of flax to symbolize the Ulster linen trade.
</P>
<P>
   Compromise will be more difficult on a weightier question:
reorganization of the Royal Ulster Constabulary so that it will no
longer be a weapon of unionist power. A commission headed by Chris
Patten wants to change the name to the Northern Ireland Police
Service, encourage nationalists to join, and ensure that
representatives of both communities oversee police activities.
</P>
<P>
   The British government filed a bill to implement the Patten
recommendations, but made changes that could dilute the proposed
reforms. It is especially worrisome that nationalist recruitment
quotas will last only three years (subject to renewal), instead of
the 10 proposed by Patten. Parliament will consider the bill for
several months. The final version has to be unambiguous in support
of a force acceptable to the majority of people in the North.
</P>
<P>
   The signatories to the Good Friday agreement considered policing
too volatile an issue for the new Northern Ireland government. The
revival of the government this week will create a climate of
political dialogue that is essential to attracting nationalists to
the force. Peace is coming slowly to Northern Ireland _ slowly but
steadily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
