<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PERU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNISHING FUJIMORI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori, who was reelected Sunday to
a third term in an election roundly lamented as unfair and
illegitimate, is a tough nut and should not be expected to crack
easily when confronted with criticism from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying issue in Peru's sham election is not the
personality or the politics of Fujimori. Indeed, he has used his
power to bring an unprecedented number of schools, health clinics,
and roads to the poor of Peru, and polls suggest he probably would
have won a fair election if Peru's Elections Board, staffed with
his loyalists, had postponed Sunday's runoff, as international
observers wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's flouting of foreign election observers is significant
because it may be a sign that the democratic tide that has been
rising for a decade in Latin America has started to ebb. In
comparison with that prospect, the computer flaws in Peru's
electoral process are secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign monitors were certainly justified in asking that
Sunday's second round of balloting be delayed so they could
determine how newly installed computer software came up with 1.4
million more ballots cast than eligible voters during the first
round of voting April 9. But the perverting of democratic process
in Peru goes much deeper. It starts with Fujimori replacing
high-court judges so that he could change the constitution to
permit himself a third term. His domination of the media and his
refusal to accept the advice of international election monitors
completed the tableau of a power-drunk Fujimori mocking democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Because Fujimori recently rescheduled much of Peru's foreign
debt and because economic sanctions could have unwelcome effects on
surrounding Andean nations, Washington and its allies in the
Organization of American States ought to try political rather than
commercial methods of chastising Fujimori, much as the European
Union did after the neo-fascist Jorg Haider entered a governing
coalition in Austria. The punishment of Fujimori should be
multilateral, depriving his government of OAS positions and
prerogatives. The OAS should be a club for democracies, one in
which Fujimori can no longer be treated as a member in good
standing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
