<HEADER>
A0002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-LABS-ASIANS-NYT &LR;      05-30 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LABS-ASIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLARS URGE ASIAN-AMERICANS NOT TO APPLY AT NUCLEAR LABS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., N.M., Calif.)  (Eds.: Absence of hyphenation in Asian American organizations is
cq.) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Objecting to what it sees as racial discrimination, a national
organization of scholars and educators has formally called upon
Asian-Americans to boycott federal nuclear laboratories by not
applying for jobs there.
</P>
<P>
   The group, called the Association for Asian American Studies, is
objecting to the treatment of Wen Ho Lee, a former government
scientist accused of mishandling nuclear secrets, and to the
application of security rules to Asian-American scientists who
remain in federal laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, which called for the action on Friday, is the
second scholarly organization this year to urge Asian-American
scientists to boycott the federal labs, which are run by the U.S.
Department of Energy. In March, a California-based organization
called Asian Pacific Americans in Higher Education called for a
similar boycott, citing closely related grievances.
</P>
<P>
   Because Asians and Asian-Americans make up more than a quarter
of all doctorates awarded in science and technology by American
universities each year, the impact on the federal laboratories
could be serious if young scientists decided to heed the
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of case touches a very raw nerve,'' said Stephen H.
Sumida, a professor of American Ethnic Studies at the University of
Washington in Seattle and past president of the Association for
Asian American Studies. ``I think everybody in the organization
knows that the `suspect pattern' of the treatment of
Asian-Americans goes back to the internment of Japanese Americans
in World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the reaction among Asian-American scientists inside the
labs to the earlier resolution has been mixed, it has been the
subject of intense discussion and debate, as well as a source of
concern in the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a mistake, it's counterproductive and it will not
be effective in terms of achieving its original objective,'' said
Jeremy Wu, the Energy Department's national ombudsman, who deals
with workplace issues like diversity and equal opportunity. Because
the boycott could reduce Asian-American participation at the labs,
Wu said, ``it certainly will hurt those who are fighting against
racial profiling in the department right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sumida said the boycott resolution was approved by an
overwhelming majority of about 250 members of the association who
voted on it during a national meeting in Scottsdale, Ariz. The
association has about 700 members in academic departments around
the nation, he said. The membership, which is about three-quarters
Asian-American, is concentrated in humanities departments but also
includes scholars in mathematics and the physical sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has been charged with illegally downloading American nuclear
secrets onto unsecure computers and portable tapes. He has been
largely kept in an isolated cell while awaiting his trial,
scheduled for the fall, although more recently he has been allowed
to travel in shackles to review evidence in the case with his
lawyers. Even though Lee has not been charged with espionage, the
government has said that to free him would be to risk his
disclosing the location of the tapes, seven of which are missing,
to foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution asserts that Lee, a former scientist at the
Energy Department's Los Alamos National Laboratory was singled out
for prosecution solely because of his race and treated with undue
harshness during his incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   Those claims were rejected by Myron Marlin, a Justice Department
spokesman. ``The indictment charges Mr. Lee unlawfully created
computer tapes containing some of our most sensitive nuclear
secrets, and now several of those tapes are missing,'' Marlin said.
``It's a serious charge and the proper place for this now is in the
courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the earlier boycott resolution has had an effect on the
labs is hard to determine. Jim Danneskiold, a spokesman for Los
Alamos, said that the number of Asian scientists applying for
postdoctoral positions at the lab had dropped significantly even
before the March boycott resolution, but that Asians and
Asian-Americans were still applying and being hired.
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticisms of the resolutions, L. Ling-chi Wang,
chairman of the Department of Ethnic Studies and director of the
Asian American Studies Program at the University of California at
Berkeley, who helped introduce both resolutions, says that the
threat of withdrawing Asian-American talent from the labs is the
best available way to make their concerns widely known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully intend to use the resolution to send a very, very
strong message to our government that we do not appreciate the way
that we are being treated as Americans,'' he said. ``At the heart
of it is that the Asian-Americans' civil rights are being
violated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1920EDT &QL; 
