<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0003 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-`DEFILED'-FEATURE-LAD     05-30 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`DEFILED'-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER TRIES DEFILING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No sitcom writer could make this up _ unless, perhaps, he was a
direct descendent of Rod Serling.
</P>
<P>
   George Costanza _ or someone who looks and sounds alarmingly
like him _ rigs up a homemade bomb and holes himself up in a
library, threatening to blow the building (and himself) to
smithereens unless his not-so-Seinfeldian demands are met. (We'll
get to those demands in a second.) &QL; 
And who comes in to talk him out of it? Looks like an older,
wearier version of Lt. Columbo.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find proof that stage drama is actually stranger than
syndicated TV at the Geffen Playhouse where Jason Alexander (of
``Seinfeld'') and Peter Falk (``Columbo'') are playing fanatical
librarian and crisis negotiator respectively in the world premiere
of Lee Kalcheim's play, ``Defiled,'' which opens tonight.
</P>
<P>
   A suspense-driven, two-character play that confronts the
scariness of technology gone haywire, ``Defiled'' wasn't written as
Costanza vs. Columbo but pardon us if we hear some familiar echoes
from the dialogue and mannerisms of Harry Mendelssohn, the edgy
librarian and Detective Brian Dickey, the sandbagging cop.
</P>
<P>
   Unquestionably, Harry's smarter than George. Well read, well
spoken and in possession of technology to cause major damage, this
librarian is somebody you could see yourself having a lengthy
conversation or debate with. Under calmer circumstances, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bright guy. He's brighter than I am,'' Alexander says
over a rehearsal break dinner at a nearby Chinese restaurant.
``There's a lot going on with this guy, and there's just conditions
upon conditions upon conditions. Suicide is a big condition and the
amount of conviction he has about the why of it all. You can say
the words, but they have to mean something.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you have to do a lot of work, thinking about what am I
really fighting for here.''
</P>
<P>
   In a word: he's fighting progress, the type of advancements that
only a computers could create. The book tracking system in Harry's
library is about to be computerized, meaning the card files
(remember those?) will be purged. Harry wants those cards to stay.
More than that, he wants the ease and convenience the cards
represent not to be, well, defiled. If not, kaboom! And Harry won't
negotiate, not even with a good hearted plain talking cop like
Detective Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system works, it is fast. And it is personal. It is
perfect,'' Harry says during one of several long speeches. ``Why
change it just to change?''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily a techno-phobe, Alexander says he can
nonetheless relate to Harry's plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Internet, for all its good, could be the undoing
of civilization,'' he says. ``I think it becomes potentially a
replacement for actual experiences which is part of the thesis of
this play. I think technology is ahead of our ability to use it
ethically and morally, so I have some of the concerns that the
character has about the dehumanization that we're going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk, who joins the conversation a little later, agrees. He is,
after all, a man who possesses a Masters degree but confesses that
he is too intimidated to make a long distance call from an airport.
What does it say about the convenience of the information age, he
wonders, if you have to remember 15 different telephone numbers
(phone, office phone, office fax, new area codes.)
</P>
<P>
   The Internet? Don't get him started.
</P>
<P>
   ``The few times that I have ever gone on the Internet, I was
surprised at how superficial the information was,'' says Falk, 72.
``There's this terrific book I've been wanting to read for 30 or 40
years about ants and termites and termitaries. I looked that up on
the Internet to find out more about it, all I got was superficial
information. You have to read the book! You read the book, you'll
know something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people are intimidated by technology,'' he
adds, sounding a bit like Harry Mendelssohn. ``They don't know how
it works, and half of the time it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk, who last appeared on an L.A. stage 15 years ago, first
came across ``Defiled'' during a series of readings run by the
Coronet Theatre. Twice he participated in non-staged readings of
``Defiled'' opposite Woody Harrelson.
</P>
<P>
   Very early, Falk found himself hooked, both on the relationship
that develops between the two very different characters, and on the
play's themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fascinating play with a subject that everybody is
thinking about,'' Falk says. ``There is nobody alive on this planet
who hasn't thought about the things we're talking about in this
play.''
</P>
<P>
   If Falk's participation in the premiere of ``Defiled'' was a
given, Alexander's was less certain. When director Barnet Kellman
first sent him a copy of the play, Alexander had convinced himself
that stage work wasn't currently an option. Despite his theatrical
background _ including a Tony award for ``Jerome Robbins'
Broadway'' and an appearance in the Reprise! version of ``Promises,
Promises'' at UCLA _ Alexander said stage roles aren't convenient
when you've got a young family to consider.
</P>
<P>
   The busy actor/producer will appear as Boris Badenov in ``The
Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' this summer, and he'll return
to television in a new series he's developing for Fox in 2001. But
movie and television projects have convenient or short term
schedules that can be worked around school routines and vacations.
Not so a five-week run in Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love musicals and I love the theater, but what everything is
weighed against these days is fatherhood,'' said Alexander, 40, who
has two sons, ages 8 and 4. ``So the material has to be so
worthwhile that I can look my sons in the eye and say, `I gotta do
this. Everybody kind of has to do something for their soul now and
then. I gotta do this.''' If the material doesn't hold up to that,
there isn't a conversation to be had.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Defiled,'' he says, the conversation was worth having.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really intrigued with the story and flattered at the
idea of being asked to play the character and also a little
intimidated by it. It had been a while since I had found something
that I really cared about. So I talked to my wife, and said, `This
could be a good thing.' She read it, and she said, `You need to do
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The pairing has been an intriguing, and, by all accounts, a
successful one. The two actors, both East Coast born and raised
(Falk in New York City, Alexander in New Jersey), say they have
enjoyed working with _ and, in some cases, against _ each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with his emotional availability,'' Falk says
of Alexander, ``his ability to generate genuine emotion very early
and his flexibility in terms of the various attitudes that this
character has to take. It's nice to be engaged when the other actor
forces you to be engaged. When you really hear them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to make a joke, but it was largely true, that I never
HEARD another actor, but I hear (Alexander).''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being very gracious,'' replies Alexander. ``At the same
time, I have to come loaded for bear because you don't walk into
the first rehearsal with this little time and with an actor whose
work you respect, you don't walk in and say `Well, let's see what
happens.' You gotta show up. You gotta show up when they're that
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus there was another consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter is my father's favorite actor, you know,'' Alexander
says. ``He's unimpressed that I'm doing this play, but he's very
impressed that I'm working with Peter Falk. His advice to me is,
`Don't screw him up.''' &QL; 
--- &QL; 
What: ``Defiled.'' &QL; 
Where: Geffen Playhouse, 10886 Le Conte Ave., Westwood. &QL; 
When: Through July 2, Performances Tuesdays through Thursdays at
7:30 p.m., Fridays at 8 p.m., Saturdays at 4 p.m. and 7 p.m. and
Sundays at 2 p.m. and 7 p.m. &QL; 
Tickets: $20-$42. Call (310) 208-5454 or (213) 365-3500. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0005 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-30 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PLEASE PROTECT US AGAINST DIRTY MEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This is crazy _ and very, very dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   A judge in Texas has ruled that the Agriculture Department has
no legal authority to enforce modern scientific standards of meat
inspection, which were approved five years ago by Congress after a
bitter partisan fight.
</P>
<P>
   That judicial nitwit held that a meat processing plant showing
unacceptably high levels of contamination with salmonella bacteria
could not be closed down by federal inspectors. If little kids get
sick from eating diseased hamburgers, that's not the industry's
fault, U.S. District Judge A. Joe Fish in effect concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Many conservatives loathe the very concept of government
regulation on grounds that it unduly burdens the functioning of the
free marketplace. American consumers are supposed to be on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   The meat processing industry stalled the new inspection system,
which detects dangerous microbes through modern scientific testing
methods, for 15 years after its development. The industry was aided
by anti-regulation Republican allies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But public outrage and scary salmonella outbreaks finally forced
the GOP in 1995 to stop defending a 90-year-old system that
depended on seeing and smelling rotten carcasses. That year, when
Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, then a presidential candidate,
conceded defeat, he complained he was being accused unfairly of
wanting to feed people ``dirty meat.'' He had been seen as putting
the principle of saving money for a big campaign-contributing
industry, which would have to install new equipment and retrain
workers, ahead of saving lives.
</P>
<P>
   Safeguarding public health is not some plot hatched by
overzealous socialists to hamstring honest businesses. It is the
minimum a responsible country can do to protect the well-being of
its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials should never forget they have been given their
power to use it for the public good, not the good of vested
interests.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Fish is trying to accomplish from the bench what
Congress could not do in defiance of the public good. He strained
mightily to rationalize his decision that flunking three tests for
salmonella contamination did not prove that the Supreme Beef
Processors' plant in Dallas had sanitation problems that warranted
its closing. The contamination could have occurred before the meat
got to the plant, Fish explained.
</P>
<P>
   The logic of this escapes those of us who think dirty food is
directly related to being processed in dirty places. And if the
plants weren't dirty when the food got there, the contaminated food
would certainly spread germs to the machinery when it was ground,
and they would be passed along to future batches. And what was the
plant doing accepting dirty food without checking on its purity in
the first place?
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being closed by inspectors, the plant was also
forced to recall 180,000 pounds of ground beef because a sample
tested positive for E. coli bacteria, which can be a big killer.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge's convoluted ruling stands, it could undermine the
standards now protecting meat consumption all over the country and
force a return to the antiquated poke-and-sniff system.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fish's decision applies directly only to the northern
district of Texas, it may have consequences across the country.
Plants elsewhere may be emboldened to challenge the federal system.
</P>
<P>
   Before its troubles, Supreme Beef had a contract with the
Agriculture Department to supply hamburger for federal school lunch
programs in many states. Parents did not know their kids were
threatened with foul hamburgers and possible sickness. Surely the
federal government was right in stopping the plant's operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department will appeal Fish's ruling. Most other
plants have had no trouble complying with the new tests. Ninety
percent of the larger companies and 84 percent of the small ones
have already installed systems to keep salmonella-tainted beef out
of their plants.
</P>
<P>
   One political argument against the upgraded testing system used
to be that the danger of salmonella was being exaggerated. But this
illness is not fun. It can be deadly for infants and tots, the
elderly and those with weakened immune systems. About 600 deaths
and 1.4 million illnesses were attributed to salmonellosis last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional approval of overdue modernization of the meat and
poultry inspection system was a near thing. If it hadn't been for
Dole's concern about getting an anti-consumer image as he went into
a presidential campaign, the processing industry might have
succeeded in quietly burying the new high-tech regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, under public pressure the majority leader called off
his troops who were ready to block the new rules. Dole confessed to
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, a fellow Kansan, that he didn't
want any more ``food fights.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's GOP presidential heir-apparent, George W. Bush, whose
home state is the focus of the new controversy, is unlikely to want
any food fights either.
</P>
<P>
   Congress could quickly pass legislation to reassert and bolster
the administration's power to enforce its inspection standards,
bypassing the political limbo of a long judicial appeals process.
It would be a powerful pro-consumer demonstration. But there will
be no pressure from Bush on the Republican majority to do so, and
you can bet it won't.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-APOLLO-HIP-HOP-475(2T     05-30 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLLO-HIP-HOP-475(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBLING ON A HIP-HOP MUSICAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NINA SIEGAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a group of rap legends and Harlem-based artists
announced last month that they would be mounting a Broadway-style
musical in the landmark Apollo Theater, the show was presented not
only as an indicator of Harlem's economic and cultural renewal, but
as the birth of a virtually new theatrical genre as well: the
hip-hop musical.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is ever simple when it comes to exploring an
embryonic artistic form, or, for that matter, stretching the
borders of artistic expression in Harlem. The Apollo has never been
known as a venue for plays. And while hip-hop may have invaded
every other aspect of culture, it has not yet established a place
for itself on the American stage.
</P>
<P>
   The play, ``Echo Park,'' opens Thursday. It has drawn on rap
legends and community resources like the National Black Theater and
the Julia de Burgos Cultural Center, and it looks to set down a
version of hip-hop history at a time when the genre, now more than
20 years old, is given more and more to reflection and
historiography. As with almost any theatrical production, this one
has had its share of artistic struggles, sleepless nights and
financial headaches, but ``Echo Park'' also comes to the stage
bearing the burden of trying something that has not been done
before.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the curtain was to rise, the big dance numbers
were almost seamless, with break dancers leaping effortlessly into
back flips and diving across the stage into head spins, and the
rappers hitting their marks dead on. But the director was lamenting
that the dramatic scenes verged on lethargy, and the producers were
still worrying about the financial troubles of a venture that must
turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The first installment of a trilogy that traces the genre's
history since 1978, ``Echo Park'' is a would-be ``Hair'' for the
hip-hop generation, chronicling the rise of a rough-hewn cultural
form from the neglected parks and train yards of Harlem and the
Bronx to a multibillion-dollar industry. The cast includes the rap
luminaries Kurtis Blow, Grandmaster Caz and D.J. Hollywood, but the
producers, Lifted Productions, also took a grass-roots approach,
enlisting graffiti writers to design the set, city B-boys for
break-dancing parts and untested neighborhood actors for other
roles.
</P>
<P>
   The producers, who regard this presentation of Echo Park as a
work in progress, have held ticket prices to $20 to $35 and have
not invited critics to the one-month run at the Apollo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get input from the community and improve it so it's
ready for a tour, or going overseas, or maybe going to Broadway,''
said Eric H. Vinson, the executive producer. ``The idea is to get
an affirmation from the Harlem community, because, if you've ever
watched `Amateur Night at the Apollo,' you know how hard the
audiences there can be. That's the real test for us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
