<HEADLINE>
AISLES OF CAPRIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, May 31, and thereafter.) 
ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By JENNIFER MOSES    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ I suffer from shopping anxiety, no doubt
because nothing looks good on me now that I'm past the age I never
thought it was possible to be in the first place. But it doesn't
really matter these days anyway, since most women's clothing seems
to be designed for skinny 14-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, every once in a while, when my children say
something like, ``Hey, Mom, the '60s are over,'' as they did a
couple of weeks ago, I jump in the minivan and drive to the mall
looking for something to update my wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't do well. At the Gap, the store I've relied on for years
to supply me with blue jeans in progressively bigger sizes and
white T-shirts in a seemingly inexhaustible variety, I could find
nothing but capris _ those tight, above-the-ankle pants that have
spread from coast to coast like some terrifying virus.
</P>
<P>
   Capri pants and the little cropped shirts designed to go with
them hung on every hanger, in brilliant yellow, magenta, purple
passion, lollipop lime and poppy red. I tried on a few pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look cute,'' the saleswoman said as I emerged in one after
another pair of the tiny pants and the matching little tops that
made me look like a linebacker in fancy dress or, more accurately,
a fairly thin, 5-foot-4, middle-aged mom pushing the envelope in a
big, big way. Who was she kidding?
</P>
<P>
   The things weren't even comfortable to begin with, let alone
cheap. And what was with my calves, anyway? Why did they look so _
large? My legs are thin, so thin that in high school my best friend
called me ``Stick Legs,'' and I used our own '60s fashion
must-have, Frye boots, to hide them.
</P>
<P>
   But now I feel ... what is the word? Old? Dowdy? But I'm none of
the above. Thus I pushed on: Banana Republic, Urban Outfitters, the
Limited, Old Navy, Sears. I also needed a bathing suit, but how can
a woman locate a bathing suit when the entire mall seems devoted to
capri pants?
</P>
<P>
   What is it with the fashion industry, anyway? Because, suddenly,
I saw capri pants not just in the mall, but everywhere: at the
grocery store, on the mothers of my children's friends, on my
neighbors, and on the women who gathered recently at a fancy art
opening for another friend, who was also wearing capri pants.
Perhaps, I thought, this was just one of those fashion trends that
catches on only among gullible people in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   But, no, it seems that actual urban sophisticates, professional
women with cell phones and expense accounts, are wearing them, too.
My sister, who lives on the Upper West Side in Manhattan and is a
lawyer, reports that Zabar's is full of capri-clad women, and that
at her law firm, they have become a staple of casual Friday
wardrobes. Lawyers in capris? In Manhattan? Don't they know we're
wearing them on the Bayou, too?
</P>
<P>
   Even my own 6-year-old daughter has a pair. Actually, she is the
one person I know who looks good in them. After all, they were made
for her.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Moses is the author of ``Food and Whine: Confessions
of a New Millennium Mom.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the OPED
package and other features.
</P>
