<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-APOLLO-HIP-HOP-ART-2N     05-30 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLLO-HIP-HOP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: for us.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The project was born two and a half years ago, when Kelly Scott,
a former model and actor who has appeared in small parts in
television sitcoms including ``Martin'' and ``Living Single,''
teamed up with Sean Couch, a former NBA basketball player and,
later, a financial analyst for such Wall Street firms as
PaineWebber and Shearson Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Couch and Scott were both working on an all-black
production of the Maxwell Anderson play ``The Bad Seed'' at the
Victoria Five Theater in Harlem. Neither is an accomplished
playwright, though each has done some theatrical writing _ in 1996,
after Couch left Wall Street, he wrote ``The History of the
Blues,'' for the National Black Theater; Scott, a published poet,
has written two unproduced scripts. They wrote the script and
produced ``Echo Park'' together, with Scott, a neophyte, directing.
</P>
<P>
   The two had grown up just blocks apart but had never met, and
they shared many of the same childhood experiences. Both spent time
in the late 1970s in Echo Park, in the west Bronx, where disc
jockeys would rig their sound systems to lampposts and mix funk and
R&AMP;B sounds to create a danceable beat. They witnessed the emergence
of break dancing at such ``park jams,'' where teen-agers from
opposing gangs faced off and ``battled'' each other to flaunt head
spins, back flips, robotic maneuvers and other novel moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a whole generation of kids who grew up in hip-hop
culture but don't understand its origins,'' Couch said. ``They
don't know that it's a lot more than them getting on the mike and
rapping. Hip-hop was an explosion of suppression. The thread that
runs through it all was the desire to be seen and heard, the
ability to shine. I wanted to tell that history through the people
who lived it.''
</P>
<P>
   The writers looked to their own experiences for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote the park scenes because I was in the park a lot
playing ball, and the club scenes were Kelly, because her aunt was
a big promoter and she was in the modeling scene,'' Couch said.
</P>
<P>
   But they were also influenced by the stories of those around
them. As Scott put it, ``D.J. Hollywood, Grandmaster Flash and all
those guys were my heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, they lifted moments from the life of Grandmaster
Caz, born in the Bronx as Curtis Brown, and reborn in the '70s as
M.C. and D.J. Casanova Fly. When he was 19 and a member of the Cold
Crush Four, Brown offered a book of his rhymes to his group's
manager, Henry (Big Bank Hank) Jackson, who went on to record the
seminal ``Rapper's Delight'' (``I said, hip hop, the hippie, the
hippie, to the hip hip hop'') as part of the Sugarhill Gang in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   The song is widely regarded as the hit that began rap's invasion
of the mainstream, and Casanova Fly, supported by a number of
hip-hop historians, claims authorship, although he says he has
never seen a dollar for his work. In the play, a character named
Doc achieves fame after stealing the main character's signature
raps.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's is a quintessential music business story, and because he
is also performing in the show, it hovers in the rehearsal hall
like a kind of medieval morality play. As a generic D.J. narrator
in ``Echo Park,'' Brown is boyishly gleeful in his role, especially
when he's spinning mixes at the turntables. ``I think this story is
based on everyone's story,'' he said. ``Everyone coming up in the
pioneer days of hip-hop can relate to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors also borrowed loosely from Kurtis Blow's early life.
Born Kurt Walker, he was a precocious young man who grew up in
Harlem in the '70s and much to his mother's consternation spent a
lot of his time scratching up her records. ``At 13, I knew I wanted
to be a D.J.,'' he said. ``I knew this was going to be big, huge. I
had no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   The main character, Scott Jenkins, routinely clashes with his
mother, secretly a rhythm and blues singer, who calls his form of
expression ``loud, stupid music.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, as he prefers to be called, now 40, was living in
Woodland Hills, Calif., enjoying life as a family man with his
three young sons, writing theme songs for the NBA teams, and
working as a disc jockey on the Los Angeles radio station KPWR,
``Power 106,'' when Scott, an old friend, asked him to return to
New York City for the production last year.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the city for the first time in 15 years, Blow, who is on
a leave of absence from his radio job, appreciates the admirers who
stop him as he walks from the East Harlem rehearsal studio to a
pizza place nearby. ``I go home feeling life has revisited these
old bones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wonders privately if the M.C. character, Doc, may be
portrayed as a bit too much of ``a snake,'' (arguing that M.C.'s
were often the ones who got lost in the fame game) he says he
wanted to participate in the musical because it helps set the
record straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many different versions of the history,'' he said.
``Now, everyone is fighting for their own part of the history when
in actuality, we're all part of the fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the writers were on a mission to create a comprehensive
picture of hip-hop's early years, 1978 to 1981, they brought a
variety of elements together on the stage: break dancing, graffiti
art, D.J.'s and rappers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This show is the first of its kind to incorporate all the
elements of hip-hop culture, the music, dance, art and spoken
word,'' said the show's choreographer, Adesola A. Osakalumi.
``You're not just seeing the parts, but the integration of the
parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Osakalumi, who has been break dancing since the '70s, is a
member of GhettOriginal Productions, the dance company behind ``Jam
on the Groove,'' which ran at the Minetta Lane Theater in 1995. Jon
Pareles, the chief pop critic of The New York Times, called the
show ``jubilantly hyperactive'' in a review.
</P>
<P>
   But Osakalumi said that keeping the dances period-specific was a
challenge. ``There were dance moves that were done then that are
now lost,'' he said. ``Then there are others that have evolved,
like the elbow spin _ they used to do a half-spin and now they do
four or five spins _ so the dancers have to resist the temptation
to push it forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar difficulties were faced by the Big Time Crew, a graffiti
art group from the Tremont section of the Bronx, which spraypainted
the boldly colorful wild-style graffiti set. ``It's much more
elemental than the work today,'' said Joe Rodriguez, a member of
the Crew. ``Now, we're more into background and sceneries. Before,
it was just your name, or wild-style train art.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers spent two years looking for the right mix of
artists, and, about a year ago, held auditions that attracted
actors and dancers from as far away as Germany and Japan. But they
decided to cast closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   One dancer, Josh Ortiz, 18, is a nephew of the Bronx dancers the
Incredible Breakers and learned many of his moves from his uncles.
Alien Ness, 32, born Luis Martinez in the Bronx, was an original
member of Zulu Nation, a group that assembled around the rap figure
Afrika Bambaataa, and often frequented Echo Park as a teen-ager.
``I'm practically playing myself,'' said Martinez, whose character
in the show is called Kid Ness. ``That's what they called me when I
was 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Because many in the cast had no professional acting experience,
the group spent six weeks training at the National Black Theater in
Harlem. And they spent five weeks in rehearsal at the Burgos center
in East Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Writing the script and assembling the cast, the producers said,
was easier than securing financial support. Couch and Kelly
enlisted Vinson to do the heavy hitting. Until 1993 Vinson headed a
sports and entertainment management and marketing company whose
clients included Savion Glover and Ossie Davis; he is now a
managing partner in Interactive Sports Signals, which he said
enhances the sound systems in sports arenas. As executive producer,
he had enough pull to convince executives at Colgate-Palmolive and
Pepsi to support the production through joint marketing efforts.
But Scott, Couch and Vinson also invested some of their own money
in the production, which has a $250,000 budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-LYNCHING-REVIEW-NY     05-30 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LYNCHING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TULSA LYNCHING OF 1921': IN THE AIR, HONEYSUCKLE AND GUNFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By JULIE SALAMON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confronted by a mob bent on destroying the neighborhood, a World
War I veteran put on his uniform and stood at attention in front of
his house. It was Tulsa, Okla., in 1921, and he surely prayed that
his recent military service would protect him. As a black man,
however, he may also have suspected his actual fate was to be shot
point blank by his fellow citizens, who were white.
</P>
<P>
   In one day that mob murdered more than 300 African-Americans and
burned down the Greenwood neighborhood, one of the country's most
prosperous black communities, referred to as the Negro capital of
the Southwest. Greenwood, whose population had reached 15,000, had
thrived on hope as well as hard work, making its destruction all
the more improbable.
</P>
<P>
   This riot was perhaps the most devastating in the nation's
history and destroyed any illusions that upward mobility could fend
off racism. After the riot ended, in one survivor's words ``the
heavy air was soaked with the scent of honeysuckle as extravagant
and lavishly unreal as the gunfire.'' But someone else remembered a
different scent. ``A terrible smell,'' she recalled. ``Did they
burn bodies?''
</P>
<P>
   Local officials encouraged the destruction, so when the carnage
stopped, the cover-ups began. For 50 years this ugly chapter was
buried, and then exhumed by a new generation. Survivors came
forward; old newspapers were dusted off and read. In 1997 the
Oklahoma legislature created a commission to study the Tulsa riot _
to try to explain it and then to determine whether the state should
pay reparations of some kind to Greenwood itself or to individual
survivors. Its conclusions have yet to be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the commission was formed, Michael Wilkerson, an
inspector for the Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigation turned
documentarian, was working on his own examination of this shameful
event. ``The Tulsa Lynching of 1921: A Hidden Story'' _ which
Wilkerson produced, wrote, directed and jointly edited (with
Michael Brown) _ is being shown Wednesday night at 6:30 on Cinemax.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly survivors and witnesses recollect; historians comment;
actors (including Bill Cosby, Nell Carter, Ed Asner and Alfre
Woodard) read from newspaper and personal accounts. The style is
straightforward, and that's fitting. The pyrotechnics are built
into the stories of machine guns raining down bullets on civilians
in peacetime, of women dragging children down residential streets
to escape. Vivid photographs illustrate the horror (a scorched
body) and the loss (rows of comfortable homes destroyed;
well-dressed children turned into refugees).
</P>
<P>
   This explosion of emotion and firepower was detonated by an
unproved allegation that a 19-year-old black man named Dick Rowland
had assaulted a white female elevator operator. He was arrested and
then word circulated that a lynch mob was gathering at the jail. A
group of black men arrived to protect him. Someone fired a shot,
which hit a black man, and the riot began.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours the police commissioned and armed 500 deputies, all
of them white, except for at least one light-skinned black man,
mistakenly enlisted. He reported that he and the other deputies
were told: ``Now you can go shoot any nigger you see and the law
will be behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary explains the context. Despite the prosperity
evident in Greenwood, with its black businessmen, doctors and
lawyers, Oklahoma didn't exactly welcome blacks. The railroads were
segregated, voting restricted and newspapers routinely reported
lynchings of black people. The Ku Klux Klan, which had almost
disappeared after the turn of the century, had been revitalized by
the release of D.W. Griffith's ``Birth of a Nation'' in 1915. Klan
recruitment ads ran next to newspaper advertisements for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   (This context is documented in ``Without Sanctuary: Lynching
Photography in America,'' a New-York Historical Society exhibition
that runs through Aug. 13.)
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa officials tacitly and directly supported the mob as it
looted, burned and killed, and even blocked firefighters from doing
their jobs. The rampage was spontaneous but also calculated:
telephone and telegraph wires were cut and trains blockaded to
prevent outside interference.
</P>
<P>
   The National Guard did finally arrive and martial law was
imposed, but the indignities continued. African-Americans had to
register at detention centers; insurance claims by black families
were rejected; city officials declared the Greenwood area a fire
zone and put the land up for sale. Then the cover-up: the death
toll was wildly underreported, a white grand jury placed blame for
the riot on black residents, and newspaper articles encouraging the
lynching of Dick Rowland disappeared from archives.
</P>
<P>
   This intelligent and troubling documentary raises lingering
questions of guilt, retribution and reconciliation. We look at
pictures of the ruins, and listen to the words of one Greenwood
survivor: ``After that we distrusted every white person.'' What
kind of reparations can fully heal that wound?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TULSA LYNCHING OF 1921: A HIDDEN STORY'
</P>
<P>
   Cinemax, Wednesday night at 6:30.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Michael Wilkerson; edited by Wilkerson
and Michael Brown; produced by Wilkerson; Nancy Abraham,
supervising producer; Sheila Nevins, executive producer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HAITI-POLITICS-320&AMP;AD     05-30 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-POLITICS-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARISTIDE PARTY APPARENTLY GAINS CONTROL OF HAITI'S SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In a preview of its strength in the coming presidential
election, the political party of former President Jean-Bertrand
Aristide gained firm control of the Haitian Senate, according to
preliminary results from the May 21 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The results, which were released late on Monday by the
Provisional Electoral Council, gave Aristide's Family Lavalas party
14 of the 19 senate seats that were at stake in Haiti's first
parliamentary elections since 1997. Scoring large margins of
victory, the vote gives Lavalas the majority in Haiti's 27-member
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other five seats up for election, an independent
candidate won one race, while the results for the two seats from
the capital, Port-au-Prince, have yet to be announced. The two
remaining Senate seats for Grande Anse Province will be determined
in an election June 11 after electoral officials postponed the
original date because of disorganization and technical difficulties
in the weeks before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The elections represent Haiti's first step at resolving a crisis
that has left its government paralyzed and without access to $500
million in international aid since 1997. Bitter arguments between
current President Rene Preval, of the Lavalas party, and an
opposition-led Parliament over the results of the 1997 legislative
elections prevented the naming of a prime minister for nearly two
years. Last year, Preval appointed a new prime minister, but only
after Parliament was dissolved, and the nation has been without a
lawmaking body since then.
</P>
<P>
   Lavalas' apparent sweep of this year's elections did not extend
to the lower house of parliament; there its candidates won outright
only 16 of the 83 seats in the Chamber of Deputies. A runoff will
be held on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lavalas' strong showing places it in the lead for
November's presidential election, where Aristide is seeking a
return to office.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Opposition candidates have accused Lavalas of manipulating the
recent election through a campaign of violence and intimidation
that resulted in 15 politically motivated killings since late
March. They also said Preval forced the postponement of elections
three times to wear down opposition and secure a compliant
Parliament for Aristide's return.
</P>
<P>
   A Lavalas spokesman who was also a candidate for senator
dismissed those accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no totalitarian intentions,'' Yvon Neptune told the
Associated Press. ``The Haitian people want to get out of the rut
of crisis, and we want to implement a project that will change
society. We want peace and security, so we can concentrate on the
big problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But peace has been elusive in the days since the election.
Tuesday, poll workers in the Delmas section of Port-au-Prince set
fire to the local election office when they were not paid. Last
week, Lavalas supporters ransacked the headquarters of a minor
political party and killed a person, according to diplomats and
international election observers. About 30 opposition candidates
have been arrested since last week on charges that many of the
observers said were trumped up. Most have been released.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall take is that Lavalas did do very well in the
elections,'' said a State Department official who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``But its heavy-handed tactics like with
the arrests are marring what could have been a decent victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The final vote tally, which could come later this week, has been
delayed by disorganization at electoral offices. In some cases,
ballot boxes were dumped at collection stations, damaging records
and making recounts impossible. But election observers said there
was no indication of systematic fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying there was absolutely no fraud,'' said Mary
Durran, a spokeswoman for the observer mission of the Organization
of American States'. ``It's just the nature of the fraud, it's not
organized on a national and systematic level that would have an
impact on the elections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
