<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      05-30 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BLAMES DECLINE IN MILITARY MORALE ON CLINTON-GORE
ADMINISTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday challenged Vice
President Al Gore's fitness to serve as commander in chief of the
armed forces, saying that an erosion of the military's might and
morale during the Clinton-Gore administration was reason ``for a
new sign on the Pentagon that says Under New Management.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush used an appearance here at the Veterans of Foreign Wars
Post No. 1, the group's oldest, to recite a laundry list of current
problems with the military, reiterate his commitment to making
necessary improvements and question whether voters should have much
confidence in Gore's capacity for leadership on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent _ who's no stranger to exaggeration, I might add _
boasts on his Web site that he has been intimately involved in the
best-managed build-down in American military history,'' said Bush,
an unmistakable sprinkling of sarcasm in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want the people of Colorado and America to consider the
results of seven years of the vice president's management
involvement,'' Bush said. ``Entire Army divisions are not prepared
for war. Military recruiting fell thousands short of its goal. And
6,000 United States soldiers are on food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore claims that qualifies him for a promotion,'' Bush
continued. But, he said, ``The Clinton-Gore record cries out for a
new sign on the Pentagon that says Under New Management.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's pointed remarks represented an aggressive attempt by the
Texas governor to turn the tables on Gore and blunt the questions
that Gore and other administration officials have raised about how
well the Texas governor is prepared to manage the country's
military and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts have long considered Bush's inexperience on
the global stage, along with a series of gaffes that underscored
it, to be a significant potential weak spot in his candidacy. Over
the last week, both Gore and Defense Secretary William S. Cohen
have expressed particular concern over Bush's proposal for the
research and development of a missile defense system more vast than
the one being considered by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, a Republican, warned that it could lead to an arms
buildup by other countries, and, during an appearance on a Sunday
television news program, he even invited Bush in for a briefing by
State Department officials. Bush, making his first public comments
on the matter Tuesday, implied that he would not be R.S.V.P.-ing
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found the comments to be political in nature,'' Bush said at
a news conference here after his speech at the veterans post. Bush
said that he had been amply informed and advised by his own team of
foreign policy and defense experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the briefing I got from Colin Powell and Dick Cheney
and Henry Kissinger was substantial,'' Bush said. ``I've got one of
the finest foreign policy teams ever assembled, and I call upon my
opponent not to allow members of the administration to politicize
matters of defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, for its part, said Tuesday that the vice
president had made his own set of proposals for strengthening the
military and increasing spending on defense, particularly for
higher pay for enlisted men and women. Douglas Hattaway, a
spokesman for Gore, also said that low military pay was not a new
phenomenon and that there were about 19,400 service people on food
stamps in 1991, when Bush's father was president.
</P>
<P>
   And Hattaway questioned whether Bush was the right person to be
raising questions about military preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush can talk about military readiness all he
wants,'' Hattaway said. ``Experts say his irresponsible position on
missile defense could lead to a new arms race. With all the complex
national defense issues we face, the next commander in chief should
not be going through on-the-job training.''
</P>
<P>
   During a telephone conference call with reporters that was
arranged by the Democratic National Committee, Jesse Brown, former
secretary of U.S. Veterans Affairs, made those criticisms even more
personal, questioning the nature of Bush's military service during
the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not go overseas but served instead in Houston in the
Texas Air National Guard. Gore went to Vietnam as an Army
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's complaint with the health of the country's armed forces
was not new, but he rendered it in especially strong terms Tuesday.
Bush has said he would call for an extra $1 billion a year over
what Congress has already agreed to pay in salary increases for men
and women serving in the military. That is one of several ways in
which Bush would spend more on national defense, which he says is
currently being shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense spending as a percentage of the gross national product
is the lowest it has been since prior to Pearl Harbor,'' Bush said
Tuesday as he presented a litany of facts and figures to portray
what he views as a military in alarming decline. ``United States
Air Force readiness for combat has fallen to its lowest level in 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we've asked our service men and women to do
too much with too little,'' he said, adding that their morale had
suffered sharply as a result.
</P>
<P>
   He said the blame rested with the Clinton administration, which
had overextended troops and deployed them in a sometimes haphazard,
poorly planned and unnecessarily prolonged fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we commit troops, there has to be a clear strategy,''
Bush said, citing Bosnia and Haiti as two examples of places where
that was arguably not the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
