<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, managing editors, wire editors:
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sunday, and continuing for six weeks, The New York
Times will publish a series of articles on race in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Race Is Lived in America'' represents a yearlong effort by
reporters and editors of The New York Times to capture some of the
troubling issues that Americans continue to face and the voices of
ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   These stories, two or three each week, are long, at 6,000 words
and up. They will move on The News Service wire the day before
publication and will carry a slug of the form BC-RACE-SLUG-NYT.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief description of the first three articles.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, June 4:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-CHURCH _ What happens when backs and whites try to end the
most segregated hour in America, the Sunday church service.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, June 5:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-IMMIGRANTS _ They were best friends in Cuba. Now, living
new lives in Miami, their racial difference suddenly matters.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, June 7:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MILITARY _ The military can enforce a code of behavior, but
can it ever change attitudes about race?
</P>
<P>
   We will update this advisory later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Following publication of the series, there will be a special
issue of The New York Times Sunday Magazine on July 16 devoted to
the subject of race. Articles from the magazine will NOT be a part
of the News Service, but will be available as a separate buy from
the New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
