<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEACHER-SERVICE-COX     05-30 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-SERVICE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher remembered as a man of grace
 &HT;    By Stephanie Desmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla _ As a child, Barry Grunow would collect
bugs from neighbors' yards and keep them in a jar. He didn't want
to steal them, though, so he left pennies and nickels in their
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just how Barry was,'' his brother, Kurt, recalled
Tuesday in a speech he was too emotional to give himself.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to kill spiders and palmettos inside his house,
carefully luring them back into the wild, Rev. Bill Corristan said,
reading Kurt's words.
</P>
<P>
   When he got a dog from the pound, young Barry Grunow picked
Wilma because ``she was the ugliest dog there and if he didn't take
her, nobody else would,'' his oldest brother Steve said.
</P>
<P>
   So went the glimpses into the too-short life of 35-year-old
English teacher Barry Grunow, remembered Tuesday at Good Shepherd
United Methodist Church before 1,600 teachers, friends, students,
family, maybe a stranger or two.
</P>
<P>
   In a crime that has touched a nerve in Palm Beach County and
nationwide, Grunow was shot and killed Friday in the hallway
outside his classroom at Lake Worth Middle School, during the last
class of the last day of school. The boy who police say shot him,
seventh-grader Nathaniel Brazill, could face charges of
first-degree murder and a lifetime in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Many in attendance Tuesday were other seventh-graders, clad in
black, crying and hugging one another, passing crinkled tissues. Up
front were those he left behind, his wife Pam, his 5-year-old son
Sam, his baby daughter Lee-Anne, his mother, his siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry was reaching out with grace, even to the end,''
Corristan said. ``Even to the young man with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   At the front of the church, alongside the roses and carnations,
stood a giant photograph of the way most people remember Mr. Grunow
and collages of happy family snapshots: Grunow swimming. Grunow
playing ball, Grunow holding his newborn baby, Grunow at a
graduation. Grunow smiling. Before the concluding hymn Amazing
Grace, the music of the 70-minute service was dominated by Grunow's
favorite, the songs of Jethro Tull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well the dawn was coming, heard him reading my bell,'' went
the strains of Teacher. ``He said, 'My name's the teacher, that is
what I call myself and I have a lesson that I must impart to you.
It's an old expression but I insist it's true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jump up, look around, find yourself some fun, no sense in
sitting there hating everyone. No man't an island and his castle
isn't home, the nest is for nothing when the bird has flown.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Krolick, a friend of Grunow's for 19 years, dating back to
when they worked together at a North Palm Beach record store,
remembered his love of sports. Grunow was a top basketball player
at Jupiter High School, played pickup games and helped coach the
sport at Lake Worth Middle.
</P>
<P>
   Krolick, a native New Yorker, is a lifelong Knicks and Yankees
fan. Grunow, originally from Michigan, followed the Detroit Pistons
and Detroit Tigers just as fanatically. The two watched these
rivalries play out over the years, Krolick recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do this for just anybody,'' Krolick said, taking off
his suit jacket and replacing it with a Piston's basketball jersey,
adding levity to the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry,'' he shouted, looking skyward, ``what do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grunow recalled talking to his nephew Sam after a
hurricane last summer. Sam told his uncle how his father took him
out to the ocean to see the big waves. Was he scared? Uncle Steve
asked. ``Sam said: No, I wasn't scared because my Daddy was holding
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Corristan implored those in tears to celebrate the Grunow's life
and not focus on his unexplainable death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the answer to how something like this could
happen, to why,'' he said. ``It's supposed to happen somewhere else
if it's to happen at all. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We can look to Tallahassee. We can look to Washington. We can
look to leaders all over the place to try to change things. We can
put laws on the books but until people change ... we'll never know
the peace that we want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush called Pam Grunow on Monday, telling her to ``take
her time about healing and grieving.'' He did not attend Tuesday's
service but Republican Congressman Mark Foley, an alum of Lake
Worth Junior High, interim schools Superintendent Ben Marlin, Lake
Worth Middle Principal Sharon Walker and several school board
members did.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they learned, Barry Grunow was a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always said he was going to make a difference in his
class's lives,'' Krolick said. ``You could tell teaching was
Barry's niche in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Writers Ron Hayes and Marcia Gelbart contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   stephaniedesmon(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
