<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC FIELD'S NEW `MILLIONAIRE' TO COUNTER CBS'S `SURVIVOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ABC is making one thing clear Wednesday night: It may
be in the business of making millionaires, but not at CBS.
</P>
<P>
   As CBS kicks off its island survival test, ``Survivor,'' at 8
p.m. Wednesday _ a show that CBS clearly hopes will become this
summer's phenomenon, as ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' was for
ABC last summer _ ABC has decided to make that goal as elusive as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, past the date by which it could even be
included in program listings, ABC threw in yet another edition of
``Millionaire'' to go head to head with the opening of the 13-week
run of ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   The news got out last week, about the time TV Guide was arriving
with ``Survivor'' on its cover.
</P>
<P>
   The next sound heard was a howl of anger at CBS headquarters.
Several executives there, who asked to remain unnamed, accused
their ABC counterparts of playing dirty pool scheduling-wise to
undercut CBS's hopes without having anything to gain for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One CBS executive who did speak for the record was Leslie
Moonves, the president of CBS Television, who acknowledged that he
was far from happy with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's bad for the network television business,''
Moonves said. ``You would think that ABC could accept their
victories and not have to go out and try to stop someone else from
having a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   This position left Stu Bloomberg and Lloyd Braun, the two
co-chairmen of ABC Entertainment, a but nonplussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not do it?'' Bloomberg asked. ``It's a competition. We
obviously don't want them to get on the air and get traction with
their show. I have absolutely no regrets about doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is ABC's position, even though putting another edition of
``Millionaire'' on this week, after the official television season
has ended, does not provide any ratings benefits for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   And the decision does fly a bit in the face of the sentiment
expressed by some ABC executives that ``Millionaire'' is a precious
program resource that should not be overused. Even Bloomberg
conceded, ``I'd like to rest the show a bit if I can.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chance to stop ``Survivor'' before it can get going
apparently was too strong a lure to be passed up.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves noted that the decision seemed last-minute, as if ABC
suddenly got worried about the attention ``Survivor'' was
receiving. ``It clearly came after the TV Guide cover and all the
other press we've been getting,'' Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   But Braun said, ``This is not something we thought about
yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the ``Millionaire'' production staff said the extra,
anti-``Survivor'' edition of ``Millionaire'' had been in the works
for weeks. Which led to the speculation that ABC fully intended a
kind of stealth effort against ``Survivor'' at a time when CBS
could not alter its starting date.
</P>
<P>
   Braun said, ``We're totally trying to be smart in how we use
`Millionaire.' I don't believe by scheduling our programs against
theirs we're in any way compromising the television business. Our
job is to get people to watch our network, not the other
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   The test of interest in ``Survivor'' may be skewed Wednesday,
but CBS executives said they always felt its real test would unfold
with the full length of its run, measured by how much word of mouth
the series can build up.
</P>
<P>
   Each week one of the contestants gets voted off the island by
the others, in a game of attrition leading to a climax in which the
last survivor takes home $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's hopes for a similar series, ``Big Brother,'' which will
play out over 90 straight nights later this summer, may hinge on
how well ``Survivor'' builds that audience.
</P>
<P>
   But ABC may try to play a hand there as well. ``We've haven't
decided yet what we'll be doing with `Millionaire' the following
week,'' Braun said.
</P>
<P>
   RICHTER'S LATE FAREWELL
</P>
<P>
   With a week of shows celebrating his status as sidekick, Andy
Richter got a great send-off from ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien''
in every way, except from the NBC schedulers. Richter's final
night, Friday, coincided with coverage of one of NBC's NBA playoff
games.
</P>
<P>
   The game ran so late that it delayed the start of ``The Tonight
Show'' almost until the usual 12:35 start of O'Brien's show. That
meant ``Late Night'' couldn't start until almost 1:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   So the ratings for Richter's finale _ he quit the show to pursue
an acting career _ were nothing to post in his book of memories.
That show averaged only a 2.7 in the biggest cities, not even as
high as the previous Friday when the show scored a 2.8. Each rating
point represents just over a million homes.
</P>
<P>
   BROKAW Quizzes PUTIN
</P>
<P>
   Tom Brokaw will interview the new Russian president, Vladimir
Putin, on ``The NBC Nightly News'' Thursday, the first in-depth
interview Putin has granted to American television since he took
office on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw said Tuesday that he and his staff had been working on
scheduling an interview with Putin for several months, but the
Russian leader had proved elusive. With the summit meeting with
President Clinton scheduled this weekend, the timing apparently was
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are four big areas we'll concentrate on,''
Brokaw said. ``First, who is this guy? Then of course, the
relationship with the United States and the question of the nuclear
arsenals, crime and corruption, and how on earth do you revive that
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview is likely to occur about midday in Moscow, and
Brokaw said he expected to use a sizable portion of it during
Thursday night's broadcast. More of the interview will be seen on
the ``Today'' program on Friday morning and on ``Meet The Press''
on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the chance to really sit down with
him,'' Brokaw said, noting that he was the first American
television journalist to interview Mikhail S. Gorbachev after he
assumed leadership in the former Soviet Union. ``I think for the
most part Putin is still an enigma.''
</P>
<P>
   On another NBC outlet, MSNBC, George W. Bush will sit down for
an interview with Chris Matthews on his ``Hardball'' program
Thursday night at 7 p.m. This interview will be conducted live,
from a restaurant named El Pinto in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews said he planned to emphasize education, Social
Security, missile defense, possible running mates and Bush's
campaign strategy against Al Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
