<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, May 31 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-TALC (Seattle) _ The talc used by Crayola and most of
America's other crayon makers comes from a century-old mine long
embroiled in battles over whether its product contains
cancer-causing asbestos. The mine in upstate New York, owned by
R.T. Vanderbilt Co., has been the center of a 30-year-long fight
pitting the asbestos and talc industries against physicians and
public health experts over just what, precisely, constitutes
asbestos. 2,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider and Carol Smith. (Story has moved in the
``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-WITNESS (Seattle) _ The ``independent'' scientist who
tested crayons for Binney &AMP; Smith, makers of Crayola, after the
Post-Intelligencer reported asbestos in crayons last week has
testified more than 250 times for asbestos companies and has been
paid about $7 million by them, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider and Carol Smith. (Story has moved in the
``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-WEST (Los Angeles) _ Game 5 of NBA's Western Conference
finals: Portland at Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKW-SEATTLE-STORM (Seattle) _ The Seattle Storm makes its WNBA
debut Wednesday against the Sacramento Monarchs in Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   By Meredith Bagley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKW-VECSEY-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Column on the Seattle Storm.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Mariners vs. Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Caple. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOW-AGAIN (Undated) _ Again, a network bull has become a
steer when faced with the prospect of rendering aid and comfort to
a quality show that's struggling in the ratings. Two weeks ago, CBS
chose the wimpy route and decided not to give ``Now and Again'' a
second season.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
