<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0020 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-NOW-AGAIN-SPI &LR;      05-30 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOW-AGAIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S FICKLE NATURE KILLED `NOW AND AGAIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last July, in that heady time when every producer thinks his new
show will be the next ``ER,'' Glenn Gordon Caron was talking about
the coincidence of his show being launched on CBS at the same time
ABC was introducing a new drama with a similar title.
</P>
<P>
   Caron's show was ``Now and Again.'' The one on ABC was ``Once
and Again.'' Even critics who keep track of this sort of thing for
a living were confused, often mentioning one title when they meant
the other.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Caron learned of the similar names, he figured he
should mention it to Leslie Moonves, president of CBS Television.
But Moonves didn't seem concerned. ``He said, `Oh, let them worry
about us,' '' Caron recalled, ``and I thought, whenever you can get
bullishness from a network head about your show, you don't want
anything to diminish that. I took Les' confidence in the show as a
great sign, and we're just sort of charging ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   That was then.
</P>
<P>
   This is now. And, again, a network bull has become a steer when
faced with the prospect of rendering aid and comfort to a quality
show that's struggling in the ratings. Two weeks ago, CBS chose the
wimpy route and decided not to give ``Now and Again'' a second
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt it was our toughest call to make,'' CBS spokesman
Chris Ender said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then why make it?
</P>
<P>
   Ender's response is that CBS has ``a very deep roster'' of
dramas in development for next season and beyond. Isn't that like
saying your new car works fine, but the dealer has a bunch more
he's aching to sell so you're unloading the new car and buying an
even newer one to help the dealer out?
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is further validation of my theory that the TV
industry is more interested in keeping the assembly line going than
in fostering the growth of good shows. After all, it's just as
likely that whatever replaces ``Now and Again'' also will finish
the season at No. 76 in the Nielsen ratings, so why not keep ``Now
and Again'' on the air and let the audience warm to it? Besides,
``Now and Again'' finished just ahead of ``City of Angels,'' which
CBS renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the show are hoping they can pester CBS sufficiently to
get the network to change its mind. They took out an ad in
Tuesday's Hollywood Reporter that read: ``Cost of building a
superhero: $3,000,000,000. Cost of losing a superhero:
Incalculable. Value of saving a quality TV show: Priceless. Bring
back `Now and Again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The ad also contains a blurb from a piece by Bruce Fretts of
Entertainment Weekly magazine, who wrote: ``When `Now and Again' is
at its best ... it's as good as anything on TV, including ``The
Sopranos.' ''
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't go that far, but ``Now and Again,'' which tried to be
a drama, a romance, a comedy and an action/adventure sci-fi show at
the same time, was an Altoid in a prime-time lineup that was mostly
a megadose of halitosis.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, ``Now and Again'' was, in Caron's own
words, ``the story of a middle-aged man (Michael Wiseman) who dies
a violent death, only to disover that the government has saved his
brain in order to put it in a younger, stronger body. That body is
the scientific prototype of a special agent invented to take on the
kind of battles most men don't want any part of. Michael is
forbidden from ever making contact with anyone he knew before, for
to do so would put his friends and family at risk of death.''
</P>
<P>
   The most frustrating thing about ``Now and Again'' was its
all-things-to-all-viewers approach. But Lisa Polly of Baton Rouge,
La., who helps maintain a mailing list of the show's fans and is a
leader of the campaign to save it, thinks that was its beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never knew if it would be about the superhero or about this
man and his family,'' she said Tuesday. ``It just was always
something new and fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   In my precinct, the treatment of ``Now and Again'' has caused
more buzz than any other cancellation, probably because of CBS'
early show of support. Moonves had brought Caron, the creator of
``Moonlighting,'' back to network television with a carte-blanche
invitation to do whatever he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Caron took the bait, and he succeeded in creating a vibrant,
unusual, kicky show. Some weeks it really clicked. Some weeks it
missed the target. But it always made Fridays at 9 a time slot
worth reserving.
</P>
<P>
   Next time Les Moonves offers his support, Caron might want to
frisk him first.
</P>
<P>
   The save ``Now and Again'' Web site:
http://nacampaign.tripod.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
