<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TONYS-POLITICS-610&AMP;AD     05-30 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONYS-POLITICS-610&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL TWISTS THIS YEAR IN THE COMPETITION CALLED TONY MADNESS
</HEADLINE>
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It doesn't rise to the level of ``Shakespeare in
Love'' versus ``Saving Private Ryan,'' but the competition before
the Tony Awards on Sunday night nevertheless amounts to what
producers call Tony madness, a frenzy of promoting, politicking and
nitpicking by Broadway producers aimed at winning votes from the
705 voting theater people that can mean the difference between
millions in losses, even closing, and a show with legs.
</P>
<P>
   The splashy, celebratory publicity events in this period _ the
nominees' brunch at Sardi's, the photo op on the stairs of Radio
City Music Hall, where the awards will take place _ mask the
bottom-line desperation of producers to see their shows win best
play or best musical, the only two awards that they say affect the
box office.
</P>
<P>
   Because a Tony in those categories can lure tourists in New York
and ensure solid runs on the road, producers pull out all the stops
they can for their shows: spending as much as $250,000 to advertise
a show with a good chance of winning best musical, trying to book
television appearances and in some cases picking up the telephone
to cajole Tony voters they know.
</P>
<P>
   While the awards in other categories amount to little
financially, producers say, they promote those nominees anyway, in
part to get whatever attention they can from Tony voters but mostly
because they have no choice. There is an unspoken expectation that
producers will put promotional money behind the people in their
productions who have been nominated. The importance of that factor
was made starkly clear when Patrick Stewart announced from the
stage of ``The Ride Down Mount Morgan'' this month that the Shubert
Organization was inadequately promoting the show. (The producers
answered by filing charges with the Actors' Equity Association,
which ruled that Stewart had to write an apology.)
</P>
<P>
   Some suggested that the timing of Stewart's curtain speech just
before the nominations amounted to a personal Tony campaign.
Although awards for best actor or best actress may not sell
tickets, they have been known to enhance careers.
</P>
<P>
   For a few shows this season the awards are a matter of life and
death. ``The Wild Party,'' the new musical by George C. Wolfe and
Michael John LaChiusa, was gasping for breath when it was nominated
for best musical. It was selling only 50 percent of its tickets,
and there was some question whether the producers would keep it
running even after a nomination. They did.
</P>
<P>
   For Wolfe, the artistic director of the Joseph Papp Public
Theater, which is the lead producer of the show, an award would
also be a vindication (given the show's mixed reviews, including a
negative one in The New York Times) and a validation of his
decision to gamble big on Broadway again as he did last season with
the unsuccessful revival of ``On the Town.'' If ``Wild Party''
doesn't win, however, there is some question about whether it will
have built enough word of mouth to keep running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Party'' is considered the main competition for best
musical facing ``Contact,'' Susan Stroman's acclaimed dance show _
given that ``James Joyce's `The Dead' '' has closed and ``Swing!''
is generally considered a weak contender because of its lukewarm
reviews. Though favored to win, ``Contact'' would be a shoo-in if
it weren't for some fierce opposition to the show's being
considered a musical because it has no singing, original music or
live orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians' union, Local 802, has objected to the decision to
make the show eligible for the best musical award. Jack Goldstein,
the executive director of the Theater Development Fund, which runs
TKTS and theater support programs, resigned from the Tony
nominating committee to protest its inclusion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But ``Contact'' is not alone this season in challenging
traditional notions of what constitutes a book musical. ``The
Dead,'' which features Irish parlor songs, and ``Swing!,'' a dance
revue, also defy the conventional definition. And these shows
follow seasons of shows like ``Fosse,'' a dance revue that won best
musical last year, and ``Smokey Joe's Cafe,'' a revue that had a
long run largely because one of its numbers was performed on the
Tony Awards show, which can offer invaluable national exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gersten, executive producer of Lincoln Center Theater,
which produced ``Contact,'' said he was outraged by the objections.
``They are the forces of darkness, those who have argued that it is
not a musical,'' he said. ``The music is no less original to what
it was originally made for than the music in `Swing!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody objects to `Fosse' because it doesn't have new music,''
Gersten continued. ``Suddenly we don't have a musical score.''
</P>
<P>
   This year members of the nominating committee _ a 24-member
group that can include performers, composers, educators and others
involved in the theater _ seem particularly dismayed that the Tony
Administration Committee ruled on questions of eligibility and that
the nominators' views were not taken into account. The
administration committee is made up of members of the League of
American Theaters and Producers and of the American Theater Wing,
which jointly present the awards.
</P>
<P>
   In his resignation letter, Goldstein of the Theater Development
Fund cited a letter he wrote last fall in which he suggested that
the administration committee brief the nominators after eligibility
petitions had been submitted but before making its decision public.
Another suggestion was to establish a Tony for Innovation ``to
recognize evolving theatrical forms, new technical advancements or
any creative approach to theater.'' Neither suggestion was adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the playwright A.R. Gurney, who resigned from the
nominating committee this year because he was not allowed to
abstain from votes in which he felt ill equipped to take part, said
he felt frustrated by the fruitlessness of the nominators' attempts
to make their concerns heard. ``We were told to write letters, and
the problems would be addressed,'' Gurney said. ``That was in
September. Then they said we'll talk about it in January. Then they
said after we voted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this rolling of the eyes when we meet because there
doesn't seem to be any opportunity to discuss things.''
</P>
<P>
   The nominators were invited to such a discussion on May 18 with
members of the administration committee. It was partly in response
to that meeting that the committee voted on May 23 to establish a
new category next season for special theatrical events.
</P>
<P>
   ``There actually seems to be a rough justice to all of this,''
said Edgar Dobie, managing producer of the Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   While producers say they don't pressure Tony voters, they
certainly call their friends. ``You get those who are calling
everybody, trying to collect favors for a quid pro quo,'' said one
producer who refused to be identified. ``It's a secret ballot, so
you never know whether they kept their word or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The producer Rocco Landesman, said he might, for example, call
the producer Michael David if they don't both have shows competing
in the same category. ``I might well say to him, `Moon for the
Misbegotten' is in the best play category, don't forget,''
Landesman said. ``Producers tend to call their friends, and friends
are reassuring. And generally, people do vote with their friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the more tentative nudging that producers do,
sending special trinkets in the mail along with keep-us-in-mind
notes. On the theory that people remember best what they saw last,
the producers of ``Kiss Me, Kate'' are nervous that their show,
which opened in the fall, is at a disadvantage against ``The Music
Man,'' which opened in April. As a result, Tony voters have
received the cast CD and a souvenir program and have been invited
to return to ``Kate'' as a guest of the producers ``to get a fresh
look,'' said Roger Berlind, who produced it with Roger Horchow.
</P>
<P>
   A frustration for many producers in Tony season is that many
voters give their free tickets to friends or don't use their
tickets at all, but vote anyway. This has long been a problem. In
1996 The New York Times informally surveyed 17 voters, including
producers and other theater people, and found that 13 acknowledged
having missed one or both of two best-musical nominees that had
already closed, ``Chronicle of a Death Foretold'' and ``Swinging on
a Star.''
</P>
<P>
   While the tickets are supposed to be nontransferable, producers
say they are reluctant to enforce this rule by demanding
identification from those who pick up the tickets for fear of
creating ill will and losing votes.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``True West'' are upset that the two leads who
share roles are competing against each other because the Tony
committee denied the producers' request to have them considered
jointly. But ``True West'' seems unlikely to be hurt if neither
star wins because of the prominence of its two stars, Philip
Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly, who are known for their film
work. And the producers are promoting both actors equally.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell, a staunch supporter of theater, has featured
them on her show along with the actress Blair Brown of
``Copenhagen,'' who is also well known for her television series
``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, however, producers of straight plays say they are
paralyzed on the publicity front during the pre-Tony period and
have to let the work speak for itself. ``We don't have a souvenir
program, we have a play,'' said Berlind of ``Copenhagen,'' which he
also helped produce (along with ``The Wild Party'' and ``The Ride
Down Mount Morgan''). ``We hope they come. There's not much we can
do beyond that that is not obviously self-serving and inappropriate
to the seriousness of the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the shows that are no longer running say they have
little choice but to sit tight, that pouring money into promotion
would be money lost. ``No, we are not launching a PR offensive,''
said Gregory Mosher, a producer of ``The Dead.'' ``What are we
going to do, take everybody out on a boat?''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that ``The Dead'' is actually dead; it will open at the
Ahmanson Theater in Los Angeles in July and then tour the country.
But it would be foolish, Mosher said, to expect much out of the
nomination period because the show has already left Broadway.
``It's like an indie film competing against `Mission: Impossible
2.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, shows that were shut out of the nominations _ like
``Saturday Night Fever'' _ or that only drew a few nominations,
like ``The Green Bird,'' have to work doubly hard to stay alive,
particularly without a musical number on the broadcast, which has
been known to be decisive. Already there have been casualties:
``Waiting in the Wings'' closed on Sunday and ``Taller Than a
Dwarf'' is closing on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   Shows that were scheduled as limited runs to begin with _ like
``A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' ``Uncle Vanya'' and ``The Real
Thing'' _ are expected simply to play out to the end, though Tony
Awards can sometimes mean extensions.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, after all the jockeying and marketing, producers say
there is only one thing left to do. Anita Waxman, who helped
produce four nominated shows this season _ ``A Moon for the
Misbegotten,'' ``The Real Thing,'' ``The Wild Party'' and ``The
Music Man'' _ summed it up: ``Pray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
