<HEADLINE>
REGIS SPAWNS `SURVIVOR` 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - What hath Regis wrought?
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the resurgence of dark suits and a stupid catch
phrase, he's spawned ``Survivor,` the CBS `dramality` series (I'll
explain) that debuts May 31.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, marooning 16 people on a desert island off
Borneo for 39 days and televising their struggles doesn't sound
like it has much in common with ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.'' But the top prize is the same: a million bucks. Both
are competitive.
</P>
<P>
   And neither adheres to the traditional TV structure of comedy or
drama. Networks will try almost anything to cash in on
Millionaire's success (thus the Fox debacle ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?''), and reality shows are CBS' current attempt.
(Look for ``Big Brother'' later this summer.)
</P>
<P>
   `If they get sick and need to get off (the island), they can get
off,` Mark Burnett, `Survivor's` executive producer, said in a
conference call. `So clearly we're not doing ``Lord of the Flies''
here. It's not true, pure reality. On the other hand, it's not
scripted drama. It's somewhere in between.`
</P>
<P>
   Thus `dramality,` the term Burnett came up with to describe the
show.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six episodes, the `survivors` divide into two
groups and build competing communities on the island. Every three
days, there is a `reward challenge,` in which they compete for
luxuries like a hot shower or a call home, and an `immunity
challenge` - the winning team doesn't have to vote one of its
members off the island (the losing team does).
</P>
<P>
   After that, the remaining people form a single team, only now
the challenges reward individuals, until one person is left (and
rich).
</P>
<P>
   The competition is actually over already; CBS is keeping mum
about who won. While Burnett promised lots of intriguing TV (the
survivors cook and eat rats), if you're hoping to see heartless
back-stabbing - you know, literally - you're out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   `I was very worried about it turning into a Jerry Springer-type
thing by choosing people before they even got to the island I knew
would be at each other's throats,` Burnett said.
</P>
<P>
   `I knew I was going to get the conflicts and friendships needed
to make a dramatic show without slanting it that way, which could
have become a complete free-for-all and nothing that anybody wants
to watch.`
</P>
<P>
   Ha. Good thing for him he doesn't work at Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz(at)Arizona!Re public.com
or (602) 444-8974.
</P>
</TEXT>
