   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   GEOGRAPHY-GENDERGAP (Undated) _ No girls were finalists in the
National Geographic geography contest last week, leading to
conflicting opinions among researchers about a gender gap in the
study of geography. By Kate Zernike. (Scheduled to move by 8:30
p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to MARKET (New York) _ The Nasdaq composite index surges
to its biggest percentage gain and the second-largest point gain in
its 29-year history as investors snap up technology heavyweights
like Intel, Cisco Systems and Oracle. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-POLITICS (Miami) _ The party of former President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide gained firm control of the Haitian Senate in
the May 21 election, preliminary results show. The results,
released late Monday by the Provisional Electoral Council, give
Aristide's Family Lavalas party 14 of the 19 Senate seats at stake
in Haiti's first parliamentary elections since 1997. By David
Gonzalez. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court expands its continuing
review of the Clean Air Act by agreeing to decide whether the
statute requires the government to look beyond the public health
benefits of reducing air pollution and consider the economic costs
as well. The court's action raised the stakes even higher in a
case, to be argued next fall, that already promises to be one of
the most important environmental and administrative law cases in
years. By Linda Greenhouse. (The story has moved in ``w'' news
file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S.-SPY (Miami) _ A veteran immigration official is
convicted of espionage in a case that caused the expulsion of a
Cuban diplomat and heightened political tensions between the United
States and Cuba. A jury in U.S. District Court in Miami found the
official, Mariano Faget, guilty of violating the Espionage Act. By
Rick Bragg. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
700 words.
</P>
<P>
   ORE-ADOPT (Seattle) _ More than 18 months after Oregon's passage
of the first voter-approved law in the nation allowing all adult
adoptees access to their birth records, the U.S. Supreme Court ends
an emotional legal-appeals process and clears the way for the law
to take effect. By Sam Howe Verhovek. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.) 700 words.
</P>
