u f BC-CHINA-INSURANCE-NYT     05-30 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TRADE LINKS STRONGER, U.S. INSURERS SCOUT FOR BUSINESS IN
CHINA
</HEADLINE>
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Sy Sternberg, the chairman of New York Life
Insurance, was in China this week trying to figure out whom to meet
in order to ensure that his company is next among the dozens of
insurers who have applied for a license to do business in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the process is in awarding licenses,'' said
Sternberg, though his company has devoted more resources than
almost any other American insurer to securing the right to operate
here. He has tried to touch all the bases _ from officials of the
China Insurance Regulatory Commission to Prime Minister Zhu Rongji.
Still, he cannot be sure he has met the person who makes the final
decision.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes in China's murky business world, where market access
depends on whom you know and how happy you have made them _ though
no one will tell you who those people are. Instead, chief
executives like Sternberg operate on supposition and hearsay to
identify the hidden decision makers and cultivate what they call
``top of mind,'' which means making their company the first that
Chinese leaders think of when considering foreign supplicants from
their industry.
</P>
<P>
   China's entry into the World Trade Organization is supposed to
change all that, and with the House willing to grant China
permanent normal trade relations, American companies are expected
to share in any WTO bounty. The Senate, too, is expected to approve
normal trading status for China. Were Congress not to grant Beijing
such status, it could enter the WTO anyway and exclude the United
States from many trade benefits that WTO membership conveys.
</P>
<P>
   As part of China' WTO membership, the country has promised to
publish all rules and regulations governing trade and to create
clear procedures for acquiring licenses to do things like sell
insurance in the country. If Beijing holds to its promise, China
will undergo a sea change in how business is conducted here and
take a step toward government by rule of law instead of
administrative fiat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to happen overnight, but 10 years from now
we'll look back and say it was a turning point,'' said Patrick
Cranley, who is the head of Cigna's efforts to win a license in
China and chairman of Shanghai's American Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, China's transition to Western-style transparency is
likely to be piecemeal and slow. But the insurance industry is one
of the areas that promises a reasonable pace of change, for one
thing because there is little concern that foreign companies can
dominate a market in which comfort and familiarity play such a key
role. The state-owned People's Insurance Co. of China currently has
70 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic companies stand to benefit almost as much as foreign
concerns from the promised candor. Already, Western companies have
helped crack open markets that orthodox state-owned companies never
considered or dared not try to enter for fear of angering officials
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, no Chinese insurer sold life insurance to
individuals before the American International Group won a license
to do so in Shanghai seven years ago. The slim commission paid to
Chinese insurance agents did not warrant the effort. Then AIG began
paying its agents as much as 40 percent of the first year's
premium, and the individual life insurance business took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one imagined that Beijing would allow that, so no one ever
tried,'' said Albert Lu, a former agent for the China Pacific
Insurance Co. and now ING Insurance's chief representative in
China. All major Chinese life insurers offer individual policies
today.
</P>
<P>
   China needs a developed insurance industry now more than ever as
the country tries to shift the burden of cradle-to-grave benefits
away from its over-encumbered state enterprises, half of them
breaking even or losing money. Instead of providing free medical
care, many state-owned companies are buying health insurance for
their employees. A move from state-subsidized housing in favor of
individually owned homes has increased the need for property and
casualty insurance. And many people now buy life insurance with an
annuity attached that serves as a pension.
</P>
<P>
   Growth in the market has slowed from what it was a few years
ago, but remains higher than in Western economies. Life insurance
premiums, which grew 40 percent annually early in the 1990s, are
still growing at more than 10 percent a year. And life insurance
premiums account for only about 1 percent of China's total economic
output _ one of the lowest rates in the world, and behind nations
like Bulgaria and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Once China enters the WTO, the country has promised to lift
restrictions on the number of foreign companies it will allow to
operate. And foreigners will be allowed to sell insurance in at
least three cities immediately upon China's joining the global
trade group. After three years, all national restrictions will
disappear and foreign insurers will be allowed to sell group
insurance, the market's largest segment, from which foreign
companies are still barred.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, no one knows what the licensing process will be
and so companies like New York Life and Cigna are continuing their
relationship-building strategy. New York Life, for example, has
established a $250 million infrastructure investment fund that it
will use to support Beijing's current drive to build up the
country's long-neglected Western regions. To help invest the money,
the insurance company has hired the China Development Bank, run by
Chen Yuan, former deputy governor of the Chinese central bank,
which was the country's insurance regulator until late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sternberg of New York Life has spent much of his own time
lobbying for the license or otherwise trying to demonstrate his
support for China, meeting with more than 100 members of Congress
to push for normal trading relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our growth strategy is to expand into high-growth emerging
markets, and China is an important part of that strategy,''
Sternberg said, ``so it's important that I dedicate my time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
