 PERSONALS: The Cases of the Disappearing Mayonnaise  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Champaign, Ill., the theft of a trailer loaded with $20,000
worth of Kraft mayonnaise was cause for that town's newspaper, the
News-Gazette, to survey recent incidents of food theft in the
Champaign area. Personals is indebted to  &UR; J. Ehrlich &LR;  for passing
along the story. Among the crimes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Several months ago, $200,000 worth of Snickers and Three
Musketeers bars were taken from a truck parked at a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last December, $1,530 worth of Kraft cheese _ including
Velveeta, mozzarella and Philadelphia cream cheese _ was stolen
from Kraft trailers.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1997, 11 cases of pizza _ worth $5,500 _ disappeared from a
Kraft freezer truck.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development on the national food crime scene, a
truck containing a shipment of Newman's Own salad dressing was
stolen recently on the way from Southern California to Portland,
Ore. The vehicle was recovered without the salad dressing, which
included 664 cases of Olive Oil &AMP; Vinegar, 238 cases of Balsamic
Vinaigrette and 344 cases of Family Recipe Italian.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mirror says  &UR; Jodie Foster &LR; , whose first son was born in
1998, is 11 weeks pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bob Blumer &LR; , ``The Surreal Gourmet,'' will be driving around
San Francisco this week in his customized vehicle, an Airstream
trailer with two giant pieces of toast popping out of its roof. And
the Washington Monthly reports that during the 1998 congressional
session, 84 representatives and senators were stopped for drunken
driving and released after they claimed congressional immunity.
Elsewhere in transportation,  &UR; Tom Walton &LR;  observed a flying missile
propelled from a FedEx truck in the East Bay the other day, took
note of its receiver and realized it was a dog biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Al Guthertz &LR;  checked  &UR; Newt Gingrich &LR; 's registry at Macy's and
reports that not one of the requested four  &UR; Ralph Lauren &LR;  tub mats
has been purchased.
</P>
<P>
   _ The San Francisco swing band  &UR; Lavay Smith &LR;  and Her Red Hot
Skillet Lickers' second CD, ``Everybody's Talkin' 'Bout Miss
Thing!'' is No. 12 on the Billboard traditional jazz chart this
week. Smith turned down offers from major record companies and
produced the album on her own Fat Note Records; everything near it
on the chart is from a major label.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MODERN TIMES &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steve Begley &LR;  has received his first ``Christian spam,'' a
letter that promises ``Two Free Gifts 4 U _ from one who knows
you!'' The message expounds the glories of being saved, provides a
suggested prayer, and offers a free ``best-seller,'' a book about
knowing God.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women-only investors' clubs earn an average return of 21
percent, says a University of California at Davis study reported in
Publishers Weekly, but men-only clubs earn only 15 percent. This is
said to be because women do more careful research.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR;  was surprised that the Cafe Mediterraneum in
Berkeley, which opened in 1950 and is Berkeley's most venerable
``haunt of bohemians and aged hippies,'' has an ATM machine. It's
been there for four months, a worker told Personals, and the only
complaints from customers have come when the money hasn't come out.
</P>
