<HEADER>
A0038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-ALTHORP-ART-N     05-30 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ALTHORP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN A NAME? A LITTLE HISTORY, A LOT OF CLASS DISTINCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Foreign Journal) 
(ART ADV: a map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT BRINGTON, England _ It is spelled simply enough, in just
two syllables, with no strange or gimmicky combinations of letters.
But for centuries, it has been grievously mispronounced by everyone
who is not anyone.
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder. Why would the average person know that the word
Althorp is supposed to be pronounced AWL-trupp?
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly the question Earl Spencer, brother of the late
Diana, Princess of Wales and the owner of Althorp, the family's
impressive ancestral estate next to this tiny village, asked
himself recently. In a highly unaristocratic move, the earl
announced that Althorp should henceforth be known the way common
people might think it should be known, as AWL-thorp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems fitting to change the pronunciation once and for all
to a version that everyone can pronounce and understand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The earl, who particularly wants things to be user-friendly for
the tens of thousands of visitors he hopes to attract this summer
to the Diana-themed memorial at Althorp, said that the word had
always given him trouble. Before he inherited his earldom and went
by the lowlier title of Viscount Althorp, for instance, he arrived
at a new job in New York to find his name listed as ``Al Thorp.''
</P>
<P>
   But if it was a shot across the bow, Spencer's bold declaration
of linguistic democracy does not seem to have unsettled the
countless British aristocrats who wear their own flamboyantly
semi-pronounceable names, and those of their enormous homes, like
badges of honor.
</P>
<P>
   The Cholmondeley family, for example, was not suddenly moved to
declare that from now on they no longer wanted to be called the
CHUM-leys. Nor did the Earl of Harewood announce an end to his
preferred pronunciation, HAR-wood, either for himself or his
estate, Harewood House, even though the adjoining village of
Harewood, full of non-aristocratic residents, calls itself
HAIR-wood.
</P>
<P>
   And the Beaulieus are still clinging to their traditional style,
simple and decidedly un-Frenchified: BEW-ley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of those things that either you know, or you
don't know,'' said an official at Cholmondeley castle, explaining
how civilians learn, apparently by osmosis, that the unwieldy word
is supposed to be spoken as chumley. (``No, indeed not,'' she
added, when asked whether her name might be used.)
</P>
<P>
   What gives these people, you might ask, the right to defy the
conventions of the alphabet and insist on eccentric pronunciations
of their own choosing?
</P>
<P>
   ``All this nonsense is about who's in the club, and who's out,''
said Harold Brooks-Baker, publishing director of Burke's Peerage.
``There is a tendency in this country to change names around, in
order to appeal to the upper classes in a way that doesn't allow
the lower classes to pronounce things correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many things connected to the upper classes in Britain,
though, it is more complicated than that. Many of the most
aristocratic families in Britain have names that date back many
hundreds of years, to a time when words were not always spelled or
pronounced as they are now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is that we've been literate for so long,''
said Graham Pointon, a pronunciation adviser in the BBC's
Pronunciation Department. ``The English language has been written
down since Anglo-Saxon times. While the pronunciation has moved on,
the spelling has lagged behind.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, he said, the pronunciation of long words changed
simply because people were sick of having to use so many syllables.
Think of how Worcestershire is supposed to be pronounced
WUSS-ter-sheer; or how Magdalene, a college at Cambridge University
(and also at Oxford, but there spelled without the final `e'), is
supposed to be pronounced MAUD-lin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole purpose of language is to communicate as much as
possible with the least possible effort, so sounds which used to be
pronounced are left out over time,'' Pointon said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a Britain where people of all stripes are highly attuned
to social distinction, the way words are pronounced cannot help but
separate the wheat from the chaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those class distinction indicators that people
like to hang onto to show that they're upper class,'' said Robin
Harcourt Williams, the librarian at Hatfield House, the home of the
very upper class Cecil (rhymes with thistle) family.
</P>
<P>
   And changing one's name _ or one's pronunciation _ has long been
used by the lower classes to affect a patina of poshness. One of
the most popular comic creations on television, for instance, is
the character Hyacinth Bucket in ``Keeping Up Appearances,'' who
insists that her name be pronounced Boo-KAY.
</P>
<P>
   And many Britons speak fondly of people their parents or
grandparents knew who were desperate to save themselves from
embarrassing names by inventing exotic pronunciations. That way,
for instance, the comical Sidebottoms became the flamboyant
sid-AY-boh-TOMS.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the same family often disagree on how their names
should be pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Powell, Prime Minister Tony Blair's chief of staff,
pronounces his last name to rhyme with towel. But Charles, his
older brother, a Conservative who served as chief of staff for
former Prime Minister John Major, decided that he wanted to
pronounce it in a slightly snootier way, to rhyme with roll _ the
usage also favored by the late novelist Anthony Powell. (Major
himself has a brother named Terry Major-Ball, but dropped the
``Ball'' in his own name).
</P>
<P>
   In Great Brington, where they have always said AWL-thorp, there
was general relief at Spencer's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visitors were always embarrassed when I told them they were
mispronouncing it,'' said Christine Whiley, the Great Brington
postmistress. ``I'm glad he's finally bowed to public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   But Geordie Greig (pron. gregg), the editor of the Tatler
magazine and a keen student of Britain's upper classes, being a
member himself, said he was sorry to see the old usage go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always thought I was being incredibly clever, knowing it
was AWL-trupp,'' he said, fondly mentioning one of his other
favorite words, equerry (pron. uh-QUAIR-y by those in the know,
apparently). ``It was always nice to have thought one was on the
inside track, and now we're all left with this lowest-common
denominator word, with everything reduced to its simplest, blandest
and most approachable level.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Spencer said, he is sure people will continue
to find ways of getting the name Althorp wrong. When his sister
died, he said, one American television station reported that her
body was heading to its ``final resting place, at Antwerp.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
