<HEADER>
A0040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-30 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: PRIVATE FILES DELETED
</P>
<P>
   The government has moved to dismantle a huge computer database
that could generate detailed files on 34 million Canadians, alive
and dead. In face of protests, the Human Resources Ministry sent
tax computer files back to the Canada Customs and Revenue Agency,
and government workers deleted a program that connected databases.
A Human Resources Ministry spokesman said no backups existed of the
files, which included health, tax, travel, employment and welfare
records.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: LEFTIST SURGES IN POLL
</P>
<P>
   Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, the candidate for Mexico City mayor
from the leftist party governing the city, has surged to a 17-point
lead over two rivals, a poll of 1,109 people by the newspaper
Reforma said. The poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percent. His stunning rise came during a monthlong challenge to his
residency credentials by President Ernesto Zedillo's party. A court
threw out the challenge, and the candidate appears to be drawing
support from voters who see him as a victim of official harassment.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA: ATTACK CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a large-scale offensive, Russian troops were trying
to destroy a Chechen rebel force of about 400 in the southeast
mountains. At the same time, Russia's government representative in
Chechnya, Nikolai Koshman, said he had dismissed Bislan Gantimirov,
a Chechen political figure freed from prison last fall and put in
command of pro-Russian militia forces. Gantamirov was fired along
with 295 members of his 353-member militia, a move seen as a
setback in the effort to create a pro-Moscow security force.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: FUROR OVER GAY EVENT
</P>
<P>
   Rome's city leaders ran into heavy criticism for a decision by
the municipal council to withdraw official support, and some
financial support, for a World Gay Pride festival planned for July
1-9. Mayor Francesco Rutelli was attacked by left-wing party chiefs
and by Amos Luzzatto, president of Italy's Jewish communities, who
praised homosexuals' bravery during persecution by the Nazis. But
city leaders appear determined not to let the festival clash with
the Catholic Church's jubilee celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: POLICE HOLD TERRORIST SUSPECTS
</P>
<P>
   As home rule returned to Northern Ireland, the police in Dublin
and Limerick arrested five men suspected of membership in dissident
republican groups like the Real IRA, the group reportedly behind
the 1998 Omagh bombing that killed 29 people. Fifteen other men
have been arrested and released in the past week after the seizure
of bomb-making materials in Dublin. The IRA's promise to put its
weapons beyond use has caused an increase in fringe republican
activity.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: MINE PROPOSALS
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration presented proposals at a meeting in
Geneva to strengthen land mine restrictions in a 1980 global
weapons pact that has been ratified by some of the biggest users of
the devices, including India, China, Pakistan and the United
States, which have not, however, signed the 1997 Ottawa anti-mine
accord. A State Department official said the proposals would, among
other things, extend restrictions to mines dropped from planes and
to anti-vehicle mines, in addition to anti-personnel mines.
Adoption of the proposals would not come before December 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: TAX STRIKE CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   Markets remained closed for the second day as merchants
continued a strike against a tax survey designed to flush out tax
evaders and to increase the paltry number of taxpayers in the
country. Traders said they will continue their protests with a
series of demonstrations in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: U.S. RULES OUT ARMS AID
</P>
<P>
   After meeting President Chandrika Kumaratunga, Undersecretary of
State Thomas R. Pickering ruled out American help to Sri Lanka for
arms purchases that would aid the country in its battles with
separatist Tamil rebels. But he also warned the rebels that the
United States would not recognize a separate Tamil state and urged
them to enter peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: 44 SLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Armed men believed to be from a militant Muslim group were
reported to have killed at least 44 villagers, most of them
Christians, on a remote eastern island, the latest of thousands of
people to die in violence in the Spice Islands over the past 17
months. The attack follows a similar raid in the same area last
week that took 34 lives.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: SPEAKER ELECTED
</P>
<P>
   The new parliament elected a mid-ranking cleric as speaker after
days of debate and compromise among pro-reform groups. Mehdi
Karroubi, 63, was elected with 186 votes in the 290-seat assembly
and faces a confirmation vote considered certain to approve him.
Karroubi was a member of parliament until 1992 when the
conservatives defeated his pro-reform party. He re-emerged as a
supporter of President Mohammad Khatami in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
