<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-RUN-NCAA-PREVIEW-COX     05-30 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NCAA-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Desired finish line awaits in Sydney
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ When the NCAA Track and Field Championships start
today, a number of elite athletes will be aspiring to use their
performances as a springboard into the Olympic Trials later this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina hurdler and sprinter Terrence Trammell has a
legitimate shot of competing in Sydney. Others such as Georgia
hammer thrower Andras Haklits (Croatia) already have earned spots
on their countries' Olympic teams. And some, like Georgia Tech
freshman 800-meter whiz Brendon Mahoney, are just soaking up the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is definitely to make the (NCAA) finals, then to run a
fast enough time to qualify for the Olympic Trials,'' Mahoney said.
He is a Marist product whose 1-minute, 48.4-second clocking is the
fastest by a collegiate freshman this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an unbelievable experience to run with Olympic
hopefuls but also a great learning experience for the next Olympic
Trials,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC 800-meter champ needs to lower his time to 1:46.7, and
his next shot comes tonight in the 800 semifinals. Advancing to the
Friday final will be the eight fastest runners in a talented field
that features defending champion Derrick Peterson, a Missouri
senior and Lovejoy High graduate.
</P>
<P>
   If the championships hold to form, the meet can be counted on to
produce Olympians _ possibly even Sydney medalists.
</P>
<P>
   In its pre-trials form chart, Track and Field News picks
Peterson fifth in the 800 and Trammell third in the 110 hurdles.
Stanford's Gabe Jennings is picked second in the 1,500, and UCLA's
Seilala Sue ranks as the favored discus thrower. The best shots for
collegians to make the U.S. team are in the sprints, with such
hopefuls as Coby Miller of Auburn, Shawn Crawford of Clemson and
Southern Cal's Angela Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long distances are so much mental and experience, and a
lot of these people they'll be racing against at the trials have
had years of world-class racing,'' said Rachel Cook, distance coach
at the University of Georgia. ``Then, Gabe Jennings has run 3:37,
and, on any given day, that can make the team. Plus, he's been good
at an international level.''
</P>
<P>
   And gifted as the sprinters might be, they will have their hands
full at the trials. The 100 world record-holder, Maurice Greene,
also is challenging record-holder Michael Johnson in the 200. It's
no easier on the women's side, where Marion Jones and Inger Miller
are favored in the 100 and 200.
</P>
<P>
   To improve his chances, Trammell, a Southwest DeKalb graduate,
plans to try the rare double of the 100 and the 110 hurdles, both
here and at the trials in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't see why a collegiate athlete could not make
the (Olympic) team unless they were injured or mentally drained,''
said Trammell, defending NCAA hurdles champion. ``The top times
right now in the U.S. are mostly collegiate athletes. The biggest
thing for the collegiate athlete, because of the strenuous season,
is getting rest and still staying sharp for the Olympic Trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
