<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-RUN-TEXAS-COX     05-30 2224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Bev Kearney is at the pinnacle of her
profession. But is that enough for the driven women's track and
field coach at the University of Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   She's come so far. At 42, she's in the third year of a five-year
contract that pays her an annual base salary of $110,000, and few
college track coaches make more. Of course, few have accomplished
more than the former Auburn sprinter who got into coaching almost
by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Kearney is a seven-time national coach of the year. Her
Longhorns have won four of the last five NCAA team titles,
including the past two outdoor crowns leading into this week's meet
at Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kearney sees so much still to be done, both in terms of
rebuilding her young team as well as the much bigger and more
significant picture of the gender and racial equality in her
profession.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain, however: Success hasn't mellowed her. If
anything, it's merely stoked her already raging competitive fire,
which was one reason she was so upset last week after Nebraska
snapped Texas' string of nine straight conference outdoor
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd heard she was intense, but it's even more than I
thought,'' said John Rembao, Kearney's assistant for three years.
``She's a vicious competitor. After the Big 12 meet, she was like,
`I believe in them. Why don't they believe in themselves?' Things
like that just tear her up. She takes it personally because she
believes it's her fault when we don't do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not her nature to sit idly by and allow bad things to
happen when she thinks she can do something about it,'' Rembao
added. ``A lot of people don't know quite what to make of her
because they can't imagine anyone hating to lose as much as she
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearney arrived at Texas in 1993 after five seasons as coach at
the University of Florida. Her overall coaching resume includes 30
coach-of-the-year honors, 20 NCAA top-10 finishes, five NCAA
titles, 25 NCAA individual champions and 16 conference team crowns.
</P>
<P>
   And she shows no sign of letting up. It's apparent by the way
she paces nervously at big meets, usually alone. Often, not even
her own assistant coaches and support staff can find her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always been tough, and she's getting tougher,'' said
former UT quartermiler Suziann Reid, a 17-time All-American who
continues to train with Kearney along with numerous other elite
athletes. ``It doesn't matter how much success she's had. She knows
people are coming after her, so she demands the best from herself
as well as us. She gets tougher every day, and that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   A question-and-answer session with Kearney:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you gotten over losing the Big 12 outdoor meet to
Nebraska?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know if you get over it. You just move on. Whether
you have a good experience or bad experience, it stays with you.
Unfortunately, the bad experiences seem to linger a lot longer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you discussed it with your team?
</P>
<P>
   A: We've had some small meetings and some individual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was said?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm pretty direct. Some people would probably call it harsh.
It just depends on where your head is as to how you receive it. If
you understand that what I'm telling you is said in a manner that's
trying to help you, then you'll take it in the right way. If you're
in a defensive move, it's going to be offensive. It depends on the
person receiving it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you worry about how they take it when you're being direct?
</P>
<P>
   A: You always worry about how it's going to impact somebody, but
the bottom line is you have to weigh that against whether or not
withholding the information is going to hurt them more than giving
them the information. I always feel that if you've got a way to
help a person get beyond what prevented them from doing their best
in the first place, the personal sacrifice may be to you because
sometimes there is some fallout from their reaction. But you've got
to be willing to take that chance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did you think at the Big 12 meet when you saw the
Nebraska women celebrating after (UT's) Nicole Hoxie false-started
in the hurdles?
</P>
<P>
   A: I immediately wanted to come back in the next event and drill
them. When that happens, it makes me want to shut you down.
Unfortunately my team didn't respond that way. It's like in
basketball. If someone slams on you, you can either pout about the
slam or come back and turn the crowd back in your direction by
doing something even greater. Me? I want to shut you back down. My
goal is not to give you any more ammunition than you've already
got.
</P>
<P>
   Q: People would say you're at the top of your profession. Do you
feel that way?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you start to get wrapped up in the success and failures
in your past, you forget about what you're doing now. Whether I win
or lose, I'm moving on because winning last year isn't going to
help me win this year. Losing last year doesn't mean I'm going to
lose next year. The greatest tragedy any program, coach or team can
do to itself is to rely only on tradition to sustain itself.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is winning national championships what you thought it would
be?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's what I thought it would be and more. It's also a lot
less. It depends on what perspective you're looking at it from.
When you finally get it done and you see the look on your team's
face and all the accolades that come from it, it's wonderful. It's
like you can finally exhale. But if you think it's going to mean a
life change, you're wrong. It did not guarantee me greater
acceptance as a coach. It did not guarantee me access to the inner
circles. I still had to face a lot of the biases that women and
minorities face. That was one of the things that was really
discouraging to me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has that aspect gotten better?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. And I don't know if it will ever change. That was the one
thing I had to realize. You think if you work and achieve all these
things, all of a sudden life will become fair, and it doesn't. It
doesn't create a greater or equal playing field for you. You still
have to overcome a lot of biases in society and in sport.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you cite an example?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can't pinpoint and I'd prefer not to pinpoint any
particular situation, because I've never used it as a crutch. But
you've got to look at the lack of numbers of women and minorities
in coaching, and you've got to understand there is a struggle still
going on. A lot of what I've done has been pioneering, and that's
made it very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In terms of salary and prestige, you're at the top of your
profession. So do you still consider this your fight?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most definitely. Money doesn't change that aspect of it.
That's always going to be a very strong passion of mine. That's one
of the reasons I've made it, because I hope I can open up doors to
show administrations and universities that we can do this. If
that's not part of the mission of what I do, winning and losing
isn't worth it. You can't pay us enough money for the amount of
hours, stress, time and effort we put into this. It's not just
about the money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has reaching this point in your career been as fulfilling as
you thought it would be?
</P>
<P>
   A:I'm amazed at where I am. I'm in shock. Sometimes I walk
around the campus and I wonder, ``Is it me here?'' I get
embarrassed when I walk in the Co-op and see that poster of myself
because I never thought that would be me. I see videos from
national telecasts and think, ``C'mon, is that really you?'' At
some point you're going to wake up, and it's all going to
disappear. I think I'm more amazed than anything else. I know it's
not my doing but the grace of God that I'm here because you never
think that you have the type of abilities or special skills to
accomplish all that I've done. I can't give you a road map on how
I've done it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you as big a target as your team?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think I'm the main target. I have absolutely no idea why. I
know I can be very outspoken. I say what I feel and fight for what
I believe in, and I can be very passionate when I believe in a
cause. When I go to a meet, I'm there to take care of my team and
so I don't do a lot of socializing, and that can be misunderstood a
lot of times.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So other coaches perceive you as aloof?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know what it would be called, but they don't know me
well. There are only a few coaches that I have a lot of
conversations with. At a meet, I'm working. I'm a basket case
before my athletes compete. When I leave a meet, I'm exhausted.
I've run, I've jumped, I've sprinted, I've done exchanges, I've
hurdled. I go home and I'm just busted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you're not a social animal at meets?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've been burned a lot. I used to be a lot more open, but
when you sit down and talk about situations and then you hear the
information back in a way that wasn't given, I've learned to be
more protective of myself. When I first got started in the
profession, I went to some older coaches and got burned. It ripped
my heart out. I have a lot of acquaintances on the track circuit
but not a lot of friends.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a lot of jealousy toward you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some people have, in the past, felt this was their job and
that I didn't deserve it. I've heard comments like, ``If I had the
team she had, I'd have won, too.'' Or, ``She can't coach. She can
just recruit.'' I've heard it all, man. I'll tell people in a
minute that there are coaches more technically proficient than me
and more meticulous than me. But nobody works harder than me in
this sport.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But hasn't it taken more than hard work for you to reach this
level?
</P>
<P>
   A: Honestly, I think it has to do with the fact that what I
don't know, I'll find out. I made a pact with myself that I'd never
let what I don't know hurt my athletes in achieving what they seek.
I think my greatest asset is like when a mom knows when something
is wrong with their child. I think I have very good instincts. God
has blessed me with that ability, and that goes beyond any type of
coaching. Sometimes, if you really watch what I do, it doesn't make
sense, because I'll invent some stuff. I'm out there. I'm
completely off the wall when I coach. Sometimes I'll stay up all
night because I can't figure something out. I should literally be
exhausted when I get to the track but I'll just be wired, because
I've got it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has your philosophy changed with your success?
</P>
<P>
   A: When it gets to the point where I no longer desire to be the
best, I don't think I need to be at Texas. It doesn't mean when I
can't win, I don't need to be here because that's impossible for
anybody to expect, to win all the time. It's just unrealistic. But
when you lose the desire to be the best, whatever the best might be
at that point in time given the circumstances, you need to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can success get old?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think that ever happens. I think the fight sometimes
can get tiring. Or you can lose the passion for what you're
fighting for. If you cease to believe this is a battle, then it's
time to move on to another battle. I was told once that I always
complain that I don't get enough rest but that I always manage to
fill up the calendar even when I don't have to. At first I refused
to believe that about myself, but I realized that last year, yeah,
I'm like that. I need to learn to say no sometimes and take some
time off.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there anything in coaching you still want to do?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, not in coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Then what?
</P>
<P>
   A: I might like to start a business. I originally wanted to go
into counseling with a spiritual base, but I want to do something
in fitness, counseling and wellness. I want to eventually develop a
sanctuary of peace where people can come and just forget. Where
they can get pampered by fitness and counseling. It's not
necessarily a religious thing, but it has to have a spiritual base
because I think that's the only true means to peace and joy. It
would have to have a very peaceful environment. I'm kind of corny,
I guess.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there time in your life now for serenity?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, and I think that's why I'm seeking it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is coaching as much fun now as it was when you were trying to
reach this point in your career?
</P>
<P>
   A: In some ways yes, in some ways no. I miss the naivete of it
all from when I first started. But I don't miss not even being
given a visit by a prospect. Now I can get my foot in the door. It
doesn't guarantee me any results, but at least I can get my foot in
the door. I now have people wanting to come to Texas and train with
Bev Kearney. I love that aspect, but I miss the naivete of it all,
when you just didn't know what you couldn't do. I just didn't know
any better, starting out. I try to retain a little bit of that in
everything I do. I always try to hire coaches who don't have a huge
past in coaching because they're enthusiastic enough and still
present that naivete of why can't we do this or that. I always want
people with that kind of mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But for you personally, the fire's still there?
</P>
<P>
   A:It ain't going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Randy Riggs at rriggs(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
