u f BC-DEPOT-EXPO-COX     05-30 0315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-EXPO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    xpo Design Center entering Chicago
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Homeowners in Chicago will soon get their first taste
of Home Depot's Expo Design Center stores.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot said Tuesday it has nailed down sites to open three
interior design showrooms in the Windy City next year. Real estate
brokers are looking for a fourth spot, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The Expo stores, designed to sell high-end remodeling projects
and decor, will open in several new markets this year as part of a
national rollout. Home Depot, based in Cobb County at I-285 and
Paces Ferry Road, currently has 15 Expos in six states. The
retailer wants to open about 200 Expos over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Existing Expo markets will get more stores, too. Last week, Home
Depot opened an Expo buying office in Orange, Calif., to support
its West Coast expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Two Expos are scheduled to open this year in Southern
California, where it already has three Expos. Another two will open
this year near San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Other expansion sites this year include Boston and Detroit,
which are both new Expo markets, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, the retailer is scouting real estate in
Buckhead, Kennesaw and northern Gwinnett County. Expo President
Bryant Scott has said he wants to open four more showrooms here, in
addition to the Perimeter Mall and Alpharetta locations.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Indoors, a competing concept by Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.,
is speeding up growth plans as Expo moves across the country. Sears
Chairman and Chief Executive Arthur Martinez recently told analysts
that 100 sites would be picked by 2002. The Great Indoors currently
operates two stores in Denver and Scottsdale, Ariz. and plans to
open two more in Detroit and Dallas this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
