<HEADLINE>
MARKETS SURGE AS TECH STOCKS RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Nasdaq composite index surged to its biggest
percentage gain and the second-largest point gain in its 29-year
history Tuesday as investors snapped up technology heavyweights
like Intel, Cisco Systems and Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index shot up 254.37 points, or 7.9
percent, to 3,459.48. Of the stocks that make up the Nasdaq 100
index, 98 rose in price, while the remaining 2 lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the gains, the Nasdaq is still down nearly 15 percent
so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index jumped 44.43 points, or
3.2 percent Tuesday, to 1,422.45, and the Dow Jones industrial
average gained 227.89 points, or 2.2 percent, to 10,527.13.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the Nasdaq was the highlight of a very strong
session for stocks generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be the start of something good,'' said Bill Allyn,
head of listed trading at Jefferies &AMP; Co. Allyn and others said it
was significant that stocks, which opened strong, remained that way
throughout the session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors expected the market to rally and fail, as they have
so many times during this correction,'' he said. ``When the market
didn't pull back, it came as a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the positives and the possibility of an impending summer
rally, there are some caveats. This was the first day following a
long weekend, and trading volume, a good gauge of investor
enthusiasm, was fairly light. About 844.2 million shares traded on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   And the gains were recorded without a great deal of
market-moving news developments. Later this week investors will be
confronted with a number of important economic reports, including
May employment data scheduled to be released on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But for a day, optimism reigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nasdaq is the index people will be watching going forward,
because it is seen as still being vulnerable,'' said Bill
Schneider, head of block equity trading at Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   The gains came on a day when Laszlo Birinyi, one of Wall
Street's most bullish stock market forecasters who runs his own
market research firm in Westport, Conn., turned a bit cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Birinyi, whose forecasts over the last few years have been
closer to the market's actual performance than most of his
colleagues, started the year predicting that the S&AMP;P 500 would rise
another 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things have changed,'' since then, he said Tuesday.
As a consequence, Birinyi says the S&AMP;P will record a gain of
between 8 percent and 10 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we look at the flow of funds, we don't see nearly as many
stocks being bought as over the last several years,'' he said,
``and the stocks that are being bought are not being purchased as
aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, although money flowing into equity mutual funds is
up 150 percent from a year ago, and funds flowing into aggressive
growth funds are up 220 percent, ``those stocks aren't really
reacting,'' he added. ``And cash levels are not unusually high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not bearish,'' Birinyi concluded. ``There are still a lot
of situations which under our metric look very good. I guess I am
rationally exuberant.''
</P>
<P>
   Big technology stocks like Cisco and Oracle jumped Tuesday.
Cisco gained 4 15/16, to 59 7/8. Oracle, the database software
maker, gained 7 3/16, to 74 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor manufacturers like Intel and Advanced Micro
Devices rallied after a Lehman Brothers analyst issued a bullish
report on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Stock Exchange's Semiconductor index rose 11.1
percent, its biggest gain in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro soared 11, to 85. And Intel surged 8 3/16, to 125
3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone stocks got a boost from France Telecom S.A.'s $40
billion acquisition of Orange PLC from Vodaphone AirTouch.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's PCS wireless unit rose 7/8, to 54 3/8. AT&AMP;T's Wireless
Group gained 1 3/8, to 27 5/8. And SBC Communications rose 1 5/8,
to 44 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream Wireless jumped 19 1/2, or 19.4 percent, to 119 7/8
after a Japanese newspaper reported that NTT DoCoMo, Japan's
largest mobile phone company, is in talks to buy as much as 20
percent of the U.S. cellular phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm was the most actively traded stock, rising 10 5/16, to
76 3/8. The stock, which rose 27-fold in 1999, is down 60 percent
so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Financial service did well after analysts at Goldman, Sachs
issued a report saying they expect investment banking business to
pick up.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch gained 3 3/16, to 94 5/8. Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette rose 2 11/16, to 39{. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter closed at
67, up 3 5/16. And Goldman Sachs rose 2 3/16, to 72.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
