u f BC-BARCLAYS-AD-COLUMN-NY     05-30 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARCLAYS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: BANK'S UNUSUAL `BIG' ADS AIM FOR BRANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``What is this about big?'' Sir Anthony Hopkins asks in
a new campaign for Britain's second-largest bank, Barclays PLC,
which carries the tagline ``A Big World Needs a Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, seeing the big picture, having the big idea,
clinching the big deal. Nobody wants to clinch the little deal. Who
wants to do that? You'd be a little-deal clincher, a small shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, everything about Barclays' first branding campaign is
big. The actors that appear in the three commercials are big names:
Sir Anthony, Tim Roth and Nick Moran. Each actor commanded a big
fee; according to reports, Sir Anthony received a very big $1.2
million. The commercials are directed by a big-time director, Tony
Scott, who also directed ``Top Gun'' and ``Enemy of the State.''
The commercials themselves are shown on big screens at big movie
theaters across Britain, as well as on television and in print. And
the campaign has already reached a big audience: Barclays estimates
the campaign is reaching 80 percent of the British population.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one small problem with the $15 million campaign.
Barclays is _ as Hopkins mockingly forgets the campaign's
catchword, asking, ``Um, what's the word?'' _ well, small.
</P>
<P>
   The British bank is in the midst of a very big cost-cutting
program that at the very least will make the 300-year-old financial
institution smaller: It just closed 172 branches. Matthew Barrett,
the bank's new chief executive, is hoping that by having a big
brand, with the big reach of the Internet _ where he thinks most
consumers will bank in the future _ he can counter the effect of
the branch closings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it's a brand that is under-leveraged,'' Barrett
said. ``Brand is going to be increasingly important. When people
are surfing the Internet, why will they pick one supplier versus
another? It will be because they are aware of the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which was created by Leagas Delaney in London, was
a challenge because of the traditionally staid image of British
banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem that Barclays had was similar to the other banks
and financial institutions,'' said Tim Delaney, the advertising
agency's co-founder. ``Despite the enormous amount of money spent
on advertising in the last 10 to 15 years, they are all perceived
to be the same by customers.''
</P>
<P>
   While the commercial starring Sir Anthony waxing on about all
things big has received the most attention, Barclays created two
other commercials playing on the ``big'' theme and several print
ads. In the commercial starring Tim Roth, he cites the World Trade
Center as an example of the tallest building in the world _ for
only 29 days, until another was built even taller.
</P>
<P>
   Legas Delaney won the Barclays account, beating J. Walter
Thompson, a unit of the WPP Group; the London office of Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy; and BMP DDB, part of the DDB Worldwide unit of the Omnicom
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays settled on the unusual campaign after research pointed
them toward something a bit radical, at least for a bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most banks, if you examine advertising around the world, they
position themselves as trying to be the friend to the customer,''
Barrett said. ``Bankers want to be loved, and that never flies.
People have lives, they have their own friends. They don't need us
for friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers may not need bankers as friends, but at least some
Londoners have questioned why anyone would want to use a big bank
as opposed to a small one, perhaps with personal service.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's taking it too literally,'' said Caitlin Thomas, head of
brand advertising at Barclays. ``It was always a metaphor for the
breadth and depth of the resources we provide. Bigness is not all
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Anthony himself has come under increasing criticism for
participating in the advertisement. In a hand-written postcard to a
Labor Party politician, Gwenda Thomas, who had sought his support
in her campaign against some of the branch closings, Sir Anthony
said: ``It seems that I have been wholly responsible for leaving
thousands of people destitute. I just have to set the record
straight by saying that I do not run Barclays. I made a commercial
back last June. But I suppose the press love to have a scapegoat,
so why not an actor?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
