<HEADER>
A0056 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MEMORIAL-ATLANTA25-CO     05-30 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORIAL-ATLANTA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Vietnam memorial at the Atlanta History center
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's just a simple slab of marble, but a new Vietnam
War Monument located at the Atlanta History Center represents a
great deal to a local veterans group.
</P>
<P>
   The monument is meant to honor patriotism and remind visitors
that the Vietnam conflict hit Atlanta hard, claiming the lives of
at least 412 metro-area men.
</P>
<P>
   Believed to be Atlanta's first permanent Vietnam memorial, it
was erected in a Walk of Honor in a landscaped, flower-filled park.
It was unveiled in a solemn ceremony by the Atlanta Vietnam
Veterans Business Association, a low-profile group whose primary
mission is to honor those Atlantans who never returned.
</P>
<P>
   The group was founded on Veterans Day in 1981 by businessman Don
Pardue and several other Atlanta veterans who had gathered in a
local pub to toast their friends who never made it home. It has
grown to an organization of 250-plus members. For the past 13 years
it has erected monuments to individual Atlantans in locations
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Atlanta History Center, one of Atlanta's premier
tourist attractions, asked the group to dedicate a monument to all
metro Atlantans who died in Vietnam and to erect it on its property
at the corner of Slaton Drive and West Paces Ferry Road. The
history center's Walk of Honor, outside its pay-to-enter grounds,
is open to the public 24 hours a day and will eventually include
other monuments as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are honoring us by putting the memorial up here,'' says
history center director Rick Beard.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans group president, Rick Lester, 52, an Army
helicopter pilot who narrowly escaped death when he was shot down
in 1969, says thousands of people will be able to see the monument
in its prominent spot. ``This location will allow visitors to see
that Atlantans who selflessly answered their country's call and
made the ultimate sacrifice are forever in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the group will revert to its original plan of placing
monuments to individual Atlantans around the city, Lester says.
</P>
<P>
   The history center is covering the cost of the park, estimated
at $200,000, but the veterans group, which operates on the $25
annual dues of its members, is erecting the monument. Post
Landscape Group donated several thousand dollars for design.
</P>
<P>
   For the memorial's dedication, bagpipers, a 30-piece Army band
from Fort McPherson and an honor guard participated, and a rifle
squad fired a 21-gun salute. Lester, Beard and Gen. Hal Hornburg, a
veteran of the Vietnam, Persian Gulf and Kosovo wars, delivered
brief remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Lester says scores of family members of Atlantans who died or
who are still missing attended the dedication.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.), an honorary member of the Atlanta
Vietnam Veterans Business Association who became friends with
Lester when the two spent months in an Army hospital recovering
from their wounds, says ``what they do is a wonderful thing.
``Dedicating memorials to young Vietnam veterans in places where
people live, work and play _ I think that's a fascinating concept.
It's done with great dignity, with little fanfare. It's the Vietnam
veterans themselves and the families involved that are the focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just beautiful that in a quiet way, they have honored one
of their own every year. And only now is this group coming to
public attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Beard says the decision to erect the Vietnam memorial grew out
of the history center's decision earlier this year to host several
Vietnam War displays, which have proven popular. ``Reqium,'' a
collection of photos taken by journalists who died in action;
``Snapshots of the War'' by Capt. George Herren, depicting barracks
life in Vietnam; and ``Local Memories of a Distant War,'' featuring
artifacts loaned by members of the Atlanta veterans group, will
stay up through June 4.
</P>
<P>
   One of the goals of the veterans business association is to
improve the Vietnam vets' image, which many feel was tarnished by
Hollywood and the news media during and after the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't see yellow ribbons tied around trees to remember
friends and neighbors who were serving,'' Lester says. ``But I
think the public has realized what our true role was, and I've had
many people thank me for what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Army chopper pilot Mitch Johnson, 52, sees the veterans
group as ``a great representation for all soldiers, regardless of
what war they served in _ businesspeople who went through a lot and
are now doing things to help others.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a former Army nurse who remembers with horror
working on hundreds of wounded GIs, calls the veterans association
``a wonderful group which has given a lot to the city of Atlanta,
most particularly these families of these boys who were killed in
Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Pardue, a 54-year-old infantry officer shot in the chest after
two months in Vietnam, says the group's founders never dreamed the
organization would grow into what it has become. But after its
first informal meeting, word spread among Atlanta Vietnam vets, and
by 1987 the group had enough members to begin erecting monuments to
individual Atlantans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kicked it around one night and said, `Why don't we do
something like they did in Washington but for Atlantans who
died?''' Pardue says. ``So we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit group's members range from FBI agents to business
owners, corporate executives, attorneys, physicians, ministers,
judges, airline pilots and professors. They represent all ranks,
from enlisted men up to generals.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland says the ``image of the Vietnam veteran was sealed for
years as a walking time bomb, out of sorts with himself ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact is that most came back and in a very courageous
and positive way, picked up their lives and moved on. That's what
the AVVBA is _ people who saw vigorous combat but have moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
