<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0057 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-POET-LAUREATE31-COX     05-30 1568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POET-LAUREATE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quiet intuition forges David Bottoms' connection between verse
and life
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The handwritten sign on the door of the convenience
store reads ``Gone to Doctor's. Back as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaning across his seat to peer through the passenger-side
window, David Bottoms weighs his few options, then nudges the green
Toyota pickup back onto the two-lane highway. ``I knew he'd been
sick,'' he says. ``Well, I got to bring you back up here. This
place'' _ a Circle K somewhere in Cherokee County, Ga., _ ``it's
got the best CDs of anywhere around.''
</P>
<P>
   He turns the CD player in the truck up a gentle notch and the
disappointment is gone. ``Listen to that clear mountain voice,'' he
is saying as he points us back toward Canton, the town where he
grew up. ``That's Mac Wiseman. Lester Flatt and Mac Wiseman are two
of the best country singers ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's new poet laureate, appointed by Gov. Roy Barnes and
officially sworn in today, is a man who lets you know his
enthusiasms. He sets them before you like a man wanting to pour a
guest a drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to see my truck,'' he was saying a few days earlier
over lunch, slapping an open hand on the table. ``That is a great
truck. Best truck I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Later: ``I want you to meet Kelly. She's a trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Jean Beard is his wife of 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Driving to a Cobb County cinema to buy movie tickets for his
daughter's 10th birthday party: ``Rachel wants to meet you. You got
to meet Rachel. Little girls are something, aren't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Mac Wiseman again: ``You say your wife likes
bluegrass? That's got to be a good woman.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be around Bottoms long to know what revs his
engine. A sweet-running pickup, bluegrass the way it's supposed to
be played, old tapes of the late Duane Allman's guitar riffs, a cut
of beef at Longhorn Steakhouse, poetry that hears the deep truths
the world is trying to tell us.
</P>
<P>
   Ask David Bottoms' acquaintances and former students at Georgia
State University what qualities define the man, and certain words
and descriptions keep coming up. He is unpretentious. He is
relaxed. He is comfortable with himself. He is patient. He takes
others more seriously than he takes himself. He has an intuitive
feel for what a student's poem wants to say, and helps her say it
in her own words.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are basically two kind of workshop leaders,'' says
Michele Newcome, who did graduate work in creative writing under
Bottoms. ``One kind is a good line editor, and another kind can
read a poem and know immediately what has to reach the reader. I
think it's a magical quality, and Dr. Bottoms has it.''
</P>
<P>
   He does have a Ph.D., but on the fourth or fifth time you hear
someone call this unprofessorial man ``Dr. Bottoms,'' your
curiosity is piqued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if everyone calls him that,'' Newcome says,
laughing, ``but for me, at least, it's a measure of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The respect goes beyond the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Bottoms would invite us to his home for workshop,''
Newcome says, ``and we'd often bring our children. It never once
bothered him. One time, there was a student who had a 3-year-old,
and the child didn't have a tricycle. Dr. Bottoms went in the
garage and dug out a tricycle that had been his daughter's. He just
gave it to her.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't surprise you, once you've spent time with him. There
is a groundedness about Bottoms that seems more connected to the
simple upbringing in Canton, Ga., than to his upscale neighborhood
in east Cobb County, Ga., (``I couldn't live here if Kelly wasn't a
lawyer''). He was the only child of a father who nearly died at sea
in World War II and a mother who took him to a bookstore in Canton
every week. These are the kinds of things he remembers from his
childhood. The bookstore is long gone, replaced by a business that
deals in sewage treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, too, is the old wooden desk in a Canton classroom _ the
desk where his father, David Bottoms Sr., once carved his name as a
boy, the same desk his son found himself sitting in when he was in
sixth grade. ``You know how you go into a room the first day of
class and find where you want to sit,'' he says. ``I go to this
desk at the far corner of the room and I'm looking at my name
carved into it.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of his poems, Bottoms imagined breaking into the school's
boiler room one night, hammer in one hand, flashlight in the other,
climbing a staircase, finding a door and sweeping the darkness with
his beam until it lights upon the tangible evidence of his father's
childhood, with its unspoken dreams and its silent sorrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Bottoms,'' says Ernest Suarez, a professor of English at
Catholic University of America, ``is a poet who focuses very
intensely on the physical world. But the poetry never stops there.
It's always with the intent of making us see beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, in Bottoms' poem ``The Desk,'' he imagines wresting the
scarred oak top free of its frame and slipping away with it into
the night. The minor vandalism would be discovered, but nothing of
value would be missing _ no typewriters, no business machines, no
audiovisual gear. Only a broken window and, inexplicably, a topless
desk.
</P>
<P>
   School officials would scratch their heads, wondering why anyone
would want an otherwise useless slab of wood, and that would be the
end of it. But years later the desk top would lie against the
vandal's basement wall, and he would ``wonder what it means to own
my father's name.''
</P>
<P>
   At 50 years of age, Bottoms has the look of a man in a
19th-century daguerreotype _ solemn of mien, slightly hunched in
posture, a salt-and-pepper beard that gives his face a look of
stern Calvinism. He and wife Kelly are Episcopalians, but he grew
up a Baptist, and his no-frills religious upbringing influenced his
poetic voice. He points to the First Baptist Church in Canton where
his mother went and, a few blocks away, Oakdale Baptist where his
father went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hers was the uptown church,'' he says. ``Or as uptown as
anything in Canton can be.''
</P>
<P>
   On most Sundays he worshipped uptown, but there were other weeks
when he would find himself in the pew with his father. The earthier
language of his father's church left him, he guesses, with a feel
for concrete images, natural speech rhythms and a directness of
manner. But he has since come to think of religion in terms of
mystery and revelation, and both, he says, are at the heart of what
a poet is attempting to do.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his truck in a parking lot that once had been a
baseball field his father had cleared and laid out, he says: ``It's
all gone now. It was very sad when they did all this.''
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of the lot is a tanning salon, a place to get your
nails done, a Domino's pizza house, an outlet for AirTouch cell
phones ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The world sends us all these signals,'' he says. ``The poet's
kind of the interpreter.'' Whatever the poem says on the surface,
there are emotional connections to what lies hidden beneath. It's
the poet's job, he says, to dig deep enough in his words and images
to find what is universal in his personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always looking for the mystery, in poetry and in life,''
says Megan Sexton, managing editor of Five Points magazine and a
former graduate student under Bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   He is looking for it even _ or maybe especially _ when he drives
a country back road, listening to the music of people whose voices
are the echo of generations. He is talking about something
contemporary _ public education _ when a note catches his ear.
``Listen to ol' Doc Watson play that guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   He turns it up a notch, his ears a receiver for the signals the
world is sending him.
</P>
<P>
   DAVID BOTTOMS FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: 1949 in Canton, Ga. Lives in Cobb County.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family: Married to Kelly Jean Beard, a lawyer. They have one
child, daughter Rachel, 10.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Occupation: Teaches creative writing and poetry at Georgia
State University, since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: Doctorate in creative writing and American poetry
from Florida State University, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Master's in American poetry from West Georgia College, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Bachelor's in English from Mercer University, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Graduated from Cherokee High School, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Books of poetry: ``Vagrant Grace'' (Copper Canyon Press,
1999); ``Armored Hearts'' (Copper Canyon Press, 1995); ``Under the
Vulture-Tree'' (Morrow, 1987); ``In a U-Haul North of Damascus''
(Morrow, 1983); ``Shooting Rats at the Bibb County Dump'' (Morrow,
1980); ``Jamming With the Band at the VFW'' (Burnt Hickory Press,
1978).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Novels: ``Easter Weekend'' (Houghton Mifflin, 1990. Reissued
in 1998 by Louisiana State University Press); ``Any Cold Jordan''
(Peachtree Publishers, 1987).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Awards and honors: Poet laureate of Georgia, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheim Fellowship in poetry, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Award in Literature from the American Academy and Institute of
Arts and Letters, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Fellowship in creative writing from the National Endowment for
the Arts, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson Prize from Poetry magazine, 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Whitman Award from the Academy of American Poets, 1979.
(Robert Penn Warren was awarding judge.)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
