<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0058 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TVPSURVIVOR31-COX     05-30 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVPSURVIVOR31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rashes, rats and sex: `Survivor' bids to be next `Millionaire'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to Pulau Tiga, a remote island near Borneo, erstwhile
home to 16 castaways, one newly minted millionaire, an omnipresent
TV crew and a lot fewer rats than there used to be.
</P>
<P>
   The island was home-unsweet-home to ``Survivor.'' In March, 16
carefully screened volunteers were ``stranded'' on Pulau Tiga,
forced to build their own shelter, forage for food (rat-on-a-stick,
you'll learn, tastes just like chicken) and cope with infected
insect bites.
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't fun enough, every few days they would hold a
tribal council and vote to exile one person. The last one standing
after 39 days on the island got $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of re-creating last summer's instant TV craze, ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' CBS will run ``Survivor'' as a 13-week
summer series. The network has been carefully orchestrating the
show's hype, setting up phone interviews for journalists but
refusing to send any tapes out in advance. A brief clip was shown
to advertisers in New York two weeks ago, but it was the equivalent
of a movie trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really couldn't let your guard down. You didn't know who
you could trust,'' Ramona Gray, 28, said in a telephone interview.
``I was prepared for anything physical, but the psychological part
was the hardest. One minute somebody could like you, the next
minute they would hate you.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Gray, the participants included a retired CEO, a
single gay father, a housewife-mother, a basketball coach, a female
truck driver, a former Navy SEAL and a substitute teacher. They
range in age from 22 to 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' has been compared to MTV's ``The Real World,''
``Gilligan's Island'' and ``Lord of the Flies,'' William Golding's
classic novel about castaways who revert to the basest level of
human nature. These ``Survivors'' didn't stoop to murder, but there
was sex among the competitors as well as plenty of tension and
arguments, all to the delight of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of water and oil mixing, or not mixing,'' said
Gray, back in her job as a chemist in New Jersey and contractually
forbidden to divulge too much detail (particularly who won). ``I
think any time you mix total strangers, not everyone's going to get
along.''
</P>
<P>
   She says there was particular tension between some of the older
castaways who tried to take charge _ the retired CEO and Navy SEAL
_ and the 20-somethings. ``We were all young and high strung, and
just like, `No, we don't agree with that.''' She said although she
expected racial tension _ there were two blacks and 14 whites _
there was none.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real surviving part was surviving each other,'' says
executive producer Mark Burnett, who lived on the island with the
contestants. ``It's a petri dish of humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   And a well-culled petri dish it was. As Burnett went through the
6,000 applicants and narrowed the pool, he did extensive background
and psychological tests on the potential players. Then they signed
a contract as thick as ``War and Peace,'' Burnett said. That's
because when an earlier version of the show first aired on Swedish
TV, a participant who was rejected later committed suicide. Fox's
``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire'' scandal added to the
pressure to make sure all the players were clean going in.
</P>
<P>
   That cleanliness soon passed. Several survivors have joked about
the ripe smell they soon developed, particularly after two straight
days of torrential rain. One man who brought a toothbrush (players
could bring one item each) was in demand to loan it out, and skin
rashes got so bad that hardly anyone wore underwear.
</P>
<P>
   And although only one person won cash, there was at least a side
benefit for all the contestants. Nearly everyone lost between 10
and 20 pounds during their stay. Just not enough rats to go around.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Who will be the lone survivor?
www.cbs.com/network/tvshows
</P>
<P>
   /mini/survivor/
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
