<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SARA-LEE-MARKETPLACE-     05-30 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARA-LEE-MARKETPLACE-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SARA LEE PLANS TO TRIM FOUR DIVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 of C. Steven McMillan is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Sara Lee, the giant consumer goods company that sells
everything from Ball Park hot dogs to Playtex bras and Hanes
underwear, said Tuesday that it would reorganize its operations and
divest itself of four divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has annual revenue of about $20 billion, said
that later this year it expected to take two of those divisions
public: Coach, its leather goods business, and PYA/Monarch, one of
the nation's largest food service distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee executives say the company also intends to sell
Champion, the athletic apparel maker, as well as the international
fabrics unit of Courtaulds Textiles, the British retailer that Sara
Lee acquired in March. Together, the four units generate about $4
billion in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The moves, which executives say will narrow and sharpen the
focus of the conglomerate, which is based in Chicago, are also
expected to raise about $2.5 billion for Sara Lee, which could use
the money to make acquisitions that better complement its core
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled by lackluster earnings growth and a belief that the
company's stock price is undervalued, top executives moved Tuesday
to re-energize Sara Lee with promises of a more centralized and
efficient management structure, a more focused portfolio and a more
aggressive investment strategy, particularly in emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, the company has been acquiring dozens
of major brands. And now, with its longtime chief executive, John
H. Bryan, set to step down this summer, the company says it would
like to create a more streamlined global enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a new vision for Sara Lee, a vision that will focus
our business portfolio and resources,'' said C. Steven McMillan,
the president and chief operating officer of Sara Lee, who will
take over as chief executive on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sara Lee rose slightly Tuesday, up 12.5 cents, to
$18.875, on the New York Stock Exchange. The gains may have been
tempered because Sara Lee executives also warned Tuesday that
earnings in the coming year could come in about 5 percent below
expectations because of currency weakness in Europe, which accounts
for about 40 percent of the company's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts, however, largely praised the move by Sara
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good news, bad news day,'' said John McMillin, an
analyst at Prudential Securities. ``But now that Sara Lee got a
haircut, they should be a better looking company. Sara Lee had
clearly gotten into too many businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee executives said the company could divest itself of
additional units in the coming year. And analysts said that might
help remove some of the stigma in the investment community that the
company is too diversified.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the divestitures, they'll be a little less of a
conglomerate, but much more so than other food companies,'' said
Terry Bivens, an analyst at Bear Stearns. ``They want to prune back
operations they feel are no longer strategic.''
</P>
<P>
   The analysts, however, say the move does not set the stage for
Sara Lee to enter into a major merger with another food or consumer
goods giant, or make it likely that Sara Lee will acquire a major
company.
</P>
<P>
   While other large food companies may get tangled up in the
bidding war over Bestfoods, Sara Lee is a different kind of beast.
The company is too diversified, the analysts say, and it is too
much of a hodge-podge of food and consumer product companies to be
attractive as a takeover target. And the company's depressed stock
does not give it the currency to use to take over another food
giant.
</P>
<P>
   But several analysts said they expected Sara Lee to continue to
move aggressively in acquiring smaller companies. In the last year,
Sara Lee acquired Chock Full o' Nuts, the the nation's
fourth-largest coffee roaster.
</P>
<P>
   Now, analysts say, there are rumors Sara Lee could target
Flowers Industries or the Dial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sara Lee is reorganizing itself into three
units: food and beverages, intimates and underwear and household
products. The company previously had five units.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McMillan, at a news conference Tuesday in New York, said the
company would retain its long tradition of operating as a
decentralized company but that he would begin to push the company
into a slightly more centralized bent to take advantage of the
company's desire to capitalize on its global scale.
</P>
<P>
   The company chose to divest itself of Champion, Coach and the
international fabric units of Courtalds because they did not fit
neatly into the company's strategy, and in some cases they were
tied to the ups and downs of the fashion business.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan said that the company would rather focus on
``inner-wear'' rather than outerwear, which is why Sara Lee
maintains Playtex, Hanes and other apparel.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said Tuesday that it had made investments in
three small companies: Uniao's coffee business, the largest coffee
business in Brazil; Sol Y Oro, a leading intimate apparel business
in Argentina; and a minority interest in the Johnsonville Sausage
Co., one of the largest makers of fresh premium sausages in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   PYA/Monarch, the nation's fourth-largest food service
distributor with about $2.7 billion, also did not fit into the
company's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Tuesday's move is also aimed at reaping value
for divisions that were locked in a company that is largely
undervalued by the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really to unlock value,'' said William Leach, an
analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``Other food companies are
trading at much higher multiples. Sysco is trading at 30 times
earnings and Sara Lee trades at 12 times earnings. If they sold off
all their brands, they'd probably get 25 times earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said that it hoped to take Coach and PYA/Monarch
public by the end of the year, keeping an 80 percent stake in the
companies. Within 18 months, however, the company hopes to sell off
that stake if market conditions are favorable.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan, the incoming chief executive, said the company decided
that a mix of public offerings and outright sales would be most
beneficial to the company. He also said that the company was
motivated by concerns about the stock's weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decisions are frequently made because we are trying to
drive value for our shareholders,'' he said. ``We think we are
substantially undervalued right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
