<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGS-MEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOVELS FOR ALL SEASONS, AND FOR ONE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This being a campaign season, novels with a political spin must
be tolerated. It was ordained, for example, that Joe Klein would go
to the Beltway again in hopes that a book under his own name would
repeat at least some of the success of one by Anonymous. Ah, where
is Bill Clinton when a writer needs him?
</P>
<P>
   One reviewer of the best-selling ``Primary Colors'' drew
attention to the debt that the then-anonymous author owed to ``All
the King's Men,'' Robert Penn Warren's 1946 novel based on the
career of Huey Long, reminding readers of the central emotional
relationship between Long and the narrator, Jack Burden. the
governor's main aide. Although Klein delayed admitting his own role
as writer, he frankly signaled his borrowing: In ``Primary Colors''
(Random House) President Jack Stanton's chief aide and the book's
narrator is Henry Burton.
</P>
<P>
   The Klein novel was credited with perfect pitch in capturing the
players and the spirit of the 1992 campaign. When Klein's identity
was revealed, any reader could recognize the Washington
journalist's know- how in the portraits of George Stephanopoulos,
Mario Cuomo and Gennifer Flowers aka Cashmere McLeod. That was the
novel's strength. But set against its model, it also demonstrated
the limitations of a good book by a good journalist compared with a
smashing book by a very good novelist. For the reader, it was the
difference between admiring a clever reproduction and being knocked
out by the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal sellers swiftly go, but the recent extortion conviction
of the flamboyant Edwin Edwards, sometime governor of Louisiana,
will have served a cultural purpose if it sends readers back to
``All the King's Men.'' In its marriage of political pertinence and
literary distinction, Robert Penn Warren's novel endures where many
other ``topical'' works speedily vanish.
</P>
<P>
   A half-century after its appearance, the combination of Warren's
prose and the character of Willie Stark, his reimagining of Huey
Long, retain their power. In Willie, Warren created not only a
zesty campaigner but a figure who combined earnest populism with
unscrupulous tactics, high-minded aspirations with tough-minded
calculation, an irresistible appeal with appalling cynicism. He is
a big figure, an American original.
</P>
<P>
   The first glimpse of Willie tells a lot about his just-folks
manner and the book's flavor. Stopping off at a soda fountain on
the way to visit his pappy, Willie spies ``a tall, gaunt-shanked,
malarial, leather-faced slice of jerked venison, wearing jean pants
and a brace of mustaches hanging off the kind of face you see in
photographs of General Forrest's cavalrymen.''
</P>
<P>
   Their conversation goes like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``How's your boy?'' Willie asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aint doen so good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sick?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw, jail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, what they doing round here, putting good boys in
jail?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good boy. Hit wuz a fahr faight, but he had a leetle
bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit wuz fahr and squahr, but he had a leetle bad luck. He
stobbed the feller and he died.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tried yet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't complainen. Hit wuz fit fahr and squahr.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Glad to seen you. Tell your boy to keep his tail over the
dashboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Willie directs Jack Burden to get onto the case and scout
out a smart lawyer to help the countryman's son or to put in a
quiet fix. When it comes to a face-off between the law and a good
old boy, Willie is with the fellow with a leetle bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   And when, in an important turn, Willie runs up against a judge
with a reputation for honesty who decides not to endorse Willie's
candidate, the order is to dig up dirt on the judge: ``It's dirt
makes the grass grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppose there isn't anything worth the digging? Jack asks.
Willie, with his Old Testament view of his fellow man, sets him
straight: ``Man is conceived in sin and born in corruption and he
passeth from the stink of the didie to the stench of the shroud.
There is always something.'' ( Klein has one of his characters make
the same point in almost the same words: ``There's always something
there.'')
</P>
<P>
   Something is found; no one doubts that, if pressed, Willie will
use it even if it means the good judge's ruin. Willie is not fond
of the law; it keeps getting in the way of his plans to better the
lives of all the down-and-outers who know that he is on their side
against those who these days are known as special interests.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech, Willie draws Depression-era cheers with promises
that, given a little spiffing, resemble those that today's
candidates still find useful although they may lack Willie's
incantatory locutions: ``And it is your right that every child
shall have a complete education. That no person aged and infirm
shall want or beg for bread. That the man who produces something
shall be able to carry it to market without miring to the hub,
without toll. That no poor man's house or land shall be taxed. That
the rich men and the great companies that draw wealth from this
state shall pay this state a fair share. That you shall not be
deprived of hope!''
</P>
<P>
   Willie means it on the stump, and his audiences believe him. He
is a radical in a jurisdiction where the wealthy and the powerful
are accustomed to reign. He has a tendency toward the dictatorial
but he steers clear of flat-out extortion. Yet he does not allow
squeamishness to get in the way of what he believes needs to be
done; forget the pieties of those who never get their hands dirty
or do anything worth doing.
</P>
<P>
   As for the law, neither Edwards nor Long were sticklers. Willie
shares their unenthusiastic outlook. He calls the law ``a
single-bed blanket on a double bed and three folks in the bed and a
cold night.'' And he goes on: ``There ain't ever enough blanket to
cover the case, no matter how much pulling and hauling, and
somebody is always going to nigh catch pneumonia. Hell, the law is
like the pants you bought last year for a growing boy, but it is
always this year and the seams are popped and the shankbones to the
breeze. The law is always too short and too tight for growing
humankind.''
</P>
<P>
   What Willie understands is that society is bent on doing
business, and if that means winking at the law, that's the way
things are and were and always will be: ``It's just a question of
who has got his front feet in the trough when slopping time
comes.'' The observation doesn't seem to have lost much in the last
50 or 100 years or a lot longer.
</P>
<P>
   When reformers cry ``Graft!'' Willie grants that OK, there may
be a little, just enough to make the wheels turn without squeaking.
He would probably have faulted Edwards for squeaking so noisily
that he compelled the righteous to crack down.
</P>
<P>
   It is unfair to ask that Klein's portrait of Bill Clinton in
``Primary Colors'' should approach Warren's vividly reimagined
portrait of Huey Long. Whatever one's opinion of the president, he
was no Huey Long.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Klein book's popularity, along with being an engaging
read it seems to have benefited both from the hoopla about the
anonymity of the author and from readers' belief that they were
getting the down and dirty goods from the season's Deep Throat.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking that appeal, Klein's second try at a political novel,
``The Running Mate''(Dial Press), has stirred little interest, and
the Clinton-Stephanopoulous doings are yesterday's news. As for
Willie, he endures. His language may be a touch dated, more's the
pity, but the character is as vibrant as ever. Warren wrote a book
for all seasons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SOTHEBYS-AUCTION-NYT &LR;      05-30 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBYS-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S SHAREHOLDER OPPOSES CHAIRMAN'S SON AS BOARD LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The largest outside shareholder in Sotheby's Holdings
says electing the son of the company's former chairman to its board
would represent an inappropriate conflict of interest in the face
of the continuing criminal investigation into price fixing at the
auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's and its rival, Christie's, are the subjects of a
Justice Department investigation into allegations that the
auctioneers fixed commissions charged to buyers and sellers for
several years. Christie's disclosed on Jan. 28 that it had agreed
to cooperate in exchange for leniency, and people involved in the
case said prosecutors were in the late stages of evaluating
possible criminal charges involving Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   A. Alfred Taubman, the wealthy real estate developer who owns a
controlling interest in Sotheby's, resigned as its chairman in
February after Christie's disclosure. Taubman retains voting
control of the company and its board through stock ownership.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Robert, was scheduled to replace Taubman on the board
in April, but the company's annual meeting was postponed at the
last minute after objections by Ronald Baron, whose investment
funds are the largest outside investors in Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Robert Taubman's appointment to be inappropriate at
this time,'' Baron wrote to investors in his funds in a quarterly
report obtained Tuesday. ``We believe Robert Taubman will soon
recognize the enormous conflicts of interest he will face.''
</P>
<P>
   Baron also said other board members were exceptionally close to
Albert Taubman. Baron also complained that he had been assured
several times in recent months that there was no substance to the
federal price-fixing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Baron questioned the independence of Sotheby's board in a filing
with the Securities and Exchange Commission in April, and he has
been negotiating with the company over the makeup of the board.
Baron's funds have invested nearly $500 million in Sotheby's stock,
which has lost about half its value in recent months. But Baron
sought to reassure his investors that Sotheby's long-term prospects
would be strong after the conclusion of the federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sotheby's declined to comment on Baron's remarks
and said that the annual meeting had not been rescheduled. A lawyer
for Albert Taubman also declined to comment, and a spokeswoman for
Robert Taubman, president of Taubman Co., said he would have no
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the criminal inquiry, Sotheby's and Christie's
are subjects of class-action litigation in U.S. District Court in
New York. On Friday, Judge Lewis A. Kaplan, who is presiding over
the case, chose the law firm of Boies, Schiller &AMP; Flexner as lead
counsel in the combined suits.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, best known for its role in the Microsoft Corp.
antitrust suit, was chosen from among 20 that submitted bids to win
the right to lead the effort to win damages from the auction
houses. The judge said his decision was based on the economic terms
of the bids ad the ability of the lead counsel to best serve the
people suing the auctioneers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
