<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0076 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-GEOGRAPHY-GENDER-GAP-     05-30 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEOGRAPHY-GENDER-GAP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S IRKUTSK? ASK A BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATE ZERNIKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten students from across the country gathered as finalists in
the National Geography Bee on a Washington stage last week,
standing alongside ``Jeopardy'' host Alex Trebek and waving at
their parents beaming in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Only one could name two of the three largest sections of Denmark
(Jutland, Sjaelland and Fyn.) But all shared one notable trait, the
same shared by all but two finalists in the 12-year history of the
contest.
</P>
<P>
   And the answer is? They were all boys.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, educators have bemoaned that a large percentage of
Americans cannot locate their own country on a map, much less point
the way to Irkutsk. Geography slipped off school curriculums,
derided as too dependent on rote learning, as educators blended it
into broader social studies classes. Students who learned it tended
to do so at home or on their own time.
</P>
<P>
   But the efforts to emphasize the importance of the subject over
the last few years have highlighted a new problem. With students
left to their own devices, a geography gender gap has become
evident, so wide that with five million students participating in
the bee, boys are 45 times more likely to end up as finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers and educators have bounced back and forth over the
last few years debating whom schools shortchange more: boys (in
reading) or girls (in math and science). But with so much attention
focused on them, those disparities have begun to fade.
</P>
<P>
   Why the geography gap endures, researchers say, has something to
do with the fact that most schools are still not teaching the
subject, and something to do with the toys geared toward boys and
other social influences. But mostly, they say, the gap stems from
cognitive differences that give boys better spatial skills than
girls. The same advantages that help boys in the geography bee make
them, in general, better at navigation and finding their way. And
that, they add, just might explain why men so stubbornly _ some
would say determinedly _ refuse to ask for directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really are some differences biologically, and unless you
can provide different kinds of enrichment in education and what
parents do, you're not going to see this difference go away,'' said
Lynn S. Liben, distinguished professor of psychology at
Pennsylvania State University, a co-author of a study the National
Geographic Society commissioned on why girls do not do as well on
the bee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I have to say this as a woman,'' she said, ``that it's
not true that every woman is worse than every man or every girl is
worse than every boy. But at the group level, it is true. If you
have to bet money, bet the man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Geographic Society started the geography bee a decade ago
out of concern that Americans did not know anything about the
subject. A Gallup survey in 1988 found that 20 percent of Americans
18 to 24 years old could not find the United States on a map
without labels. American students performed the worst among
students of 10 nations when asked to identify regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The problem began, geographers and educators say, in the 1950s,
when schools began absorbing geography and history into one course:
social studies. This was seen as a way to get students thinking
about the broad picture, to analyze rather than just memorize
facts.
</P>
<P>
   After the surveys, the Geographic Society began arguing that
understanding geography is key to understanding other subjects _
the history of wars, the development of cities and regions.
Congress agreed, declaring a National Geography Awareness Week.
</P>
<P>
   The Geographic Society distributed atlases and handbooks on how
to teach geography to every public, private, and parochial school
in the country. In recent years, several companies have developed
computer interactive games to emphasize geography.
</P>
<P>
   These efforts seem to be paying off in some small ways: an
overwhelming proportion of students rate geography as the least or
second-least favorite subject, but the fraction of those who say it
is their favorite has risen to 14 percent, from 8 percent in 1983;
74 percent of American teachers have taken a college course in
geography, up from 59 percent in 1983. And the College Board now
offers an advanced placement exam in the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Still, teaching of geography is haphazard, and most students who
learn it study it out of interest, not because a teacher asks them
to. Notably, 4 out of 10 finalists in this year's bee were schooled
at home. The year's winner, 13-year-old Felix Peng from Guilford,
Conn., learned at home as a toddler, as his father would point to
Taiwan, his birthplace, then spin the globe and have Felix find it
again. As Felix grew, his father added more and more countries to
the game.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, the Geographic Society had a new concern. Worried about
the dearth of girls not just in the finals but in the entrance
round of the contests in schools, it commissioned a study by Liben
and Roger M. Downs, a geography professor, also at Pennsylvania
State. The society was worried that it might be asking questions in
a way biased against girls.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that was not the case. Rather, they said,
the gap results from a combination of factors, the most significant
being the difference in spatial skills between boys and girls.
Research on cognition, Liben said, shows that boys tend have higher
mental rotation skills, allowing them to better imagine what things
look like reversed or upside down. This helps them interpret maps _
as well as the diagrams that accompany allegedly easy-to-assemble
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Young, a finalist from Reston, Va., learned his geography
by studying a map on a shower curtain, requiring him to recognize
his Mozambiques and Madagascars backward.
</P>
<P>
   Women turn the maps and diagrams around to figure out where they
are, Liben said, or simply ask for directions, while men will
struggle through the mental rotation. (``Whether you view that as a
negative or positive, as you're stubborn or trying to be macho,
depends on whether you're a man or a woman,'' she adds.)
</P>
<P>
   This cognitive difference, though, was exacerbated by social
factors, the researchers said. Boys, for instance, tend to play
with blocks and mechanical toys.
</P>
<P>
   And teachers notice what the study said: that girls simply do
not gravitate toward maps and geography.
</P>
<P>
   In Guilford, Felix's teacher, Louis Russo, started a
before-school geography club. No girls showed up. ``I always
encourage the girls to get involved, I don't want them to think
it's an all-male situation,'' he said. ``But they just don't pick
up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The interest starts young. ``The boys just seem to naturally
take to it,'' said Howard S. Becker, a social studies teacher in
Yorktown Heights, N.Y., and a coordinator of the state's geography
bee. ``Whenever I ask them, `How long have you been doing this?'
they say, `Since I was 3 or 4, I've always had an interest in
looking at atlases and maps. I've never seen one girl who says
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Girls are more likely to end up on the honor roll or do well in
school, teachers say. But unless the school or the teacher focuses
explicitly on geography, they are not likely to become interested
in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls at this stage are much more interested in the big
picture; they tend to explore areas that don't lend themselves to
this much detail,'' said Linda Ague, the librarian at the Cal Young
Middle School in Eugene, Ore., who coached Alex King, 13, to the
finals last week. ``Geography tends to be get blended into a block
curriculum; we don't have a geography textbook in the whole
building. For kids who think in that generalized, big picture way,
the geography stays just a piece of it. The boys tend to gravitate
to the detail, to the map part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liben and Downs study found that the girls who ended up in
the higher rounds of the Geography Bee were more likely to come
from smaller states or territories, where there is less
competition. This year, the two girls in the semifinals were from
Puerto Rico and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Friend, the entry from Barton, Vt., says her secret is
reading, especially newspapers, and looking up any place she
doesn't know. ``I like to find out about things that are happening
and where they are happening,'' she said. ``Not many of my girl
friends do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessie is an excellent all-around student. An aspiring doctor,
she wrote in her Geography Bee biography that she admires Marie
Curie, Amelia Earhart, and Susan B. Anthony, ``because they proved
that women could succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe they would have known that Irkutsk is a city in
Russia. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
