<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHAIR31-COX     05-30 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHAIR31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No verdict in kidnapping case
 &HT;    By Andrea Ball
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A federal jury did not reach a verdict Tuesday
during the first day of deliberations in the Madalyn O'Hair
kidnapping case. Jurors will return to court today.
</P>
<P>
   In the third week of the high-profile case, the eight-man,
four-woman jury spent almost seven hours weighing the evidence in
the trial of Gary Paul Karr, 52, who is accused of kidnapping
atheist leader O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and granddaughter
Robin Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations will continue at 8:30 a.m. in the Austin federal
courthouse. If convicted by a unanimous jury vote, Karr faces life
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it for money,'' prosecutor Gerald Carruth told jurors
in closing arguments. ``He did it because he was greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say David Roland Waters, the O'Hairs' former office
manager, recruited Karr and Florida friend Danny Fry in 1995 to
hold the family hostage and steal $500,000 in gold coins. The
O'Hairs were later murdered, dismembered in an Austin storage unit
and buried in a Camp Wood ranch, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Fry was found dead on a Dallas County riverbank just days after
the O'Hairs disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   During the past few weeks, prosecutors have built a
circumstantial case without bodies, eyewitnesses or concrete
physical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Hairs remain missing. No one reported seeing the family
kidnapped or murdered. Blood found inside the storage unit rented
by the alleged kidnappers could not be linked conclusively to the
O'Hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, prosecutors connected Karr to the atheist leaders
though an extensive paper trail including credit card, telephone
and van rental records. Witnesses connected Karr to Waters,
ringleader of the alleged plot.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Tom Mills called the circumstantial case weak
and attacked prosecutors' theory that the kidnappers disposed of
all the physical evidence by washing away the blood with a
beach-filled spray bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have 15 quarts of blood and some guy's going
to come in with some goofy insect sprayer and make it so there's no
blood?'' Mills said. ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills contends that Karr was hired by Waters to help the O'Hairs
flee the country to escape federal tax. If the O'Hairs were
murdered _ and the defense won't concede they were _ Karr was not
involved, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors, who began deliberating at 11:30 a.m. and stopped at 6
p.m., have not been sequestered.
</P>
<P>
   Their task could be arduous. The jury must consider hundreds of
documents, testimony from more than 70 witnesses, and a 10-page
statement in which Karr told police that Waters killed the O'Hairs.
</P>
<P>
   They must also decide whether a conspiracy existed and, if so,
whether Karr participated in it.
</P>
<P>
   For Karr to be found guilty of kidnapping, the jury must agree
that he conspired with others to kidnap the O'Hairs, that he held
them for financial gain, and that he forced Jon Garth Murray to do
business in another state.
</P>
<P>
   The jury must also determine Karr's guilt or innocence on four
other charges: conspiracy to interfere with commerce by robbery and
extortion, interstate travel in aid of racketeering enterprise,
conspiracy to engage in monetary transaction in criminally derived
property, and interstate transportation of stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   The jury will vote on each charge separately.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers awaited the verdict in the federal courthouse
Tuesday, while federal prosecutors retreated to their Congress
Avenue offices. Neither side was surprised at the jury's lengthy
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're just doing their job conscientiously,'' Mills
said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea ball at aball(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
