</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: COMPANY COMBINES OFFICE SPACE, INTERNET AT
AIRPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Duplication warning: also moving in `t' category) By JOE
SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Brilliant, one hand wrapped around a cold can of Coke on
his desk at SoftNet Systems Inc., was describing a way of life that
most people might regard as road torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people traveling on business all the time, working
like maniacs, an average of 2.4 separate visits each week to an
airport, where they spend an average of two hours each trip,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I see this as cause to notify Amnesty International, but
Brilliant, a physician who got into the computer world as an early
investor in Apple Computer, sees it as his major market. These
potential customers, he said, are the creme de la creme among the
estimated 30 million business travelers around the world who belong
to a group that fits his description of ``They're
price-insensitive, time-sensitive, and on the road constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Brilliant is the chairman and chief executive of SoftNet, whose
businesses include providing broadband Internet technology for
cable systems. Recently, SoftNet, with partners that include Nokia,
Compaq Computer and Cisco Systems, sank $100 million into a
subsidiary, SoftNet Zone, which is planning in the fall to start a
system of local area wireless networks in airports, hotels and
convention centers that will provide high-speed Internet service
and e-mail access for business travelers on the move.
</P>
<P>
   As a part of that initiative, SoftNet and Delta Air Lines last
month announced a deal to set up centers for Delta customers to
access the Internet, as well as their corporate intranets and
e-mail systems. Delta plans to begin this service later this year,
starting at its hub airports in Atlanta, Cincinnati, Salt Lake City
and Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived recently at Softnet's headquarters in San Francisco's
booming dot-com district through a circuitous route. Back in
February, on a layover at the Tampa International Airport in
Florida, I had spent a productive hour working at a storefront
business center called Laptop Lane, which rents private office
cubicles with desks, phones and computers offering high-speed
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   This struck me as a spectacular innovation, being able to rent a
private office _ I paid $2 for the first 5 minutes and 38 cents for
each additional minute _ in a place as invincibly dismal as an
airport. The parent company, Laptop Lane Ltd., had said it would
open locations in 80 airports worldwide within two years.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time I got home and called Laptop Lane, the company
had been acquired by Brilliant's SoftNet for $45 million.
Brilliant, and backers like Nokia, it turned out, had an even more
ambitious idea: Use Laptop Lane's hard-won airport real estate as a
base for SoftNet's plan to sell wireless and fixed-line high-speed
Internet connections to business travelers. Until Laptop Lane
entered the picture, SoftNet had been considering that hotels would
be the main anchor for its local-network Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Brilliant said that he visited his first Laptop Lane only about
10 months ago, and began to see the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stranded at O'Hare and I bumped into this Laptop Lane,''
he recalled. ``Man, I was hooked. This was my own room. I was
paying for it. I made a conference call and took my shoes off.'' He
added that as a business traveler he belonged to all of the major
airline premium clubs, but ``in those clubs, you're never that
comfortable working; you always feel like the person behind you is
waiting for you to get out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Laptop Lane was limited by physical space, even as
its locations increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Atlanta airport, 250,000 people circulate every day,
and about 80,000 of those are the people Larry is talking about as
potential customers,'' said R. Bruce Merrell, the founder and chief
executive of Laptop Lane, who was in Brilliant's office when we
talked. ``We have three locations in Atlanta, but they can only
accommodate 400 people at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting to me about SoftNet's plan, beyond its
world-view audacity, is the practical combination of high-flying
technology with the most down-to-earth business concept of all,
real estate.
</P>
<P>
   In airports, Laptop Lane locations will do double duty as
customer-service centers for Softnet Zone customers going online at
the gate or ``anywhere else you want, including the shoe-shine
stand and the bathroom,'' Brilliant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical to have human beings nearby, because things will
go wrong with your computer,'' he said. ``They will have
technicians who can find you immediately and get you online.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrell said the idea of linking up with an Internet provider
that someday expects to sell wireless access directly on airplanes
in flight hadn't dampened the enthusiasm for the physical real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to have Laptop Lanes in the top 60 United States
airports and the top 30 international airports within a five-year
period,'' he said. ``Since we went in with Softnet, in fact, it's
been raining airports.''
</P>
<P>
   Brilliant, meanwhile, suggested that Merrell's original business
plan would probably have led the company to expand its businesses
through local area networks providing Internet access anywhere in
an airport, not just in the limited space of the storefront
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they probably could have done this on their own,
Brilliant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, thanks Larry,'' Merrell replied, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Provided they had the money,'' Brilliant added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
