<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0086 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-VOLS-COX     05-30 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charges of academic abuses could
 &HT;    still make big trouble for Big Orange
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knoxville _ A year ago, no college football fans were more
upbeat than the University of Tennessee's. And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols were coming off two SEC championships in a row and
their first national title since 1951. From Knoxville to Memphis,
Tennessee's faithful were convinced that they finally had broken
Florida's stranglehold on the conference and were headed for a
lengthy reign.
</P>
<P>
   But now Big Orange Country is slightly uneasy. No one is
panicking, but subtle signs point to what could be difficult times
ahead for a football program that won 99 games in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   _ After going 9-3 last season, Tennessee's talent base was hit
hard by the NFL draft. Of the nine starters taken, five were
juniors. As a result, many of the early polls are picking Tennessee
to finish behind Florida and Georgia in the SEC East this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another projected starter, center Greg Barnum, shocked coaches
after spring practice when he suddenly left school and returned to
his native Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sophomore running back Onterrio Smith, a future star, was
dismissed from the team earlier this month for several violations
of team rules.
</P>
<P>
   Because Tennessee has recruited at a high level since Phillip
Fulmer became head coach in 1993, the effects of those personnel
losses should not last long. But a threat looms on the Big Orange
horizon that could have a more profound effect on the football
program for years to come
</P>
<P>
   Since September, Tennessee's football program has dealt with
charges of academic abuses in its tutorial system, which is run by
the athletics department. Among the charges by Linda Bensel-Meyers,
a tenured English professor, is that Tennessee's academic support
system for athletes conspired with members of the UT faculty to
steer athletes to easy courses in order to keep them eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers also charges that some tutors have written papers
for athletes and that athletes at Tennessee receive an unusually
large number of grade changes, when compared with the rest of the
student body.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bensel-Meyers charges, some athletes leave
Tennessee without meaningful degrees and are unable to make a
living if they don't succeed in professional athletics. She says
Tennessee is selling a dream that, for the vast majority of the
athletes, will never come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletes aren't fully aware, when they first come in, how
mythic the dream of going to the pros really is,'' Bensel-Meyers
said. ``We perpetuate that myth in the athletic department, and
that's dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee officials, from president J. Wade Gilley to football
coach Phillip Fulmer, have strongly denied these charges. Some,
like athletics director Doug Dickey, have gone on the offensive to
defend the school's image.
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable people can disagree about how athletes receive
tutorial assistance and suggest changes to make the system better,
said Dickey. But, he emphasized, there is no conspiracy to keep
athletes eligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to violate academic integrity to be
successful,'' Dickey said. ``But if anybody wants to suggest
changes that will strengthen our program and make people feel
better about it, we will be happy to work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges went public Sept. 26 on ESPN.com. Tennessee
conducted an internal investigation into the charges and found no
violations of NCAA rules. That report was forwarded to the NCAA,
which in March said the matter was closed.
</P>
<P>
   But in April, Bensel-Meyers released her report on the academic
performances of 39 UT athletes 24 football players, 13 basketball
players and two others. The performances showed, in her opinion, a
consistent pattern of academic abuses. Among her charges where that
the athletes received a total of 105 grade changes.
</P>
<P>
   The records were turned over to Gilley and are in the process of
being studied by a subcommittee of the university's faculty senate.
</P>
<P>
   Other Tennessee officials, after looking at the same records,
are beginning to disagree publicly with some of the conclusions
drawn by Bensel-Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   One charge by Bensel-Meyers was that 18 of the 39 athletes in
question had not declared a major by the beginning of their junior
season, which is required by the NCAA's satisfactory-progess rules.
A check of those records by the registrar's office, however, showed
that 38 of the 39 had declared majors by their junior year and that
the other athlete had left school early.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee athletic officials also disagreed with the alleged 105
grade changes, saying that 41 were incompletes granted and that
only 11 were actually one grade changed to another grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to find out now is why there are two different
stories,'' said Burton English, a professor of agriculture and
chairman of the athletics committee of the faculty senate.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next?
</P>
<P>
   The athletic committee of the faculty senate already has called
for more faculty oversight into the tutorial program for athletes.
The subcommitte charged with studying Bensel-Meyers' records might
make even more recommendations when it finishes its study, which is
expected to take all summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers says that she thinks the entire tutorial and
academic-assistance program for athletes should be moved out of the
athletic department and placed under the academic umbrella. The
primary interest of Tennessee athletics, she says, is financial,
which means keeping the athlete eligible at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey disagrees, saying that athletes, given the extraordinary
time demands they face, need an advocate as they attempt to
navigate some of the rough waters of college academics. ``There
will be some structural changes,'' English said. ``Whether tutoring
will be brought out of athletics or not, I don't know. But there
will be additional faculty oversight, I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   After giving the university a clean bill of health in March, the
NCAA now says it will return to Tennessee later to study the
records to determine whether it violated rules.
</P>
<P>
   But to focus solely on whether Tennessee violated NCAA rules is
to miss the point, Bensel-Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've created a very effective system of not violating NCAA
rules but violating academic integrity,'' Bensel-Meyers said. ``We
use these kids up, make as much money as we can off of them, and,
when they're done, we kick them down the hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer, the coach since 1993, strongly disagrees. He points to
the fact that the American Football Coaches Association cited the
school for its high graduation rate three of the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm proud of my degree at the Univeristy of Tennessee,
and lots and lots of people are,'' said Fulmer, a former Volunteer
player who graduated in 1972. ``And we're no different than the
people at Georgia, Kentucky, and Florida. It's a fine institution,
and we've done quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision will rest with Gilley, who has been on the job for
less than a year. Gilley is caught between loyalty to his faculty
and to the 107,000 fans and alumni who pack Neyland Stadium for
football games on Saturdays in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gilley insists that it is not an either/or situation. ``We're
going to take every charge seriously, and we will make sure to
protect the integrity of the institution,'' he said. ``If you do
things in the right way, in the long run it will pay dividends. And
we're going to do things in the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's fans appear to feel comfortable with the situation,
for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans who call us feel there have been no NCAA violations,
so their anxiety level is not as high,'' said Jimmy Hyams, who
hosts a daily sports-talk show on WNOX in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the NCAA finds no violations, people here think the way
Tennessee tutors its athletes.
</P>
<P>
   With the publicity given the case, the athletics department will
have to change the way it does business. And any big change will
become part of the recruiting process. Recruiting at this level is
cut-throat, and rival schools will take any advantage.
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee significantly tightens down academically on
athletes, even if those changes appear to be reasonable, recruiters
from opposing schools will use that information against the
Volunteer program. ``The issue is about college football,'' Fulmer
said, ``and, typically, whether it be recruiting or budgets or
admission standards or whatever, we're typically not going to put
ourselves at a disadvantage with Florida and Georgia, and Alabama
and Auburn, and LSU and others. I'm sure all of that will be
weighed as we go through.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to the football program say that Tennessee can
overcome the problems. But the highest levels of college football
already contain enough obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
