<SLUG> BC-GLF-NCAA-PRVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech, Georgia swing for a title
 &HT;    By Stan Awtrey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Georgia and Georgia Tech golf teams are expected to have
leading roles when the NCAA Championships begin today in Opelika,
Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is the defending national champion, and Georgia Tech is
the No. 1 seed for the 72-hole event on the Lake Course at the
Grand National Golf Complex.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia State is making its first trip to the NCAA Tournament.
The Panthers are seeded 20th but tied Georgia for fifth place in
the East Regional in Moosic, Pa. Georgia State's top players have
been D.J. Fiese and Jack Croyle.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Georgia came from five shots behind on the final day
to beat Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about us winning by three shots last year,''
Bulldogs coach Chris Haack said. ``Out of almost 1,200 shots, you
can always think of three that got away from you, and that's where
the breaks factor in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a four-day grind that takes a lot of focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is the No. 4 seed in the tournament. The Bulldogs are
led by Michael Morrison, who shot a 1-under 212 to earn medalist
honors in the East Regional, and by Erik Compton, who holds the
school's tournament scoring record.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech earned the tournament's No. 1 seed, despite placing
third in the East Regional. The Yellow Jackets missed the cut in
the nationals last year after finishing third in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really not tried to focus on what went wrong,'' Tech
coach Bruce Heppler said. ``We've moved on and are getting ready to
do our best again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech is led by junior Bryce Molder and senior Matt Kuchar.
Molder is a two-time ACC Player of the Year and is ranked as the
No. 1 collegiate player by Golfweek. Kuchar, a former U.S. Amateur
champion, leads the team with a 70.63 stroke average.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal always has been to help bring Georgia Tech a national
championship,'' Kuchar said.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are familiar with the course. They played at the
Ping/Golfweek Preview Invitational at Grand National in the fall.
Georgia Tech finished fourth and Georgia fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson, which won the East Regional, is the No. 2 seed. The
Tigers are led by John Engler, Jonathan Byrd and Lucas Glover, who
all tied for fourth in the regional.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State, the No. 3 seed, was third in the Central
Regional in Victoria, Texas. Among the Cowboys' top players is
Charles Howell of Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
