<SLUG> BC-BKW-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS HOPE THEIR TIME HAS COME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ With the fourth WNBA season under way, the
Sparks have made it clear that their aim is to move one step
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks came within one victory of advancing to the
championship series last season when they extended eventual
champion Houston Comets to the decisive third game in the Western
Conference finals. Now that they've tasted postseason victory, they
are hungry for more.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks have a new general manager in former teammate Penny
Toler, a new coach in former Laker Michael Cooper, and a new, more
assertive attitude this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that now is our time,'' forward DeLisha Milton said.
``We can't sit around and wait for opportunities to come to us, we
have to kick the doors down, go in head-first and demand whatever
we want through us earning respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks, who open the 2000 season at the Forum tonight at
7:30 against Utah, finished last season with their first winning
record at 20-12 and made their first post-season appearance. They
defeated Sacramento in a one-game playoff, and took the first of
three games against the Comets, who went on to win their third WNBA
title.
</P>
<P>
   Until some team shows otherwise, Houston is still in command of
the league, as was evident of its 84-68 victory over New York in a
rematch of last year's finals.
</P>
<P>
   But it is widely discussed that the strength of the league lies
in the West and there are several capable teams that could shake
the Comets foundation. The Sparks are one, Sacramento with 1999
Most Valuable Player and Defensive Player of the Year Yolanda
Griffith is another. Utah, which has a front court that towers over
the rest of the league, has as good a chance as any team,
especially if point guard Jennifer Azzi returns healthy after
undergoing hand surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper feels the Sparks defensive shortcomings last season
prevented them from going all the way. But that won't be an excuse
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the staples that separates Houston from the
rest of the league and right now,'' said Cooper, who was the NBA
Defensive Player of the Year in 1987 and was a five-time
all-defensive first team member. ``Obviously, there are more teams
that can match with Houston, such as ourselves, Sacramento, Utah
and Phoenix. But the difference between us and them is defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Milton (9.9 points, 5.5 rebounds) along with 6-5 Lisa Leslie
(15.6 ppg, 7.8 rpg) and swing Mwadi Mabika (10.8 ppg, 4.8 rpg)
return to their starting roles as the team's leaders in scoring and
rebounding. Mabika led the team is assists with 3.8 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Ukari Figgs, who started the first 10 games last season before
spraining her ankle, is back to start at the point, and so is
shooting guard Tamecka Dixon (6.8 ppg), who started 14 of 32 games
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks should be strong off the bench with two versatile
players in 6-3 LaKeisha Frett, who started 18 games last season,
and 6-2 Vedrana Grgin, a Croatian native who joined the team Friday
after leading her Brazilian team to the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper isn't worried about Grgin's late start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard for teams to matchup with us,'' he said.
``She's already picked up what we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Paige Sauer, a 6-4 center from Connecticut and second-round
draft pick, and 6-5 Clarisse Machanguana is expected to pick up the
slack for Leslie, Allison Feaster is another option at the small
forward spot, and Nikki McCrimmon is the backup point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to take off where we pretty much left off,''
Leslie said. ``We feel very strong and confident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
