<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-CLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS: SCHOOL ISSUES WARRANT VOTERS' ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By HUBERT B. HERRING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Education is the ultimate apple-pie issue: To vote against it is
to be branded anti-child and un-American. Ask any group of
suburbanites to say yea or nay to the proposition ``Should we do
the best for our children?'' and the vote will surely be unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   But it is, alas, never that simple, as I discovered recently
when the town where I live _ Dobbs Ferry, just up the Hudson from
Manhattan _ voted on a bond issue to expand and upgrade the
schools.
</P>
<P>
   My neighbors' opinions, often adamant, were all over the map.
Many people rallied around the bond, but many others found fault.
It cost too much. The construction estimates were inflated. The
planning process was flawed. We hired the wrong architect. The
students' needs were not being met. In the end, the doubters
prevailed, and the bond failed.
</P>
<P>
   So, does that mean Dobbs Ferry is anti-education? Not at all.
There were legitimate concerns about the process, especially since
another bond had passed two years earlier but construction had
never started. Now the district was asking for more, and many
people were puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   The stated reasons for hitting us twice included rising
construction costs and necessary changes, but to a casual observer
there was no real way to know if that was the truth or if the
project, which included a much-needed gym and new classrooms for a
growing student population, had been bungled.
</P>
<P>
   And that is precisely the problem: Most voters on a small-town
school bond will, of necessity, be casual observers. Those of us
who are neither architects nor construction managers _ and lack the
time for a crash course in such matters _ have little choice but to
put our faith in the school board we elected, and the
superintendent that board has chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I could be better informed. But I have a job, plus two
teen-agers. That combination puts a dent in my day. And many people
are in a similar position.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, of course, took the time to study the issue
closely, but their conclusions varied widely. At least one couple
split, with the husband voting no, the wife yes. One architect said
that it was a good plan, while another said that it was a disaster
from the start _ that if we had hired the architect he had
recommended, the school addition would be built by now. Who do you
believe?
</P>
<P>
   I chose to put my faith in the school board and backed the bond.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I was wrong. Most people know little of school board
candidates when they cast their votes. We read reams of details,
intimate and otherwise, about national politicians, but no
investigative reporters swoop in to delve into the qualifications
of school board candidates. It usually comes down to ``He seems
like a decent person'' or ``Her credentials look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong, we've got a good school board. But they are
volunteers, often squeezing this work into busy lives; there's only
so much energy they can devote to school issues. Even in the best
of circumstances, there will be a certain haphazard quality to the
whole business, not just in Dobbs Ferry, but in any small town.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent and assistant superintendent are, of course,
paid to focus on these issues, but that's a big burden for two
people who must also deal with all sorts of other district issues.
An added complication in Dobbs Ferry is that we just got a new
superintendent during winter. The construction bond was a lot to
throw at someone new, though to the superintendent's credit, he
seems to have hit the hallways running.
</P>
<P>
   And voters, no matter how objective they try to be, no matter
how much they say, ``I want to do what's best for the district,''
will find their own interests sneaking in. I, for instance, cannot
help wondering whether the new gym will be ready for my son, a
junior, and how the changes will affect my daughter, a
seventh-grader. Those with younger children, no doubt, scrutinize
the plans for the elementary school more closely.
</P>
<P>
   Those without children face a different choice. They could
easily vote down every proposal to spend extra money on the
schools, trying to keep their taxes as low as possible, but those
who take the long view realize that quality schools are part of
what keeps property values high in many suburbs. They cannot
jeopardize that.
</P>
<P>
   But the childless are unlikely to scrutinize the process as
closely as parents do. In the recent vote, I'm sure many of them
said, ``Now they want more money? After we just voted $22 million?
Forget it!''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a relative handful of people decided the issue. In a
town of about 10,000, only about 1,400 people voted, rejecting the
bond by 100 or so votes.
</P>
<P>
   For me, this is what it adds up to: Even after focusing a fair
amount, it is frustrating to have so little understanding of an
issue that will surely have as much, if not more, impact on my
family than the actions of the national politicians we hear about
ad nauseam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
