<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RENEWS HIS EMPHASIS ON EUROPEAN PARTNERSHIP 
 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ It took President Clinton a year into his
first term to visit Europe, and continental leaders weren't sure
what to expect. As a candidate, Clinton belittled the international
interests of the man he defeated to win the White House, and his
early months in office were consumed by domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But when Clinton finally got to Brussels, Belgium, in January
1994, he set out an expansive agenda, calling for the United States
and Europe ``to revitalize our partnership,'' arguably the
strongest intercontinental alliance in history. With the Cold War
ended, Clinton said, ``we must build a new security for Europe,''
based on integration of security forces, market economies and
national democracies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, six years later, on Clinton's 21st presidential journey to
Europe, the White House contends the American president has made
good on his promise without sacrificing the United States' strong
influence on European security and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made significant progress,'' said Sandy Berger,
Clinton's national security adviser. ``The U.S. has supported a
stronger Europe as a complement to, not a competitor of, a stronger
transatlantic alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on Europe is accentuated in Wednesday's session
between Clinton and leaders of the European Union, the 14th such
U.S.-E.U. summit of his presidency. Clinton meets with Portuguese
Prime Minister Antonio Gutteres, who holds the revolving presidency
of the E.U. Council of Ministers, and Romano Prodi, the former
Italian prime minister who is president of the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official warned against
expecting any breakthroughs on more difficult, long-running
U.S.-E.U. disputes such as the European resistance to Latin
American bananas grown by U.S. companies and U.S. beef raised with
hormones. Washington has reacted by slapping tariffs on some luxury
goods and banning others.
</P>
<P>
   Such controversies ``are certainly not trivial,'' Berger said,
``but it's not surprising, I think, given the volume of our trade.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-E.U. trade grew seven-fold between 1994 and 1998, Berger
said, and now stands at almost $400 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Agreement among the leaders is more likely on efforts to fight
infectious diseases, especially HIV-AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a solemn responsibility to take the benefits of the
information economy, of the explosion in biomedical discoveries,
and to use them to give every young person in the world the chance
to live up to their God-given potential,'' Clinton said in a speech
Tuesday at a science museum in Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's approach to Europe gets generally good marks from
continental observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole, the Clinton presidency has been perceived in a
favorable light,'' said Dirk Berg-Schlosser, a political scientist
at Philipps University in Marburg, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But there are problems beyond the trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Berg-Schlosser said Europeans are uniformly distressed by
Clinton attempts to sell Russia on amendments to the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty to accommodate the United States'
prospective national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Guterres, in a meeting with Clinton, relayed objections to the
missile shield from a recent meeting with Russian President
Vladimir Putin. The controversy is expected to highlight a
Clinton-Putin meeting in Moscow this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in Lisbon early Tuesday after an overnight
flight from Washington. He was greeted by President Jorge Sampiao
at a monument beside the Tagus River that commemorates the role of
Portuguese navigators, including Vasco de Gama, in exploring the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The central portion of Clinton's day was taken up in meetings
with Sampaio and Guterres, both part of Portugal's Socialist ruling
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton was in office a year before visiting Europe, he
has made up for any lost time. Clinton, by now the most traveled
president, has ranged widely across the continent in his 21 trips,
from Ireland in the west to Russia in the east, from Finland in the
north to Turkey in the south.
</P>
<P>
   From Portugal, where Clinton is the first U.S. president to
visit since President Reagan in 1985, he is to fly on to Germany,
Russia and Ukraine during his week-long tour.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced that Clinton will hold a separate
meeting in Berlin on Thursday with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel, who canceled a trip to Washington recently because of
renewed fighting in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said that Clinton and Barak
believe it is important to further discuss prospects for an
Israeli-Palestinian framework agreement, especially in light of
Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Barak will be in the German capital to participate
in a meeting on governing in the information age and global
economy.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
