<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0094 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MASUR-REPLACEMENT-ART     05-30 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASUR-REPLACEMENT-ART-925&AMP;ADD-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO DARES CALL THIS MAESTRO A LAME DUCK? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 4) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kurt Masur and the New York Philharmonic ended
another season at Avery Fisher Hall June 3 with Mahler's Ninth
Symphony, one of the great valedictory works in the symphonic
repertory. And indeed, goodbyes might seem to be in order, as talk
in musical circles centers increasingly on who will replace Masur
as the orchestra's music director.
</P>
<P>
   Philharmonic representatives traveled to Milan recently to talk
terms with Riccardo Muti, and other candidates are said to be
waiting in the wings. But often lost in the seeming confusion of
the last year or so has been the fact that whoever is selected, the
72-year-old Masur, who has done so much to restore the orchestra to
a lofty international standard of performance since taking it over
in 1991, is to remain in place for two more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   This imposing and politically savvy maestro, who played a
significant role in the downfall of the East German regime, is
surely no one's idea of a lame duck, and few have ever found it
wise to underestimate his determination, staying power or
resilience. Yet his ebullience seems to have faded a bit during
years of battles with the Philharmonic management.
</P>
<P>
   To a visitor who had not spoken to him at length for years, he
seemed subdued in a conversation in his Avery Fisher Hall studio
the other day, as he reflected on his achievements in New York and
discussed the future. This year he also becomes the principal
conductor of the London Philharmonic, and in 2002, he exchanges one
music directorship for another, taking over the Orchestre National
de France in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major point for me is still the New York Philharmonic,
because I don't want to leave as someone who says, `I'll say
goodbye poco a poco, diminuendo,''' Masur said, giving a musical
twist to the fate of MacArthur's old soldiers. ``This I never can
do, because we are too close together. The players are expecting
that I will fight till the last day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fight with them as well as for them, one suspects, given the
tempestuous nature of some of Masur's rehearsals over the years,
especially the early ones. His tone of voice made clear that he
does not intend to disappoint them.
</P>
<P>
   Justifiably, Masur, whose annual salary is about $1.3 million,
takes great satisfaction in the orchestra's improvement over the
last decade. What Zubin Mehta left behind was a group loaded with
talent, largely because of his many superb hires, but seemingly
bereft of morale. Although Masur has hired wonderful players
himself, including Carter Brey as principal cellist and Sheryl
Staples as associate concertmaster, his greatest feat may have been
to instill the needed spirit, pride and sense of discipline among
the players.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, this was not a one-time feat but something that had
to be maintained, as became apparent when the orchestra repeatedly
lapsed into old bad habits under lenient guest conductors; it still
does so on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would like to leave behind is this kind of feeling
responsible,'' Masur said, ``this kind of pride to be a member of
the New York Philharmonic, to be a member of one of the leading
orchestras of the world, as it is now without a doubt, so that the
ups and downs are not so dependent on the music director or the
director or the board or the money they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my goals exactly when I came, and it was not easy with
the orchestra at the beginning. But as they learned that I was open
to them, they started to trust me. We have grown together, and this
is the most wonderful thing I have achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, his greatest satisfaction may have led to his
greatest disappointment. ``It disturbed some people,'' Masur said.
``I was criticized for being too close to the orchestra. Where else
should I be as a conductor? My disappointments are not in any
direction toward the orchestra. Absolutely not. My disappointment
is that it was possible that with a change of chairman of the
board, the whole politics of the Philharmonic turned around 180
degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   This was as close as Masur came to naming names. Stephen Stamas,
who had been the chairman of the orchestra since 1989, was replaced
by the present chairman, Paul B. Guenther, in 1996. Deborah Borda
was then the executive director of the Philharmonic, having arrived
shortly after Masur in 1991; she left last December to become
managing director of the Los Angeles Philharmonic. The resulting
vacancy has just been filled by Zarin Mehta, the executive director
of the Ravinia Festival and Zubin Mehta's younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   Masur's relationship with Philharmonic management through the
years has been at least as stormy as his relationship with the
players ever was. The final battle became public in early 1998,
when the board refused to extend his contract the usual three
seasons ahead. It was agreed that Masur would stay until 2002 but
that a search for a successor would begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a raw deal with some people,'' Masur said. ``Decisions
were made by three or four people.'' Masur's view that he got a raw
deal is widely shared among players as well as the public. Not that
he finds much comfort in such support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that this is a free country, and a lot of people
don't feel free,'' he said. ``They come to me and say, `I'm so
sorry about what happened, but I have no power.' Maybe they should
have gone through the school we went through in East Germany. You
had no power, but you had to be brave. And it makes you proud if
you always try to say what you think and to say what you believe is
useful.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the very least, the timing of the board's action was awkward,
for Masur had resigned his longtime position as Kapellmeister of
the Leipzig Gewandhaus Orchestra just a year before, ostensibly to
devote himself more fully to New York. The conductorial world was
not rich in obvious candidates to succeed him, and the Philharmonic
did not seem to have anyone particular in mind: certainly no one,
it may be said two years later, whom it could pin down quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever will happen to the Philharmonic was, in my opinion,
not planned very carefully,'' Masur said. ``I was ready to stay
longer. I was ready to go earlier if we found the right person,
just to keep things going as they should go. And at the moment we
are a little bit between two chairs, as we say in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wonderful achievement of the board that we have a lot
of money. We can do nearly everything, and we can do everything in
an artistic way. On the other hand, it could have been a closer,
more open cooperation. This is my only disappointment, that I found
some people who are simply not honest, only looking for their
interests, their power.''
</P>
<P>
   Guenther, for his part, said, ``If you look at the history of
the New York Philharmonic, we have had very few music directors who
have served much longer than a decade.'' Zubin Mehta, at 13 years,
served the longest tenure in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is that for a dynamic institution like the
Philharmonic, change is often necessary, and this was one of those
times,'' Guenther continued guardedly. ``Kurt Masur has done a
spectacular job.''
</P>
<P>
   Philharmonic administrators have also expressed dissatisfaction
with perceived limitations in Masur's repertory, which leans
heavily toward the Germanic.
</P>
<P>
   So what remains for Masur to accomplish?
</P>
<P>
   He has evidently given up one of his cherished goals: to see a
pipe organ installed in Avery Fisher Hall. Although such an option
exists in current planning for renovation of the building along
with others in Lincoln Center, it seems to be largely theoretical,
for the ample cost has not been included in figures bandied about
to date.
</P>
<P>
   But Masur is still hopeful about setting up a summer home for
the orchestra in the Seventh Regiment Armory, across Central Park
from Lincoln Center, and establishing a series of informal,
adventurous concerts modeled after the London Proms, to attract,
especially, a young audience. Although complex negotiations with
the various parties controlling the building have repeatedly bogged
down, they evidently remain alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last goal, even if it doesn't occur until I go away, will
be to do the first concert,'' Masur said, ``an open concert in
whatever condition the hall will be in in summertime, to prove that
young people will come with the right programming.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
