<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SMOKIES-BEARS-COX     05-30 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKIES-BEARS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bear warnings don't slow visitors to Smokies
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elkmont, Tenn. _ Jay Kelley and his grown son, Shane, looked
forward to their hike on the Little River Trail, one of the most
popular in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park. Besides winding
next to a river and through a hardwood forest, its great attraction
is that the walk starts on a flat roadbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the easiest hikes in the Smokies and that's why we
decided to go,'' said Shane Kelley, 26, from Lebanon, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But a yellow sign stapled to the trail marker made the hike less
inviting to his father: WARNING. Bears Are Active In This Area.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers posted the notices soon after a black bear mauled a
Tennessee school teacher on the trail May 21. The fatality
apparently is the first from a bear attack in the park's 66-year
history. Officials are awaiting an autopsy report to verify that
the attack caused the woman's death. Previously, the only recorded
death caused by a black bear in a national park occurred at
Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the Kelleys had heard about the attack a week before
their Memorial Day weekend visit. Despite assurances from rangers
that the attack was an isolated incident, the elder Kelley decided
to take a shorter walk.
</P>
<P>
   His son hiked on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see a bear, all I have to do is outrun you,'' Shane
Kelley joked with his dad, before hiking 2.3 miles on the Little
River Trail to another path. The attack has raised bear awareness
but not deterred visitors from the most popular national park in
the country, which straddles the Tennessee-North Carolina line. Few
people have cancelled reservations in the park's developed
campsites or withdrawn backcountry permits.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the park reopened three backcountry campsites (Nos.
21, 23 and 30) near where school teacher Glenda Ann Bradley was
killed. A fourth, No. 24, remains closed because of reports of a
third bear in the area. Rangers there have set up a simulated
campsite and are cooking bacon and other fatty foods to see if it
attracts a bear. A video camera will monitor the area through the
week.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,600 black bears live in the park, which is visited
annually by 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say 99 percent of the people who visit have a respect for
black bears,'' park resource officer David Carney said at the
Sugarlands Visitor Center just outside Gatlinburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 1 percent of 10 million people is still a lot. Someone who
might chase a black bear with a Nikon camera needs to realize it's
not a dog, it's not a cat, it's not a domesticated animal. It's a
wild animal. If you picked up a rabbit here, it's a wild animal, it
will bite you. A black bear just happens to be big enough to do
more damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the entrance to the Elkmont Campground, which is adjacent
to the Little River Trail, a sign clearly designates the area: BEAR
HABITAT. But every campsite was filled over the Memorial Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Massey, a 38-year-old metals buyer from Newnan, didn't
hesitate hiking the Little River Trail with his wife and 4-year-old
son. ``You've got a lot more chances of getting hurt in Atlanta
than on the trails out here,'' Massey said. ``Everybody that's come
up to the Smokies has seen a bear. It's such a rare incident that
someone gets hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The park averages about one minor injury a year because of a
black bear encounter, officials said. A female hiker was
hospitalized 10 days in 1989 after a black bear attack.
</P>
<P>
   The two-lane roads that snake through the Smokies frequently are
clotted by ``bear jams'' _ traffic backups caused when motorists
pull off to watch black bears wandering in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   A bear jam Sunday clogged Little River Road between the Elkmont
campground and the Sugarlands Visitor Center on U.S. 441. George
Kabel of Dallas, Ga., had his zoom lens zeroed in on the bears. It
was the first time he had seen a wild black bear. It was nothing
new to his wife, Susan, who had seen similar beasts on previous
trips to the park.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of the fatality, ``I wouldn't go out on the
trails,'' Susan Kabel said.
</P>
<P>
   On May 21, Bradley and her ex-husband, Ralph Hill, entered the
park around noon, officials said. A few hours later, Hill went
fishing and Bradley stayed behind near the intersection of the
Little River and Goshen Prong trails.
</P>
<P>
   Hill returned and found Bradley's pack. Her body was about 40
years off the path. Hill tried to scare off two bears _ a 110-pound
female and her 40-pound cub _ hovering over the body, officials
said. Nearly a dozen hikers threw rocks at the bears but couldn't
scare them off. After a hiker ran to get them, two rangers killed
the bears by firing 19 rounds from their 9 mm and 10 mm
semiautomatic pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Bradley's autopsy won't be released for two to
three months. There's no suspicion of foul play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been saying that we're about 100 percent certain that it
was a bear attack,'' said park spokeswoman Nancy Gray. ``But we
can't say for certain until the autopsy.'' Not far from the park in
eastern Tennessee, Jones Cove Elementary School, where Bradley
taught fourth grade, will establish a memorial garden in the
teacher's honor. Earlier this month, her colleagues named her the
school's teacher of the year. Her funeral is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought there was nothing more that would please her,''
said Jo An Trentham, principal of the 200-student school. ``She
loved the outdoors and hiked a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
