<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-375(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT TO CONSIDER CLEAN AIR ACT AND ITS ECONOMIC IMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for rewriting and additional details on Clean Air case and
new material on two other cases; story grows by about 950 words and
is now 2 takes) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday expanded its
continuing review of the Clean Air Act by agreeing to decide
whether the statute requires the government to look beyond the
public health benefits of reducing air pollution and consider the
economic costs as well.
</P>
<P>
   The court's action raised the stakes even higher in a case, to
be argued next fall, that already promised to be one of the most
important environmental and administrative law cases in years.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the justices agreed to hear the Clinton
administration's appeal of a ruling by the federal appeals court
here that the Clean Air Act, as interpreted by the Environmental
Protection Agency, handed such broad authority of a legislative
nature to the administrative agency as to amount to an
unconstitutional ``delegation'' by Congress of its lawmaking power.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Tuesday in the same case, the court granted a separate
appeal, filed by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and a group of
regulated industries, that asked the justices to examine the Clean
Air Act from a different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   If the court were to read a broad cost-benefit requirement into
the EPA's rule-making authority, the business groups said, the
whole delegation question could be avoided, because the
cost-benefit requirement ``could functionally serve as the
necessary intelligible principle'' to preserve the law's
constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had argued against granting the
business groups' appeal, characterizing it as an invitation to a
judicial override of a choice that Congress had already made. In
enacting the Clean Air Act, the administration told the court,
Congress ``reasonably concluded'' that pollution standards ``should
be based on health and welfare considerations alone so that
Congress and the public know that EPA's judgments on the health and
welfare threats posed by particular criteria pollutants are not
compromised by considerations of economic and technical
feasibility.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case are new standards, set by the agency in
1997, for ozone and small airborne particles. The administration's
appeal is Browner vs. American Trucking Associations, No. 99-1257,
and the appeal granted Tuesday is American Trucking Associations
vs. Browner, No. 99-1426.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In invalidating the new standards in its ruling last year, the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit said the
EPA lacked ``any determinate criteria for drawing lines'' and had
``failed to state intelligibly how much is too much.'' The opinion,
by Judge Stephen F. Williams, suggested strongly that a
cost-benefit analysis could supply such criteria.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams said the appeals court was constrained by its own
precedent, a 1980 decision known as the Lead Industries case that
specifically barred the agency from considering any factor other
than public health. Only the Supreme Court was in a position to set
that decision aside.
</P>
<P>
   Although it declined to review the Lead Industries decision at
the time, the Supreme Court is familiar with the cost-benefit issue
from a series of regulatory battles in the early 1980s involving
the Occupational Safety and Health Act. In a 1980 case, a deeply
splintered court struck down the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration's standard for exposure to benzene, holding that
although OSHA did not have to engage in full cost-benefit analysis
to justify new regulations, it did have to make a preliminary
finding that current exposure levels posed ``a significant risk of
harm.'' That requirement presented a limiting principle that would
avoid a finding of undue delegation, the court said then.
</P>
<P>
   In a case the next year, involving standards for worker exposure
to cotton dust, the cause of brown lung disease, the court refused
to read a cost-benefit requirement into the occupational health
statute and said Congress had made its choice ``by placing the
`benefit' of worker health above all other considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Edward W. Warren, a lawyer here who won
the benzene case 20 years ago and will  &QC; argue for the business
groups in this case, said his clients were not asking the court to
adopt a ``technocratic, lives-for-dollars'' analysis of the Clean
Air Act or to use the case as a vehicle to ``transform the
administrative state.'' He said it was possible to interpret the
statute as making public health the primary consideration, with
cost considerations coming in only at the point of selecting among
alternative strategies.
</P>
<P>
   For purposes of the case, the most relevant phrases of the Clean
Air Act are those that instruct the administrator of the EPA to set
air quality standards that while ``allowing an adequate margin of
safety, are requisite to protect the public health.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no completely safe levels, above zero, of the
pollutants that the law regulates. According to the business
groups' brief, the phrase ``adequate margin of safety'' suggests
that the agency ``must trade off the costs and benefits of
additional safety, just as designers strive to engineer `adequate'
_ but never complete _ safety into every product they design.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were also these developments at the court Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   Potomac River Dispute
</P>
<P>
   Exercising its infrequently used ``original jurisdiction'' to
resolve suits between states, the court said it would allow
Virginia to proceed with a suit against Maryland over use of the
Potomac River, which forms a border between the two. Maryland owns
the river, under a grant from King Charles I of England in 1632,
but under various interstate compacts Virginia has been allowed to
make ``reasonable use'' of the Potomac from its own shoreline,
including the construction of pipes to draw river water for
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia brought this case, Virginia vs. Maryland, No. 129
Original, to protest Maryland's refusal to allow the Fairfax County
Water Authority to build a new intake pipe from the shoreline to a
point in the main channel, 725 feet offshore. The county authority
says the new pipe is needed because the current intake pipe, at the
shoreline, is subject to runoff, clogging by leaves or ice, and
other problems that would not occur near the middle of the river.
</P>
<P>
   Church Arson
</P>
<P>
   After its ruling last week that the federal arson law does not
apply to arson of a private residence, the court ordered two
federal appeals courts to reconsider whether the law applies to
arson of a church. In one case, Rea vs. United States, No. 99-6136,
the 8th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in St. Louis, found that a
church annex, used as a schoolhouse and for other activities, was
sufficiently connected with interstate commerce to be covered by
the law.
</P>
<P>
   But the 5th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in New Orleans,
almost simultaneously vacated a man's guilty plea for burning a
church. In that case, United States vs. Johnson, No. 99-1266, the
appeals court said the government had not shown that the Hopewell
United Methodist Church in Centerville, Texas, had the ``explicit
connection with or effect on interstate commerce'' necessary for
federal jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   In its unanimous decision last week, Jones vs. United States,
No. 99-5739, the court held that Congress did not intend the arson
law, which requires that a building be ``used'' in an activity
affecting commerce, to apply to a house used as a private
residence.
</P>
<P>
   If the appeals courts disagree on how the ruling applies to
churches or other types of buildings, there is a good prospect for
further Supreme Court decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
