<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS MAYOR'S TROUBLES GROW AS FRAUD INVESTIGATION WIDENS
</HEADLINE>
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The web of scandal surrounding the mayor's office here
got a little more complicated Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial sources said that 15 city officials, including Mayor
Jean Tiberi's top aide, had been put under formal investigation for
election fraud.
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another blow to President Jacques Chirac's Gaullist
party, which is maneuvering frantically to hold onto the mayor's
office, one of the most prestigious posts in France. Apart from its
wedding-cake ceilings and crystal chandeliers, Paris' city hall has
a huge budget and provides a national platform for whoever runs it.
</P>
<P>
   With elections just 10 months away, Chirac's party, Rally for
the Republic, has just dumped Tiberi as its candidate for
re-election after five years of scandals and judicial
investigations into his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But the new investigations reach far beyond Tiberi and threaten
even to taint Chirac as they involve fixing Paris elections while
he was its mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on computer records in one district of Paris,
investigators have apparently found 859 names fraudulently added to
electoral rolls in 1995 by officials associated with the mayor's
party.
</P>
<P>
   The race for mayor has proved so far to be one of the more
entertaining political stories in France. Partly, this has to do
with Tiberi, who has behaved like gum stuck to the party's shoe.
Despite polls indicating that only 5 percent of Parisians consider
him honest, Tiberi has pressed on, holding news conferences to
deplore his treatment and to tout his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Tiberi tried to force his party to put his
candidacy to a vote of local members. But the party's national
headquarters unveiled a little problem: the list of local members
Tiberi had supplied contained 1,500 ghost members. Some had moved
away, stopped paying dues or died. One party employee found seven
strangers listed as living in her house.
</P>
<P>
   Tiberi is still threatening to run without the party's backing.
</P>
<P>
   But Tiberi has not provided the only theatrics. Half a dozen
heavy-hitting politicians have thrown their hats into the ring and
then retrieved them again.
</P>
<P>
   They include the party's former prime minister, Edouard
Balladur, and Jack Lang, a Socialist who was former President
Francois Mitterrand's culture and education minister and is still
one of the best known faces on the French cultural-intellectual
scene. Lang was recently drafted into Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin's government, presumably to clear the way for Bertrand
Delanoe, Jospin's choice to become mayoral candidate of his
Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Rally for the Republic has chosen Philippe Seguin as its
candidate. Seguin is often described as large in stature and
personality, and the party no doubt hopes that his presence will
eclipse Tiberi's sordid reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The scandals attached to Tiberi have been unrelenting. His wife,
Xaviere, before her conviction was set aside on a technicality, was
found guilty of accepting $36,000 from the government for a 36-page
report on a subject in which she had no expertise. At trial, a
witness testified that Tiberi had suggested she be given the job.
Other scandals have involved awarding public housing contracts to
party supporters. Allegations that some of the mayor's political
cronies hold city jobs but do no work are still being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 officials now under formal investigation include Tiberi's
deputy mayor, Jacques Dominati, who belongs to the Rally for the
Republic's sister party, Liberal Democracy. The newspaper Le
Parisien quotes him today as admitting to limited fraud in the 1989
election, but nothing ``very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just some activists who were a bit too enthusiastic and
signed up extra names in my arrondissement,'' he told the
newspaper. ``But there was no large-scale organization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
