<SLUG> BC-CUBA-U.S.-SPY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS OFFICIAL CONVICTED ON ESPIONAGE CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A veteran immigration official here was convicted
Tuesday of espionage in a case that caused the expulsion of a Cuban
diplomat and heightened political tensions between the United
States and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in U.S. District Court found the official, Mariano Faget,
54, guilty of violating the Espionage Act by disclosing government
secrets to a boyhood friend who wanted to do business in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Faget, an acting deputy director with 34 years of service with
the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service office here, was
convicted of disclosing official secrets, using those secrets for
his personal use and lying to federal investigators about his
foreign business ties and his meetings with a Cuban diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Faget, who came to the United States from
Cuba when he was a teen-ager, said when he took the stand last week
in his defense.
</P>
<P>
   But federal prosecutors argued that Faget, whose job involved
reviewing government decisions on naturalization and asylum, had
sold out his country to help a business partner and himself.
</P>
<P>
   The case came as Cuban exiles in Miami protested the decision by
Attorney General Janet Reno to send 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez home
to Cuba, and as Cubans demanded the boy's return in
government-sponsored demonstrations on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Faget's arrest led to the expulsion of a Cuban diplomat, Jose
Imperatori, who had dealings with Faget and was accused of spying
by U.S. officials. Cuban officials denied the accusations.
Imperatori refused to leave the country and did so only after
federal agents escorted him to a Washington airport.
</P>
<P>
   Faget, who faces up to 10 years in prison, is scheduled for a
sentencing hearing in August.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested after a government undercover operation in
February, when government agents passed phony information to him
about the fictitious defection of a Cuban diplomat, and warned him
that the information was secret. Faget, as a senior supervisor with
the immigration service, had a high security clearance.
</P>
<P>
   Just 12 minutes after the meeting with the agents, he called a
Cuban-American boyhood friend and business partner, Pedro Font, and
told him the name of the Cuban official.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mariano Faget was a government employee willing to betray the
trust of the people he was sworn to serve,'' Curtis Miner, an
assistant U.S. attorney, said in his closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Faget, who was nearing retirement, was on the board of directors
with Font of America Cuba Inc., a corporation formed to pursue
business interests in Cuba if the U.S. trade embargo against the
island is ever lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Faget told the jury last week that he called his friend because
Font was supposed to meet later that day with the Cuban official
named by the government agents, and he was afraid that Font would
be harmed if Cuban officials thought he was somehow involved in the
defection.
</P>
<P>
   But the 12-member jury apparently did not accept that Font, a
New York businessman, would have been in any danger from Cuban
officials.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``He disclosed classified information information for no better
purpose than his own personal reasons, his own personal gain,''
Miner said. ``He took it out of the realm of control of the United
States government and gave it to someone else to use however they
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Faget's lawyer had argued that his client was not doing anything
that threatened national security and that he was only trying to
help a boyhood friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``An honest government servant,'' said Edward O'Donnell, Faget's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors used surveillance tapes to show meetings between
Faget and Cuban diplomats in a Miami bar, acts that are illegal
under federal law because of Faget's job at the immigration
service.
</P>
<P>
   And Faget had marked ``no'' on a disclosure form for immigration
service employees when he was asked if he had any foreign business
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Font and Faget had known each other in Cuba, where Faget's
father had worked in the police force controlled by Cuba's
president at that time, Fulgencio Batista. Faget and his family
fled Cuba in 1959.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
