A0113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MILITARY-HNS &LR;      05-30 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MILITARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS ADMINISTRATION TRYING TO `POLITICIZE' HIS NUCLEAR ARMS
PROPOSAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ George W. Bush on Tuesday accused the Clinton-Gore
administration of trying to ``politicize'' national defense by
criticizing his proposal to reduce the number of American nuclear
warheads and build a large anti-ballistic missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush issued his rebuke on the same day that he, in turn, accused
the Democratic administration of plunging military morale to
``dangerously low'' levels by over-deploying troops around the
world, under-paying them and poorly equipping them.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking off a four-day campaign swing through the West, the
likely Republican presidential nominee reacted to Secretary of
Defense William Cohen's offer to brief Bush and his national
security advisers on the state of America's strategic nuclear
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters on Tuesday that he already has received
``substantial'' national defense briefings from Colin Powell,
former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff; former Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney; and former National Security Adviser Henry
Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one of the finest foreign policy teams ever
assembled,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, the only Republican in President Clinton's Cabinet, and
Vice President Al Gore, Bush's likely Democratic opponent, both
have criticized Bush's nuclear arms proposal. They contend it would
harm arms control efforts and threaten world security.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor announced last week that he would consider
making unilateral reductions in nuclear weapons at a deeper level
than the one being negotiated by the United States and Russia. He
also called for the construction of a larger anti-ballistic missile
defense system than proposed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, in a nationally televised interview on Sunday, said that
Bush's larger anti-missile system would prompt Russia and other
countries to respond by increasing their own nuclear arsenals. Were
that to happen, he said, it would make negotiated reductions in
nuclear warheads less likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call upon my opponent not to allow members of the
administration to politicize national defense,'' Bush said. ``I
found the comments (by Cohen) to be political in nature.``
</P>
<P>
   Former Secretary of Veterans Affairs Jesse Brown denied Cohen's
comments were political. In a conference call with reporters
arranged by the Democratic National Committee, Brown questioned how
Bush would pay for his anti-missile defense system and warned that
it could spur an international arms race. He also questioned
whether the technology existed to build it.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also said the administration recognized the problems that
American troops face and was ``working responsibly to address
them.``
</P>
<P>
   But on a visit in Denver to the country's oldest Veterans of
Foreign Wars post, Bush blamed President Clinton for military
morale problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a man who's in charge of morale in the military. We
have a commander in chief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also ridiculed Gore for claiming, on his campaign Web site,
that the administration has had a well-managed military
``build-down.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that America's defense spending, as a percentage of
Gross Domestic Product, was at its lowest level since the 1941
attack on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. troops are over-deployed and underpaid and under-trained.
Entire Army divisions are not prepared for war. Military recruiting
fell thousands short of its goal, and 6,000 United States soldiers
are on food stamps,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore record cries out for a new sign on the
Pentagon that says, `Under New Management.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Bush vowed to increase military pay, renovate substandard
military housing, upgrade training and give the military a ``clear
sense of mission.'' He said that, if elected, he also will order an
immediate review of America's overseas commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would honor America's peacekeeping commitments in
the world's hotspots but also would negotiate political solutions
and convince America's allies to shoulder more of the peacekeeping
load.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
