<HEADER>
A0114 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HAYNES-DRUMMER-$ADV04     05-30 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYNES-DRUMMER-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO DARES CALL THIS MAESTRO A LAME DUCK? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, June 4) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a performance in Chicago a few years ago, a woman came up
to Roy Haynes and told him that the way he played drums reminded
her of the four seasons. Not Vivaldi, but
winter-spring-summer-fall.
</P>
<P>
   He liked that remark. Haynes embodies a great deal of jazz's
history. He is among a small group of musicians who have seen 50
years' change of weather in jazz from the best vantage point _ the
back of the bandstand, the rhythm section. He has played with
practically everybody of major significance since the 1940s _ from
Louis Armstrong to Pat Metheny, as he likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   He is 75, small, bald and careful about his clothes, and he
looks as fit as a soldier. The way he plays the drums sounds
unprogrammed and original. When he's onstage, especially, he seldom
repeats a pattern on the high-hat or the ride-cymbal. Where many
drummers use those two cymbals as comfortable pulse-setters to lay
underneath the main event of the drums themselves, he emphasizes
them, smacking the cymbals loudly and making the audience hear the
harmony and density in the metal. He displaces a band's rhythms,
making the music sound as if it's spilling out over the sides of
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm listening to something on the radio and it becomes the
same thing over and over,'' Haynes said last week, while sitting in
the living room of his house near Long Island's south shore, ``I
change the channel. If it's moving, I find out where it's going. It
has to go someplace. If it just stays in one place, it becomes
stagnant _ water, music, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   When Haynes lived in Harlem in the late '40s and early '50s, the
jazz musicians of his acquaintance were listening to Afro-Cuban
music all the time _ the Cuban conguero Chano Pozo had joined Dizzy
Gillespie's big band, and the orchestras led by Machito, Tito
Puente and Tito Rodriguez were playing regular gigs at uptown dance
halls. Whether there is a cause-and-effect relationship or not (
Haynes disdains most suppositions about such things, feeling that
his style has always been within him), he developed an outgoing,
open sound on the drums that has led many compare him to a timbale
or conga player. He lets rhythm flow through him without a feeling
of constraint; sometimes the pulse gets stretched, but it's
constantly changing, the kind of musicianship that always sounds
modern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way he breaks up time,'' said David Kikoski, who has
been Haynes' regular pianist since 1986. ``The accents he does with
his different limbs are more complex than anything that came before
him. The syncopation that he developed influenced all modern
drummers. It sounds natural because it is natural. What he plays on
the drums is the way he lives, the way he talks, the way he
walks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Roy Haynes Trio,'' a new disc on Verve/Universal recorded
with the pianist Danilo Perez and the bassist John Patitucci, is an
unpretentious little record that in some ways is a retrospective
for Haynes. Cut in half between two sets, like an LP, it's
half-studio and half-live; its repertory stretches from his early
days (Bud Powell's ``Wail,'' which he recorded with Powell in 1949
on one of the most fundamental recording sessions in jazz) through
the 1960s (a song by Chick Corea, on whose first album, ``Now He
Sobs, Now He Sings,'' Haynes appeared, and with whom he still
occasionally plays) and into the recent years (Pat Metheny's
``Question and Answer,'' taken from Metheny's 1989 trio album of
the same name, with Haynes and Dave Holland).
</P>
<P>
   It's got a few formula bebop rhythms, a minimalist piece written
by Thelonious Monk and beloved by drummers called ``Green
Chimneys,'' as well as that open, unyielding conga sound, which
happens quite naturally in a few places; Perez, from Panama, tends
to draw Latin rhythms out of drummers by turning jazz vamps into
Latin montunos, and Haynes responds energetically.
</P>
<P>
   The trio, starting an American tour, will perform at Birdland in
New York this Thursday through Saturday. ``I never thought I would
be this age and touring,'' Haynes said. He says he never wanted to
become the kind of jazz musician who's still on stage after the
point when he should have been told to hang it up. But forget age _
there are few better drummers in jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when he first heard bebop, Haynes flinched a little. ``I
feel like I've been playing it all my life,'' he said. ``I'm one of
the inventors of it! Well, not really, but that's my period.''
</P>
<P>
   All paradigm-shifting art styles have debatable beginnings:
there are precursor figures who point the way and then a next wave
young enough to swallow it whole and make an actual style of it.
Haynes was from the latter camp.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston during the early '40s, Haynes was part of the vibrant
black jazz subculture in the Roxbury section: he played for
lindy-hoppers and zoot-suiters. He was in touch with the bebop
coming from New York, buying the first records by Coleman Hawkins
that carried intimations of the new style, taking the bus down to
New York's 52nd street on weekends before he was out of his teens.
He remembers writing a letter to his brother in 1943 in which he
tried to describe the new sound he was hearing as something like
the famously tight, complex music of the John Kirby band but with
different harmonies.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to New York in 1945 at the request of the bandleader
Luis Russell and joined the cast of characters who hung around the
crossroads of 126th Street and Eighth Avenue. Jazz had central
locations back then; musicians would sit in the bar of the Hotel
Braddock, cruising for work, or stand on the corner eating and
talking, holding a sort of open-air office hours. His first gig was
at the Savoy Ballroom, playing for dancers again. In 1947 he joined
Lester Young's band; two years later, when Young split up his band
to go on tour with the popular Jazz at the Philharmonic revue,
Haynes started working on 52nd Street, the new locus of activity,
with different young bandleaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fashionable, then, to leave the big bands and play with
the small groups,'' he said. Haynes turned down a job offer from
Duke Ellington in 1951, preferring to keep playing with Charlie
Parker. ``That's what we wanted to do _ just stay in New York and
gig.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his most instructive periods was his time spent as a
member of Thelonious Monk's band during Monk's long residency at
New York's Five Spot in the late '50s. ``Monk played the oddest
tempos,'' Haynes recalled, singing a few floaty,
neither-fast-nor-slow bars of ``Let's Cool One.'' ``He used to say
that drummers can usually just play a few tempos,'' he said. ``If
you take them out of those tempos, they'll either bring the tempo
up or bring it back. And he may have had a point there.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes also recorded and worked at clubs with jazz's finest
vocalists and learned how to negotiate his way around each one's
rhythmic center. ``Playing with Ella Fitzgerald,'' he said,
alluding to her exact sense of time, ``was like playing with the
Basie band. Playing with Billie Holiday was like playing with Prez.
Playing with Sarah Vaughan was like playing with Charlie Parker.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Vaughan _ her great self-titled album from 1954, including
Clifford Brown as well as Haynes, has just been reissued by Verve _
was one of the most challenging jazz musicians of the century.
``During that period,'' Haynes said, ``she sang the slowest ballads
I have ever heard. Mmm. Today, it's harder to play really slowly
with most bass players, because they don't fill out that space that
needs to be filled out if the drummer's going to play with
brushes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see,'' he added, warming up to the topic, ``you can play
something slow, but it can still have intensity in it. There's a
way that 'Trane did it too, when he played a ballad. It wasn't
necessarily that slow, but you'd be up there'' _ he raises his head
above his head to show the rhythm section's level of intensity.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   His favorite subject seems to be time and what can be achieved
by the subtle altering of it; he had just seen Willie Nelson
performing on television and was full of praise for how the singer
races the tempo of his singing and guitar playing while keeping an
inner sense of steady time. ``He played one of Django Reinhardt's
tunes,'' Haynes said. ``I said, my god. I didn't know he was that
slick.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes started leading groups in the late '60s, and like a
number of other drummers _ Elvin Jones, Max Roach, Jack DeJohnette,
Arthur Taylor _ has been a cultivater of young talent. He offers
his experience to his charges, but experience has not taught Haynes
to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got more energy than 20- and 30-year-old musicians I've
travelled with,'' said Kikoski. ``We can be on a train for hours
and hours, get to the bandstand and Roy will always be completely
energized and ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes contends that when he's not playing he gets restless. ``I
probably sleep better when I'm playing,'' he said. ``If you really
mean it, that's your life, that's your love, that's your religion.
I mean, some people just start studying this thing, and that's a
little different. I do it the old-fashioned way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
