<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-CONFERENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time Warner: `We're committed to CNN'
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta and Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One thing won't change when Time Warner merges with
America Online: The marriage of old and new media will retain its
commitment to CNN and Atlanta, according to Ted Turner's boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission in life is to preserve, protect and defend the
journalistic heritage of CNN,'' Time Warner Chairman Gerald Levin
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are totally committed to Atlanta,'' said Levin, who added
the merger will ``enhance the role of Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin offered his reassurances Tuesday evening at Atlanta's
Centennial Olympic Park bash that kicked off the annual CNN World
Report Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who founded CNN, will remain influential in the new
company, Levin said, despite recent news reports that he feels like
he has been relegated to a back seat. ``He's not going to lose
control. ... He and I are still here,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner declined to say anything Tuesday about what role he
expects in the new company, but he said he's ``not worried about
the intermediate future of CNN. In the long term, anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, his bosses and many of his CNN employees have gathered
in Atlanta this week for the cable news network's annual conference
and its 20th anniversary, which is Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary will be marked by a huge invitation-only party
at Philips Arena with 15,000 guests, speeches, presentations and
rock music from Rod Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is keyed to ``CNN World Report,'' a weekly show
in which international journalists affiliated with CNN file special
reports on their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, more than 300 journalists and TV executives
will hear from newsmakers including Vice President Al Gore, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Queen Noor of Jordan. They'll also
do a good bit of partying.
</P>
<P>
   Although the events are closed to the public, CNN has scheduled
two retrospectives on its 20 years, to air 9-11 p.m. Thursday and
Friday, hosted by Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
