<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 1STLEDE &HT;    1STLEDE
 &HT;    Eds: Removes improper coding
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Prosecution wants Lewis' limo driver back on stand
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Prosecutors want another shot at witness Duane
Fassett, the limousine driver who last week failed to say he saw
NFL star Ray Lewis deliver a blow in a fatal street fight.
</P>
<P>
   But a big question remains: Can they make him return?
</P>
<P>
   Fassett, a tortured soul during his court appearance, testified
he did not see Lewis hit one of the victims in the lower chest as
he had earlier told police. Also, Fassett backed off earlier
statements to police that he overheard Lewis' co-defendants,
Reginald Oakley, 31, of Baltimore, and Joseph Sweeting, 34, of
Miami, admit to stabbing the victims.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard did not
follow proper procedures, and there may lie the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Howard hoped to introduce Fassett's incriminating statements
into evidence Tuesday through the testimony of a police detective
who was with Fassett when he made them. But Superior Court Judge
Alice D. Bonner refused to let that happen, saying Georgia law
requires prosecutors to first confront witnesses about inconsistent
statements. She noted Howard failed to do that.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, the district attorney expressed
confidence that the Baltimore-area resident would return. ``I plan
on calling him,'' said Howard. ``He's still under subpoena.''
</P>
<P>
   But Howard released Fassett from his subpoena in open court,
said Bruce Harvey, attorney for Oakley. ``Mr. Fassett is absolutely
under no obligation to reappear,'' Harvey contended.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Howard was on the phone to David Irwin, Fassett's
lawyer in Baltimore. Irwin said Howard wanted him to fly Fassett to
Atlanta Tuesday night. ``He's not going to like that,'' said Irwin,
who had yet to tell his client.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett can either return voluntarily or require prosecutors to
issue an interstate subpoena, which requires several steps. Also,
Fassett must be served the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   ``By recalling him, it tends to suggest that Howard does not
believe his own witnesses,'' said Dan Summer, a Gainesville
attorney. ``That would not look good to a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over Fassett's re-appearance marked a day of
testimony from two limo passengers and two of the victims' friends.
One of the friends shot at the limo as it sped away from the scene
where Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, of Decatur were
stabbed to death Jan. 31 after a night of post-Super Bowl partying.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Sparks, a 24-year-old college student from Chicago,
buttressed prosecution contentions that Lewis led a cover-up after
the killings.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Lewis' hotel that night, Sparks said, she was a
passenger in a car where another limo passenger threw a bag in a
Dumpster behind a fast-food restaurant. She said the white hotel
laundry bag thrown into the trash was big enough to carry clothing,
supporting the prosecution's belief that Lewis was getting rid of
the blood-stained suit he wore that night.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks also testified that Jessica Robertson, who spent Super
Bowl weekend with Lewis and drove the car to the Dumpster,
destroyed a photo of the Lewis entourage taken that night at the
Cobalt nightclub. The photo would have allowed investigators
quickly identify those in the limo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jessica said she took it out of my purse,'' Sparks said. ``She
said she burned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks also said that she saw blood on the pants and shoes of
limo passenger Carlos Stafford, the man she saw dispose of the
laundry bag. Stafford has not been charged and is negotiating with
prosecutors for a grant of immunity in exchange for his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin Burros, an Akron, Ohio, native who grew up with the
victims, admitted to firing seven shots at the limo as it fled the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Burros testified he witnessed the fight from a distance and then
saw as many as 10 people run to the limo. He said he walked up, saw
Baker lying on the street and ran towards his GMC Yukon Denali
parked nearby. But a friend was already driving it toward the
scene, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burros said he grabbed his .45-caliber handgun from under a rear
seat and jogged up the street pumping off rounds. He said he only
tried to shoot the tires, which he did. In fact, Howard in his
opening arguments, credited Burros' action with allowing police to
identify the limo.
</P>
<P>
   However, defense attorneys repeatedly dwelled on the fact that
prosecutors have not charged Burros with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I would be dealt with at a later date,'' said
Burros, admitting he could be charged with aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   David Wolfe, one of Oakley's two attorneys, pointed out a
contradiction in Burros' testimony. The lawyer noted that the
shell-casings from Burros' gun eject to the right. But the casings
were found around Baker and Lollar's bodies, to the left of and up
the hill from where Burros said he fired the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Tony Axam, one of Lewis' attorneys, got the 185-pound
Burros to say he had a 46-chest and 34-inch waist and could bench
press twice his weight. In previous testimony, a cabdriver said he
saw an athletically built man with a V-shaped build standing over
the bodies, angrily pointing at them.
</P>
<P>
   Axam then displayed a red leather jacket that Burros wore the
night of the killings. A woman who witnesses the fight from the
apartment window said the most ``ferocious'' of the attackers wore
a red jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
