u a BC-LA-WOMAN-SLAIN-NYT     05-30 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-WOMAN-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES POLICE ARE SEEKING CLUES IN KILLING OF CHIEF'S
GRANDDAUGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Nev.) By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The police were searching for clues on Tuesday in
the fatal shooting of the police chief's granddaughter, who they
believe became the unintended victim of a gunman who fired into her
car at a drive-through restaurant on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know she was not the intended target,'' said Lt. Horace
Frank, a spokesman for the Los Angeles Police Department. ``She
just happened to be at the wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Bernard Parks' granddaughter, Lori Gonzalez, who would
have turned 21 next week, was shot about 10:15 p.m. on Sunday as
she and a male companion were leaving the restaurant at La Brea
Avenue and Jefferson Boulevard in the South-Central neighborhood of
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman, described as a heavy-set African-American in his
20s, approached the passenger side of the car as it slowed and
fired several shots into the car, the police said. The passenger
ducked and Gonzalez, who was driving, was struck several times, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were investigating whether the 20-year-old
passenger may have been the intended target. The identity of the
man was not made public. He was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   The police had no motive for the shooting, and continued to
interview the passenger on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Jason Lee, a public information officer, said the police
were investigating the possibility that the shooting was gang
related.
</P>
<P>
   Several gangs operate in the area, Lee said, and drive-by
shootings have been a problem. He declined to say whether
Gonzalez's passenger was a gang member.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a gang problem, Lee said the crime rate in the
neighborhood had fallen about 30 percent over the last three years.
The neighborhood is a mix of commercial and residential buildings,
with numerous strip malls and middle- to lower-income residents.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities speculate that the gunman, who may have had a
grudge against Gonzalez's passenger, spotted him while they were at
Popeyes Chicken and Biscuits restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at the restaurant said there had been no problems in
recent years, although the restaurant was equipped with special
security devices, including a protective shield at the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an area that's had problems with criminal activities,''
Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of the neighborhood have expressed concerns about
drug dealers and gang problems.
</P>
<P>
   Parks and his wife, Bobbie, were in seclusion on Tuesday. They
have four children and several grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, a student at Saddleback College in Mission Viejo, was
in Los Angeles visiting her mother when the shooting occurred,
according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Joe Gonzalez, told The Los Angeles Times that he and
his wife had divorced 18 years ago. About two years ago, Gonzalez
moved to Mission Viejo to live with her father, and enrolled at
Saddleback College last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez described his daughter as ``wonderful with people and
full of life.'' She had worked as a clerk at a drugstore and as an
operator with Pacific Bell. She also taught Sunday school to third,
fourth and fifth graders and had recently gone to Tijuana, Mexico,
to build houses for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was said to go frequently to Los Angeles to visit her
mother and other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The police on Tuesday were asking the public for assistance in
solving the killing, appealing to anyone who might have
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation where we really need the public's help,''
Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   If the authorities are correct in their assumption that the
passenger was the gunman's target, it will not be the first time a
relative of the police chief has been at risk because of a
passenger in the car.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, one of Park's daughters was charged with conspiracy to
sell cocaine and trafficking in cocaine in Clark County, Nev.,
after she gave a ride to a man and unknowingly became enmeshed in a
drug deal. The charges were dropped in October 1998 at the
prosecutor's request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
