<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS INCREASING THEIR ACTIVITY FOR GORE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Environmental groups, worried that a Republican in
the White House would harm their cause, are stepping up their
campaign activity in favor of Al Gore and against George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the League of Conservation Voters became the first
major national environmental group to back Gore, during an event on
the banks of Lake Michigan in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it has not yet endorsed a presidential contender,
the Sierra Club is running television ads in a number of Midwestern
states featuring two Houston-area residents who criticize Texas
Gov. Bush's environmental record in his state.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore, who has long championed environmental
causes and wrote a 1992 book on the subject, ``Earth in the
Balance,'' clearly hopes that this issue will move voters,
particularly suburbanites concerned with sprawl and congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Touting the record of the Clinton administration, Gore said,
``We have proven once and for all that pollution does not have to
be the price of prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, however, accused environmental activists of
distorting the Texas governor's record.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett argued that the League of
Conservation Voters was biased because its president, Deb Callahan,
worked on Gore's unsuccessful 1988 presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious where their loyalties lie and that is with Al
Gore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee Callahan introduced Gore by saying he had fought
for cleaner air, measures to combat global warming and expansion of
the federal park system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Al Gore wins, the planet wins,'' said Callahan, who
dished out as much criticism of Bush as she did praise for the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   She said that as Texas governor Bush has presided over a state
with some of the worst air, water and land pollution in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's friends are the biggest corporate polluters
and lobbyists for timber, mining and oil companies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan also claimed that ``under the Bush administration not
one single acre of land has been added to the state park system.
And Texas ranks 49th among the states in government spending to
support its parks.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bartlett said that under the governor's watch 90,919 acres
have been added to the state park system. One of those additions
was a 40,000-acre donation in 1996 to the Chanati Mountain State
natural area in Presidio County in West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said that the Legislature in 1999 approved a $16
million bond package that could be used for park land purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Loyless, the Conservation League's political director,
said that while the state may have received land donations, that is
not the same as the government budgeting for and actively pursuing
park expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does say something about how the state of Texas reacts
rather than advances public land acquisition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may have a hard time selling his environmental credentials,
particularly with the media focus on Houston overtaking Los Angeles
as the city with the nation's worse ozone smog record last year. A
recent Pew Poll found that voters believed Gore would be better
than Bush in protecting the environment by a margin of 55 percent
to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even many environmentalists who do not believe the Clinton
administration has been as aggressive as it should have on a number
of their issues are wary of a Bush presidency.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been some dissension on the board of the Sierra
Club over whether to endorse Gore, the group's political director,
Dan Weiss, said that there is ``zero possibility'' that Bush would
receive the influential organization's backing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
