<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-RAVE-FILM-MUSIC-$ADV0     05-30 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVE-FILM-MUSIC-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING THE WORLD, ONE ENDLESS DANCE AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By DAVID BAHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, the director Jon Reiss could not have cared less
about raves. As far as he was concerned, they involved nothing but
hordes of teen-agers, psychedelic drugs and mindlessly repetitive
techno music.
</P>
<P>
   Then he went to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just blew me away,'' recalls Reiss, 35. ``The hair on the
back of my neck was standing up. The music and collective energy
brought me to this spiritual level that I had only experienced
while meditating. I knew I had to learn what made it tick.''
</P>
<P>
   So he set out to make a documentary about the phenomenon,
``Better Living Through Circuitry,'' one of three new films, along
with the recently released ``Human Traffic'' and ``Groove'' (which
opens Friday, to celebrate the rave scene. As Greg Harrison, the
director of ``Groove,'' says, ``Rave serves a powerful purpose in
the modern Western world because those kinds of communal, cathartic
experiences based on music have been factored out, or at least
commodified, in our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Rave itself began in England during the late 1980s, when
rebellious youths took over abandoned warehouses, consumed
hallucinogens and danced to live DJs into the morning hours. It was
not until the early 1990s that these events made it to this
country, much to the dismay of narcotics enforcement officials and
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, in movies like ``Trainspotting'' (1996) and last
year's ``Go,'' rave culture has been presented as little more than
a backdrop for misery and death. But for this most recent crop of
rave moviemakers, the films are an attempt to dispel misconceptions
and portray the subculture in all its blissed-out, trippy glee.
``For the most part, raves have been unjustly vilified by the
media,'' Harrison says. ``With `Groove,' I wanted to portray the
positive aspects and optimism that underlies the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   That optimism, vibrantly apparent in all three films, stems from
ravers' faith in music and dance as regenerative, liberating
forces. Unlike the aggressive and nihilistic currents that ran
through the punk rock scene, rave, as the documentary ``Better
Living Through Circuitry'' (which opened May 12) portrays it,
cultivates a life-affirming attitude and socially productive
spirit. In fact, for the technologically savvy and musically
innovative, it provides a vast outlet: participants communicate and
network over the Internet (since the locations of underground
events are ever-changing), designing cutting-edge graphics and,
perhaps most intriguingly, composing and generating electronic
dance music.
</P>
<P>
   ``DJs have replaced rock stars in our world,'' says Justin
Kerrigan, the 25-year-old British director of ``Human Traffic'' and
an outspoken rave devotee. ``The freshest tracks around come from
DJ's and kids playing around on their bedroom computers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Reiss, what is most impressive about rave culture are its
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I found amazing is that they share the same
fundamental values that I have but thought were gone,'' he says.
``And that is the notion that if society doesn't offer the avenue
you want, to go out and create it yourself. Here are people with a
view of the world where money isn't the be-all and end-all of
everything. People are drawn into raving because of the
transformative effect of the experience, not just materially, but
spiritually, psychically. And there's something about that
collective purpose that gives it an additional dimension, a
communal energy if you will.''
</P>
<P>
   As Reiss' compelling documentary shows, rave is open to anyone
regardless of race, sexual orientation or age (though participants
tend be well under 30), and it's that inclusiveness that attracts
revelers _ many of them outsiders who feel uncomfortable at other
social and athletic events. Reiss spoke with scores of DJs,
musicians, promoters and fans, accumulating over 200 hours of
interviews before editing the film down to a richly packed 88
minutes. What emerges is a self-determined community dedicated to
creative expression and personal freedom, of which drugs are not
necessarily an integral part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned that drugs are not important to a lot of people who
have kept the culture going,'' says Stuart Swezey, who produced
``Better Living Through Circuitry'' with Brian McNelis. ``Certainly
drugs can be a transporting experience, but there are many ravers
that have never taken them and those who still rave that have grown
out of them. And that's one of the reasons we put off addressing
the issue until halfway through the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Swezey does not dispute the indelible imprint of
drugs, particularly Ecstasy and acid, on the rave scene, something
all three films boldly reflect. Both ``Human Traffic'' and
``Groove'' portray drugs with such cozy familiarity that their
presence is merely taken for granted. The skimpy plot of the
infectiously energetic ``Human Traffic'' involves a group of
British friends living for the weekend so they can pop Ecstasy,
dance and forget their problems.
</P>
<P>
   The more substantive and equally entertaining ``Groove'' weaves
together several drug-related story lines. The central one involves
an uptight writer named David (Hamish Linklater) whose first
rave-Ecstasy experience teaches him a lesson in liberation. Along
the way, he falls for the lost and jaded Leyla (Lola Glaudini), a
perpetual party-goer unable to escape the scene. Strategically,
however, no one dies in either film.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no overdoses or shootouts in my film,'' says
Harrison, who, like Kerrigan, refused to cave in to early pressures
by film company executives to inject a little death and gunfire
into the plot. ``The darkness in my film is more realistic and
pervasive in that it deals with getting trapped in the scene. Yes,
rave can be an epiphany that changes the way you see your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it can also be a trap, as it is for Leyla, sucking you
into a false sense of happiness and well-being if you're unwilling
to examine your life as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   By acknowledging a wider range of rave experience as well as the
limits of its liberation, ``Groove'' has greater emotional
resonance than the frenetic, cartoonish ``Human Traffic.'' But in
the end, even ``Groove'' is too much of a tidy crowd-pleaser to
satisfactorily explore the various motivations behind recreational
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what all three films do successfully convey is the
passion and primal power surrounding communal dance. As McNelis
notes, drugs are not the focus of raves; collective transcendence
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our film is not about telling people to attend these events to
do drugs,'' he says. ``If anything, it reveals a world that
encourages them to attend these events to dance, sweat, let go,
and, if you want, experience some kind of enlightenment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0124 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BARYSHNIKOV-RAINER-DA     05-30 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARYSHNIKOV-RAINER-DANCE-ART-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON AN IMPROBABLE QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 27 and 28 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, June 4)  
(Editors: Capitalized NO in 6th graf from end is cq.) 
 By WENDY PERRON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From opposite ends of the dance universe come two
superstars: Mikhail Baryshnikov and Yvonne Rainer. He from the
purest centuries-old classical tradition, she from the
rule-breaking Judson Dance Theater of the 1960s. He the prince of
Russian ballet; she the high priestess of the American avant-garde.
He known for his natural theatricality, she for her resistance to
anything theatrical.
</P>
<P>
   They are rehearsing together for a season of the White Oak Dance
Project, of which Baryshnikov is founder and director as well as
lead performer, at the Brooklyn Academy of Music from June 7 to 11.
In addition to a new work by Rainer, there will be premieres by
Mark Morris and John Jasperse and Trisha Brown's ``Glacial Decoy''
(1979). How did it happen that Baryshnikov asked Rainer, who had
not choreographed a dance in decades, to contribute to this
program?
</P>
<P>
   In the last 25 years Baryshnikov has journeyed deep into the
repertory of American modern dance, while Rainer, in the last year,
has returned to the dance studio after 25 years as a noted feminist
filmmaker. Since its inception in 1990, White Oak has commissioned
40 new dances from modern choreographers, starting with its initial
resident choreographer, Mark Morris, and on through Lar Lubovitch,
Maurice Bejart, Kevin O'Day, Neil Greenberg and Lucy Guerin.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall Baryshnikov, 52, came to Judson Memorial Church in
Greenwich Village when Rainer, 65, danced in a new version of her
seminal ``Trio A'' (1966), a five-minute continuous phrase in which
the dancers never look out at the audience. Planning a program for
this fall featuring choreographers from Judson Dance Theater,
legendary as the incubator of postmodern dance, Baryshnikov invited
Rainer to choreograph something.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to see White Oak and met him, I was surprised and
pleased that he was familiar with the titles and the personnel of
my past work,'' Rainer said recently during a rehearsal at the
Trisha Brown Studio near Columbus Circle in Manhattan. ``He'd done
his homework. I said I could give him `Trio A' and `We shall Run'
(1963). Then he said, `Maybe you'd like to do a new piece.' I
gulped. And then it began to obsess me. What would I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Separated by a quarter-century from her work in dance, she went
home and riffled through her book ``Work: 1961-1973'' to gather
bits and pieces from her past artistic life that could be
rearranged. Harking back to the Dadaist method of fragmentation,
Rainer chose a collage structure to contain the selections. Like
much of her work in both dance and film, the ideas and images are
presented not in a beginning-middle-and-end format, but in a series
of radical juxtapositions of tasks, interactions and spoken texts.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients for this collage, titled ``After Many a Summer Dies
the Swan,'' are drawn from ``Three Satie Spoons'' (1960), ``The
Bells'' (1961), ``The Mind Is a Muscle'' (1968) and ``Continuous
Project _ Altered Daily'' (1970). Actions may be simultaneous,
deflecting attention from one another, or sequential. One section,
in which dancers cushion one another's movements with pillows, has
a goofy precision.
</P>
<P>
   In another, two women link arms around each other's waists as
they repeatedly melt to the floor and rise, still attached. They
are reciting, in falsetto, a Gertrude Stein-ish bit of text by
Rainer: ``That was so lovely.'' ``Yes yes that was so lovely.''
``It was so lovely it will make me think about it a lot.'' ``In
fact we will write about all that thinking,'' and so on. Rainer
advises audience members: ``You kind of roll with the different
elements that keep coming to the surface and disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Rainer and Baryshnikov in a studio together makes perfect
sense. Both have short spiky hair, long torsos and arms, boyish
bodies. When they kissed each other hello they seemed to be exactly
the same height, and their rehearsal demeanor has a similar balance
of readiness and calm. They understand each other's physicality,
and more, they seem to understand each other's state of mind.
Rainer said, ``He has this restless intellect that's led him into
this '60s corner of dancing.'' He affectionately called her a
``professional revolutionary,'' and added, ``It's fun to see such
passion in her.''
</P>
<P>
   While rehearsing the group sections, the six White Oak dancers _
besides Baryshnikov, they are Raquel Aedo, Emily Coates, Roselynde
LeBlanc, Michael Lomeka and Emmanuele Phuon have vivid
personalities and dance technique to burn, but Baryshnikov shows
slightly more relish for the movement than the younger performers
do.
</P>
<P>
   A high point of the piece is sure to be ``Valda's Solo,''
originally from Rainer's first film, ``Lives of Performers''
(1972). Here, it reveals Baryshnikov in a different mood. He wears
a velvet gown, and lets a red ball roll off his hand and drop to
the floor. Not much happens, but it's riveting. While the dancer
and actor Valda Setterfield looked elegant and aristocratic in the
film, Baryshnikov looks lonely and pensive, creating an aura of
melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   Far in the pasts of both Rainer and Baryshnikov are precursors
to this collaboration. Baryshnikov started dancing with modern
dance choreographers soon after he defected from the Soviet Union
in 1974, including Twyla Tharp, Alvin Ailey, Martha Graham, Paul
Taylor, Erick Hawkins and Merce Cunningham. Even earlier, during
his last year in St. Petersburg, he presented a program in which he
chose and danced in works by experimental choreographers, including
Mai Murdmaa from Estonia. She had him rolling on the floor _ quite
simple and grounded compared to what his audience expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer and ballet critic Nina Alovert recently said:
``From the beginning, he wanted to do contemporary dance. He tried
to do every way of ballet which we've had in Russia. In 1971 he
danced in `Creation of the World' by Natalia Kasatkina. It was
everything not classical. It combined knees turned in and knees
turned out. He danced it like a god.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainer remembers seeing Alicia Markova dance ``Giselle'' in the
late 1950s. ``She was the only dancer I have ever waited for at the
stage door,'' Rainer said. ``I was totally transported.''
</P>
<P>
   Much later, one of the many bits in ``The Mind Is a Muscle'' was
something she called the ``Nijinsky pose.'' In the new piece, she
extends the cushion section with a kind of classical pas de deux
with Coates, the most obviously balletic of the White Oak women,
partnered by Baryshnikov with pillows. She is using their
virtuosity as a ``found object,'' in almost the same way visual
artists like Robert Rauschenberg did in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Baryshnikov traces his interest in Judson Dance Theater back to
David Gordon, whom he invited to choreograph for American Ballet
Theater when he was its artistic director. Gordon created ``Field,
Chair and Mountain'' (1986), in which Martine van Hamel was
promenaded on point on top of a metal folding chair.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said of Baryshnikov's being drawn to this experimental
work: ``His attraction is to dance with integrity. He's willing to
back up his own taste and intuitions. He refuses to stay in the
past. He takes other people's past and tries it on; he's an
inquisitive guy.'' The choregrapher Trisha Brown has called
Baryshnikov ``a questing spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   His quest, at this point, is partly a search for what sits
comfortably in the mind as well as on the body of a no-longer-young
dancer who wants to keep dancing. Two years ago, Baryshnikov told
Laura Shapiro of Newsweek: ``I've gotten into minimalism in my
dancing. In the first part of life you accumulate experience, and
then at the end you try to get rid of what's not necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainer started getting rid of the extras early on. In fact, it
was her modus operandi as a dance minimalist. After working on
``Parts of Some Sextets,'' she wrote the now-famous manifesto, ``NO
to spectacle no to virtuosity no to transformations and magic and
make-believe no to the glamour and transcendency of the star image
no to the heroic ...,'' first published in 1965 in The Drama
Review. But in the new piece, she uses not only Baryshnikov's
heroic image, but also a new text about transformation _ an essay
by Vladimir Nabokov about a caterpillar turning into a butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of her manifesto, Rainer now says, ``One of the
functions of a manifesto is to clear the air, to start over or
re-examine expectations.'' Here, Rainer and Baryshnikov join
together in the postmodern project of re-examining, reconstructing,
reanalyzing and representing. He is re-examining his role(s) in the
dance world and she is reconstructing and rearranging her works
from the past.
</P>
<P>
   For Rainer, the challenge is to bring her quotidian, tasklike
dances onto a proscenium stage.
</P>
<P>
   One of her few forays into such a situation was at the Billy
Rose Theater on Broadway in 1969, when the producer Charles
Reinhardt invited several young, unorthodox choreographers to
perform, including Twyla Tharp, Meredith Monk and Rainer. Pat
Catterson, new in New York at the time, remembers the effect that
Rainer's ``Rose Fractions'' had on her: ``I'd never seen anything
like it. It was in that anything-can-follow-anything mode. In one
part, Yvonne did Lenny Bruce's monologue on snot. In another part,
dancers and nondancers were doing `Trio A.' It was unpretentious,
accessible, egalitarian and totally of the moment. They ended by
doing it to the Chambers Brothers' `In the Midnight Hour,' and the
audience was on its feet hooting and howling. We all felt like we
wanted to do that. After it was over, some audience members went
right up on the stage and did it. When I got home, I did all the
moves I could remember from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainer is enjoying her return to the dance world: ``I love
working with dancers. I've never been entirely comfortable as a
filmmaker because I never shot my own film. I'm a techno-idiot, so
much of it is out of my control. Here I feel like I'm back where I
belong. It's like coming home, at least temporarily.'' She has the
utmost regard for Baryshnikov's choice to delve into dances of the
rebellious '60s. ``It's unprecedented for a classical dancer to do
this,'' she said. ``And he's pulling in an audience that, in many
cases, is unfamiliar with that history. So in that sense he is a
revitalizing force in the dance world.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month while on tour, after two standing-room-only
performances by White Oak in Clearwater, Fla., Rainer faxed this
report: ``The first night we softened them up. Misha introduced me
and I basically told them not to worry. They laughed at everything.
The second night: no introduction, much more subdued response
during the piece, but at the end, a combination of standing ovation
and boos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
