<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0133 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1STLD-     05-30 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VISITS EUROPE FACING SAMES ISSUES REAGAN ENCOUNTERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for rewriting, updating and additional information; adds
dateline and changes byline; story grows by about 925 words and is
now 2 takes)  
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ President Clinton on Tuesday became the first
president to visit Portugal since Ronald Reagan in 1985, and as
Clinton opened his last scheduled trip to Europe as president, he
found himself confronting the same major issues that Reagan faced _
trade disputes and missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   While Reagan supported a space-based missile defense system
known as Star Wars, Clinton will be pushing his own plan to deploy
a limited missile defense system, if he can reach agreement on
modifying the 28-year-old Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   As they had done for days leading up to the trip, aides to
Clinton stressed again Tuesday that they did not expect him to
reach any concrete agreements, as Reagan also failed to do 15 years
ago. But in contrast to the significant anti-American
demonstrations that Reagan received, only one ``Clinton Go Home''
slogan was seen Tuesday on a wall in Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   An article Tuesday in the left-of-center daily Publico
underscored the difficulty Clinton faces in selling his missile
defense initiative _ not only to Russia but also to the rest of the
world. The newspaper compared Clinton's dilemma to that of Reagan
on ``Star Wars,'' saying Clinton will ``have to persuade his
European partners that the new American anti-missile defense system
that the U.S. wants to develop can bring advantages to European
security and world peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a difficult task,'' the article continued,
``especially for a president at the end of his career, in the face
of negative reaction already expressed in most European capitals.
Europe is afraid that this initiative, a `soft' version of Ronald
Reagan `Star Wars' in the '80s, will end up triggering a new arms
race, alienating Russia and feeding Beijing's nuclear ambitions.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Few people turned out to see Clinton on Tuesday. But the
president still found that the opening day of his weeklong trip to
Europe was full of mutual praise and old-fashioned sightseeing, and
his day of meetings with a close ally was relatively free of
contentious issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reinforced just how enjoyable a day it had been, saying
in a toast to Portugal's president, Jorge Sampaio, at a state
dinner Tuesday night: ``It has been a pleasure for me to spend time
with another president who likes to read detective novels, listen
to good music and play golf. We could have had a two-day summit on
those three topics alone.''
</P>
<P>
   From here Clinton will travel to Berlin, to Moscow _ where he
will have his first meeting with Russian President Vladimir Putin _
and finally to Kiev, Ukraine. While in Berlin, he will also meet
privately with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who will be
attending a political conference along with Clinton and other
leaders. The two leaders are expected to discuss Israel's
withdrawal from southern Lebanon last week and the status of
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Welcoming Clinton to Portugal on Tuesday, Sampaio said: ``It was
from here five centuries ago that the Portuguese navigators _ who
explored the Atlantic coast of Africa, discovered the maritime
route to India, found Brazil and circumnavigated the earth _ set
sail. Our increasingly globalized world owes a lot to their
deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton echoed Sampaio's words, saying, ``Here at this historic
point of embarkation, from which Portuguese explorers led an entire
continent to see beyond the horizon, we find ourselves again, as
you said, Mr. President, on a new voyage of discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The two men stood together at the sun-bleached limestone
16th-century Belem Tower at the entrance to Lisbon's harbor, where
Portuguese frigates honored Clinton with a 21-gun salute. The two
presidents reviewed an honor guard of paratroopers in fatigues,
white gloves and purple ascots who are headed to East Timor as part
of a United Nations peacekeeping force. Portugal asserted residual
rights over East Timor, which is now moving toward independence,
for more than two decades after the territory was seized by
Indonesia in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that this nation is proud of those troops and their
mission, and on behalf of the American people, I thank you for
it,'' Clinton told Sampaio.
</P>
<P>
   From there, a cavalry regiment of musicians on horseback led
Clinton's motorcade to the Jeronimos Monastery in the town of
Belem. There, he laid a wreath at the carved tomb of poet Luis
Camoes and spent half an hour touring the 16th-century structure.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a tour of the interactive Knowledge Science Center,
Clinton told scientists and researchers, ``I have just had a lot of
fun.'' He also praised what he called cutting-edge research across
national boundaries on diseases like AIDS, malaria and
tuberculosis. ``These diseases can ruin economies and threaten the
very survival of societies,'' said Clinton, whose administration
has elevated issues like disease to the top of the national
security agenda.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, at the 17th-century Queluz Palace outside Lisbon,
Clinton will meet with the European Commission's president, Romano
Prodi, and Portugal's prime minister, Antonio Guterres. Portugal
currently holds the six-month rotating presidency of the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and the 15-nation European Union are locked in
complicated disputes over European restrictions on the importation
of bananas, U.S. beef and genetically modified foods.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the European Union objects to a sales tax
break that the United Sates grants to major corporations that set
up operations in offshore tax havens like the Virgin Islands and
Barbados. Those companies are not required to pay U.S. sales tax
and duties on their exports, which the European Union argues is a
form of subsidy that will amount to about $25 billion to U.S.
companies over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, Clinton will attend a meeting with leaders of more
than a dozen other countries on ``third way'' politics hosted by
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. The approach, also described as
``progressive governance,'' explores a middle ground between
traditional forms of socialism and capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Aachen, Germany, on Friday, Clinton will be awarded the
International Charlemagne Prize, presented annually to a person who
has worked toward European unity. Other recipients of the award
have been Winston S. Churchill and Francois Mitterrand. The only
Americans to have received the award have been George C. Marshall,
author of America's plan to rebuild Europe after World War II, and
former Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   During the weekend, Clinton will be in Moscow for his first
summit meeting with Putin. Samuel R. Berger, the national security
adviser, told reporters last week that the visit would produce no
breakthroughs in arms control or Russia's objections to a U.S.
missile defense plan.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton will address the Russian Parliament, the
first U.S. president to do so. Later that day, he will travel to
Ukraine for a meeting with President Leonid Kuchma before heading
home to Washington that night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton has less than eight months left as president, but in
some quarters he is already being talked about in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's article in Publico, the Portuguese daily, said of his
visit: ``On the other side of the Atlantic, he is looked as if he
already belonged to the past. In Europe, he is being given the
prize to those who have aided the European cause. Bill Clinton was
a good president to Europe.'' The article was titled, ``Clinton
Says Goodbye to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   And Portugal's leading tabloid newspaper, Correio da Manha,
focused on Clinton's enormous $4,000-a-night suite at the Dom Pedro
Hotel. Situated on the top floor, it has, the newspaper said, a
panoramic view of the capital, ``a private elevator for security,
luxury furniture, original works of art, a spacious hall, tropical
plants, a bar, a winter garden and a private terrace of 160 square
meters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It also has a private dining room for 12 people, with a
terrace of 60 square meters, connected to a fully equipped
kitchen,'' it continued. ``The suite has two more rooms, the bigger
of which looks out to a natural solarium. There is a dressing room
and a marble bathroom connected to this room, as well as panoramic
vistas over Lisbon, a sauna, a Jacuzzi with hydro massage.''
</P>
<P>
   At the state dinner Tuesday night, Clinton was serenaded by
Mafalda Arnauth, Portugal's hottest young fado singer. Fado is
melancholic Portuguese music played with string instruments and
built around the concept of saudades, the yearning for a past that
was better and may never return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
