<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FCC Proposes Relaxing Some Broadcasting Rules
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission proposed easing several
decades-old regulations on broadcasters, including one that
prevents companies from owning a broadcast station and newspaper in
the same city and another prohibiting a company from owning more
than one national television network. The proposals may
significantly affect several pending and recently completed
mergers. Existing rules would have required significant
divestitures after Viacom's acquisition of CBS and the Tribune
Co.'s proposed purchase of Times Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Breakup Fees Detailed in Airline Deal
</P>
<P>
   According to a copy of the proposed merger agreement between
United Airlines and US Airways filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, US Airways would have to pay $160 million to
United's parent, UAL, if it breached the contract, while UAL would
be forced to pay $50 million to US Airways if it got cold feet. In
addition, either company can terminate the agreement if the merger
is not completed by Dec. 31. Shares of US Airways rose 6.25 cents,
to $43.625, while UAL fell 81.25 cents, to $51.9375.
</P>
<P>
   NTT of Japan Is Urged to Cut Fees
</P>
<P>
   Senior members of Japan's ruling party are pressing Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone, the dominant telecommunications company,
to reduce the high connection fees charged to competitors, an issue
that has caused deep trade friction with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Confidence Resurfaces
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence surged in May, according to the Conference
Board, to 144.4, close to the record it reached in January despite
the roller coaster stock market and six increases in interest rates
in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Tackles Clean Air Act
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court expanded its continuing review of the Clean
Air Act to consider the economic costs. The court's action raised
the stakes even higher in a case, to be argued next fall, that
already promised to be one of the most important environmental and
administrative law cases in years.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Nicest Man on Wall Street
</P>
<P>
   It was luck that got him out of Nazi Germany in the 1930s, John
H. Slade says, and luck that got him his first job in New York as a
runner for Bear, Stearns at $15 a week. Decades later, he says, it
was a lucky encounter on a train that led to romance and marriage.
Today, Slade, 92, the honorary chairman of the executive committee
at Bear, Stearns, puts in a four-day week and calls himself ``the
luckiest man in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's Board Choice Is Criticized
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Baron, whose investment funds are the largest outside
investors in Sotheby's Holdings, says electing Robert Taubman, the
son of the company's former chairman, to its board, would represent
a conflict of interest in the face of the continuing criminal
investigation into price fixing at the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Access for Road Warriors
</P>
<P>
   Larry Brilliant, chairman of SoftNet Systems, empathizes with
business travelers in need of computer access. A unit of his
company plans to start a system of wireless networks in airports,
hotels and convention centers that will sell high-speed Internet
services and e-mail access.
</P>
</TEXT>
