<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GREENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN, NATURAL LAW PARTIES MOVE CLOSER TO TEXAS BALLOT 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Two alternative political parties met a Tuesday
deadline for delivering petitions to Texas election officials in a
bid for space on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party of Texas collected an estimated 74,000
signatures, and the Natural Law Party of Texas said it collected
about 76,000.
</P>
<P>
   To get their candidates on the ballot, the parties had to
collect 37,380 signatures from registered voters who did not
participate in this year's Democratic or Republican party
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Sandage, a Houston mediator and Green Party candidate for
U.S. Senate, said his party's apparent success in gathering
signatures is evidence of the desire among voters for political
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message is that the two big parties are merely
ding and dong, and voters need a third choice,'' Sandage said. ``I
really think the desire for a third-party alternative, more than
our party's environmental issues, got me more signatures than
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Nickless, assistant director of elections in the Texas
secretary of state's office, said it could take all summer to
verify the two parties' petitions.
</P>
<P>
   If enough signatures are validated, the parties will appear on
the Texas ballot with the Democratic and Republican parties, plus
the Libertarian Party.
</P>
<P>
   Libertarians won automatic ballot access without petitioning
this year, after one of their statewide candidates in 1998 won more
than 5 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Less successful in their petition efforts this year were the
Reform Party of Texas and the Constitution Party of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution Party submitted only about 2,500 signatures, in
part to protest what organizers claim is the two-party system's
dominance of the election process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to demonstrate to the Legislature how impossible it is
to get on the ballot in this state,'' said Jim Wade, state chairman
of the Constitution Party. ``It's ridiculous, it's Draconian.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, Reform Party members alerted state election
officials that the party would not be submitting petitions to
appear on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The party, which grew from 1992's United We Stand effort
launched by Dallas billionaire Ross Perot, was unable to fulfill an
ambitious plan to collect signatures in Texas this year.
</P>
<P>
   Many party activists have blamed Pat Buchanan, a presidential
contender who bolted the Republican Party for the Reform Party last
year, with helping to derail the party's statewide efforts.
</P>
<P>
   To secure his own place on the Texas ballot, Buchanan in early
May submitted his own petitions as an independent candidate,
calling it ``insurance'' in case the Reform Party failed in its
statewide efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he will seek the party's presidential nomination
at its convention this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party, meanwhile, is fielding four candidates for
statewide office in Texas, including Sandage, who is challenging
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party presidential nominee is expected to be national
consumer advocate Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   The Natural Law Party is fielding 31 candidates in Texas. The
party's presidential nominee is likely to be John Hagelin, who also
is seeking the Reform Party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley Brooks, who is stepping down as Natural Law Party
chairman to run Hagelin's campaign, said getting on the ballot in a
large state like Texas is central to building credibility for
alternative political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real desire out there for something other than the
same old, same old,'' Brooks said. ``Voters feel that democracy has
been stolen from them. I think people really want to take it back,
and there is a huge voice out there crying to be heard.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
