<SLUG> BC-HUNT-LAWSUIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMAR HUNT JR. SETTLES ASSAULT LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ As potential jurors waited to be picked Tuesday
morning, Lamar Hunt Jr. settled a civil lawsuit that alleged he
sexually assaulted his mentally disabled sister-in-law on three
evenings in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas County District Judge John McClellan Marshall ruled that
provisions of the settlement were confidential. He instructed
lawyers not to discuss its details.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt Jr., 43, son of Kansas City Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt and
owner of a 20 percent share of the Chiefs, attended a closed
hearing on the settlement. He slipped out a side door at its
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   He was not charged criminally for the episodes alleged in the
civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going home,'' his lawyer, Donald H. Flanary, said after
the hearing, declining further comment on the case. Hunt Jr. now
lives in a Dallas suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Baldwin, a lawyer representing Judy Fitzpatrick, Hunt Jr.'s
sister-in-law, would speak only generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judy Fitzpatrick is very happy and pleased to have this whole
torrid story behind her so she can pick up the pieces of her
life,'' Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick, 42, declined to comment as she left the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   According to her lawsuit, Fitzpatrick has been diagnosed with
``severe learning disabilities, cognitive deficits and social
deficiencies.'' Baldwin said she now lived with family members in
Pennsylvania and worked in a cannery.
</P>
<P>
   A former Kansas City resident, Hunt Jr. was an acclaimed flutist
with the Kansas City Symphony for 11 years before returning to
Dallas in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt Jr.; his brothers, Clark and Daniel; and his sister,
Sharron Munson, each own 20 percent of the Chiefs under a trust
established in 1997 as part of his father's succession plan, which
ensures that the team remains in the family. The elder Hunt
retained the remaining 20 percent and serves as the club's owner.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Lamar Hunt Jr. worked for the Chiefs as a promotions
manager.
</P>
<P>
   In her lawsuit filed in December, Fitzpatrick alleged that Hunt
Jr. came to her room and forced her to perform sex acts three times
while she was visiting his family in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In his formal response, Hunt Jr. acknowledged engaging in sexual
activity with Fitzpatrick but contended she participated willingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hunt Jr.) specifically denies (Fitzpatrick) ever showed any
fear in connection with their sexual activity, and to the contrary,
she freely participated in sexual activity with (Hunt Jr.),''
according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Had the case gone to trial, a key piece of evidence would have
been a 10-page handwritten document prepared by Hunt Jr. sometime
after October 1997 and titled ``Confessions of a Sex Addict.''
</P>
<P>
   In great detail, Hunt Jr. described his sexual and spiritual
history from age 11 to the alleged assault on Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made unwanted advances on her on consecutive nights,'' Hunt
Jr. wrote. ``...If this is disturbing I am sorry, but I think that
for whatever reason God wants me to expel this demon once and for
all and make that complete and thorough confession once and for
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he begged for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Judy, I am sorry for the repulsiveness of my behavior to
your honor as a woman,'' Hunt Jr. wrote. ``I hope you can forgive
me....To God, I throw myself on your mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanary has acknowledged that his client wrote the letter but in
court filings argued that Hunt Jr. was not a sex addict. In a
deposition given earlier this month, Hunt Jr. acknowledged he was
under treatment by a therapist for ``obsessive compulsive
disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Hunt Jr.'s wife, Jocelyn, filed for divorce, citing as
evidence the 10-page ``confession.'' No final decree has been
issued. They have seven children.
</P>
<P>
   Court records showed the couple had spent about $1.25 million
litigating the divorce, including fees for legal work and
psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   In those records Hunt Jr. acknowledged he once estimated his net
worth at $95 million, though now he says it is between $5 million
and $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   He is an employee of Unity Hunt, a company that services the
Lamar Hunt family and its interests and assets. He also is a member
of partnerships that own the United Center basketball arena in
Chicago and present cable television broadcasts of Chicago sporting
events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
