<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0149 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-FCC-CROSS-OWNERSHIP-1     05-30 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC-CROSS-OWNERSHIP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC MOVES TO RELAX SOME LIMITS ON OWNERSHIP OF MEDIA OUTLETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs graf 12 to give full name of WB, graf 13 to clarify timing of
when rules would be implemented; graf 14 to explain how New York
area would be affected; graf 16 to change `prevented a company' to
`prevented the stations owned by a company'; graf 19 to change `one
company' to `one company's stations' and change `wisest' to
`widest'; graf 21 delete reference to `Washington group')  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Communications Commission on Tuesday
proposed to ease several decades-old regulations on broadcasters,
including one that prevents companies from owning a broadcast
station and newspaper in the same city and another prohibiting a
company from owning more than one national television network.
</P>
<P>
   In a biennial review that Congress ordered as part of its
overhaul of the telecommunications industry four years ago, the FCC
said it had begun preparing new rules to relax, but not eliminate,
both the cross-ownership and dual-network restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   It also proposed easing the way the listening audience of local
radio markets are measured by regulators in a way that could enable
companies to own more stations than they do under current limits.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals may have significant implications for several
pending and recently completed mergers in the broadcast and
newspaper industries. Existing rules would have required
significant divestitures after Viacom's acquisition of CBS and
Tribune Co.'s proposed purchase of Times Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said some restrictions had become outdated as
Americans increasingly turned to new technologies like satellite
television and high-speed Internet services offered through
telephone and cable companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a wave of corporate deals has led to new
levels of concentration in the broadcast, cable and telephone
industries, testing the ownership limits imposed by both the FCC
and Congress in the Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media marketplace has become increasingly dynamic and
competitive, with an expanding number of information outlets and
media platforms and more Americans than ever before are using these
options,'' said William E. Kennard, the FCC's chairman. ``The
report we issue today balances the public interest in diversity of
ownership with the demands of a changing marketplace and the
broadcast industries' need to realize economic efficiencies and
remain competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the cross-ownership and dual-network regulations were
rooted in the idea of promoting diversity of the airwaves, and
officials at the FCC said they were not planning on eliminating the
restrictions but easing them in particular cases.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the proposed changes outlined Tuesday are more gradual
than some large companies had sought, they mark a significant
policy change for the FCC, which has defended legal attacks and
criticisms over the rules for many years.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the cross-ownership rules, the FCC said there was
still a need for restrictions in many areas across the country to
prevent a company from controlling both a newspaper and television
station.
</P>
<P>
   But the FCC also concluded that in some cities, particularly
large ones with many media outlets, ``there might be situations in
which the rule may not be necessary to protect the public interest
in diversity and competition.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the dual-network rule, the FCC said that two
emerging television networks, UPN and Warner Brothers, were still
developing and ought to be able to attempt to attract new
investments from a major network. But FCC officials said they would
not alter rules that prevent the four majors _ ABC, CBS, Fox and
NBC _ from acquiring one another.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expect the proposed rules to be issued in the next few
months, and the commission would then consider them. The proposed
changes have come after heavy lobbying by some of the nation's
largest broadcasting and newspaper companies, which have big stakes
in trying to hold onto recently acquired television companies.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-ownership restrictions have threatened to force
Tribune Co., which has agreed to buy Times Mirror, to sell some
properties in three cities _ New York, Los Angeles and Hartford,
Conn. _ where the companies have newspapers and broadcasting
properties. In New York, Tribune would own both WPIX, a WB
affiliate, and Newsday, which is based in Long Island. The Tribune
Co. has also spent years trying to persuade the fcc to permit it to
own both a newspaper and a television station in Fort Lauderdale,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The dual-network rule has threatened to force Viacom, which
recently completed its acquisition of CBS, to sell its half
interest in UPN. When it approved the deal four weeks ago, the FCC
gave Viacom one year to sell its stake in UPN. But if the agency
finishes writing new rules before then, the company might not have
to put the network up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC stopped short of recommending any easing of the
limitations that have prevented the stations owned by a company
from reaching more than 35 percent of the national television
audience, prompting Fox, which is at the limit and wants to
continue to expand, to immediately file a lawsuit against the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC decision today is a textbook case of arbitrary and
capricious government action,'' said Chase Carey, chairman and
chief executive of Fox Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The national TV ownership cap, which may have served a purpose
in the days when only three TV networks competed in local markets,
long ago outlived its rational and is now harming rather than
promoting its original public interest objectives of diversity,
localism and competition,'' he said. ``In an era in which scores of
nationwide programming networks are available to viewers from cable
and satellite providers, it makes no sense to artificially limit
the number of markets in which broadcasters can compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said that Fox's argument had confused trends in the
local market with trends in the national market and that there
remained a compelling need to prevent any one company's stations
from controlling the national market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of Americans still get most of their news and
public affairs information from broadcast stations, and in a
participatory democracy like ours, it is vitally important that we
encourage the widest possible dissemination of this information
from diverse and antagonistic sources,'' he said. ``Our structural
ownership restrictions seek to promote this First Amendment
principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics said that Kennard's own observation that most
Americans relied heavily on broadcasting to get their news
demonstrated the need to keep the cross-ownership in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadcasting remains the single most important source of
information at the local level for many many voters, and most of
the rest get their information from newspapers,'' said Andrew Jay
Schwartzman, president of the Media Access Project, which promotes
diversity on the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have these voices controlled by fewer and fewer owners
cannot help democracy,'' he said. ``The evolution of the Internet
has yet to make any significant change on how people decide to cast
their vote for the mayor. The degree to which a few large economic
powers in any community can control the debate is no less today
than it has been in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
