<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT     05-30 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREMIER, IT SEEMS, ISN'T ALONE IN SEEING JAPAN AS DIVINE
</HEADLINE>
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ With a furor over his characterization of Japan
threatening his party's hold on power, Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori
stood before journalists for 40 minutes last Friday denying that he
had blurred the boundary between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's strenuous self-defense rested on his contention that in
calling Japan ``a divine country with an emperor at its center,''
he had intended to say nothing more than that the emperor is a
popular and cherished national symbol.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the prime minister's intentions, by touching on a
taboo subject with such little caution he has shown the jagged edge
of a nostalgic form of nationalism that is enjoying a powerful
resurgence among conservative politicians.
</P>
<P>
   His statement continues to embroil his office, giving his
cabinet a 19 percent approval rating in a poll after he had made
the remarks, the lowest ratings of any prime minister on the eve of
national elections.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the denials is that the pronouncement was a
perfect summation of State Shinto, the official religion that drove
Japan's expansionism in Asia and its war with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mori may have denied that he was advocating a state religion or
deification of the emperor, as existed in the past, saying, ``That
is utterly contrary to my personal belief.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics said it strained credulity for him to argue that his
phrase, uttered before a Shinto political group, was unrelated to
militarist Japan's wartime creed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course he recognized the nuance of what he said, and tried
to show his sympathy for the people he was addressing,'' said
Takeshi Sasaki, a professor of politics at Tokyo University. ``He
tries to do this at whatever gathering. It may not have seemed like
a very serious statement, but it has become a very serious
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   To be properly understood, critics and historians say, the
``divine nation'' remarks must be seen in the light of recent
right-wing statements and initiatives that call for, among other
goals, moral indoctrination for youth, a clampdown on foreigners,
and a national holiday to honor the wartime emperor, Hirohito.
</P>
<P>
   Late last summer, conservatives in the legislature won passage
of a law to legalize the flag and a national anthem that is a paean
to the emperor. Others have begun agitating for rearming the
country, potentially even with nuclear weapons. A deputy defense
minister, Shingo Nishimura, had to resign in the fall in a storm of
criticism after he made such a proposal.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the conservatives' project is the revision of a
constitution written under American occupation and a dream of
reversion to a mythical state that is strong and unsullied by undue
foreign influences.
</P>
<P>
   That members of the Liberal Democratic Party, which has governed
since 1955, except for a period of less than two years, openly
contemplate such ideas is at once an expression of the party's
strength and its weakness.
</P>
<P>
   The party remains powerful because more than ever it lacks an
effective opposition. Even the diplomatic constraints of the Cold
War, when Japan was locked in an anticommunist alliance with the
United States and several Asian countries, have faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although many LDP members have a reactionary view of history,
they were not able to express themselves, because of the
overwhelming influence of the United States on the one hand and
because of the restraint required by the international situation in
East Asia on the other,'' said Yasuaki Onuma, a professor
international law at Tokyo University. ``However, with the sharp
decline of the Socialist Party and the end of the Cold War, the
feeling of the majority is that we have gone too far in keeping
silent on the issues of our relationships with others and national
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the constraints have loosened, the Liberal Democratic
Party has been weakened by a decade of economic decline as severe
as any advanced nation has experienced since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there is no strong opposition, the party owes its
governing majority to an unusual and unpopular alliance with a
pacifist Buddhist-affiliated party. And nowadays, most voters are
skeptical independents.
</P>
<P>
   Seen in this light, the appeals to the values and methods of the
past may simply reflect a party desperately reaching to the past
for answers to Japan's problems _ and to appeal to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's plummeting poll numbers since the ``divine country''
remarks, however, strongly suggest that such a clumsy approach is
doomed to backfire.
</P>
<P>
   And the ruling class' nostalgia may cost it more than votes.
When a legislator states, as one did in Parliament this week, that
Hirohito ``built today's peaceful and prosperous Japan,'' the first
casualty is the truth.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the historical record, as long as the leaders remain
prisoners of an unexamined past, other countries will continue to
look on Japan as an insincere, untrustworthy and potentially
threatening nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mori refusal to retract his statement harms Japan, and
understandably so, because for Westerners in particular, Pearl
Harbor caused Japan to be labeled as treacherous,'' said Herbert P.
Bix, an American historian at Hitsosubashi University in Tokyo, and
author of a coming biography of Hirohito. ``His explanation borders
on deceitfulness of the worst sort. Over and over again in Japanese
politics, you can see leaders speaking out of both sides of the
mouth, and the result is that Japan just isn't trusted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
