u w BC-GLICKMAN-PIE-NYT &LR;      05-30 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLICKMAN-PIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTER'S PIE GRAZES AGRICULTURE SECRETARY GLICKMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The secretary of agriculture, a former House member
from Kansas, had just begun to speak at the opening session of the
National Nutrition Summit here Tuesday when an animal rights
protester leaped onto the stage and threw a pie at him.
</P>
<P>
   The protester's message was loud and clear: ``Shame on you, Dan
Glickman, you meathead. Shame on you for promoting meat.'' But her
aim was off.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman ducked, and the pie _ tofu cream, according to members
of People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, with which the
protester claimed association _ grazed the back of Glickman's
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   As Glickman peeled off his jacket to reveal a lilac colored
shirt, he didn't miss a beat: ``That was not a very balanced meal
she threw at me.'' Then he turned to former Sen. Bob Dole, who was
also on the stage, and said, ``Bob, I don't think we're in Kansas
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman was one of the speakers at the nutrition meeting,
convened 31 years after the original White House Conference on Food
Nutrition and Health, which was instrumental in starting many of
the government food assistance programs that are now familiar, like
Head Start and the school breakfast program.
</P>
<P>
   The pie thrower, Arathi Jayaram, 24, of Mansfield, Ohio, who
lives in northern Virginia, is a member of People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals. She was carried out by a member of Glickman's
security team with help from a guard assigned to Donna Shalala, the
secretary of health and human services, who was also on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Jayaram was reportedly charged with assault. She is being held
by the Washington Metropolitan Police Department and will be
arraigned on Wednesday morning. The charge carries a recommended
penalty of up to a year in jail, but there is no category in
federal sentencing guidelines for assault with a pie in a
disposable aluminum tin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
