<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JESSE-JAMES-HNS &LR;      05-30 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSE-JAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAVE EXHUMED OF MAN WHO CLAIMED TO BE JESSE JAMES &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Efforts to determine if the ``real'' Jesse
James is buried south of here in Granbury were delayed slightly
Tuesday when workers exhumed a grave and found a sealed, metal
coffin instead of a wooden box.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason we had thought it would be a wooden
container,'' said spokeswoman Mary Saltarelli.
</P>
<P>
   Saltarelli said the entire coffin must be removed and would be
opened at an enclosed location later. Previously, anthropologist
David Glassman from Southwest Texas State University in San Marcos
had hoped to open the coffin in the grave and retrieve matter for
testing immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Material from the coffin, hair, bones and teeth will be sent to
the University of California at Davis for DNA testing by Professor
David Glenn Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the Granbury site has been simmering for years, ever
since a man known as J. Frank Dalton claimed to be the true Jesse
James.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, who came to Granbury shortly after 1900, repeated his
claim often. He lived until 1951, at which time he would have been
104 if he were Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   However, scars on Dalton's body were consistent with James'
exploits and many believed him. The story eventually found its way
to Bud Hardcastle, a Purcell, Okla., used car dealer and amateur
historian.
</P>
<P>
   Hardcastle secured a power of attorney from Dalton's known
relatives and was granted a court order to exhume the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton's claims were at odds with historians, who believe James
was killed by Bob Ford in 1882 in St. Joseph, Mo. James Starrs, a
George Washington University professor, exhumed what has been held
to be James' grave in Kearney, Mo., in 1995 and tested material
then.
</P>
<P>
   Those tests, which compared DNA results with a known DNA profile
of a James family descendant, showed the body was that of a man
related to the James family.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the best that will be determined about any
gravesite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tests are exclusionary,'' said Smith, who will do the
testing on the Granbury material. ``We can tell you he wasn't Jesse
James or that he could be Jesse James, but not that he definitely
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will show whether he was a descendant.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he hopes to begin tests within two weeks after
receiving the samples and should be finished by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
