<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0166 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT     05-30 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AFTER THE FALL, IN TOO MUCH OF A HURRY? 
</HEADLINE>
  By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Poor little Ricky.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he could scamper away from the Clinton curse.
</P>
<P>
   But there was the curse, slouching towards Babylon. The day
before the biggest day of Rick Lazio's life _ his speech in Buffalo
accepting the Republican nomination for the Senate, with all the
cameras zooming in for a close-up of that boyish grin. Bam! Splat!
Thwack!
</P>
<P>
   The guy falls flat on his face at the Babylon Memorial Day
parade and cuts his lip so badly he has to get eight stitches, and
the lip gets so swollen it's hard to talk and smile, and
fuhgeddabout kissing babies with that scary kisser.
</P>
<P>
   David Letterman was already having a ball: ``Rick Lazio. One day
you're a busboy at the Olive Garden, the next day you're running
for Senate against Hillary Clinton. ... Rick Lazio. Isn't he that
Cuban kid's uncle?''
</P>
<P>
   So then Ricky has to take his big bow to the theme from
``Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody should just come out and ask Hillary if she's got one
of those tannis-root charms, the kind Ralph Bellamy and Ruth Gordon
made Mia Farrow wear in ``Rosemary's Baby.'' That gal has left way
too many spooky casualties in her wake.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, you never want a misstep to be upgraded to
metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Ford was a college athlete. But when his stumbles were
lampooned by Chevy Chase, the humor resonated because Americans
deemed Ford politically clumsy. His first act as president had been
a pratfall _ pardoning Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   When Jimmy Carter collapsed while jogging in black socks, it
crystallized the sense that he was a wimp. We were fine; he had
malaise.
</P>
<P>
   When a railing gave way and Bob Dole tumbled off a stage in
Chico, Calif., in '96, it reinforced the idea that his campaign was
in free fall and his time had passed.
</P>
<P>
   In the New Hampshire primary last winter, Gary Bauer plummeted
backward off a stage while flipping pancakes. Four days later his
campaign did a back flip offstage as well.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, when Bill Clinton tore a tendon in the wee hours
while visiting the golfer Greg Norman in Florida in 1997, it had no
figurative echo. Everybody simply reckoned that the president had
been cavorting a bit.
</P>
<P>
   But when Little Ricky went tumbling down, the stature issue came
bubbling up.
</P>
<P>
   He looked like an eager puppy springing out of the gate and
going all splay-legged. Republicans fretted again: Is he ready for
the big show?
</P>
<P>
   It was the most overcaffeinated entry into a race since George
Bush announced Dan Quayle as his running mate in New Orleans.
Little Danny, another congressional pup itching for the sun, raced
up and hugged the startled Bush, looking, for one terrifying
moment, as if he were going to lick the older man's cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had been leery of Little Ricky's gratingly unsubtle
ambition. Couldn't he at least thinly veil it? The New York GOP had
had to yank at the 42-year-old's leash after he noisily gnawed Rudy
Giuliani's leg before the mayor learned he was sick and dropped
out.
</P>
<P>
   When the nomination suddenly fell into the Long Island
congressman's lap, he was off and running, fairly panting with
charm, as Dorothy Parker might put it. At the parade on Monday, he
was doing so much dashing and bounding and nuzzling and zigzagging,
you just wanted to call out, ``Down, boy, down.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd think a face gushing blood would be a great excuse to get
out of a parade. But the dazed Lazio tried to keep going as though
nothing had happened until his wife, a nurse, made him go to the
hospital. When he rushed back, stitched and swollen, for a second
parade, sprinting and air-kissing, Giuliani patted him on the back.
(Down, boy, down.)
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has the self-promoting energy of Chuck Schumer and Bob
Torricelli without the craftiness. He came out swinging in Buffalo,
joking about getting a rematch with the pavement, pillorying
Hillary as the candidate of Hollywood and left-wing special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   He has already accomplished the impossible: He has made the
first lady, relentlessly ridiculed by conservatives as a
panting-for-power yuppie, look laid back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the underdog in this race,'' Ricky barked in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   (Down, boy, down.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
