   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 05/30/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- WENDYS-MURDERS-FUNERAL --
Family members after the funeral Tuesday for Ramon Nazario, one of
the five victims slain during a robbery at a Wendy's restaurant in
Queens last Wednesday. Two men have been charged with murder.
Ramon's brother, Benjamin Nazario, has demanded the death penalty
for the killers. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) SAN RAFAEL, Calif. -- May 30, 2000 -- NICE-BOSSES -- The
American workplace has evolved into a kinder, gentler phase. With
unemployment at a 30-year low, bosses realize that they have to do
more than pay good salaries and lavish perks on their employees if
they want to keep them. They also have to be nice to them. David
Lein, Mary Morse's boss at Autodesk in San Rafael, even treats her
dog with kindness at the office. (Dan Krauss/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
YOGA-MUSIC-2 -- The tuneful route to spiritual bliss is surging in
popularity. Krishna Das was recently called the ``Pavarotti of
Kirtan'' by Yoga Journal. Krishna Das with Wah!, on bass, and Nina
Rao Khol, on tabla, at the Jivamukti Yoga Center. (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) HIGHLAND PARK, Ill. -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 4 -- MASUR-PHILHARMONIC -- Zarin Mehta was just named
executive director of the New York Philharmonic. How does his
arrival affect Kurt Masur? (Courtesy Ravinia Festival/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
THEATER-OVERVIEW -- No musical season in New York will ever be
entirely barren as long as the ``Encores!'' series of American
musicals in concert continues to flourish at City Center. Donna
Murphy, aloft, and other members of the cast in the recent
``Encores!'' concert version of ``Wonderful Town.'' (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- May 30, 2000 -- OBIT-FRYER-B&AMP;W -- Robert
Fryer, the producer or co-producer of many Broadway hits including
``Wonderful Town,'' ``Auntie Mame'' and its musical adaptation
``Mame,'' ``Sweet Charity,'' ``Chicago'' and ``Noises Off,'' died
Sunday in Los Angeles. He was 79 and lived in Los Angeles. (The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
BARYSHNIKOV-RAINER-DANCE-2 -- Yvonne Rainer, far left, with Mikhail
Baryshnikov, second from left among the dancers holding Emily
Coates aloft, during a rehearsal of a new work by Rainer. They come
from opposite ends of the dance universe: he from the purest
centuries-old classical tradition, she from the rule-breaking
Judson Dance Theater of the 1960s. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
BARYSHNIKOV-RAINER-DANCE-1 -- Mikhail Baryshnikov rehearsing a new
work by Yvonne Rainer for a season of the White Oak Dance Project,
of which Baryshnikov is founder and director. They come from
opposite ends of the dance universe: he from the purest
centuries-old classical tradition, she from the rule-breaking
Judson Dance Theater of the 1960s. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- CHINA-INSURANCE -- Sy
Sternberg, the chairman of New York Life Insurance, is doggedly
pursuing China, seeing it as the largest emerging market. ``Our
growth strategy is to expand into high-growth emerging markets, and
China is an important part of that strategy, so it's important that
I dedicate my time,'' Sternberg said. (Edward Keating/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BUFFALO, N.Y. -- May 30, 2000 -- NY-LAZIO-REPUBS-2 --
Rep. Rick Lazio and his wife, Patricia, right, acknowledged the
audience at the Republican Party's state convention in Buffalo on
Tuesday after Lazio accepted his party's Senate nomination. Behind
them, from left: Rep. Tom Reynolds (Lazio's interim campaign
manager), Gov. George Pataki, Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue, Rep. John
Sweeney and Erie County Comptroller Nancy Naples. (Ruth Fremson/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- SARA-LEE-MARKETPLACE -- Sara
Lee, the giant consumer packaged goods company, said Tuesday that
it would restructure its operations and divest itself of four
divisions. ``We have a new vision for Sara Lee, a vision that will
focus our business portfolio and resources,'' said C. Steven
McMillan, the president and chief operating officer of Sara Lee who
will take over as chief executive on July 1. (Chester Higgins
Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- May 30, 2000 -- KINGS-MEN-B&AMP;W -- One reviewer
of the best-selling ``Primary Colors'' drew attention to the debt
that the then-anonymous author owed to ``All the King's Men,''
Robert Penn Warren's 1946 novel based on the career of Huey Long,
reminding readers of the central emotional relationship between
Long and the narrator, Jack Burden. Although Joe Klein delayed
admitting his own role as writer, he signaled his borrowing: In
``Primary Colors,'' President Jack Stanton's chief aide and the
book's narrator is Henry Burton. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
YOGA-MUSIC -- The tuneful route to spiritual bliss is surging in
popularity. Krishna Das was recently called the ``Pavarotti of
Kirtan'' by Yoga Journal. ``Everybody loves music,'' Krishna Das,
the chanting master who was born Jeffrey Kagel in Long Island in
1947, said in a recent interview. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
TONYS-HERSCHER -- Sylvia Herscher in her West 42nd Street
apartment. She is one of the recipients of the Tony honor for
excellence in theater. ``Lots of people did what I did,'' she said.
``It's just that I was lucky. Timing. In real estate, it's
location; in the theater, it's timing. A confluence of everything
coming together and a lot of luck. That's all.'' (Andrea Mohin/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
TV-IMMIGRATION -- The new documentary ``Well-Founded Fear,''
directed by Michael Camerini and Shari Robertson, penetrates the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's confidential system of
granting or denying asylum to tens of thousands of refugees each
year. The film's title refers to the requirement that an applicant
prove a ``well-founded fear of persecution based on race, religion,
nationality, membership in a particular social group or political
opinion.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
TONYS-TV --Jeb Bergh filming Deborah Yates and Boyd Gaines of Susan
Stroman's dance play ``Contact'' on stage for a documentary segment
of the PBS Tonys broadcast - you know, the hour that directly
precedes the CBS show. ``Some people may think of us as the
preshow, but we're not,'' said Jeff Folmsbee, the hour's
co-executive producer. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- TONYS-POLITICS -- The
competition before the Tony Awards on Sunday night amounts to what
producers call Tony madness, a frenzy of promoting, politicking and
nitpicking by Broadway producers aimed at winning votes from the
705 voting theater people that can mean the difference between
millions in losses, even a closing, and a show with legs. Michael
Mulheren, foreground center, of ``Kiss Me Kate,'' and Heather
Headley, foreground right, star of ``Aida,'' during a bruch for
Tony award nominees at Sardi's, Tuesday. (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MONTCLAIR, N.J. -- May 30, 2000 -- HORSES-WORKPLACE --
Sam Brown, 60, is a horse trainer, seller and riding instructor, at
Montclair Riding Academy in New Jersey and at Cedar Lane Stables in
Brooklyn. ``With proper instruction, anyone can ride with
confidence, knowing what to do in case a horse is going and he
moves laterally, which can pop you out of the saddle,'' he said.
(Nancy Wegard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- SLADE-BOSS -- John H. Slade,
92, honorary chairman of the executive committee at Bear Stearns.
``Every day, I have visitors from all over the world come into my
office and ask my opinion on various investments,'' he said. ``And
I always tell them they can have my opinion, but it's just a guess.
I've been real lucky in the past, but who the hell knows what's
going to happen tomorrow?'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WALDO, Fla. -- May 30, 2000 -- FL-WILDFIRES -- Forester
Dave Conser tries to control a fire in his sector Tuesday
afternoon. The wildfires in Florida have become so severe that the
federal government will help pay for protection. Once local and
state governments spend $1.5 million to fight fires, the Federal
Emergency Management Agency will pay 70 percent of the rest of the
costs, it was announced Monday. (Timothy O. Davis/The Gainesville
Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) POINT PLEASANT, N.J. -- May 30, 2000 -- NJ-CORZINE --
New Jersey U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine paid at least $200,000
for an attorney and private investigators to conduct an inquiry
into the background of his opponent, Jim Florio, and members of
Florio's campaign staff, both candidates acknowledged Tuesday.
Corzine waved a flag of the New Jersey Devils hockey team during a
campaign swing, Monday. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- May 30, 2000 -- LEBANON-PRISON-2-COX
-- A week ago, as the SLA and Israel gave up their two-decade
occupation of southern Lebanon, about 140 inmates were set free
from the Al-Khiam prison in Beirut. The prison is open to
inspection now. Former inmate Hassan Qussan stood near one of the
small solitary confinement cells at the site. (Larry Kaplow/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- May 30, 2000 -- LEBANON-PRISON-1-COX
-- Nine months ago, a 25-year-old Lebanese journalism student named
Cosette Ibrahim was snatched from her house by the South Lebanon
Army, the Israeli-allied militia, and placed in the Al-Khiam prison
in Beirut. A week ago, as the SLA and Israel ended their two-decade
occupation of southern Lebanon, Ibrahim and about 140 other inmates
were set free. ``I was happy that I was released, but I am shocked
at some of the things they did,'' she said of her captors. (Larry
Kaplow/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- NY-CHILD-CARE -- In Bushwick
and other Brooklyn neighborhoods like it across the city, the child
welfare agency is regarded as a potent, ubiquitous presence. There
is a real everyday fear that a momentary crisis can result in a
difficult child taken away by authorities. After picking up her son
Juan, right, who has had emotional problems, Cynthia Marquez rides
a bus last week through Brooklyn's Bushwick neighborhood to pick up
another child from school. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times )
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 30, 2000 -- APOLLO-HIP-HOP -- When a
group of rap legends and Harlem-based artists announced last month
that they would be mounting a Broadway-style musical in the
landmark Apollo Theater, the show was presented not only as an
indicator of Harlem's economic and cultural renewal, but as the
birth of a virtually new theatrical genre: the hip-hop musical.
Members of the cast of the upcoming show gather for a group shot
during rehearsals. (Chester Higgins, Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- May 30, 2000 -- MARIJUANA-FILM-REVIEW --
``Grass,'' directed by Ron Mann, is a punchy and enjoyable new
documentary on the history of marijuana in the U.S. during the 20th
century. Pro-legalization of marijuana activists parade through
Washington, D.C., in a scene from the film which is narrated by
Woody Harrelson. (Unapix Films/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NICKERSON STATE PARK, Mass. -- May 30, 2000 --
CAPE-HOMELESS-ART-BOS -- More than four years without a permanent
residence, Susan O'Donnell, a waitress for the past 10 years, is
living at a campsite in Nickerson State Park with her three
daughters. The O'Donnells and some 67 other families, including 122
children, are caught in an affordable housing vacuum on quaint old
Cape Cod. O'Donnell embraces her four-year old daughter Emily as
her other children, Melissa, 14, center, and Lindsay, 11, look on
near their camp site. (Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BUFFALO, N.Y. -- May 30, 2000 -- NY-LAIO-REPUBS --
Promising to take his campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton
``block by block'' and ``house by house,'' Rep. Rick Lazio on
Tuesday prepared to accept the U.S. Senate nomination of Republican
leaders gathered in Buffalo for their state convention. Lazio
during an appearance at a function titled: ``Women for Lazi,''
Monday. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- May 30, 2000 -- WINE-TALK -- In 1966, Louis
Jadot bought a 66-acre estate in Moulin-a-Vent called Chateau de
Jacques and is now offering five Moulin-a-Vents from separate
vineyard parcels within the estate. These are traditional
Beaujolais, full and rich, aged in oak and capable of improving
even more with bottle age. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- May 30, 2000 -- FOOD-BOOK-REVIEW -- ``Paris in
a Basket: Markets -- The Food and the People'' right, by Nicolle
Aimee Meyer and Amanda Pilar Smith (Konemann) and ``The Greenmarket
Cookbook: Recipes, Tips and Lore From the World Famous Urban
Farmer's Market'' by Joel Patraker and Joan Schwartz (Viking). One
new book tours the outdoor food markets of Paris; the another, New
York's Greenmarkets. In each city, the markets are a vibrant part
of the food scene. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- May 30, 2000 -- BEETS -- Beets, so variable in
color, are tickling chefs pink, so to speak. Generally perceived as
a winter staple, beets actually comes into season around this time
in colors, sizes and shapes that beet phobics reared on the canned
kind could never imagine. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LONDON -- May 30, 2000 --BRITAIN-ABSINTHE -- Absinthe was
blamed for causing insanity, which is why it was banned in most of
Western Europe and the United States. Then in 1998, a group of
curious Londoners uncovered that absinthe was never legally banned
in Britain so they soon began importing it. It was an instant hit
among the young bar crowd. Ben Reed, the bar manager at Woody's, in
West London, pours absinthe to make a cocktail called ``Dragon's
Breath'' (Jonthan Player/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BRAY, England -- May 30, 2000 -- BRITAIN-FOOD-SCIENCE-2
-- Heston Blumenthal runs the Fat Duck, a restaurant 35 miles west
of London, where science joins art in the endless search for better
flavor. Blumenthal has allied himself with Peter Barham, a
physicist at the University of Bristol, with remarkable results. An
example, Bavarois of butternut squash, with goat's milk ice cream.
(Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BRAY, England -- May 30, 2000 -- BRITAIN-FOOD-SCIENCE-1
-- Heston Blumenthal, bottom, runs the Fat Duck, a restaurant in
this idyllic village on the Thames, 35 miles west of London, where
science joins art in the endless search for better flavor.
Blumenthal has allied himself with Peter Barham, top, a 49-year-old
physicist at the University of Bristol, with remarkable results. In
only a few years, the Duck has waddled to the top of several lists
of England's best restaurants. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
