CAPE-HOMELESS-ART-BOS -- More than four years without a permanent
residence, Susan O'Donnell, a waitress for the past 10 years, is
living at a campsite in Nickerson State Park with her three
daughters. The O'Donnells and some 67 other families, including 122
children, are caught in an affordable housing vacuum on quaint old
Cape Cod. O'Donnell embraces her four-year old daughter Emily as
her other children, Melissa, 14, center, and Lindsay, 11, look on
near their camp site. (Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BUFFALO, N.Y. -- May 30, 2000 -- NY-LAZIO-REPUBS --
Promising to take his campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton
``block by block'' and ``house by house,'' Rep. Rick Lazio on
Tuesday prepared to accept the U.S. Senate nomination of Republican
leaders gathered in Buffalo for their state convention. Lazio
during an appearance at a function titled: ``Women for Lazi,''
Monday. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- May 30, 2000 -- WINE-TALK -- In 1966, Louis
Jadot bought a 66-acre estate in Moulin-a-Vent called Chateau de
Jacques and is now offering five Moulin-a-Vents from separate
vineyard parcels within the estate. These are traditional
Beaujolais, full and rich, aged in oak and capable of improving
even more with bottle age. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- May 30, 2000 -- FOOD-BOOK-REVIEW -- ``Paris in
a Basket: Markets -- The Food and the People'' right, by Nicolle
Aimee Meyer and Amanda Pilar Smith (Konemann) and ``The Greenmarket
Cookbook: Recipes, Tips and Lore From the World Famous Urban
Farmer's Market'' by Joel Patraker and Joan Schwartz (Viking). One
new book tours the outdoor food markets of Paris; the another, New
York's Greenmarkets. In each city, the markets are a vibrant part
of the food scene. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- May 30, 2000 -- BEETS -- Beets, so variable in
color, are tickling chefs pink, so to speak. Generally perceived as
a winter staple, beets actually comes into season around this time
in colors, sizes and shapes that beet phobics reared on the canned
kind could never imagine. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LONDON -- May 30, 2000 --BRITAIN-ABSINTHE -- Absinthe was
blamed for causing insanity, which is why it was banned in most of
Western Europe and the United States. Then in 1998, a group of
curious Londoners uncovered that absinthe was never legally banned
in Britain so they soon began importing it. It was an instant hit
among the young bar crowd. Ben Reed, the bar manager at Woody's, in
West London, pours absinthe to make a cocktail called ``Dragon's
Breath'' (Jonathan Player/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
