</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH EWING OR WITHOUT, KNICKS' ROAD GETS ROUGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ With a heavily padded sneaker protecting the
sore tendon in his right foot, Patrick Ewing shot his requisite
number of free throws Tuesday, barely perspired and afterward
proclaimed, ``I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ewing did not declare himself ready for Wednesday's Game 5
of the Eastern Conference finals, he told a teammate before
practice that he expected to play at Conseco Fieldhouse in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The mere suggestion that Ewing is returning to the lineup after
the Knicks knotted the series at two games apiece brought all the
old Ewing questions to bear, including the most prominent one:
</P>
<P>
   With their franchise center soothing his own health concerns,
are the wounded yet recharged Knicks also fine?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done doing that,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said, bristling at
the idea that Ewing's return might tinker with his team's on-court
chemistry. ``Let the foolish remain foolish. I'm not even trying to
educate them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are 5-1 against Indiana in complete postseason games
without Ewing the past two years. If Latrell Sprewell, Allan
Houston and Marcus Camby re-energized the Knicks with their offense
in Ewing's absence a year ago, Larry Johnson has picked up the pace
in Games 2, 3 and 4 of this playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is shooting 59 percent from the field in the past three
games, having hit 26 of 44 field goals and all five 3-point
attempts in Monday's stirring Game 4 victory at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to take advantage of my opportunities when I can when
the big fella is playing,'' Johnson said Tuesday. ``When the big
fella is not playing, we have to have some low-post presence.
That's why I was able to move down there, get some good looks, good
touches. They really weren't doubling as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't feel like some Pacer killer,'' he added. ``We beat
these cats without him last year, but he doesn't bring us down. I
think he helps. With him, I think it would be easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has not played since the first quarter of Game 2, when
acute peroneal tendinitis forced him to the bench. Without him, the
Knicks have averaged 94.5 points in the past two games, using their
transition game to combat a slow-footed and stupefied Indiana team.
</P>
<P>
   How the injury will affect Ewing's play is up for debate. Ewing
has said he is having trouble cutting and planting the injured
foot. He has struggled with his lateral movement all season, trying
to keep up with quicker big men.
</P>
<P>
   Rik Smits does not present those type of problems, but the
7-foot-4-inch Pacers center is determined to erase the memory of
his last six quarters against the Knicks, in which he has scored
only 18 points and has become almost a forgotten option in
Indiana's offense.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is not the only Knick still battling an injury. Marcus
Camby's sprained knee, suffered in Game 3, has improved enough for
the Knicks reserve forward to play extended minutes in Game 5.
Sprewell said the slight fracture in his left foot will not hamper
his play.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is the only Knick who has missed games, and how soon he
recaptures his rhythm may mean the difference between a successful
night or a struggling return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful for the best,'' Van Gundy said. ``He has been
off for seven or eight days, so that is a concern.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Knicks traveled to Indianapolis in much the
same fashion they did a year ago. A 2-2 series. Reduced
expectations swirling about because of health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Banged up and relying more on their resolve than their talent,
they shocked the Pacers and went on to win the series in six games.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder how long those qualities can carry them this
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when things are inflicted upon us, or we inflict them
upon ourselves, we have great resiliency,'' Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what the danger is? Everybody is stroking them
today about `Gritty, determined, bounce back.' And subconsciously,
if they're content with just getting even, and they buy into all
that hype, like the Little Engine That Could type of thing ...
</P>
<P>
   ``My first point to them today was, you can't be content with
just getting even. Everyone is going to give us every excuse for
losing. And the only people who buy into excuses are losers. So we
have to put all that aside and find a way. Getting even was the
first step. Now we have to find a way to win a game on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without Ewing, that may be the most grueling task. The
Knicks have yet to win at Conseco since it opened this season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Knicks need Ewing to win the series, Houston said:
``I don't know. I can't answer that question because he hasn't been
there. We won two games at home. If he had been there and we won
those games, nobody would have said anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If we win the championship, Patrick has to be
there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
