<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COTTON SAYS HE'S READY FOR NEXT STEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As an expert on rude awakenings, Schea Cotton has
an advanced perspective in defining a basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a dream come true,'' Cotton, a former Long
Beach-area high school legend, said in reference to surviving the
wild ride that has led to this particular crossroads. ``The NBA has
always been my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But the journey that dragged this dream has offered enough
challenges to make Ulysses flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to persevere,'' Cotton said Tuesday morning after
joining Fresno prep hotshot DeShawn Stevenson in a pre-draft
workout for the Clippers at USC's Lyon Center. ``At one point, I
thought my career was at its pinnacle. I've seen the good and bad
on both sides of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The good included a ``Sports Illustrated'' feature before Cotton
led Mater Dei High to the state championship in his sophomore
season.
</P>
<P>
   The bad included invalidated test scores and questions about his
commitment to the on-court details required to reach that
celebrated potential.
</P>
<P>
   And now _ after Mater Dei, two tours at St. John Bosco, a letter
of intent to join his big brother, James, at Long Beach State,
another with UCLA, prep school in New England, a letter of intent
with North Carolina State, a sparkling-but-incomplete season at
Long Beach City College and a decent season at Alabama _ Cotton is
hoping the sound of his name being called in the first round of the
June 28 draft can drown out much of the whispering from the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear different things from different people,'' Cotton said
in regard to his future, ``but I've heard that I have a good chance
of going late in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Several scouts say the first round is possible, but also list
about 40 eligible prospects with first-round ability. The truth
will be easier to fathom following next week's pre-draft camp at
Chicago. That event could be crucial for Cotton, a devastating
baseline player in high school who averaged 15.5 points per game at
Alabama while continuing his evolution as a shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   Most unofficial Cotton advisors would have prescribed another
season in Tuscaloosa. But the demands of a dream and his father's
fight with prostate cancer are credited for launching the explosive
left-hander into the draft pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support of my family and my trust in God are the reasons
why I have persevered,'' said Cotton, who reports that his father,
James Sr., is doing a ``a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' basketball staff may no longer include assistant
coach Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   According to a league source, a representative for the NBA's
all-time leading scorer last week was informed Abdul-Jabbar would
not be retained as an assistant for next season. Abdul-Jabbar, who
was hired Feb. 18, was contacted by telephone Tuesday afternoon,
but he declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers also declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, the Clippers officially removed interim head coach
Jim Todd as a candidate to become permanent head coach. Remaining
from last season's staff are assistants Dennis Johnson, still
believed to be a strong candidate to become the head coach, and Rex
Kalamian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT     05-30 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONGUES WAG AND THE FINGERS POINT FOR THE PACERS  
 BY LIZ ROBBINS  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Larry Bird was laughing.
</P>
<P>
   His Indiana Pacers had just lost two games on the road to a MASH
unit eager to keep fighting. After the 91-89 defeat in Madison
Square Garden on Monday night, Jalen Rose and the reserve guard
Travis Best said the Pacers were too slow and their offense too
predictable against a Knicks team revitalized by injury and
adversity. They implied that Bird should make some changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no different from when I played,'' Bird said Tuesday.
``Every time we lost, it was never my fault, it's the coach's
fault. I understand that, I'll take the heat, but I do expect them
to come out tomorrow night and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird challenged his players to be tougher in Wednesday night's
Game 5, especially where they have wilted this season _ in the
first quarter. He urged them to defend and to rebound, calling the
7-foot-4-inch center Rik Smits' one-rebound effort in Game 4 ``a
killer.'' And that was when Knicks center Patrick Ewing was on the
bench in a suit, sidelined for the second straight game by
tendinitis in his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Without Ewing's presence in the paint, the Knicks have been more
spontaneous, setting the pace and outscoring Indiana, 45-22, in
fast-break points this series. Bird admitted his team lacked speed,
but said his players could compensate by being in the right spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look and see Reggie and Jalen running out,'' Bird said.
``They got to be in the paint there to pick up some loose
rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller may have had a team-high 24 points in Game 4, but
he had no rebounds. ``If they don't, we don't have a chance to
win,'' Bird said. ``And that's what I talked to these guys about.
Give yourself an opportunity to win by getting on the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Rose's comments, Bird believed the plays were not
the problem, but rather his players' lack of crisp execution.
``Obviously Jalen thinks we should just give him the ball, clear
out and let him go one on one,'' Bird said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 50, 60 different plays. I'm a firm believer you need
about 10, and you need to run them great every time you run them.
There can't be any flaws in them. If we do things by the numbers,
we'll score points.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, averaging a team-high 21.3 points in this series,
reiterated that the formula makes the Pacers too predictable. ``The
plays we run are pretty much the plays we've been running Larry
Bird's entire coaching career,'' he said, but then he agreed with
Bird. ``On the offensive end, we need to find a way to get easy
baskets. But by all accounts, guys just need to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose added, ``I don't think there is any reason for us to lose
confidence, to be tentative or to panic at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Having squandered a 2-0 lead, the Pacers say they are not
panicking, but they are sweating. Miller, averaging 20.3 points
this series, vowed to become more aggressive on offense, then said:
``The pressure is back on us because we have to win tomorrow on our
home court to shift the pressure back to them in Game 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird put pressure on the bench, which was missing in action, in
the last game especially. Since Austin Croshere's breakout
performance of 22 points in Game 1, he has scored a total of 12
points, and has been dismal from 3-point range. Best offers more
speed at point guard, and scored 12 Monday, but he has been
inconsistent in the series. Sam Perkins had no points in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are not hitting from the perimeter as they did the
first two victories. But the Knicks are shooting better without
Ewing, making an unconscious 10 for 14, for 71.4 percent, on Monday
night, as the Pacers were eight of 19 for 42.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The complexion of the game could change if Ewing returns
Wednesday. Miller said the team is preparing both ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, they're tougher than anyone you want to meet, and if
you beat them at their best, you feel good about it,'' Bird said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
