<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERCEPTION BLURS REALITY REGARDING JUAN GONZALEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The TV guy began the highlights of the
Rangers-Tigers game Monday with a shot of Juan Gonzalez in the
dugout. Juan didn't play, the announcer informed us, because of a
foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else is new?'' he glibly added.
</P>
<P>
   What else is new? Plenty, actually.
</P>
<P>
   When last seen in these parts, Gonzalez had just put the
finishing touches on yet another superb season.
</P>
<P>
   He batted a career high .326, hit 39 homers and drove in 128
runs last season. He was ninth in the league in batting, fifth in
RBI and fourth with a .601 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   If he wasn't quite embraced as a hero, he at least was
appreciated for his talent, for regularly getting key hits to drive
in Rangers runners, for being one of the best players in the game.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's new? Just this.
</P>
<P>
   When Gonzalez was traded to the Tigers in the off-season, the
event apparently opened a rift in the space/time continuum.
</P>
<P>
   Juan's World used to be a happy place, a simple place. It was a
place where its chief citizen, when it came to matters of baseball,
merely wanted to work hard, drive in runs and win games.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Juan's World is a place where up is down, left is right,
north is south. It's a place where perception replaces reality, a
place of misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the bon mot from the TV guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else is new?'' Yuk, yuk. Yep, we all know that Juan never
did like to play with pain, did he? We know that he always misses
bunches of games with injuries, real and imagined, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually that's wrong. It's a piece of misinformation, an
example of perception replacing reality.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Gonzalez never is going to see the word ``ironman''
before his name, but consider this:
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer, the Rangers hard-nosed left fielder, will play with
pain, right? He's the type of guy who'll do anything to stay in the
lineup, isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   Sure he is. But since the start of the 1996 season, Greer has
played 608 games. Gonzalez has played 605.
</P>
<P>
   Why do we accept Greer's various nagging injuries at face value,
and question Juan's injuries?
</P>
<P>
   Common sense should be enough to realize that if there was any
way possible, Gonzalez would play against his old club to try and
prove it made a mistake by trading him.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking common sense, an intrepid journalist could find out that
Gonzalez has been bothered by a heel injury for a week. The
technical name is plantar fasciitis, an injury that has caused Mark
McGwire and Will Clark to miss long stretches of playing time in
the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has gotten worse in the last few days,'' Tigers team
physician Terry Lock said. ``It can very easily become chronic.
That is one of the concerns about it. It tends to hang around and
be difficult to completely alleviate.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, there was another case of perception trumping
reality. A different TV station did a piece on the new Rangers'
right fielder, and a few fans were quoted as saying they liked him
better than the old right fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Why, this one hustled, they said. And gosh, it looks like he
might even be a better player.
</P>
<P>
   Huh? A better player?
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler is a crowd pleaser who'll get his uniform dirty. He
appears to be playing hard, an effect Gonzalez never quite could
pull off.
</P>
<P>
   But lest anyone forget, the old right fielder twice was chosen
Most Valuable Player of the American League. He twice led the
league in homers. He had more RBI than games played from 1996-98.
</P>
<P>
   The misinformation and perception/reality difficulties even
appear to have infected the resident of Juan's World.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has talked to local reporters about his experiences in
Texas three times since the start of spring training. Twice, he had
nothing but good things to say about the organization and its fans.
The other time he ripped the organization for its treatment of
Latin-American players.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the curious case of his address next year. He can
become a free agent at the end of the season, and reportedly told
one of his former teammates he'll be back in Texas. But when
Detroit reporters asked him about those comments, he dismissed them
as ridiculous, which they are given Rangers GM Doug Melvin's
reluctance to overpay for one player.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates acknowledged Monday before the game
that something was amiss in Juan's World.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan may go down as one of the more misunderstood superstars
of his era in baseball, and that would be a darn shame because he
is truly a special person,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez indeed is an enigma, more so now than ever. But as
Oates said, he's also a special person.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake to let misinformation and
perception/reality problems obscure the fact that he remains one of
the most talented players in the game, perhaps the best ever to
pull on a Rangers uniform.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
