<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-RULES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS RULES NEED TO BE CLEARER, SET EARLIER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Major League Soccer executive vice president
Ivan Gazidis spent several months working out the endless details
in obtaining acclaimed striker Luis Hernandez from Tigres of the
Mexican first division.
</P>
<P>
   Gazidis might be spending several more weeks simply explaining
how the deal worked.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, whose flowing blond locks and uncanny scoring touch
made him the brightest star in Mexico, was targeted by MLS
officials as a huge potential fan draw for a league that has few
marquee names. Los Angeles, with a large fan base of
Mexican-Americans, was the obvious market in which to place
Hernandez. Hernandez's debut, against D.C. United on May 20, drew a
season-high crowd of 40,303 to the Rose Bowl; his second home game,
Saturday against San Jose, drew only 17,831.
</P>
<P>
   Few deny that sending Hernandez to the Galaxy makes sense, but
it's difficult to make any sense of the process the league used to
send him to LA.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, MLS' single-entity structure is at the root of the
situation. The league controls player movements and allocations.
And league investors would help pay the reported $4 million it cost
to acquire Hernandez only if he was sent to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Galaxy already had filled its four roster spots for
foreign players. The Galaxy tried to trade with San Jose to open an
allocation spot, but the Earthquakes didn't want Costa Rican Roy
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   So, MLS created another way for the Galaxy to offer compensation
and acquire Hernandez. Los Angeles would have to give up several
other players to even out the deal, and hence the league created
the ``dispersal draft'' to add to the new MLS lingo this season,
along with the ``Superdraft.''
</P>
<P>
   The premise of the dispersal draft: players released as
compensation go into a pool and are picked by teams in reverse
order from a combination of last year's and this year's results.
That way, the have-nots have a little better chance of improving.
</P>
<P>
   The whole process has been confusing at best and bewildering at
worst. Even individuals close to the Hernandez deal, such as Los
Angeles coach Sigi Schmid, seemed perplexed. Schmid had to inform
two of his players, Joey Franchino and Clint Mathis, that they were
released to make room for Hernandez. When the Hernandez deal
stalled, Schmid admitted he had no idea what would happen to
Franchino and Mathis should the deal fall through completely.
</P>
<P>
   Gazidis attempted to explain yesterday how the deal worked, and
maintained that the league did the best possible job in making a
potentially unfair deal as equitable as possible.
</P>
<P>
   However, all of the confusion could have been avoided had MLS
clearly identified the rules that should apply when a situation
such as Hernandez's acquisition arise. And with all the hype this
season about the league's bumper crop of foreigners, such rules
should have been established, agreed upon and explained before they
had to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   There's one more underlying theme to the Hernandez saga: as
flawed as it has been perceived by many fans, it's the basic
concept of the single-entity system. Fans might not understand it
or like it, but, unless they start going to games in much bigger
numbers, the structure is here to stay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
