<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TCU-SPRINTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU MEN'S TRACK TEAM SHARES UNIQUE BOND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ They're buddies and will hook up to catch
the occasional movie, but they're not joined at the hip 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   They come from different parts of the state and globe, and
several used to live in the same apartment complex But this isn't
``Melrose Place/ or the ``Real World.''
</P>
<P>
   But something in this group of sprinters clicked off the track,
like no other group that TCU coach Monte Stratton has coached. Five
Texans and three Caribbean-born Texas transplants are proving that
in the often individual world of track and field, this sum is
greater than the parts.
</P>
<P>
   Today those eight set out to do what they came to TCU for, build
onto the ``Flyin' Frog'' tradition of world-class sprinters at the
NCAA Outdoor Championships, which run through Saturday on the Duke
campus in Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the easiest group of sprinters I've ever worked with
in terms of being able to get along and the chemistry among the
group,'' said Stratton, completing his fifth year at TCU.
``Sprinters are notoriously high-strung and temperamental, and this
group I'm not saying doesn't have some of that, but this is the
best group as a whole for doing their work, working with each other
and actually trying to be a team.''
</P>
<P>
   For senior Johnny L. Collins II, a Wyatt graduate, the reason
these eight have come together so easily comes down to one word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attitudes,'' said Collins, who will compete in the 400 meters
and the 4x400 relay. ``We're good friends. Nobody is going to cop
out on you. Usually you get a group that's very cocky, a lot of
egos, with people that want to slack and don't want to face the
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of leaders, and everybody handles their own load.
Don't nobody want to let nobody down.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good, but all the warm-and-fuzzies don't
mean a thing if the speedsters can't back it up with times and
medals. They have, winning the Western Athletic Conference Indoor
title, finishing fourth at the NCAA Indoor Championships in March
and placing second at the WAC Outdoors this month. The relay team
of Roy Williams, Anthony Amantine, Kendrick Campbell and Johnny L.
Collins II won TCU's first indoor 4x400 national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more depth in the sprints, 100 through 400, than
anytime that I've been here,'' Stratton said. ``We haven't run a
national record yet, but we haven't run at nationals yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always the objective to not only have the talent, which
is the hardest part to recruit, but once we get the talent to have
the talent with the attitude in each individual's mind that they
want to be part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   At the WAC Outdoors, Darvis Patton won the long jump and
200-meter titles. The 4x100 relay (Lindel Frater, Ricardo ``Flash''
Williams, Patton and Kim Collins) ran away from the field to post
their best time of the season at 38.56 seconds. Kim Collins also
claimed the 100-meter crown but pulled up short with an injured
right groin muscle in the 200-meters final.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Collins' injury casts some doubt on the Frogs' 4x100 chances
this week. Collins has already been pulled out of the 100 and 200,
and though Stratton is planning on running him in the 4x100
semifinals this afternoon, it's possible Campbell will sub for
Collins. Collins, who has had round-the-clock treatment for the
past 10 days, would then have two more days to get ready for
Saturday's 4x100 finals. TCU needs to finish in the top eight today
to reach the finals.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the team isn't letting the injury to the team's top
jokester get them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still feel confident, even though Kim is banged up,''
Amantine said. ``We know if he can't do it, we can always put
somebody else in and still handle our business.''
</P>
<P>
   With strong performances at the Texas Relays and Penn Relays,
the Frogs had risen to as high as fourth nationally in the
/Trackwire/ rating service. The same rating service projects TCU to
score 17 points and finish just out of the top 10 this week.
</P>
<P>
   Stratton's concern isn't team standings but how his team does in
its specialty, the sprints and relays.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sprints, it's just like it was indoors, a role of the dice.
If you're on, you're a hero. If you're not, you're an also-ran.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the sprinters come from various backgrounds, each said
they found a comfort zone quickly upon their arrival at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   Texas high school standouts Campbell and Patton were teammates
at Garden City College in Kansas. Amantine, a Houston native,
competed against those two in Kansas at Barton County College.
</P>
<P>
   For Jamaicans Frater and ``Flash'' Williams, Fort Worth has been
a home away from home. Starting with Raymond Stewart and Andrew
Smith in the mid-1980s and through recent stars such as Percival
Spencer a distinguished line of Jamaican sprinters have shined at
TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I was in Jamaica, I always wanted to be here,''
Williams said. ``A lot of Jamaicans pass through TCU, and they
always did well. Percy came here and did well, Raymond came here
and did well, just to name a few. I just feel at home here.''
</P>
<P>
   Frater, also competing in the 100 and 200, echoed those words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the tradition here,'' Frater said. ``This is some place I
wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Outdoor Championships is some place all eight wanted to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to perform, do the things we've done all year
long and take care of our business,'' Johnny Collins said. ``We're
ready and prepared, and preparation don't come without reward.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
