<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-AIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES WILL RULE ON CASE OF ENVIRONMENTALISTS VS. CORPORATIONS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case pitting environmentalists against
corporations, the Supreme Court on Tuesday agreed to decide whether
federal regulators must consider the financial concerns of
businesses before requiring them to take expensive steps to reduce
air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' action followed their decision last week to
consider whether the Environmental Protection Agency exceeded its
authority under the 1990 Clean Air Act when it imposed strict
limits on the allowable levels of ozone, an essential part of smog.
A federal appeals court has ruled that the agency went too far.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging in the balance in the court's first major environmental
case in several years &UR;  &LR; is whether the federal government can
tighten rules to reduce smog or if it must give greater
consideration to corporate concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render by July 2001 its decision
on EPA's authority and the impact of business costs on agency
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's at stake is a critical national program to protect our
children, the elderly and our communities from harmful air
pollution,'' said Vickie Patton, senior attorney of Environmental
Defense, referring to the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Conrad, senior vice president of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce's litigation division, hailed as ``a great day for us''
the justices' willingness to consider whether EPA must weigh the
financial impact of its regulations on businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, the justices refused to hear the appeals of two
former state employees who claim Texas health agencies cheated the
federal government of millions of dollars. The court's refusal to
hear the cases leaves it to the U.S. Justice Department alone to
decide whether to pursue the workers' claims that the agencies
failed to comply with rules governing Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Charles Miller said the agency has
not decided whether to press ahead with lawsuits against the Texas
Health Department and the Texas Tech University Health Science
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's refusal, without comment, to hear the Texas
cases followed its May 22 decision that federal law bars states
from being sued by citizens who claim agencies have cheated the
U.S. government. The court's ruling, however, left unresolved
whether the government can sue states under the False Claims Act.
</P>
<P>
   In the EPA case, the justices agreed to consider the arguments
of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the American Trucking
Associations that the agency had a duty to consider the financial
impact its clean-air regulations would have on truckers and other
industries that contribute to smog.
</P>
<P>
   The justices will weigh the cost issue as part of their review
of a lower court decision that prevented EPA from enforcing its
regulations. The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia ruled last year that the EPA interpreted the Clean Air Act
``so loosely'' as to give the agency more authority than Congress
intended it to have.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' ruling won't affect Houston's obligation to bring
ozone levels below an older, less stringent standard by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
