<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-LAZIO-SENATE-COX     05-30 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZIO-SENATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.Y. underdog Lazio picks up GOP's colors
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ His opponent is usually painted as the ambitious
one, but Rick Lazio displayed some reach of his own here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Republicans formally named Lazio their U.S. Senate nominee
at their biannual convention, ending a tumultuous 11-day period in
which the fourth-term Long Island congressman went from not even
being a candidate to competing in the country's most closely
watched Senate race. Plunging into the void created by New York
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's sudden withdrawal as the Republican
candidate and running against first lady HIllary Rodham Clinton,
the 42-year-old Lazio might have been expected to proceed a bit
tentatively.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhgeddaboudit! He came out swinging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the underdog in this race,'' Lazio told convention
delegates with a grin that suggested he wasn't very upset at all,
sizing up his opposition in Mrs. Clinton. ``She comes to New York
with the support of every left wing special interest group, from
Washington insiders to the Hollywood elite. But as I've said
before: `Bring 'em on.'''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't kidding. Entering the downtown hotel ballroom where he
was nominated to the stirring theme song from ``Rocky,'' Lazio
promised delegates that he would fight for his Senate seat ``house
by house.'' He then dashed over to the nearby Triple-A baseball
team's stadium to wave from high atop the grandstand as his newly
christened campaign bus was unveiled to hundreds of supporters and
a few bemused Buffalo Bisons players. A few hours later, Lazio left
town aboard the ``Mainstream Express'' for a three-day, nine-city
campaign swing around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Even the fat lip he got from a tumble during a Memorial Day
parade was offered as further evidence of his good humor and
dedication to campaigning in the face of what many consider
daunting odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of pounding the pavement, but this is ridiculous,''
said Lazio, who received eight stitches Monday and then marched in
a second parade. ``I want a rematch!''
</P>
<P>
   Such enthusiasm clearly is music for New York Republicans, who
saw their hopes for a high-profile win over the first lady in the
Nov. 7 election seemingly diminished less than two weeks ago by
Giuliani's withdrawal due to health and marital problems. Lazio
quickly stepped up _ indeed, he had planned to run until New York
Gov. George Pataki persuaded him to give way to Giuliani last
August. But Mrs. Clinton clearly had a head start in terms of
fundraising, campaigning and, it seemed, voter sentiment: In a poll
taken before Giuliani dropped out, Mrs. Clinton led Lazio by 14
points in a hypothetical matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by the time the 400 delegates arrived here Tuesday, Lazio
had effectively closed the gap. He and Mrs. Clinton now are in a
statistical dead heat according to the same pollster, Zogby
International.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone could have predicted he'd have such a
good week,'' said David Hansen, political director of the National
Republican Senatorial Committee, whose organization was filming the
scene at the baseball stadium for future use in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   What Lazio has done so far, and what he and fellow Republicans
continued to do at the convention Tuesday, was pound home the image
of the first lady as a carpetbagger pausing in New York just long
enough to pick up a Senate seat on her inevitable march to the Oval
Office. Seconding Lazio's nomination, fellow Republican congressman
John Sweeney was not the first speaker to assure delegates that
Mrs. Clinton was ``more interested in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, meanwhile, never mentioned his opponent by name or her
alleged ambition to someday run for president. Just minutes before
informing his audience that he rejected ``ripping into
challengers'' and ``politics of discord and division,'' however,
Lazio made sure they knew exactly where he was coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, New York is not just a mailing address,'' Lazio said
to an outburst of cheers and laughter. ``It's my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lazio also used part of his 27-minute acceptance speech to
draw attention to his nearly eight years in Washington. Having
garnered bipartisan support for important legislation in areas such
as cancer treatment and senior citizen housing, he said, he would
do more of the same to protect Social Security, lower taxes and
expand access to affordable health care.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this may have been in response to the Clinton campaign,
which already has begun to depict Lazio as too inexperienced and
conservative to represent New York in the Senate. On the other
hand, his speech included no mention of either abortion or gun
control, issues on which he is to the right of Mrs. Clinton, and
even Giuliani to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet among many delegates, there was an unmistakable sense of
satisfaction at having come up with the strongest candidate, not
just the one with the best name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad Rudy's not running, because I don't think he would
have won,'' said Helen Kiggins, an attorney and delegate from
Syracuse, who sported a campaign button with a line drawn through
Mrs. Clinton's face. ``And I don't think people would have been as
excited to be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
