<SLUG> BC-GLICKMAN-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAZED BY PROTESTER'S PIE, AGRICULTURE CHIEF SERVES UP A QUIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The secretary of agriculture had just begun to
speak at the opening session of the National Nutrition Summit here
Tuesday when an animal rights protester leaped onto the stage and
threw a pie at him.
</P>
<P>
   The protester's message was loud and clear: ``Shame on you, Dan
Glickman, you meathead. Shame on you for promoting meat.'' But her
aim was off. Glickman ducked, and the pie _ either apple or tofu
cream, depending on who was asked _ grazed the back of his jacket.
</P>
<P>
   As Glickman, a former Democratic congressman member from Kansas,
peeled off his jacket, he didn't miss a beat: ``That was not a very
balanced meal she threw at me.'' Then he turned to former Sen. Bob
Dole, R-Kan., who was also on the stage, and said, ``Bob, I don't
think we're in Kansas anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman was one of the speakers at the meeting, convened 31
years after the original White House Conference on Food Nutrition
and Health, which was instrumental in starting many of the
government food assistance programs like Head Start and the school
breakfast program.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Glickman announced that the government had decided to
test two of the nation's most popular diets _ low carbohydrate and
low fat _ to see which is more effective and safer. Millions of
Americans have tried one of the diets or a variation, including the
high-protein, low-carbohydrate regimen developed by the
cardiologist Robert Atkins and the low-fat diet promoted by Dean
Ornish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pie thrower, Arathi Jayaram, 24, who lives in northern
Virginia, is a member of People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals. She was carried out by a member of Glickman's security
team.
</P>
<P>
   Jayaram was charged with assault of a Cabinet official. The
charge carries a recommended penalty of up to a year in jail, but
there is no category in federal sentencing guidelines for assault
with a pie in a disposable aluminum tin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
