<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CASEY-NYT </SLUG>
 
ROBERT P. CASEY, EX-GOVERNOR of PENNSYLVANIA, DIES AT 68  
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert P. Casey, the governor of Pennsylvania from 1987 to 1994,
whose strong opposition to abortion put him at odds with his
Democratic Party, died Tuesday in Scranton, Pa., where he lived. He
was 68.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was an infection.
</P>
<P>
   Casey helped to draw national attention to organ donations after
his life was saved by a rare heart and liver transplant in 1993,
when he was still governor.
</P>
<P>
   But Casey made his national reputation as an anti-abortion
politician. In 1992, he sought to give a speech against abortion at
the Democratic National Convention in New York but was turned down
by the party's leadership. Ron Brown, who was then the Democratic
national chairman, said of Casey's abortion stance: ``We have a
fundamental disagreement with him on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Goodman, the television critic of The New York Times,
wrote that Casey ``was not permitted on camera for fear that his
sour note on abortion would disturb the symphony of unity'' at the
convention, which was on its way toward nominating Bill Clinton of
Arkansas for president.
</P>
<P>
   In a book he wrote after he left office called ``Fighting for
Life'' (Word Books, 1996), Casey said that buttons depicting him as
the pope were sold at the convention by abortion-rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was simply a case of anti-Catholic bigotry,'' he
wrote. ``What was going on here? What had become of the Democratic
Party I once knew?''
</P>
<P>
   Casey also complained of commentators who were quick to mention
his Catholicism. ``Because I'm pro-life,'' he wrote, ``my religion
is always thrown in there like some little code word to the reader
saying `Watch out for this guy. He's a Catholic. He's one of those
people.'''
</P>
<P>
   As governor he signed a law in 1989 imposing a 24-hour waiting
period for abortions in Pennsylvania. Planned Parenthood sued, and
the law ended up being argued before the U.S. Supreme Court in
1992. The Court upheld the waiting period even as it affirmed the
right to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Casey was told that he had a life-threatening disease,
amyloidosis, which caused his liver to produce an abnormal protein
that built up in the walls of his heart, weakening it. Four years
earlier he had quadruple bypass surgery after a heart attack, and
although he recovered, his health continued to decline.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 he received a murder victim's heart and liver in an
experimental operation that took 15 hours at the University of
Pittsburgh Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   He got the organs just hours after his name was put on a waiting
list for donor organs. By comparison, the United Network for Organ
Sharing said the median wait for a liver transplant was 67 days and
for a heart transplant 198 days.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Armitage, who performed the heart transplant, said
Casey received the organs because his ``life was in imminent
danger'' and that the operation was his last chance to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Casey was barred by state law from seeking a third term. After
he left the statehouse in Harrisburg, he resumed his law practice
and became a public advocate for organ donations.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Patrick Casey was born in the Jackson Heights section of
Queens, N.Y., on Jan. 9, 1932. His family moved when he was young
to Scranton, where his father, Alphonsus, worked as a coal miner
before becoming a lawyer at the age of 40.
</P>
<P>
   Casey attended Holy Cross College on a basketball scholarship,
graduating in 1953, and then went on to George Washington
University Law School, where he earned his law degree in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Casey was elected state senator and auditor general but was
defeated three times in the Democratic primary when he ran for
governor. He finally won his party's nomination for governor in
1986 and was expected to lose to the Republican candidate, William
W. Scranton 3rd, who was then the lieutenant governor and who
carried an illustrious name in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the smart guys said I would lose,'' Casey said. ``I was 17
points down in August and the other guy was the son of a former
governor, son of an ambassador. He had $1 million. I didn't have a
penny. But I never doubted I would win.''
</P>
<P>
   He won narrowly, his victory ascribed to a commercial that said
that Scranton's ``only real job was lieutenant governor, and they
gave him that because of his father's name.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey was a popular governor and was re-election in 1990,
defeating his Republican opponent by more than 1 million votes, the
largest margin in the state's history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his differences with his party over abortion, Casey
remained a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the Republican Party is concerned, the business of
government is business,'' he said in an interview with The
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette shortly before leaving office. ``That's
their agenda. That's their opening act, and their closing act and
their in-between act.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the executors of business policy. I mean, look at the
agenda. Do they talk about children's health insurance? Hell, no.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 interview in The Washington Times, Casey described
himself as a conservative Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But Ted Van Dyk, a longtime Democratic analyst, disagreed with
that definition. ``I wouldn't call Bob Casey a conservative
Democrat,'' he said.`` I would call him a moderate-to-liberal
Democrat who has a conservative stance on abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey tried to establish universal health care for every
resident of Pennsylvania, but failed. He did sign a bill providing
health insurance for children whose families were too poor to pay
for it but whose incomes were too high to be eligible for public
medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1988, a Casey plan that required most residents to
separate their trash for recycling was approved, making
Pennsylvania the largest state to require recycling. He also got
the Legislature to approve a hazardous-site cleanup law.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Ellen Theresa Harding;
four daughters, Margi McGrath, Mary Ellen Philbin, Kate Brier, Erin
Walsh,; four sons, Robert Jr., Christopher, Patrick and Matthew;
and numerous grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
