<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR BUSH, GREEN PASTURES OUT WEST
</P>
<P>
   Some are lush and others are arid, but all of the stops on Gov.
George W. Bush's four-day trek through the West will prove fertile
_ with money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, reaped an
estimated $100,000 for his campaign at a luncheon in Denver on
Tuesday and was expected to raise $300,000 for the Republican
National Committee and $125,000 for the state Republican Party in
New Mexico at a reception in Albuquerque on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, after visits to Arizona and Nevada as well, Bush
should collect $350,000 for his campaign, $200,000 for state
Republican organizations and about $2 million for the national
committee, campaign officials said. They said Bush would raise $1.3
million in regulated ``hard money'' for the committee and at least
several hundred thousand dollars in largely unregulated ``soft
money.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AD ADVISORY
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush is turning to an executive of one of the
nation's best-known advertising agency, Young &AMP; Rubicam, for
creative suggestions on television commercials. Jim Ferguson, the
advertising agency's chief creative officer, has accepted an
unpaid, advisory role in the campaign, said Stuart Stevens, a
Republican consultant and a member of Maverick Media, the
advertising arm of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tremendous respect for what these guys do, and there
are skills they have that are almost uniquely suited to a
presidential campaign,'' Stevens said. Ferguson will assemble an
informal group of people in New York who may be asked to help write
Bush's television commercials, Stevens said. Ferguson, through an
assistant, declined to comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRAISE FROM McCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's recent statements on arms-control policy,
missile defense and trade with China have drawn hearty praise from
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. In an op-ed article in Tuesday's Wall
Street Journal, McCain applauded Bush for embracing
internationalist positions that benefit America's interests. Now if
only more Republicans in Congress would follow Bush's lead, McCain
lamented, citing the Senate's vote to reject setting a deadline to
withdraw ground troops from Kosovo. Only 15 Senate Republicans,
including McCain, backed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   GORTON TAKES TO THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., formally began his re-election
campaign with a five-day bus tour of the state. Gorton, 72, vowed
to make the rising cost of prescription drugs a centerpiece of his
campaign. He has introduced a bill that would bar drug
manufacturers from charging Americans more for prescriptions than
they charge patients in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say the issue is a smoke screen for Gorton's failure
to take on corporate interests.
</P>
<P>
   A September primary will determine Gorton's Democratic opponent.
That race pits the state insurance commissioner, Deborah Senn,
against former Rep. Maria Cantwell, an Internet executive.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH Albuquerque, N.M., Phoenix, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE Chevy Chase, Md., Macon, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
