u p BC-NJ-CORZINE-NYT     05-30 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CORZINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. SENATE CANDIDATE SAYS HE PAID FOR DETECTIVES TO CHECK ON HIS
OPPONENT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NY14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Jon S. Corzine acknowledged Tuesday that he had
paid at least $200,000 for a lawyer who had private investigators
conduct an inquiry into Jim Florio, his opponent in the Democratic
primary for Senate, and members of Florio's campaign staff.
</P>
<P>
   After an article in The Philadelphia Inquirer on Tuesday
reported on the inquiry, Corzine, former chairman of Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co., said he ordered his lawyer in February to investigate his
complaints that his wife and children had received prank telephone
calls earlier in the year and saw photographers trying to take
pictures through the windows of the family home in Summit, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said that when he discovered about a month ago that his
lawyer, Stanley Arkin, had hired a private investigating company to
check out members of Florio's staff, he ordered the inquiry to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   But Florio, angered by what he called an invasion of privacy,
said Tuesday that the questions posed by the investigators were
clearly intended to dig up salacious details about his personal
life in an effort to smear his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he had received complaints from several staff
members and former employees who had been asked for personal
``dirt'' about him and his associates.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Florio demanded an apology from Corzine
and said his rival's Wall Street values and his free-spending
campaign, which has already laid out more than $30 million, were
bringing a new level of incivility to New Jersey's rough-and-tumble
politics. `` Corzine will pay anything, say anything, and now we
find out, do anything, regardless of what is acceptable to get
elected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's admission that he used a private investigator has
prompted the latest flare-up in a bitter battle for the Democratic
nomination for the U.S. Senate. Corzine has shattered all records
for spending in a primary, and much of that money has paid for a
series of advertisements attacking Florio's record as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Florio's campaign has also been true to his reputation for
combativeness, and in a series of news conferences, faxes and
television ads, Florio has accused Corzine of everything from
raiding employees' pension funds to taking part in a pipeline deal
that benefits the ruling party in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is a common, and accepted, practice for political
candidates to assign staff members to research their rivals, the
use of private investigators is controversial because such
investigators are not directly supervised by campaign staff members
and often pride themselves on using intimidation or deception to
gain information.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of political candidates and their surrogates
have turned to private investigators in recent years, from
President Clinton and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy to scores of local
officials. But many government watchdog groups say it is a practice
best avoided, because private investigators are often difficult to
control and the public regards many of them as unscrupulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets close to the old dirty-trick situation from
Watergate,'' said Charles Lewis, executive director of the Center
for Public Integrity. ``You get a group of people skulking around
in the process. You don't know who they are, what they're getting
paid or what they'll do to get information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public perceives it as over the line, an invasion of
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he first heard complaints several months ago, when a
former employee called to report that a private investigator had
asked for ``anything negative about Jim Florio.'' Since then,
George E. Norcross 3rd, a South Jersey political leader and
important ally of Florio, said he was told by several state
Democratic Party officials that the Corzine campaign had hired
private detectives to follow him. George Zoffinger, Florio's
campaign treasurer, said he too had been warned by friends in the
Corzine campaign that he was being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends who work for Corzine who told me to watch out
because I'm on the enemies list and they were going to send the
private eyes after me,'' said Zoffinger, the commerce commissioner
during Florio's term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he did not publicly complain about the
investigations earlier because he wanted to find documented
evidence that the Corzine campaign had hired a private security
company. When the Corzine campaign released its spending report
with the Federal Election Commission last week, it showed $200,000
in payments to Stanley S. Arkin, a prominent New York lawyer, and
Corzine's aides have since confirmed that part of the money paid
for private detectives. Florio said the use of private detectives
was ``despicable'' and ``disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkin did not return calls requesting comment. James Mintz,
owner of the private security concern contracted by the Corzine
campaign, also did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine aides denied that the investigators had put anyone
under surveillance, saying that their inquiry was aimed solely at
determining whether Florio's supporters had been harassing the
Corzine family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2249EDT &QL; 
