<HEADER>
A0203 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-TREES-BATTLE-KAN &LR;      05-30 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREES-BATTLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING ENDS LONG DISPUTE OVER CHRISTMAS TREE FARM...FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Santa Claus has to peek through the trees
these days.
</P>
<P>
   You can see him if you drive slowly down a gravel road southeast
of Kansas City. The giant Santa used to tower over the scotch
pines, but the limbs now reach his red cap and hide his smile.
</P>
<P>
   Fitting, because if this Santa could talk, what a tragic tale of
Christmas he could tell.
</P>
<P>
   The war on Christmas Tree Lane was fought at his feet. Hayride
wagons and mechanical tree wrappers now sit abandoned like
burned-out tanks on a battleground. Orphaned trees, long neglected,
fight for growing room on crowded hills.
</P>
<P>
   A family was destroyed. People died over the 20 years, including
the man who planted the first tree in 1957. A vibrant fellow who
commanded a submarine in World War II and was a champion wrestler,
Oscar Urquhart, died timid and depressed.
</P>
<P>
   A circuit judge recently ruled in the two-decade battle over
ownership of Christmas Tree Lane in rural Cass County, just off
Missouri 7 between Pleasant Hill and Harrisonville. The business
was one of the first and largest ``pick and cut'' farms in
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Who won?
</P>
<P>
   Elvin Douglas, an attorney in the case, chuckled and shook his
head at the question. Three boxes of legal files stand as testament
to the struggle's duration.
</P>
<P>
   Then Douglas turned grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody won,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not Oscar and Genie Urquhart, who started the farm. Not Genie's
daughter, Jackie Miller, who fought them for the land. And not
Carolyn and Leonard Whiting, friends of the Urquharts who took up
the fight against Miller, but who are now at odds with Genie
Urquhart.
</P>
<P>
   The court decision was a wash _ both sides were awarded similar
amounts. And that may be the biggest tragedy of all, said Robert
Gentry, Miller's son.
</P>
<P>
   Had the judge deemed one side a clear winner, the feud that tore
his family apart may have made some sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family worked that land for more than a century, and now
it's all gone,'' Gentry said by telephone from his home in Oxford,
Ohio. ``I used to spend summers there when I was a boy. It was a
fun and exciting time when they started planting the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Americana. To have it degenerate the way it did was so
sad and painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny...it was all over Christmas trees, and a Christmas tree
is kind of a holy thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Urquhart was worthy of family legend.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1906, he joined the Navy at 17 and served as a submarine
commander in the South Pacific in World War II. He was a champion
wrestler and a deep-sea diver who specialized in underwater
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   After Oscar left the Navy in 1954, he and his wife, Genie,
retired to the Cass County farm where he was born. They had a dream
to build the largest Christmas tree farm in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957, they planted the first trees on the 120-acre spread.
Gentry remembers those early days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seemed to be so much going on back then,'' said Gentry,
who grew up in San Diego. ``I couldn't wait for summer to arrive so
I could get to the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   The first trees were harvested in 1963. Before long, a trip to
Christmas Tree Lane was an annual rite for many area families.
</P>
<P>
   Business boomed in the 1970s. The hills were green with scotch
pines. And every year, thousands more were planted.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1970s, though, Oscar Urquhart was tired and ailing.
So the couple persuaded Genie's daughter, Jackie Miller, to take
over the business. According to court records, the couple sold the
farm to Miller with the agreement that they would all share the
profits and the Urquharts would stay in their home.
</P>
<P>
   But Genie Urquhart began to worry that her daughter was
attempting to squeeze her and her husband out. In 1981, the
Urquharts sued Miller, contending that they owned half the business
and should get half the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Miller disagreed and contended she was sole owner.
</P>
<P>
   A judge in 1984 ruled in favor of the Urquharts. The judge's
order divided the farm into two 60-acre tracts, separated by a
gravel road that bisected the property.
</P>
<P>
   The Urquharts received the northern half with the condition they
not sell trees. Miller received the southern half.
</P>
<P>
   But the next year Miller sued, again insisting the entire farm
was hers.
</P>
<P>
   As the case went back and forth, an irreparable rift in the
family developed.
</P>
<P>
   Though only a few hundred yards separated their homes, they
never spoke. Not even when Miller worked on trees in her mother's
back yard.
</P>
<P>
   By the late '80s, sales at Christmas Tree Lane began to falter.
According to court records, 6,117 trees were sold in 1988, but only
4,391 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Urquharts were ready to leave. Then age 84,
Oscar was in failing health and suffered severe depression.
</P>
<P>
   That's when a neighbor, Carolyn Whiting, and her sister, Bonnie
Wesemann, entered the picture. They said they loved the Urquharts
like family and offered to take up the fight against Miller.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 30, 1990, the Urquharts conveyed the north 60 and all
rights to Whiting and Wesemann, who used the name BCC Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble escalated on Thanksgiving 1991 when Whiting and Wesemann
began to sell trees from the northern half of the farm, an act
which, a judge would say later, violated the 1984 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides manned the roads and tried to direct tree shoppers to
their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Off-duty Cass County deputies were hired to maintain order.
</P>
<P>
   The two businesses went head to head through 1994, when BCC
ended its operation. By that time, Wesemann had sold her interest
in BCC to Whiting's husband, Leonard Whiting.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear who won the tree wars. According to court records,
both sides lost money over those years.
</P>
<P>
   Miller quit after the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   She was always reluctant to talk about her parents but in 1995
said: ``They're living somewhere in Oklahoma. We don't talk.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, a trial was held in Cass County Circuit Court in
Harrisonville. Judge William Roberts combined all the lawsuits into
a single case.
</P>
<P>
   In April this year, he announced his rulings. He awarded damages
of $103,184 to the Whitings and $107,651 to Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have appealed. Genie Urquhart isn't involved in the
litigation anymore, but she's not happy, either.
</P>
<P>
   Now 89 and living in Duncan, Okla., with another daughter, she
contends that the Whitings never paid her what they agreed to when
they acquired the north 60. According to Urquhart, BCC agreed to
pay her $180,000 for the property, but has paid only $66,000.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, the Whitings' attorney, agreed that the $180,000 had
not been fully paid but said the price was based on the Whitings
collecting money from Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whitings have paid Genie what they have been required to
pay,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   Genie Urquhart has not talked to her daughter in more than 20
years. Oscar Urquhart died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a strong, strong man, and I have no doubts he would
still be alive if not for all of this,'' Genie Urquhart said. ``I
know it killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Whitings initially declined to comment for this article, but
later Carolyn Whiting sent a fax to The Kansas City Star that said
in part: ``One thing that I've learned in life is, you cannot
control how people feel or what they say. Life is so very short,
you cannot worry about things you cannot change.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Miller, whose husband also died over the course of the
fight, could not be contacted.
</P>
<P>
   John Milholland, the attorney who fought her fight the longest,
also has died. Her current attorney, Kevin Anderson, was out of
town and could not be contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry, the older of Miller's two sons, said his mother had
health problems and recently underwent a leg amputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a tough, tenacious woman...just like my grandmother,''
Gentry said. ``Those were the qualities that made Christmas Tree
Lane successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the end, those were the qualities that destroyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Miller, Gentry said, still lives with her other son in
the red gingerbread house at the edge of Christmas Tree Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Just to the south about a quarter mile, Santa peeks through the
trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
