<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-PRIZE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CHEMISTS WIN AWARD FOR UNLOCKING VITAMIN MYSTERY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two chemists who decoded the blueprints for the
manufacture of many of nature's most beneficial products, including
vitamin B-12, are co-recipients of the 2000 Welch Award.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M University Professor Ian Scott, 72, and University of
Cambridge Professor Emeritus Alan Battersby, 75, were instrumental
in unlocking secrets of biosynthesis and bio-organic chemistry _
how nature makes products _ and learning how to re-create that work
in the test tube.
</P>
<P>
   ``These insights set the stage for further efforts to mimic
nature and produce vitamins, antibiotics and other beneficial
products in a shorter time and with less cost in terms of both
money and impact on the environment,'' said Richard J.V. Johnson,
chairman of the Welch Foundation and chairman and publisher of the
Houston Chronicle. ``The work of Drs. Battersby and Scott truly
embodies the spirit of the Welch Award: basic research in chemistry
that contributes to the betterment of humankind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Welch Award, one of chemistry's most prestigious prizes,
goes to chemists whose lifetime contributions in basic research
have had a positive influence on mankind.
</P>
<P>
   The two chemists' selection will be announced at a luncheon
Wednesday at Texas A&AMP;M in College Station. They will share the
award's $300,000 prize and will receive a gold medallion at a
banquet in Houston in October.
</P>
<P>
   Both Scott and Battersby, who've never worked together, said the
award was a great recognition not only of their own work but of the
field of bio-organic chemistry, which straddles the border between
chemistry and biology and has never received the recognition of
many other chemistry branches. Nevertheless, the two scientists'
work previously earned them the Tetrahedron Prize, another
chemistry award, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a friendly competition that lasted nearly 30 years, Scott and
Battersby pursued the decoding of vitamin B-12, a large,
complicated molecule that assists essential biochemical processes
but cannot be made in the body. The two scientists worked on
parallel tracks, which Scott compared to ``going up a mountain from
two sides.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the biosynthesis of B-12 is such a difficult feat, it was
great to have independent confirmation,'' said Scott, who was born
in Glasgow, Scotland, and came to A&AMP;M in 1977. ``What was
interesting was that even though neither of us knew where to start,
we both ended up doing many of the same experiments.''
</P>
<P>
   The decoding of B-12 involved identifying 22 steps and 22 genes,
the most of any vitamin. People unable to absorb B-12 suffer
pernicious anemia, which slows the rate at which healthy red blood
cells form and thus prevents oxygen from being transported
efficiently around the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studying how a living system makes a molecule is like building
a cathedral,'' said Battersby, who has continued his research since
his retirement in 1992. ``B-12 was the biggest challenge, but the
entire field is like a supermarket with fundamental chemical
problems stacked on its shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Scott also discovered a second process nature uses to make B-12.
The two pathways evolved 2 billion years apart.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the discovery by Scott and Battersby, scientists are
now able to increase the speed and production of B-12. And, in
principle, they say, it should lead to the creation of almost any
kind of molecule _ so scientists will no longer have to damage
ecosystems to make products.
</P>
<P>
   Both Scott and Battersby began studying synthetic organic
chemistry in Great Britain in the early 1960s. Scott studied
penicillin and anti-tumor agents, Battersby morphine and other
alkaloids.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based Welch Foundation, established in 1954 by the
estate of Houston oilman Robert A. Welch, has provided more than
$411 million to support basic research in chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
