<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS STUN STARS, 7-3, TO TAKE OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Stanley Cup finals began Tuesday
night in Continental Arena with a three-hour party for the New
Jersey Devils and their giddy fans. Breaking open a 1-1 tie early
in the second period, the Devils surged to a stunning 7-3 victory
over the Dallas Stars, the defending champions.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott scored twice for the Devils and so did Petr Sykora.
The Devils got a goal from Ken Daneyko, a veteran Devils defenseman
who had not scored in the post-season since 1995. They got one from
Scott Stevens, another veteran defenseman who is better known for
his heavy hits. And they got one from Sergei Brylin.
</P>
<P>
   They scored six times on 18 shots against Ed Belfour, the Dallas
goalie, who was replaced by Manny Fernandez in the third period. So
loose were the Devils with a six-goal lead that they allowed the
Stars to score two goals in a 12-second span in the eighth minute
of the third period to cut the margin to 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 of this four-of-seven series will be played here on
Thursday night. In that both teams are known for defense and good
goaltending, their next meeting might produce a much different sort
of performance. But the Stars might not be at full strength.
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher, the Dallas captain and rugged defenseman, left
the game in the third period with what was called a leg injury. His
status is uncertain. Aside from the Dallas goal scorers _ Darryl
Sydor, Jon Sim and Kirk Muller _ Hatcher was one of few Stars who
was effective Tuesday night. With tactics that bordered on
legality, he made contact with several Devils and left them in
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Another Devil in pain was John Madden, who left the game late in
the third period with what appeared to be a leg injury.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the lineup for the Devils was Sergei Nemchinov, a
versatile, veteran forward who missed Game 7 of the previous series
against Philadelphia after suffering a 40-stitch cut in his face in
Game 6. Nemchinov played left wing next to center Scott Gomez and
right wing Alexander Mogilny.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took a 1-0 lead at 7:22 of the first period on
Arnott's first goal, a backhander from close range that completed a
deft play with linemates Sykora and Patrik Elias, who got the
assists.
</P>
<P>
   After Arnott took a faceoff in the right-wing circle, the three
forwards worked the puck counter-clockwise around the zone, behind
the net and out front again, with a series of backhanded passes
that left Dallas defenseman Sergei Zubov between coverages. It was
Arnott's fifth goal of the playoffs. His line was New Jersey's most
productive in the seven-game elimination of Philadelphia in the
Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny had a difficult defensive shift and it resulted in a
Dallas goal that tied the score at 1-1 at 13:13. After Mogilny
failed to clear the zone on right wing at the blue line, the Stars
worked the puck behind goalie Martin Brodeur's net with Mike Keane
controlling it. Then Jere Lehtinen passed to Sydor, who drilled a
low slap shot from the left point past both Mogilny's blocking
attempt and Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the period, Elias left the ice after being cross-checked
in the back by Hatcher, who caught Elias from behind while his
partner, Richard Matvichuk, distracted Elias from the front. No
penalty was called. Nor did the referees react, shortly thereafter,
to an exchange of sticks to the body between Zubov and New Jersey's
Claude Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   Elias returned for the start of the second period and the Devils
got the next three goals to take a 4-1 lead. Daneyko scored his
first of the playoffs at 2:52 by firing from the left side, near
the blue line. The puck passed Madden, the rookie center from the
University of Michigan who had won the faceoff before screening
Belfour and jumping above the path of the puck at the last instant.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils went up by 3-1 at 10:28 when Sykora scored, set up by
Elias, who dropped Belfour to the ice with a right-to-left move
across the crease, cut past the goal line and flipped a backhanded
pass onto Sykora's stick. Arnott got the other assist. A few
moments before the goal, Brodeur had protected the one-goal lead by
stopping Mike Modano on a slap shot and Brett Hull on a rebound in
quick succession.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the period, Hatcher leveled Madden with a thundering
elbow to the head that the referees allowed to pass without
punishment. Perhaps they also did not see Madden lying on the ice,
dazed, because they allowed play to continue around his sprawled
body.
</P>
<P>
   After the Devils went ahead 4-1 _ on a slap shot by Stevens at
16:04 _ the first penalty of the game was called when Hatcher
slashed Sykora at 18:20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
