<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-ART-NYT &LR;      05-30 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP NOMINATES LAZIO TO CHALLENGE CLINTON FOR SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT7 and NYT25 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y _ New York Republicans Tuesday unanimously selected
Rep. Rick A. Lazio of Long Island as the party's candidate for
U.S.Senate in a convention punctuated with campaign attacks _ in
speeches, on bumper stickers and on lapel buttons _ on the
Democrats' Senate candidate, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio seized the platform and promised a hard-hitting campaign,
borrowing heavily on Democratic themes and speeches as he accused
Clinton of engaging in what he described as ``the politics of
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who 10 months ago was forced to the sidelines of the
Senate race by party leaders to make way for Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, found himself at the center of state Republican attention
_ and curiosity _ as the party met to choose its challenger to
Clinton. Lazio was selected by acclamation at a convention that was
scripted right down to the last speech to second his nomination by
delegates, and he set out to introduce himself both to New York
voters and to delegates who just one week ago probably expected to
be nominating Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to representing the needs, concerns and values
of the people of New York, I have one advantage that she will never
have: I can be myself, I am a New Yorker,'' Lazio said in his
27-minute acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the dominant themes used by Republican
officeholders and party leaders on Clinton throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see for me, New York isn't just a mailing address, it's my
home,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said that he would present himself to New York voters as a
moderate Republican with ``a vision guided by mainstream principles
and compassionate instincts,'' and he stressed his Congressional
votes in favor of environmental protection, expanding public
housing, and funding research on breast cancer and cervical cancer.
He attacked Clinton for seeking to identify him with the ideology
of Newt Gingrich, the former House speaker, asserting that it was
symptomatic of what he called the ``divisive'' political techniques
practiced by Democrats since President Clinton was elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some in the opposition camp think that they have a winning
strategy in repeating Newt Gingrich's name a thousand times between
now and November,'' Lazio said. ``Well, let me share with you my
winning strategy: Let the other side pursue a politics of discord
and division, I will unite all of New York behind a positive vision
for our great state.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio invoked, almost to the word, turns of phrases have been
used by both Clinton and the President about Republicans, perhaps
aiming to pre-empt Clinton's attacks on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not allow the politics of division to dim New York's
awesome potential,'' Lazio said. ``I have a goal, of course, and
it's winning the race for the United States Senate. But, more
important, I want to be worthy of winning. I want to bring New
Yorkers together.''
</P>
<P>
   Two circumstances _ both beyond the Lazio's control _ seemed to
detract from the Republican convention: the absence of Giuliani,
who withdrew from the race on May 19 because of his cancer, and
Lazio's own blemished countenance in the form of swollen, stitched
lip that resulting from a fall while marching in a Memorial Day
parade on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's absence was notable, because he was the only major
elected Republican in the state not on hand for the event. He spent
the day in New York City without, unusually, any public schedule.
Republicans said that Giuliani and Republican Party leaders decided
last week it would be better if the mayor did not attend the
convention and risk overshadowing Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican delegates paid tribute to Giuliani in a brief
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign spokesman, Howard Wolfson, described Lazio's
convention acceptance speech as ``recycled insults and rhetoric
that doesn't match his record. Time and time again Rick Lazio has
voted against New York's working families in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in Buffalo, Lazio, his wife, Patricia, and New York Gov.
George E. Pataki unveiled Lazio's campaign bus: The Mainstream
Express.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most notable contrast between the Republican
convention Tuesday and the Democratic convention in Albany two
weeks ago was that the Democrats refrained from any attacks on
Giuliani, who had recently made his illness public and had yet to
decide whether to campaign for Senate..
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Clinton was in the bull's-eye today, the target for
delegates, party leaders and Lazio himself. Within five minutes of
the opening of the convention, William D. Powers, the state
Republican Party leader, was chastising Clinton for failing to
apologize for an incident in which people attending the Democratic
convention reportedly harassed members of the police honor guard at
the Democratic convention. Mrs. Clinton wrote a letter to the
Police Department deploring the incident, an aide said last night.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki railed on Clinton for failing to pay state income taxes
since she moved to New York, possibly foreshadowing a a theme
Republicans plan to use in the campaign ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention lasted for precisely two hours in a
ballroom at the Hyatt Regency hotel in Buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
