<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY TO FACE ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND -- Chuck Finley admitted these last couple of days
have been a bit strange, watching the team for which he played 14
seasons on the other side of the field in the opposing dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight Finley's vantage point moves to the mound, where he'll
start against the Angels for his new team, the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll probably be a little weird,'' said Finley, who signed a
three-year, $27 million contract with the Indians on Dec. 16.
``When they step in the box, I'll have a story to go with every
single one of them. I still have a lot of friends over there. But a
line has to be drawn. I'm out to do a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley said he is still getting used to his new surroundings.
While his wife and two daughters have remained in Newport Beach,
Finley is staying in a downtown Cleveland hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it'll ever feel like home, but I know this is
the right place for me,'' he said. ``I knew it was time for me to
move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still getting acclimated to this team, but it's been
pretty smooth. This is a big baseball town. They're very serious
about winning. They don't take losing lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians have been hit hard with injuries this season,
ringing familiar to Finley, who watched so many Angels teams
decimated by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen plenty of stuff like this,'' he said. ``This is like
a baby ward compared to over there. We had guys having heart
transplants over there. Not only were guys out, they were out four
to five months with something broken or something that needed to be
reattached.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about this team is we have a lot more to pull from.
In Anaheim we were pretty tapped out.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley still talks regularly with some Angels players. Monday
night, he had dinner with Darin Erstad and Troy Percival. And while
they were out, they called Gary DiSarcina, who is home recovering
from shoulder surgery. ``DiSar said he's running out of pain
pills,'' Finley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels signed shortstop Kevin Stocker to a major league
contract for the rest of the season. Stocker, who was released by
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays on May 25, will join the team Friday in
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Stocker is expected to take over the starting spot at shortstop
from Benji Gil, who will move back into a utility role or be
released, depending on whether or not the club would rather use
Keith Luuloa in the utility role. Gil made his 12th and 13th errors
of the season in Tuesday's game vs. the Indians and is hitless in
his last 23 at-bats, his average down to .185.
</P>
<P>
   Stocker made 11 errors while hitting .263 with two homers and
eight RBIs in 40 games this season for the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that with DiSarcina gone for the balance of the
season, we had an opening for a four-month period here,'' Angels GM
Bill Stoneman said. ``I don't want to diminish Benji's
contributions at all, but here's a guy who's a candidate to come in
here and play shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy was given the day off Tuesday, meaning not only was
he not in the starting lineup, but he also didn't take batting
practice. He won't start tonight's game either, in an effort by
manager Mike Scioscia to get his rookie second baseman to relax.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy hit .318 with three homers and 20 RBIs in April, but in
May he's hitting .192 with no homers and five RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Troy Glaus went through a similar phase in his first
full season in the big leagues, hitting .341 with five homers and
16 RBIs in April, and falling to .130, one homer, five RBIs in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want him to clear his head a little bit and let him
relax,'' Scioscia said. ``He's really been pushing. He needs to
take a step back and catch a breath. It's a good time for it. He's
a rookie still adjusting to playing every day in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea as well,'' Kennedy said. ``I'm just
trying to think too much about everything. Everything is happening
so fast, I've got to slow things down and try to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The club his encouraged by the progress of pitchers Tim Belcher
(elbow surgery), Ken Hill (torn muscle in ribcage) and Jason
Dickson (strained hip). Belcher will throw a simulated game today
and begin a rehab assignment for Triple-A Edmonton on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson threw in the bullpen Tuesday and felt good, and is
expected to begin a rehab assignment soon. Hill is probably a few
weeks away from going on a rehab assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS AT CLEVELAND
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4:05 at Jacobs Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: ESPN; KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Seth Etherton (0-0, 5.40 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Cleveland's Chuck Finley (3-4, 4.04). Finley has pitched in
more games than any other pitcher in Angels history (436 games),
but he'll make appearance No. 1 against them tonight. Finley also
holds club records in wins (165), starts (379) and innings pitched
(2,675).
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
