u s BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     05-30 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 BUTTERFLIES: ONE SPARKLES, ONE SUCCUMBS  
 BY DAVE ANDERSON  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ They are known as ``butterflies'' for
their style, but their wings are their padded legs. Instead of
fluttering, these masked butterflies spread those wings, crouch,
sprawl, dive. Anything to stop the puck.
</P>
<P>
   They are the two goaltenders in the Stanley Cup final _ Martin
Brodeur for the Devils, Ed Belfour for the defending champion
Stars. And for all the speculation about the scorers, the
defensemen, the power plays and the penalty-killers, the eventual
winning team surely will possess the hotter goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   And in last night's opener, Brodeur was the hot goaltender when
he had to be as the Devils rolled, 7-3. Belfour was not even
lukewarm before he was benched early in the third period after
surrendering six goals. You would have thought the Devils' pucks
were made in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   With two spectacular saves a split-second apart on Mike Modano
and Brett Hull midway in the second period, Brodeur turned the
game. Had either of those two snipers scored, the Stars would have
pulled into a 2-2 tie. Instead, moments after those two spectacular
saves, Petr Sykora lifted the Devils to a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But going into this playoff final, the goaltender's stats for
three previous rounds had been virtually identical: Brodeur had a
1.77 goals-against average, Belfour's was 1.81. Brodeur had allowed
30 goals, Belfour 31. Brodeur had a .923 save percentage, Belfour's
was .931. Brodeur had two shutouts, Belfour had three. Each had a
12-5 won-lost record.
</P>
<P>
   And, equally important, each's name has been engraved on the
Stanley Cup once _ Brodeur's in 1995, Belfour's a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In hockey, a goaltender is always a team's most important player
because he is its constant on the ice. The forwards and the
defenseman change every minute or so, but the goaltender is always
out there in front of his 6-by-4-foot net.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if a baseball team could use its ace pitcher in every
game. Imagine a World Series with Pedro Martinez pitching every
game for the Red Sox or Randy Johnson pitching every game for the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're young,'' Brodeur said, alluding to the 1995
playoffs when the Devils swept the Red Wings in the final, ``you
don't pay attention to details, you just go with it. Everything
falls into place and you play the game. When you're older, you have
more responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur is 28 now, one of the bigger goaltenders at 6 foot 2 and
205 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the league better than he did in 1995,'' said Jacques
Caron, the Devils' goaltender coach. ``He knows who to look for.
For this series he knows that Brett Hull has a quick release, that
Mike Modano shoots from anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur was shaky occasionally earlier in these playoffs.
Belfour was more consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belfour's in a zone now,'' Caron said before Tuesday night's
shelling. ``He was the difference in the Stars beating Colorado in
the Western Conference final. He has great determination. He's like
Tony Esposito was with the Blackhawks years ago, a reflex
goaltender, but he's more mobile than Tony was. Martin is more of
an angle goaltender.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, who has his own Web site, is more compact at 5-foot-11
and 192 pounds, and at 35, he has more experience than Brodeur and
a more impressive resume: winner of the Vezina Trophy as the
National Hockey League's best goaltender in both 1991 and 1993 with
Chicago, first-team All-Star in both 1991 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In last Saturday night's seventh-game victory in Dallas, the
crowd chanted, ``Bel-four's Bett-er,'' meaning better than Patrick
Roy, the Avalanche goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who grew up in Montreal, idolized Roy, then with the
Canadiens. Belfour, out of Carman, Manitoba, joined the Blackhawks,
where he was tutored by the Soviet legend, Vladislav Tretiak, then
the Chicago goaltender coach. He wears Tretiak's No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the other Blackhawk goaltender was Dominik Hasek,
but Hasek was traded to Buffalo by Mike Keenan, then the
Blackhawks' general manager and coach before becoming the Rangers'
coach in 1993. Keenan had asked Tretiak which goaltender to keep.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek went on to win the Hart Trophy twice as the NHL's most
valuable player and five Vezina trophies.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour bested Hasek in last year's cup final, but Tuesday night
Belfour turned cold. Martin Brodeur was the hot butterfly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0345 </DOCNO>
