<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BATTERED-WOMEN-N     05-30 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BATTERED-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WORK-RELEASE FOR BATTERED WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 31: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under New York state law, prisoners convicted of violent crimes
are not allowed into the work-release program. In 1995 Gov. George
Pataki, concerned about crimes committed by inmates on
work-release, made violent offenders ineligible for the program.
While that prohibition makes sense in most cases, there should be
an exemption allowed for battered women who have been convicted of
violent crimes against their abusers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the State Assembly passed a sensible bill that would
allow convicted battered women to participate in work-release at
the discretion of the state corrections commissioner. It died in
the Senate, but earlier this year the Senate crime victims and
corrections committee passed the measure. The Legislature should
approve the bill promptly, and Pataki should sign it into law.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of domestic violence are generally different from other
violent offenders. Many of these women had no previous criminal
records, and are not likely to be repeat offenders. Many were
retaliating for years of physical, sexual and psychological abuse
by their tormentors. Work-release is a crucial step for these women
in making the transition from prison back into society.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would give the state corrections commissioner the
authority to grant work-release on a case-by-case basis to victims
of domestic violence, including men who have been battered. The
commissioner could reject anyone who has a history of violence or
is judged to be a threat to public safety. There are probably fewer
than 100 inmates, the vast majority of them women, who could become
eligible for work-release under this bill. It would give these
prisoners, who have been victims of prolonged violence themselves,
a chance to rebuild their lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0352 </DOCNO>
