<HEADER>
A0356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PERU-1STLD-WRITE     05-30 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PERU-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEMANDING NEW ELECTIONS IN PERU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to rewrite last two grafs)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 31:
</P>
<P>
   The national howl of protest against President Alberto
Fujimori's illegitimate re-election victory in Peru is a welcome
sign of the country's political health, but it also poses a danger.
Fujimori or his backers in military intelligence may feel cornered
and strike back with violence. To prevent bloodshed, the
international community must strongly support the protesters' goal
of a legitimate election to choose a democratic government in Peru,
and prepare to isolate Fujimori if he refuses, or uses violence.
</P>
<P>
   At this moment the most important outside voice belongs to the
Organization of American States, which holds a meeting on Peru
today and will doubtless discuss Peru in its annual general
assembly meeting on Sunday. The OAS should demand new and fair
elections, and offer its services to help Fujimori and his
principal opponent, Alejandro Toledo, agree on the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Historically when the OAS faced this situation, it would execute
a graceful diplomatic punt. In many ways the organization is more
timid and disorganized than a few years ago, when democracy seemed
to be ascendant in Latin America and leaders paid more attention to
the OAS. But there is still some hope that it will stand firm.
</P>
<P>
   The most positive indication is the resolve of the group's
election observer mission, the first to be very critical of an
important OAS member. The mission, led by the respected former
Guatemalan foreign minister, Eduardo Stein, declined even to
monitor last Sunday's runoff election, saying that an inadequate
vote tabulation method and a biased campaign environment meant the
election could not possibly be a fair one.
</P>
<P>
   Stein will present his report to the OAS today. The members at
the meeting _ every country in the hemisphere save Cuba _ can then
vote to invoke Resolution 1080, which enables the region's foreign
ministers to take political action against a member whose democracy
is interrupted. The other members could withdraw their ambassadors
from Peru, for example, though this has never been done.
</P>
<P>
   The chances that the OAS will back democracy in Peru waned on
Tuesday when a State Department spokesman backed away from
unusually direct criticism of the election an American official had
voiced the day before. Brazil's vote is also crucial, and the last
statement from that country was tepid. Brazil's president, Fernando
Henrique Cardoso, a defender of democracy, should take the lead in
helping to restore it in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori is gambling _ perhaps successfully _ that Washington
will quickly resume its cooperation with Lima, which has been an
ally in fighting cocaine and terrorism. He is also hoping the OAS
will undercut Stein's observer mission and go back to its blander
ways. But if the hemisphere returns to diplomacy-as-usual, Mr.
Fujimori will have a license to intensify repression in Peru.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-30-00 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000530.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT     05-30 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENDOZA LOSES HIS GRIP, SO YANKS LOSE A GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ramiro Mendoza likes to work fast when he is
pitching, and Tuesday he seemed as if he wanted to work even faster
on a brisk night. Mendoza lined up on the extreme left side of the
rubber, blew warm air into his right hand, tossed pitches and then
quickly returned to his original position to start again.
</P>
<P>
   But the ball felt slippery to Mendoza and he could not throw
strikes and he could not get comfortable. Usually, Mendoza does not
have trouble enticing the umpire to lift his right arm and does not
have problems performing as relaxed as someone whipping a tennis
ball around the yard. Except for Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The normally precise and normally poised Mendoza was neither as
he walked a career-high six batters, did not last beyond the fifth
inning and just plain sputtered as the Oakland Athletics tamed the
Yankees, 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza followed up a 7-0 shutout over the White Sox last
Thursday, the first time he had started in 18 days, by searching
for strikes while pitching on the normal four days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to the bullpen and the ball felt good,'' said Mendoza
after the game. ``I go to the mound and the ball felt slick. I
didn't have control today.''
</P>
<P>
   It was startling to see Mendoza deteriorate into such an
undependable pitcher. Even more than Orlando Hernandez or Andy
Pettitte, Mendoza consistently throws strikes. He does not fool
around, he uses a nasty sinker to induce groundballs and he had
walked only eight batters in 33 innings, an average of 2.4 per nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium because Mendoza
could not get solid grips with the temperature in the upper 50s and
almost matched his season total for walks in one sloppy game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't seem comfortable out there,'' said Manager Joe
Torre. ``He was inconsistent. Too many pitches were belt-high.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza's last two walks in the fifth helped lead to the runs
that enabled Oakland to tie the score, and Chuck Knoblauch's
throwing error allowed the A's to score the tie-breaking run. With
runners on first and second, Knoblauch moved to his left to corral
Ben Grieve's grounder between first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch bobbled the ball as he tried to pivot to second, his
throw was low and it bounced off Derek Jeter's glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have caught it,'' said Jeter. ``I should have caught
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's team-leading eighth error loaded the bases for the
A's and the struggling Mendoza could not maintain the 4-2 lead. An
infield groundout scored in the third run and Matt Stairs lashed a
two-run single into center to drive in two more runs, put the A's
ahead, 5-4, and end Mendoza's sluggish start.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza threw 87 pitches and 43 were balls.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did not help the situation by going one for 11 with
runners in scoring position, and Ricky Ledee's single in the second
did not even knock in a run. It loaded the bases with no outs, but
Kevin Appier struck out Scott Brosius and got Knoblauch to ground
to short and into a double play. Instead of burying Appier, the
Yankees might have buried themselves by only scoring once in that
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza walked Terrance Long to start the game and that
symbolized his night as he walked batters in four of the five
innings he pitched. Still, he survived for a while because he
secured double plays to end the first and the second.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch made a strong throw on the double play in the first,
but Randy Velarde spiked Knoblauch in the left leg. When Knoblauch
returned to the dugout, he cringed while a trainer treated his leg.
Apparently, Knoblauch was not in too much pain because he led off
by lining Appier's 1-1 fastball over the left field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez hit a liner in the second that soared by the
314-foot sign in right field for his first homer in 65 at bats,
giving the Yankees a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After the A's used a walk and two doubles to tie it, 2-2, Bernie
Williams doubled in a run in the third and Jeter continued his
torrid hitting by drilling a homer to center that put the Yankees
ahead, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the ball never felt right to Mendoza, he did not throw
strikes and he did not hold the lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
